<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SovietLeaders     05-16 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Leaders,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Change in General Secretary's Term Likely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Soviet Communist Party's
Central Committee said there is a ``good chance'' the group will
introduce laws at a party conference next month to limit the term
of office for the general secretary, according to a published
report.
   The Washington Post reports in Tuesday's editions that while
Georgi Arbatov said there was a ``good chance'' of such a change,
he added that the change would not indicate any setback for Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who now holds the general secretary
position.
   The party conference in late June will occur after the Moscow
summit with President Reagan, which begins May 29.
   Arbatov told the newspaper that Gorbachev and his propaganda
chief, Alexander Yakovlev, had been in charge of crucial
ideological issues in the party ``from the very beginning.''
   Gorbachev had weathered a strong debate with the party's second
in command, Yegor Ligachev, in the Soviet press over his reform
program, Arbatov said.
   Another high-level Soviet official, Valentin Falin, told the
newspaper that reports that there would be major personnel shifts
in the ruling Politburo were untrue.
   Falin, a non-voting member of the committee, said Kremlin
leadership had decided not to make any significant changes in top
policy-making bodies.
   Falin also said Gorbachev had recently ``learned a lot that is
new to him'' about Stalin from documents he has reviewed outlining
crimes of the Stalin era. One document proves Stalin's role in
preparing trumped up cases against his political enemies, Nikolai
Bukharin and Lev Kamenev, Falin said.
   Meanwhile, other officials predicted the Soviet leader would
give an important speech on history, highlighting the Stalin era,
at the party conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
