<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-BassoonMonsoon     05-16 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Bassoon Monsoon,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gene Shalit Among 40 Bassoonists Performing At Benefit Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Film critic Gene Shalit gets a chance to blow
off some hot air tonight, along with 39 other bassoonists at a
``Bassoon Monsoon.''
   The all-bassoon ensemble, which also will include Peter ``P.D.Q.
Bach'' Shickele, hopes to raise money to endow the bassoon chair of
the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center.
   Shalit, of NBC's ``Today,'' and Shickele, who has performed as
Johann Sebastian Bach's ``long-lost son,'' said the bassoon was not
their instrument of choice.
   ``We had a very fine clarinetist in Fargo, North Dakota,'' said
Shickele. ``After a few years, I was sent to him for lessons. He
said, `Peter, you've picked up too many bad habits. It would be
easier to start over on a new instrument.'''
   Shalit also started with the clarinet. ``I didn't practice for a
few weeks,'' he said, ``and the teacher got furious.
   ``He took away my clarinet and as punishment he said, `From now
on, you're gonna play THIS.'''
</TEXT>
