<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Family Bjt   05-16 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Family, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>His Mother-In-Law's Struggle To Win Diploma Becomes Symbol For
Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To her daughter, she was the ``chief example
of my life.'' To her classmates, she was a grandmother who
sometimes seemed as young as they. To her son-in-law, Jesse
Jackson, she was a symbol of stubborn determination in the face of
overwhelming odds.
   On Sunday, Gertrude Brown graduated from college at the age of
61. And Jackson, who continues his quest for the Democratic
presidential nomination despite mounting obstacles, was here to pay
tribute to her.
   For Mrs. Brown, a teen-age unwed mother and high-school dropout
who went on to raise five children, a college diploma was a
lifelong dream.
   ``She is of strong character, and she never surrendered,''
Jackson told the crowd of 11,000 at commencement ceremonies for
predominantly black Hampton University.
   ``Against all odds she is graduating today. ... That is what
this graduation is all about,'' he said.
   Jackson has always cited humble beginnings as a source of
strength. He did so again Sunday as he praised the mother of his
wife, Jacqueline.
   He opened his speech with a biblical story from the Book of Acts
about a shipwreck. Those who could swam to shore, while the others
clung to broken pieces of the ship to survive, he said.
   ``I want to talk today about the challenge to keep hope alive _
of making it on broken pieces,'' said Jackson. ``Keep hope alive.
Keep hope alive.''
   He described Mrs. Brown's battle to raise her family and educate
her children while working full time. Three of her children went on
to win advanced degrees, he said.
   ``I can remember her as a struggling young woman, who was a
positive person, a realist,'' said daughter Jacqueline in an
interview. ``I can also remember a number of whippings because my
vocabulary contained phrases like `I can't.' She was my chief
example in life.''
   When she was 49, Mrs. Brown got her high school diploma. Then
she slowly began her college education, still working full time,
taking one or two classes a semester.
   The degree she won Sunday was in social work. Mrs. Brown said
she wanted skills to help people _ especially teen-agers who become
parents, as she did. She retains a special fondness for young
people.
   ``I'll miss all those students on campus _ they were like my
grandchildren, but they talked to me like I was their age,'' she
said.
   Jackson spoke to the students of fighting for change _ in one's
own life and the life of the nation.
   ``We must keep America strong, and make America better. How we
relate to the least of these _ the children in the dawn of life,
poor people in the pit of life, old folks in the sunset of life _
is a measurement of our character,'' he said.
   He talked about the civil rights movement, invoking events that
happened before these students were born.
   ``We worked through blood and smiled through our tears to get to
this juncture in the road,'' he told them.
   And he semed to allude, with pride, to his own fight for the
nomination.
   ``The struggle must continue,'' he said. ``We must not
surrender.''
   As for Mrs. Brown, she was savoring her success _ and looking
ahead.
   ``I'm not stopping here,'' she said. ``I'm going to get my
master's degree.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
