<1ST_LINE>r w PM-StarkCompensation     05-16 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stark Compensation,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Stark Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Payments to Relatives of Stark Victims Still Years Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within days of the attack on the USS Stark,
Iraq accepted responsibility for what it called a case of mistaken
identity and pledged to compensate the victims and Navy.
   Administration officials who ask not to be identified say it
could be years, however, before any money changes hands.
   Last month, after notifying the families of the 37 men killed,
the United States presented Iraq with a claim for wrongful death in
each case. The amount of each claim varied depending on the
expected lifetime earnings and other actuarial information for each
victim.
   A State Department source said the United States had been
working on presentation of those claims to Iraq for months. The
official declined to give the total dollar figure, but said it was
``in the tens of millions.''
   There has been no response from the Iraqis.
   Still to be determined is the size of the claim the United
States will submit for the damage to the Stark itself. The Navy
decided to perform an overhaul on the Stark as long as it was going
into drydock, and now must figure the precise cost of the battle
damage repairs.
   The State Department official estimated it would take another
six months before that claim is figured and forwarded to the Iraqis.
   The source refused to speculate on how long it would take for
money to change hands, citing the case of the USS Liberty.
   That ship was attacked by Israel during the 1967 Middle East
war. The final claim for damages was not paid until 1980, despite
the close ties between the United States and Israel.
   In the case of Iraq, the sources predicted long negotiations
would be necessary to resolve the matter, in part because Iraq will
probably try to avoid setting any precedent that could be used by
merchant ships it has attacked over the years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
