<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WillieBrown     05-16 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Willie Brown,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attention of Jackson Chairman Diverted By His Own Political
Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final push is on for California's
crucial presidential primary, and Jesse Jackson's national campaign
chairman, Willie Brown, should be in the thick of it.
   Instead, Brown is busy fighting a bid to oust him from his job
as speaker of the assembly, traditionally the second most powerful
post in the state.
   Twice in the last week, dissidents have tried unsuccessfully to
remove Brown from his job _ the first such attempts since he became
speaker 7{ years ago.
   Brown's own political problems could diminish his usefulness to
Jackson as the clock ticks down on the June 7 contest. However,
Brown _ as the black leader of a predominantly white legislative
body and a formidable fund-raiser _ remains a force to be reckoned
with.
   Known for his flamboyant style, Brown has already ruffled some
feathers in the rest of the Jackson campaign.
   He stirred up trouble last month when he told a New York Times
reporter that a Dukakis-Jackson matchup ``would be a good ticket.''
The comment came at a time when Jackson was trying to dampen talk
that he was interested in something other than the nomination.
   Brown tried to back off the next day, saying he meant that while
a Dukakis-Jackson ticket would be good, ``a Jackson-Dukakis ticket
would be the best for the Democrats.'' But the damage was done.
   Brown also has recently said that the sooner Democratic Party
Chairman Paul Kirk leaves, ``the better the party will be'' _ a
statement that might not have endeared him to party regulars.
   He told reporters in Washington that Dukakis ``doesn't come out
of Massachusetts with a great record'' on civil rights. And he told
the Wall Street Journal that the party should not try to register
white voters ``until we're sure every black and every Hispanic is
registered.''
   Despite such stumbles, Brown is still sounding confident _ about
keeping the speakership, and about Jackson's chances in California.
   ``I think he wins California,'' he said this week of Jackson's
prospects, dismissing polls indicating Jackson trails Dukakis.
   Brown's prominence in the Jackson's campaign is a factor,
although not a major one, in his own political troubles.
   He became speaker in December 1980 by putting together a
coalition of Republicans and Democrats after a yearlong battle for
the speakership between other Democratic legislators. His principal
opponents now are five Democrats, mostly moderates from rural
areas, who call themselves the Gang of Five.
   They were once close to Brown, enjoying prestigious committee
assignments and chairmanships. But they broke with Brown last
winter, complaining that he had stacked committees with liberals to
kill bills, particularly anti-crime measures, supported by the
public.
   Brown struck back at the Gang, stripping them of chairmanships,
moving them to the smallest offices in the Capitol and at one point
removing four of them from all committee assignments.
   One of the five, Assemblyman Charles Calderon of Montebello, has
criticized Brown for heading the Jackson campaign.
   Calderon told his hometown San Gabriel Daily Tribune last
January that Brown ``rides around in a Ferrari, wears mink coats
and competes with Clint Eastwood and other stars for notoriety.''
   ``The final straw,'' Calderon continued, ``came when Willie
Brown announced he was going to be the chair of the Jesse Jackson
campaign committee.''
   Brown's association with Jackson ``will be an extreme liability
for Democrats who are marginal'' and face GOP challenges this year,
Calderon said.
   Brown, for his part, has been attacking his foes in typically
colorful terms.
   ``In a divorce situation, give me the kids or something, don't
suggest there was something wrong with me when you slept with me
the first time,'' he said at a news conference last month.
   Even if he is feeling the heat, Brown has joked about the
attempts to get him out. Speaking to reporters, he made mention of
a luncheon he was invited to.
   ``I was invited as speaker. I would hate to go and say, `You
invited the wrong man,''' he said.
</TEXT>
