<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-16 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Concentrates On Confrontation With Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis, back at the Statehouse today after a Western campaign
swing, is making apparent Republican nominee George Bush the target
of his criticism and seeking to avoid harsh words about rival Jesse
Jackson.
   Jackson was campaigning today in Oregon, which holds its primary
Tuesday. But Dukakis, after two days of campaigning in California
and Oregon, flew home Sunday night.
   On the way home, Dukakis made a brief stop in South Orange,
N.J., for a statewide Democratic dinner, and attacked the Reagan
administration.
   ``I don't want to see another four years or another eight years
like the last seven,'' Dukakis told New Jersey Democrats. ``Our
nation can't afford it, our children don't deserve it and our
economy can't sustain it.''
   Jackson also addressed the group, and the two met briefly
beforehand. Dukakis declined to give any details, but said he and
his rival had a ``warm, pleasant, respectful'' discussion.
   In California, polls in California show him with a substantial
lead over Jackson. Dukakis aides acknowledge they are campaigning
in California with an eyes both on the June 7 contest with Jackson
and a fall meeting with Bush.
   At a stop in Los Angeles on Saturday, for instance, Dukakis
abandoned his usual appeal to ignore the polls and instead cited
the ones showing him with a lead over the vice president, both in
California and nationwide.
   ``Although I'm always skeptical of poll numbers and early
matchups,'' he said, ``I think the fact that in these early
matchups between me and the vice president, the fact that I am
leading at least gives you some sense ... that this is do-able.''
   At a weekend meeting with gay political activists in Los
Angeles, Dukakis faced perhaps the most hostile encounter of his
presidential campaign.
   He faced shouts of ``bigot'' as gay leaders challenged him on
issues of concern to homosexuals. But their central complaint
revolved around allowing homosexual couples to become foster
parents _ an issue on which Dukakis is unlikely to be hurt among
the larger voting population.
   Dukakis planned to return to California to campaign by midweek.
</TEXT>
