<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     05-16 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Three In Attack On Pub In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen opened fire on a
lunch-time crowd in a pub patronized by Roman Catholics, and police
said three people were killed and six wounded.
   The gunmen escaped in a stolen taxi after the attack on Sunday.
   The incident fueled fears of reprisals in the sectarian warfare
that has ravaged this predominantly Protestant British province
since 1969.
   An anonymous telephone caller to the British Broadcasting Corp.
claimed responsibility in the name of the Protestant Action Force,
which has been linked to outlawed paramilitary groups responsible
for assassinating scores of Catholics in the early 1970s.
   However, the BBC said the caller did not give a recognized code.
   Witnesses said there were about 20 people in the Avenue Bar in
Union Street when the attack occurred. The gunmen had stolen a taxi
in the nearby Protestant Shankill Road just before the attack and
afterward drove off in the direction of the Shankill, police said.
   Police said two people died at the scene and the third was
pronounced dead on arrival at a hospital. They identified the
victims as Damien Devlin, 24, Paul McBride, 27, and Stephen McGahan.
   Ten people were taken to hospitals, six with gunshot wounds and
four suffering from shock, police said.
   Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, Tom King, called the
killings a ``revolting outrage.''
   Gerry Adams, president of the Irish Republican Army's legal
political wing, Sinn Fein, said the attack was ``an attempt at
premeditated mass murder.''
   The gunmen rang the pub bell and were admitted through the
electronically operated door, witnesses said.
   ``A guy came in and took his time looking around and then
started shooting,'' said one witness, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``Then the other one came in behind him and started
shooting at people. It was just indiscriminate; people were trying
to dive for cover but they had no chance.''
   Moments after the shooting, three priests arrived to administer
last rites to the dead.
   Police and troops rushed into the area and set up roadblocks,
and an army helicopter hovered above.
   Witnesses said a patrol of the Ulster Defense Regiment, a mainly
Protestant security force, was near the pub during the attack but
appeared to have seen nothing and carried on with its normal duties.

</TEXT>
