<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusinessOutlook     05-16 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Outlook,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Growth Forecast But Interest Rise Prompts Recession Fear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for economic growth are good
this year but interest rates, if they continue to rise, threaten to
topple the United States into a recession by the end of 1989, the
country's business leaders say.
   Most members of the Business Council, composed of 61 chief
executives of some of the nation's largest companies, say business
so far in 1988 is better than they expected at the end of 1987,
when many were worried about the effects of the October stock
market crash.
   Now, the executives, with the exception of those heading
financial service firms such as brokerage and insurance companies,
report signs of moderate or better growth.
   ``The car business is going great, actually stronger than any of
us anticipated,'' said Roger B. Smith, chairman of General Motors
Corp.
   Other executives attending the council's twice-a-year meeting
last weekend at The Homestead, a posh resort in the mountains of
western Virginia, echoed Smith's sentiments, reporting other signs
of strong demand.
   ``We're seeing a surprising increase in demand for motor
gasoline in the United States, at least 2 percentage points above
what we expected,'' said George M. Keller, chairman of Chevron Corp.
   But amid the satisfaction over the country's more than
5-year-old business expansion, the longest since the 1960s, was
concern that possible renewed inflation could trigger rising
interest rates.
   Charles W. Parry, retired chairman of the Aluminum Company of
America, said prices of metals, chemicals and other basic
commodities are up significantly.
   Such a rise ``often has been a precursor of an increase in
inflation rates ... and that has me a little bit worried,'' Parry
said.
   A forecast, representing a consensus of economists employed by
Business Council member companies, predicts modest growth as
measured by the gross national product of 2.4 percent this year.
That compares with 3.8 percent in 1987.
   a Inflationary signs ... remain muted,'' the economists said,
predicting a rise in consumer prices of 3.9 percent this year and
4.6 percent in 1989, compared with 4.4 percent last year.
   However, the economists sounded a warning that overly robust
growth ``could produce an unavoidable rise in interest rates and a
recession before the end of 1989.''
   Underscoring the warning, major banks raised their prime lending
rate from 8.5 percent to 9 percent only two days before the council
began its meeting.
   Interest rates already seem to be outstripping the council's
forecasts, which were prepared about a week in advance of the
conference.
   The average yield on 30-year bonds issued by the Treasury last
week was 9.17 percent. The executives were looking for an average
rate on 30-year bonds of 8.9 percent this year and 9.3 percent next
year.
   However, Willard C. Butcher, chairman of the Chase Manhattan
Bank, said, ``I think we're overdoing fears of inflation'' and
suggested that interest rates may fall back a bit by the end of
1988.
   Although the economy is doing a little better than expected,
growth is still moderate, he said.
   ``We tend to be more worried today about how the economy does
against how we predicted than how it actually does,'' he said.
</TEXT>
