<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Japan-US     05-16 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Japan-US,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint Japan-U.S. Joint Naval Exercises Begin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese and U.S. naval forces today began a
weeklong joint anti-submarine drill in the Pacific Ocean, defense
officials said.
   The exercises were held in a 600-mile stretch of ocean from
Izu-Oshima island, south of Tokyo, to Japan's southwestern main
island of Kyushu, said Lt. Cmdr. Masanobu Ohtsuka, spokesman for
the Maritime Self-Defense Force.
   It is the 66th joint anti-submarine drill between the two forces
since 1957 and the first time both sides contributed military
transport vessels, he said.
   The exercise involves 12 Maritime Self-Defense Force vessels,
including transport ships, destroyers, submarines and
anti-submarine patrol planes.
   Six vessels, including one transport ship and two destroyers,
joined the exercises from the U.S. Seventh Fleet based in Yokosuka,
Ohtsuka said.
   Officials planned to stage a mock battle to defend a group of
transport vessels from a hypothetical attack by enemy submarines,
Ohtsuka said.
</TEXT>
