<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-USBases     05-16 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-US Bases,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Secretary Says U.S. Should Pay More For Military Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign secretary today said the
United States should pay more for its military bases in the
Philippines.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus also said the United States
should pay the increase regardless of whether the Philippine
government gives assurances that the bases will be allowed to stay
after their lease expires in 1991.
   ``If the U.S. cannot afford it, I don't think they should be
here at all,'' Manglapus told reporters. ``It's all up to the
United States. If they can afford it, they can stay. If they
cannot, they should go.''
   Manglapus is chief of a Filipino panel which is reviewing along
with a U.S. panel the status of the 1947 pact under which the
Americans maintain Clark Air Base, the Subic Bay naval base and
four smaller installations.
   A successful review is expected to influence Manila's decision
on allowing the bases to remain after the current agreement expires.
   Filipino officials have demanded a substantial increase in the
$180 million they receive yearly for use of the bases.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt, the chief American negotiator,
has warned that budget constraints may make it difficult for
Washington to provide a substantial increase.
   U.S. officials say they are working with Japan, West Germany and
other American allies to put together a major new aid package for
the Philippines.
   President Corazon Aquino has said she does not want the new aid
linked to the future of the bases.
   Mrs. Aquino has pledged to honor the bases agreement through
1991 but refuses to say whether she would support an extension.
   A growing number of Filipinos want to close the bases, which
they see as a vestige of American colonial rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Poll-Questions     05-16 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poll-Questions,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews April 29-May 8 with 1,204 adults in
the continental United States. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult
resident of each home who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning that
theoretically the results would be within 3 percentage points of
the same 19 times out of 20 if every adult American were asked the
same questions. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five
points for Republicans, for example, and nine points for
respondents who have done postgraduate work.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll:
   1. Do you think the president of the United States and the
leader of the Soviet Union should meet at regular intervals even
without any major items on the agenda, or should they meet only to
complete major treaties?
   Regular intervals: 78 percent. Major treaties: 16 percent. Don't
know or no answer: 6 percent.
   2. The United States and the Soviets recently agreed on a treaty
to abolish each country's medium-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
Do you think that will increase the chance of non-nuclear war in
Europe, decrease the chance of non-nuclear war in Europe, or won't
it make much of a difference?
   Increase: 11 percent. Decrease: 26 percent. Not much difference:
55 percent. Don't know or no answer: 8 percent.
   3. Do you support or oppose the U.S.-Soviet treaty to eliminate
each country's medium-range nuclear weapons?
   Support: 73 percent. Oppose: 15 percent. Don't know, no answer:
12 percent.
   4. Would you support or oppose a U.S.-Soviet treaty to abolish
50 percent of each country's long-range nuclear weapons?
   Support: 73 percent. Oppose: 15 percent. Don't know or no
answer: 12 percent.
   5. If the United States and the Soviet Union abolished all their
nuclear weapons, do you think that would increase the chance of
non-nuclear war, decrease it, or wouldn't it make much of a
difference?
   Increase, 22 percent. Decrease, 30 percent. Not much difference,
40 percent. Don't know or no answer: 8 percent.
   6. Ronald Reagan has proposed the Strategic Defense Initiative,
known as Star Wars, as a missile defense system. Do you think the
United States should drop SDI in exchange for a Soviet agreement to
a big cut in nuclear weapons?
   Yes, 33 percent. No, 49 percent. Don't know or no answer, 18
percent.
   7. Without an arms agreement with the Soviets, do you think work
on SDI should proceed as it is now, or should it be increased, or
reduced, or dropped?
   Proceed as now, 37 percent. Increase, 19 percent. Reduce, 13
percent. Drop, 17 percent. Don't know or no answer, 14 percent.
   8. Which country do you think has more political influence in
the world right now _ the United States, or the Soviet Union, or
are they about equal?
   United States, 41 percent. Soviet Union, 14 percent. About
equal, 38 percent. Don't know or no answer, 7 percent.
   9. Which country do you think is stronger militarily right now _
the United States, or the Soviet Union, or are they about equal?
   United States 28 percent. Soviet Union 33 percent. About equal
29 percent. Don't know or no answer, 10 percent.
   10. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev?
   Favorable, 54 percent. Unfavorable, 20 percent. Don't know or no
answer, 26 percent.
   11. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
President Reagan?
   Favorable, 59 percent. Unfavorable, 31 percent. Don't know or no
answer, 10 percent.
   12. Do you approve or disapprove of the way President Reagan is
handling relations with the Soviet Union?
   Approve, 71 percent. Disapprove, 17 percent. Don't know or no
answer, 12 percent.
   13. Do you think the Soviets can be trusted to live up to their
arms control agreements?
   Yes, 24 percent. No, 61 percent. Don't know or no answer, 15
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
