<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusAccidents     05-16 0098</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Accidents,0100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buses' Safety Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Buses are second only to passenger trains in safety as measured
by accident death rates.
   The latest figures available, for 1985, showed only 47 passenger
deaths in 116.8 billion passenger miles traveled, a rate of 0.04
per 100 million passenger miles, the National Safety Council
reported.
   By comparison, the rates were 0.03 for passenger trains, 0.07
for scheduled domestic airplanes and 0.93 for autos.
   The 47 bus deaths in 1985 included 12 on intercity buses. At the
same time, there were 22,974 auto fatalities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
