<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash-Safety     05-16 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Safety,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Use Of School Buses For Highway Travel Questioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED STAATS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School buses like the one involved in a
fatal wreck near here Saturday are not designed for high-speed
highway use, a bus company executive says.
   ``A school bus is a specialized vehicle, designed to transport a
high number of students over rural roads at relatively low speed,''
said Mike Sodrel, who operates an intercity charter and tour
service.
   ``A typical intercity coach, like a Greyhound, weighs 26,000 to
28,000 pounds empty. A typical school bus will weigh less than half
that,'' he said.
   A pickup truck traveling in the wrong direction on Interstate 71
north of Louisville plowed into a former school bus operated by a
church in Radcliff, Ky., just before midnight Saturday. The bus,
which had just been refueled, burst into flames and many victims
were not able to flee the wreckage.
   Sodrel is president of The Free Enterprise System Inc., an
intercity charter and tour service with 17 buses based in
Jeffersonville, Ind., across the Ohio River from Louisville. He
also is a director of the American Bus Association, a trade group
based in Washington, D.C.
   ``The fuel tanks on our coaches are mounted forward of the rear
axle and are inboard,`` he said. ``What's more significant is that
intercity coaches are diesel-powered and diesel fumes are not
explosive. Diesel fuel will burn but the flash point is
considerably higher than gasoline.''
   Saturday's crash involved a 1977 Ford school bus that took
regular gasoline, authorities said.
   Sodrel said he had no special knowledge of the bus-truck
collision and was speaking in general terms about bus safety.
   He said in an interview Sunday that the U.S. Department of
Transportation has the authority to enforce certain safety
regulations on private buses in addition to for-hire coaches, but
``they have not yet elected to do that.''
   He said legislation is pending in the U.S. House to direct the
DOT to do that.
   John Snyder, executive director of the trade association, said
the group has encouraged enforcement of the rules remaining since
partial deregulation of the industry in the mid-1980s. Deregulation
led to an increase in bus companies across the country, and
competitive pressures, he said.
   ``When you start cutting costs, safety sometimes starts to
suffer,'' he said.
   ``That is why our association and our board are so strong in
support of safety. We have seen a strengthening of the enforcement
process in the last couple of years,'' he said, referring to both
official efforts and industry adherance.
   Snyder made his remarks in a telephone interview from his home
in Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0045 </DOCNO>
