<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UrbanPeregrines     05-16 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Urban Peregrines,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wild Falcons Migrating To Cities Across America</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High above downtown, two wild peregrine falcon
chicks pecked out of their shells in a nest on a skyscraper ledge.
   To Baltimoreans, the hatching of another clutch of the
endangered species is almost old hat. A pair of peregrines have
been raising families on the 33rd-floor ledge of the United States
Fidelity & Guaranty Corp. building since 1984 and at least one
peregrine has lived on the building since 1979.
   But the migration of falcons to cities is a surprising
development in a successful experiment begun by Cornell University
in 1970 to reintroduce the predatory bird to southern Canada and
the continental United States after DDT and other pesticides
decimated the species.
   Baltimore was the first city the falcons chose. The first of the
birds, which were raised in captivity, drifted down from a New
Jersey marsh. The latest chicks were hatched two weeks ago by
falcons named Blythe and Beauregard.
   Today, released peregrines and their offspring nest in 20 U.S.
cities, according to experts. Urban homes include skyscrapers along
Wilshire Boulevard in Los Angeles, on a bridge over the Schuylkill
River in Philadelphia, on the San Francisco and Oakland ends of the
Bay Bridge, in New York City and on the Hotel Utah in Salt Lake
City.
   Falcons also have settled in the mountains of New England and in
cliffs and rock quarries in the Carolinas and Virginia.
   To falcons, skyscrapers and bridges resemble cliffs and mountain
peaks.
   ``All they have to do is become accustomed to helicopters and
human noises, and they'll do fine,'' said John Barber, falcon
guardian and data manager at USF&G. Peregrines mate for life and
live 15 to 20 years.
   Barber said falcons chose cities partly because pigeons had no
predators.
   ``And most cities are cheering them on because obviously the
pigeon population is way out of control,'' he said.
   In Los Angeles, two pairs of peregrines set up housekeeping
seven miles apart on Wilshire Boulevard, said Brian Walton,
coordinator of the Predatory Bird Group at the University of
California, Santa Cruz.
   ``The peregrines fly up and down that street, using the
skyscrapers like a string of mountain peaks,'' he said.
   Most of the birds were released from artificial structures, such
as towers in marshes, which may explain their attraction to bridges
and tall buildings, said Cornell ornithology professor Tom Cade.
   ``I think they develop some sort of association or fixation
early in life for these structures. Every tower we built is now
occupied by a nesting pair,'' said Cade, chairman of the Peregrine
Fund Inc.
   The fund, a non-profit organization that co-sponsors the
repopulation project, has received inquiries about using peregrines
to keep pigeons in check. However, Cade said falcons aren't the
answer to urban pigeon blight because each pair takes 10 square
miles for its territory.
   The immediate area benefits, as pigeons avoid peregrine perches,
Cade said.
   Historically, peregrines have not shunned human beings, although
they kept their distance, Cade said. Peregrines raised chicks on
the pyramids of Egypt and European castles and cathedrals have been
traditional nesting sites. Kings hunted with the falcons, which can
be trained but not tamed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
