<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-16 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Close At Record High; Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed at a record high today on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange, and the dollar edged up against the Japanese
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the market's main barometer,
rose 291.56 points to close at 27,759.87, surpassing the previous
record close of 27,669.72 set on May 1.
   Securities brokers said investors shared the view with Wall
Street where share prices gained sharply on Friday. They also said
many investors sat out trading today, waiting for the release of
U.S. trade figures for March, which the Commerce Department is
scheduled to announce Tuesday in Washington.
   A broker at a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said high-technology issues such as Toshiba and
Mitsubishi Electric led the market.
   ``The good result of the Producers Price Index in the U.S.
relieved the investors from the concern over inflation and possible
interest rate rise,'' the broker said.
   Meanwhile, the dollar closed at 124.73 yen, 0.03 yen higher than
Friday's close. The dollar was traded in a narrow range of 124.71
yen and 124.85 yen.
   ``The market had no enthusiasm today ahead of the release of
(U.S.) trade figures,'' said Hiroaki Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank.
``But even after the release, the market will not be affected too
much unless the figure is way out of an expected range.''
</TEXT>
