<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd item 4th graf, `Huntsberry, 47 ...' to clarify that
habit was $1,000-a-day.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Chick Huntsberry has turned to God, but
the 340-pound former professional wrestler and bodyguard for rock
star Prince says turning-the-other-cheek is still hard to swallow.
   ``I might be a Christian, but I'm not an idiot,'' says the
6-foot-6 Huntsberry, who has become an evangelical sensation since
rejecting drugs and rock 'n' roll and devoting his considerable
self to Jesus.
   ``If some dude smacked me, I'd probably smack him back. But I'd
pray for him afterwards. ... You don't have to be a sissy to love
Jesus.''
   Huntsberry, 47, said he once had a $1,000-a-day cocaine habit.
He found religion when his 6-year-old grandson, Jeremy, recovered
from a choking episode last summer.
   In January, he started ``Big Chick Ministries'' and began
thundering across the nation warning teen-agers and their parents
about drugs, suicide and rock music. Looking like Grizzly Adams on
steroids, he still wears studded leather from his rock 'n' roll
days.
   ``You know I used to work for a man named Prince,'' he tells
audiences. ``I protected him. But now I work for another Prince.
The Prince of Peace. And this Prince protects me.''
</TEXT>
