<HEAD>Thunderstorms Blast Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms rumbled across the central Great Lakes
region and into the Southern Plains today after lightning, hail and
high wind lashed Illinois, Michigan and Indiana, ripping down power
lines and uprooting trees.
   One branch of thunderstorms edged across the Ohio Valley from
western New York into Ohio and Indiana, while another swept through
southeast Kansas and parts of Oklahoma.
   Thunderstorms across northeastern Illinois Sunday left a retired
firefighter in critical condition after he was struck by lightning
while fishing. The storms also knocked out electrical power for
about 25,000 customers in the Chicago area.
   Meanwhile, tornadoes spawned by severe thunderstorms touched
down in at least four southeastern Michigan areas Sunday, knocking
down trees and power lines.
   In Indiana, wind gusting up to 70 mph accompanied thunderstorms
that moved across the northern edge of the state on Sunday, downing
trees and power lines.
   ``We've had a lot of property damage,'' said Steuben County
Sheriff Robert Enyeart. There were no reports of injuries.
   The strongest thunderstorms early today were reported in central
and southern Oklahoma and were accompanied by large hail and gusty
wind. Golf ball-sized hail pelted Oklahoma City, along with winds
up to 80 mph.
   Elsewhere, a cold front brought showers to the Oregon coast.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
northern New England and the Great Lakes region into the Ohio and
Tennessee Valleys and the central and southern Appalachians;
showers and thunderstorms from Georgia across Alabama, Mississippi,
Arkansas and southeast Oklahoma into northeast Texas; showers from
the northern Pacific Coast region and northwest Nevada with a few
thunderstorms over western Idaho and northwest Montana.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s over much of
the nation; 90 over Gulf Coast states and southern Arkansas; into
the 90s and around 100 in southwest Texas, southern New Mexico and
the desert Southwest; in the 60s along the New England coast, the
California coast and much of Washington and Oregon; in the 50s and
60s over most of Michigan and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 fair; Boston 54 cloudy; Buffalo 59 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 67 fair; Cincinnati 67 partly cloudy; Cleveland 60
showery; Detroit 59 fair; Miami 72 fair; New York 54 foggy;
Philadelphia 57 foggy; Pittsburgh 63 thunderstorms; Portland, Maine
46 fair; Washington 61 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 39 fair; Chicago 62 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
73 fair; Denver 59 fair; Des Moines 61 fair; Indianapolis 68 fair;
Kansas City 59 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 49 cloudy; Nashville 68
partly cloudy; New Orleans 71 fair; St. Louis 66 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 windy; Anchorage 44 cloudy; Las Vegas 81
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 61 hazy; Phoenix 88 fair; Salt Lake City
63 fair; San Diego 61 foggy; San Francisco 57 cloudy; Seattle 52
rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 59 cloudy; Toronto 57 foggy.
</TEXT>
