<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand     05-16 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Uncertainty In Thailand As Leader Leaves For Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda left
today for a visit to the Soviet Union, and a top aide said he would
ask Moscow to pressure Vietnam to end its occupation of Cambodia.
   Prem's two-week trip, which also included stops in Finland and
Hungary, comes during deep domestic political uncertainty resulting
from his decision to dissolve the legislature on April 29 and set
new elections for July 24.
   Prem said he acted because dissident legislators in the main
party of his coalition government voted against a government-backed
bill to protect copyrights. But the opposition charged that Prem's
move was designed to avoid a no-confidence motion that had been
scheduled for May 9.
   Dissolution of parliament automatically nullified censure motion.
   The elections are expected to result in a substantial
realignment of the political parties, and it is uncertain if Prem,
a former army commander who has been in office since 1980, will be
returned to power.
   Bangkok newspapers today gave front-page display to army Chief
Gen. Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's assertion on Sunday that while the
military was strong enough to do so, there would be no coup attempt
in Prem's absence.
   But Chavalit is regarded as a Prem supporter and such talk in
the Thai media often has proven to be bluster.
   There have been 15 successful and aborted coups and 14 general
elections since 1932 when Thailand converted to constitutional
monarchy.
   The Nation newspaper said today that Prem was seen off at the
airport by top military officers, including Chavalit, and
government officials who assured reporters everything would go
smoothly during Prem's absence.
   Prem is expected to make his appeal on Cambodia in talks with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov,
said Prasong Soonsiri, secretary-general in Prem's office.
   ``Our standpoints on the Cambodian issue still differ greatly
and the talks are aimed at narrowing and resolving those
differences,'' said Prasong, who accompanied Prem on the trip.
   ``The Soviet Union claims Vietnam is a sovereign state and that
it cannot order that country around, such as in the case of
Cambodia,'' he said. ``But we're convinced that once Moscow stops
giving aid to Hanoi, then Vietnamese troops cannot hold on in
Cambodia.''
   The Thais also hope some progress on the issue will be made at
the forthcoming superpower summit. Vietnam has been stressing its
desire for a political settlement, and also has said it wants
progress at the summit.
   The Soviet Union is the main supplier of arms to Vietnamese
forces that invaded Cambodia nine years ago and are battling
guerrillas backed by Thailand and other countries. Cambodia is on
Thailand's eastern border, and Bangkok regards the Vietnamese
occupation as its major security threat.
   Prem's agenda in the Soviet Union includes giving a speech at
the Moscow State Institute of International Relations and visits to
Kiev and Leningrad.
   He goes to Finland on May 23 and is to hold talks on trade with
President Mauno Koivisto and Prime Minister Harri Holkeri.
   Prem concludes his tour with a May 25-28 visit to Hungary at the
invitation of Prime Minister Karoly Grosz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
