<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-16 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against most major foreign
currencies, including the strong British pound, in quiet European
trading today. Gold prices also rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar was supported by market
expectations that the U.S. trade deficit narrowed in March from
February's $13.8 billion. The March trade figures are scheduled to
be released in Washington on Tuesday.
   Dealers said the pound continues to draw strength from an
apparent dispute within the British Cabinet. One British pound cost
1.8905 dollars in London at midmorning today, slightly cheaper for
buyers than late Friday's 1.8910.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, an advocate of free market
policies, opposes sustained central bank intervention to stem the
pound's rise because she believes it could be inflationary. She has
stated repeatedly that controlling inflation is her primary
economic aim.
   Her top Treasury official, Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson, favors market intervention to prevent further rises in the
pound which could hurt British exports and corporate profits.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.03 yen to a closing 124.73. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 124.78 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   --1.6857 West German marks, up from 1.6830
   --1.4010 Swiss francs, up from 1.4000
   --5.7205 French francs, up from 5.7063
   --1.8905 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8855
   --1,254.10 Italian lire, up from 1,249.00
   --1.2317 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2336
   Gold also firmed in moderate European trading. Bullion dealers
said there was no market-affecting news, but there was some strong
buying from commission houses and by investors.
   At midmorning, London's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $453.40 a troy ounce, up from the opening bid
of $452.50 and from late Friday's 449.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $453.50, up from $450.00 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.39 to close at a bid $455.24.
   Silver was quoted in London Monday at a bid $6.65 dollars a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $6.52.
</TEXT>
