<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Shaplen 1stLd-Writethru a0516 05-16 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Shaplen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer For The New Yorker Magazine Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `The Princeton ...,' to give full name of
hospital. Picks up 4th graf, `Family members ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Shaplen, a correspondent and staff writer
for The New Yorker magazine who became an expert on Asia in a
career that spanned five decades, has died. He was 71.
   Shaplen died Sunday weeks after returning from Southeast Asia.
   The Princeton, N.J., resident became ill on the trip and entered
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center three weeks ago for treatment of
thyroid cancer.
   Family members said the cause of death was not immediately
determined.
   Shaplen was treated for another cancer several years ago.
   Shaplen, born in Philadelphia, reported for The New York Herald
Tribune and was an Asia correspondent for Newsweek, Fortune and
Collier's magazines before joining The New Yorker, where he worked
for 36 years starting in 1952.
   He wrote 10 books, including one novel and a volume of short
stories, most of them about Asia.
   Highlights of his career included going ashore with the Marine
on Leyte in the Philippines in 1944 despite machine gun and mortar
fire, flying over Nagasaki hours after it was devastated by the
atomic bomb in August 1945 and writing strategic and battlefield
pieces from Korea and Vietnam in the 1960s.
   His last book, ``Bitter Victory,'' published by Harper & Row in
1986, stemmed from his 1984 trip to Vietnam and Cambodia.
   Robert Gottlieb, the editor of The New Yorker, said Shaplen had
recently returned from a tour of Vietnam, Korea and Hong Kong and
had planned to write several articles. His article based on a trip
to China last year is scheduled for publication this summer in the
magazine.
   ``He was a major figure at The New Yorker for three and a half
decades,'' Gottlieb said. ``He had a fierce attachment to the
magazine and the magazine had a fierce attachment to him.''
   He is survived by his wife, the former Jayjia Hsia; two sons,
Peter, of San Francisco, and Jason, of Princeton, and a daughter,
Kate, of Minneapolis.
   The family said the funeral would be private and that a memorial
service would be held later.
</TEXT>
