<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Stock     05-16 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Stock,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Gives Membership Cards To 16 Foreign Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange today gave official
certificates of membership to 16 foreign security firms, including
six from the United States.
   The move came one week before the companies are authorized to
begin trading in one of the world's largest stock markets, said an
exchange official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Michio Takeuchi, exchange chairman, gave the certificates to
members of the foreign firms and six Japanese trading houses,
completing a process that will increase the exchange membership
from 92 to 114 on May 23.
   There are currently six foreign members of the Tokyo exchange.
They joined in 1986 when Japan yielded to pressure from the United
States and Britain to open its doors to foreign traders.
   Last December, the exchange said 16 foreign firms were among the
22 traders selected from 40 applicants seeking seats on the
exchange. Entry of the new members was timed with the completion in
May of stock exchange building renovations and upgrading of the
exchange's computer system.
   The new foreign members, who paid $9.1 million to join the
exchange, include six from the United States, four from Britain and
two each from France, Switzerland and West Germany.
   The official who spoke privately said the six American firms are
First Boston (Japan) Ltd.; Kidder, Peabody International
Corporation; Prudential-Bache Securities (Japan) Ltd.; Shearson
Lehman Hutton Asia, Inc.; Salomon Brothers Asia, Ltd., and Smith
Barney, Harris Upham International Inc.
   He said the four British firms are Baring Securities (Japan)
Ltd.; County NatWest Securities Japan Ltd.; Kleinwort Benson
International Inc.; and Schroder Securities (Japan) Ltd.
   The remaining firms are DB Capital Markets (Asia) Ltd. and
Dresdner-ABD Securities Ltd., both of West Germany; Sogen
Securities (North Pacific) Ltd. and W.I. Carr (Overseas) Ltd., both
of France; and SBCI Securities (Asia) Ltd., and UBS Phillips and
Drew International Ltd., both of Switzerland, the official said.
   Nine foreign security firms will actually begin trading May 23,
the exchange official said.
   ``The others are still in the process of preparing (personnel)
to begin trading on the exchange, and will be coming in gradually
from June on,'' the official said.
   All of the American firms except Prudential-Bache will begin
trading next week as will Kleinwort Benson, County NatWest, W.I.
Carr and SBCI Securities.
</TEXT>
