<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CohoesFire     05-16 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cohoes Fire,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three City Blocks Evacuated by Fire that Sweeps Through 12
Buildings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COHOES, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire swept through 10 homes and two
businesses, forcing up to 100 people out of their homes and sending
flames 80 feet into the air before hundreds of firefighters
contained it early today.
   Several firefighters suffered minor injuries, but residents of a
three-block area in this small community just north of Albany
escaped unharmed, said Colonie Fire Department Deputy Coordinator
Bob Winn.
   The blaze left 50 to 100 people homeless, the Red Cross
estimated. Most of the burned houses were two- or three-family
homes, said police Lt. George Donahue.
   ``I got nothing _ just a pair of shoes,'' said an elderly man
who refused to give his name. He said his apartment building was
reduced to rubble.
   The fire started shortly after 9:30 p.m. Sunday in a six-family
brick duplex in the densely packed downtown area and quickly
spread, said Cohoes Fire Chief Ray LaMora.
   The fire, which destroyed a carpet store and a pharmacy, was
contained by the 500 to 600 firefighters shortly before 1 a.m.,
LaMora said.
   The flames lit up the sky with an orange glow visible at least
three miles away. Heavy smoke filled the air, forcing residents and
firefighters to breathe through handkerchiefs. Hundreds of people
watched the blaze.
   ``I was in London during World War II during the Blitz,'' said
Lilian Foy, who lives four blocks from the area. ``London was
burning. I have not seen anything similar to that until now.''
   Some firefighters stayed on today to hose down the rubble;
police guarded empty homes.
   Roger Hordines, who lives half a block and across the street
from where the fire was stopped, said he watered down his roof with
a garden hose and ordered his wife to take everything from the
family's safe to a friend's house a few blocks away.
   His neighbor, Jim Streicher, said he became separated from his
8-year-old son in the confusion when police ordered him to leave
his home half a block from the fire. He said he found his son with
a family friend.
   ``I do feel lucky,'' Streicher said. ``I know my kid is safe and
my house is safe. My buddy owned the carpet store and he's hurting
pretty bad.''
   A church and a Salvation Army office were set up as emergency
shelters for the homeless, but most stayed with friends or
relatives, said Marion Longcoy of the Salvation Army.
</TEXT>
