<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AirportBattle 1stLd-Writethru a0495 05-16 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airport Battle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters To Decide New Airport For Denver</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with 1 graf to clarify location of proposed
airport site.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to build a $3 billion replacement for
Denver's crowded Stapleton International Airport will be decided by
voters in a special election Tuesday, with backers heavily
outspending opponents.
   The specific issue to be decided by Adams County voters is
whether to allow Denver to annex an unincorporated 45-square-mile
site in the county 10 miles northeast of Stapleton.
   The airport is the first major one planned in the United States
since Dallas-Fort Worth opened in 1974. It would replace Stapleton,
the world's fifth-busiest airport, and could become the nation's
second busiest airport by the year 2000, based on Federal Aviation
Administration predictions.
   The FAA supports the new airport because Stapleton is congested
and is predicted to lead the nation in flight delays by 1996.
   Denver's budget for buying land and building the first phase of
the airport by 1995 is $1.6 billion. Officials estimate a total $3
billion will be spent to complete the project by 2020.
   Proponents say the airport would boost Colorado's ailing economy
by providing jobs and development. The industrial and commercial
development would mean property tax relief for homeowners,
supporters say.
   Opponents contend jet noise generated by the airport would be
unbearable for homeowners, and say closing Stapleton would be a
waste of money. They also say foul air and thundering jets could
destroy the nearby 2,700-acre Barr Lake State Park bird refuge.
   The biggest push for the site east of the Rocky Mountain
Arsenal, which is adjacent to Stapleton, has been by the Adams
County Partners In Progress. The group has spent more than $825,000
in its attempt to persuade the 115,000 registered voters to approve
the annexation. The group has the support of major business, labor
and government leaders.
   Most of the opposition has come from neighborhood groups.
Ordinary People for a Better Adams County has led the effort,
spending $48,600, according to campaign financial reports filed
with the county clerk's office.
   The Committee for a Better Airport, another group opposing the
proposal, has spent $8,000 and may spend $2,000 more before
Tuesday, said spokesman Reuben Espinosa.
   Proponents point to a study that predicts a new airport would
generate 54,000 jobs by 2010.
   Armed with this projection, Gov. Roy Romer has staged his own
campaign. In the past few months, Romer has shared breakfast at
restaurants around the county with potential voters.
   ``They're looking for somebody to believe,'' said Romer. ``The
thing I've added is to help them believe somebody. I have
credibility.''
   The anti-airport side, meanwhile, picked up support recently
when major hotels near Stapleton criticized the plan. They called
it unnecessary and a waste of billions of dollars already invested
at Stapleton.
   The airlines joined the squabble early, questioning the
timetable that proposes an opening by 1995. United Airlines and
Continental Airlines, Denver's two largest carriers, say the new
airport is not needed until later in the 1990s, at the earliest.
   They also have issued minor objections, such as not being
consulted about runway configuration, and accused Mayor Federico
Pena of pushing the project to create jobs, not because the
airlines need it.
   As a result of negotiations with county officials, the proposed
site was moved three times, each time farther from Denver. The
current site is 18 miles from downtown, compared with Stapleton's
seven miles.
   ``That's why I felt it is important for Denver to have a direct
link, why annexation is so important to me,'' Pena said.
   Both sides say voter turnout will be the deciding factor.
   ``We think it's going to be tight,'' said Bill Kenyon,
communications director for Partners in Progress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
