<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea 2ndLd-Writethru a0508 05-16 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Clash With Police After Student's Public Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf ``Cho, who had...'' with one graf to clarify
that Cho wanted North Korea's demands met concerning Olympics.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of charging students hurled
firebombs and rocks at riot police today after a student committed
ritual suicide to demand the release of all political prisoners.
   Fighting occurred at Korea and Sungkyunkwan universities in
different parts of Seoul after police fired tear gas to stop 1,200
students marching into the streets to honor the death of Cho
Sung-man, 24.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship,'' students screamed as
they pelted riot police with firebombs that exploded in sheets of
flaming gasoline. No serious injuries were reported.
   At least 3,000 students and dissidents staged peaceful protests
at other colleges and at Myongdong Cathedral, where Cho stabbed
himself in the stomach Sunday before jumping from the top of a
three-story building.
   Hundreds of mourners, some of them weeping, lit incense or left
white and yellow flowers at a makeshift altar outside the
cathedral. Students marched around the cathedral compound shouting
slogans and speakers urged passersby to fight the government.
   ``Free all prisoners of conscience immediately,'' the protesters
shouted.
   Cho, who shouted anti-government slogans before leaping, left a
note calling for reunification of North Korea and South Korea and
saying that the south was not a democracy. He demanded the release
of all political prisoners.
   ``As a human being born in this barren land, the Korean
peninsula, I offer this letter ernestly desiring to see the
unification of the fatherland,'' the note said.
   Cho, who had a long history of involvement in anti-government
protests and who attended Seoul National University, urged the
South Korean government to make concessions to persuade North Korea
to take part in the Olympic Games in Seoul in September. He also
compared his anguish over the division of Korea to the suffering
and death of Jesus Christ.
   Ritual political suicide is a form of protest sometimes used in
Korea in an attempt to shame the government and draw attention to
radical causes. A number of students have killed themselves in
public protests in recent years.
   Plans were being prepared for a ``democratic peoples' funeral''
to bury Cho later in the week. More protests are expected during
the week.
   The death came three days before the May 18 anniversary of the
1980 anti-government uprising in the southern city of Kwangju in
which about 200 people were killed. The anniversary is invariably
marked by anti-government protests.
   Opposition leaders expressed regret over the death and demanded
the government free all political prisoners. The government
contends only political opponents guilty of sedition or serious
crimes remain in prison after an amnesty earlier this year.
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam, who visited the morgue where
Cho's body was being held, said the death represented ``the voice
of the entire Korean people.''
   Korean newspapers reported today that the government was
considering freeing more political prisoners. But a government
spokesman said no decision had been made.
   Radical students have been calling for the reunification of the
two Koreas, divided since 1945. The two nations are bitter rivals
that have clashed repeatedly over the years.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympic Games to demand it be
allowed to co-host the Games.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DreamFulfilled     05-16 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dream Fulfilled,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leukemia Victim Taunted by Schoolmates Gets `Dream Bicycle'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLCHESTER, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``dream bicycle'' has turned out to be
the best medicine for an 8-year-old girl with leukemia who was
taunted by schoolmates.
   Embarrassed when medication caused her hair to fall out, Sarah
Lambert became withdrawn as other kids teased her, according to her
mother.
   Sarah's disease, acute lymphocytic leukemia, was diagnosed in
August 1986 and has been in remission since October 1986. But the
drugs used to treat her illness caused her hair to fall out, her
mother, Diane Lambert, said.
   ``Some of the kids were cruel. They would say things about her
hair. And when she wore a wig, some of the kids would pull it
off,'' Mrs. Lambert said.
   One of Sarah's relatives contacted the Children's Hopes and
Dreams Foundation in Dover, N.J., thinking that fulfillment of the
little girl's greatest wish would, as Mrs. Lambert put it, ``help
her open up a little bit.''
   When asked what she wanted most in life, Sarah's response was
simple: she wanted a new bicycle.
   ``Most kinds want to go to Walt Disney World or meet a
television celebrity or the president,'' said Vic Franklin,
director of the dream foundation. ``A lot of kids go hog wild. But
not Sarah.''
   Franklin determined that Sarah met the foundation's criteria for
granting dreams: she's between 3 and 17, diagnosed with a
life-threatening illness, she hasn't received a dream before and
her parents were not in a position to fulfill the dream themselves.
   Mrs. Lambert said Sarah preferred a bicycle over a trip because
she wanted something she could hold on to and remember. Besides,
her old bike was falling to pieces.
   ``We try to make the children feel special, and we told her
parents to make sure they got the best bicycle they could find for
Sarah,'' Franklin said. ``If she wanted a basket, get a basket. If
she wanted a fancy paint job, get it.'' Mrs. Lambert shopped around
until she found the perfect bike: a five-speed beauty with a
hot-pink seat-cover and basket attached to the front handlebars. It
also came with a water bottle and new lock.
   ``She hit the road immediately and rides up and down the street
behind our house,'' Mrs. Lambert said.
   Things already have changed for Sarah since the bicycle arrived.
   ``It's been real exciting for her,'' Mrs. Lambert said.
``Suddenly, she's No. 1 at school. Getting a little attention ...
has made her really proud. And all her friends are treating her
like a celebrity. She loves it.''
</TEXT>
