<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-16 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Temple Siege Enters Second Week, 13 Killed In Revenge
Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with more fighting, quotes.
PICKS up 11th graf, `A government ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces today stepped up pressure
on Sikh extremists holed up in the Golden Temple, pounding two
lookout towers with machinegun fire and incendiary bullets amid
calls for the gunmen to surrender.
   Seven Sikhs who surrendered on Sunday were brought to the
complex to appeal to comrades still inside the holy shrine, the
center of the Sikh separatist movement.
   ``The officers are good to us. None of us have been troubled.
Please come out with your hands in the air,'' Skatter Singh pleaded
over a loudspeaker set up on a rooftop.
   There was no immediate response, but sporadic shots were heard
from inside the complex.
   Singh, a member of the Kalistan Commando Force, one of several
Sikh militant groups that has offices in the temple complex, has
been in police custody since Sunday.
   Sarabjeet Singh, deputy police commissioner, said more than 50
militants remained in the walled compound on the eight day of the
siege. He said at least 40 of them were inside the gold-domed
temple's inner sanctum, the holiest part of the shrine.
   During a 2{-hour cease-fire on Sunday, 151 people surrendered,
including 18 women and eight children. Most of 125 men who
surrendered are being detained, but Punjab state police chief
K.P.S. Gill said 17 were released today.
   Meanwhile, Sikh gunmen shot and killed 13 people in four revenge
attacks elsewhere in Punjab state, United News of India reported
today.
   The extremists have killed at least 978 people in Punjab this
year in their quest for an independent homeland.
   The recent victims included seven Hindu laborers, a Sikh
sorcerer and another Sikh. The others were not identified.
   The siege at the Golden Temple was launched May 9 after
militants in the complex opened fire on security force commanders
who were inspecting the area outside the temple's 20-foot high
walls. Five officers were injured.
   Four bodies were carried out of the temple Sunday, raising to at
least 35 the number of people who have died since the siege began.
The dead included at least five non-combatants.
   Today, bricks flew off the two towers as security forces blasted
them with bullets from nearby rooftops this afternoon.
   ``I think we will be here for quite some time,'' said one
officer who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``We will have to
starve them out or think of other alternatives.''
   Food and other supplies have been cut off since the siege
started, but the militants routinely stockpile supplies in the
complex, which contains dining halls and kitchens.
   Intermittent gunfire was heard throughout the night as the Sikh
militants and the security forces traded shots.
   The firing by the radicals increased after sunrise today, and
the security forces used rocket-propelled grenades to neutralize
their positions, Gill said.
   A government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Sunday the Golden Temple's jailed head priest, Jasbir Singh Rode,
has been asked to urge the militants to surrender.
   Rode and three of the Golden Temple's four other high priests
were detained Thursday when they tried to march to the shrine.
   Among those who surrendered Sunday was Surjit Singh Penta, 24,
who was wanted by police in connection with the deaths of more than
150 people.
   Police said that when he was recognized by security officers,
Penta asked for a glass of water and swallowed a cyanide capsule.
He died at a hospital, police said.
   The government is reluctant to send troops into the 400-year-old
Golden Temple because religious Sikhs would consider such an
onslaught an intolerable desecration of their holiest shrine.
   In 1984, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi sent the army into the
temple to drive out Sikh militants. More than 1,200 people, mostly
Sikhs, died in the raid.
   Less than five months later, Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated by two
of her Sikh bodyguards. The revenge slaying set off anti-Sikh riots
in New Delhi and other cities in which at least 2,000 people died,
many of them innocent Sikhs.
   The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, say they are discriminated
against by India's Hindu majority. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
