<2ND_LINE>PM-Crime Stopper,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head Of Anti-Crime Group Nabs Two Burglary Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pistol-packing woman who heads an
anti-crime group made her second citizen's arrest in three days
while a TV crew tried to interview her about the first.
   Lillian Jackson, coordinator of March Against Crime, was being
interviewed Saturday for a TV news report in the building where she
caught the first man.
   ``We were laughing about me catching the burglar Thursday night,
and (the reporter) said, `Come on over here, Lillian, and show me
how you did it.' We went in there, and I heard noises, ran across
the room to the stairwell, and there were two more.''
   The middle-aged Miss Jackson said she pointed her .38-caliber
pistol at the two suspects, but one got away as she took them
outside for police.
   ``I had a bead on him and was going to shoot the escaping one,
or fire over his head, and the newsman said, `Don't shoot him,
Lillian, don't shoot him, Lillian, I've got him on camera,''' she
said.
   WKRG-TV cameraman Johnny Sartin captured the entire sequence on
videotape.
   A Mobile police spokesman said Darrell Lamont Clark, 26, of
Mobile was charged with third-degree burglary. The man who escaped
remained at large.
   Thursday night, Miss Jackson and other members of her group were
moving items into the building for a garage sale when she heard
someone walking upstairs, so she called police.
   ``The officers went in through the front,'' she said. ``I went
to the back with my gun. When he came out, I told him to hold it
and marched him right to the officers.''
</TEXT>
