<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ArizonaRepublicans     05-16 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arizona Republicans,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Mecham Wins Seat As Republican Delegate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Gov. Evan Mecham says he doesn't
think his election as an Arizona delegate to the Republican
National Convention is a litmus test of his strength in the party.
   ``This was not a referendum on me,'' Mecham said after
Saturday's state convention vote. ``I am a unity candidate. I'm
trying to keep the party together.''
   Many Republicans hoped Mecham would fade from the political
scene after they voted to remove him at his impeachment trial last
month. But at the state convention, the former governor, who failed
to be picked from his own congressional district, ran successfully
as an at-large delegate.
   He was not claimed by any presidential candidate.
   ``Hurrah,'' Mecham said when told of the results by reporters
minutes before they were announced to the convention. ``Well, for
not being on a slate, that's not too bad.'' Mecham came in 17th in
the secret balloting for 18 at-large seats.
   His supporters burst into cheers, applause and chants of ``We
want Ev!'' when Mecham's name was announced.
   All 33 delegates elected said they will support Vice President
George Bush at the national convention in New Orleans, even though
three delegates were elected from a ``conservative unity'' slate
put together by the presidential campaign of Pat Robertson. The
former television evangelist is formally leaving the race today.
   Mecham's stormy, 15-month governorship tore the state GOP apart,
and former Sen. Barry Goldwater, in a keynote address greeted by
several standing ovations, urged Republicans to try to ``heal the
wounds.''
   ``I've heard and I've read of people who want to seek vengeance
upon those who ... failed to support our former governor in his
hours of trauma,'' Goldwater said. ``I hope that doesn't happen,
because if it does, I can stand here and tell you that it will mark
the end of the Republican Party in Arizona for many, many years.''
   Goldwater had backed Mecham during the 1986 campaign but later
became one of his harshest critics.
   Mecham, who was removed as governor by a Senate court of
impeachment, is facing criminal charges in a trial due to start
Thursday. He is accused of failing to properly report a $350,000
campaign loan.
   If Mecham is convicted of a felony by the start of the national
convention, it would be up to the national party's rules committee
to decide whether he would be allowed to participate, according to
Joe Abate, the state party's legal counsel.
   U.S. Sen. John McCain had said before the state meeting that he
would be ``inclined not to attend'' the national convention if
Mecham was a delegate.
   On Saturday, however, McCain placed 10th in the at-large
balloting with 296 votes to Mecham's 271 and said he had decided to
attend no matter what.
   ``Amazing,'' he said of the vote. ``I respect the decision of
the convention. I have no other comment about it.''
</TEXT>
