<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bloody Week of Gang Killings Pushes 1987 Death Toll To 123</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increased police presence in gang-infested
neighborhoods failed to curb weekend street attacks as five people
died and at least 10 others were wounded.
   The bloodshed pushed the week's countywide gang-related death
toll to 10, and increased the 1988 total to 123.
   The violence came despite a sweep by a 200-officer anti-gang
task force that counted 125 gang arrests during the weekend.
   In one killing, the mother of a gang member was booked for
investigation of murder after admitting she stabbed her son to
death in an argument over his refusal to pay back a Mother's Day
loan.
   Sammie McGee, 37, told police she killed her son, Bluefus Davis,
18, Saturday night after he said his gang status gave him the right
to welsh on the debt, said police Sgt. Jon Rygh.
   Meanwhile, services were held for a 13-year-old girl whose
killing May 9 began the heavy week of gang violence.
   About 200 people attended the service Saturday for Jamee Finney,
who was gunned down with friend Latonjyia Stover, 18, as the pair
returned from a fast-food restaurant.
   Authorities say gang members who were cheated in a drug deal
shot the two in their car, thinking that one was the sister of the
dealer who sold them two pounds of flour instead of cocaine for
$14,000. Five people were arrested in the slayings.
   Among the other victims of gang-related violence were a
20-year-old man who died Sunday after being stabbed by an alleged
gang member at a high school carnival two days earlier; a
23-year-old man shot dead outside a party early Sunday; a
25-year-old alleged gang leader who was killed Friday night after
an argument with three men believed to be gang rivals; and a
28-year-old man who was fatally gunned down early Saturday as he
fled pursuing gang members at a gas station, police said.
</TEXT>
