<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0446 05-16 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Desk: First 8 grafs new, picking up 4th graf pvs, Peres also</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres opened
talks today with Secretary of State George P. Shultz on the stalled
U.S. plan for Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   Peres, who arrived Sunday night, had breakfast with Shultz at
his home in a Washington suburb. On a busy day, he was scheduled to
see Shultz, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and Howard H. Baker
Jr., the White House chief of staff, at a luncheon hosted by
Israeli Ambassador Moshe Arad.
   A meeting on Capitol Hill with key members of Congress and then
a speech to the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, the
principal pro-Israeli lobbying group, follow.
   On Tuesday, Peres has a formal session with Shultz and then
calls on President Reagan at the White House.
   Israeli officials in Washington noted that Shultz met lest week
in Geneva with Sovier Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``He may have something from the Soviets on the Mideast peace
process,'' said one Israeli official who asked not to be identified.
   But Shultz told reporters traveling with him last week that he
discerned no major change in the Soviets' position.
   They want to play an influential role in the negotiations.
Shultz and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir are against the
idea.
   Peres also met in recent days with Soviet officials while
attending a conference of the Socialist International in Madrid,
the official said.
   Also on the agenda for Peres and Shultz was discussion of
Shultz's June 3 trip to the Middle East intended to breathe life
into his plan for Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   However, the Israelis ``are not expecting any great
breakthroughs in his talks here,'' which include a 30-minute White
House meeting on Tuesday, said the official.
   A major obstacle to the Shultz plan is its rejection by Peres'
rival, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. Shamir objects to the role
the plan gives the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council as overseers of the talks. The five are the United States,
Soviet Union, China, England and France.
   The plan calls for an international conference to launch direct
Israeli-Arab talks on self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinians in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. It envisions that
talks on the permanent fate of the territories Israel captured from
Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Mideast war would begin six months
later.
   The Soviet role in Arab-Israeli peace talks is a thorny issue
for both Israel and the United States.
   While the Arabs want Soviet participation as part of an
international peace conference, both the Israelis and the Americans
are reluctant to allow the Kremlin too much say in the process.
   Both countries have expressed willingness to let the Soviets
participate if the Kremlin renews the diplomatic links it severed
with Israel in 1967 and allows more Jews to emigrate from the
Soviet Union.
   The Soviets have in recent months increased their emigration
levels and held low-level consular talks with Israel.
   Peres is also visiting several other major American and Canadian
cities on a lecture tour and fund-raising drive.
</TEXT>
