<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0536 05-16 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0536,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Army Kills Two Arab Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, `Today's death ...,' to
UPDATE with reports on beatings. PICKS up 6th graf, `One of ...'
EDITS to tighten. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers today killed two Arab youths
and wounded nine other protesters in clashes throughout the
occupied territories as the Moslem holy month of Ramadan drew to a
close, officials said.
   Besides the Arabs who were shot, eight demonstrators in the Gaza
Strip were treated for injuries from beatings or rubber bullets,
according to Arab sources.
   Most of the protests erupted during marches in which
Palestinians waved flags and shouted nationalistic slogans after
morning prayers at mosques for Id el Fitr, the end of a month of
fasting called Ramadan.
   PLO underground leaders of the Arab uprising have urged that Id
el Fitr be a day of ``national mourning'' for Palestinians killed
in the five-month rebellion.
   Today's deaths brought to 190 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8, according to U.N. figures. An
Israeli settler and soldier also have been killed.
   The daily newspaper Haaretz reported, meanwhile, that reserve
soldiers returning from duty in the occupied territories were
complaining that beating or humiliating Arabs was becoming routine
in the army.
   The reservists, who were not identified by name, said
humiliating tactics included stripping people naked during
questioning. Some reservists said they witnessed Arab homes being
vandalized by soldiers.
   One of today's worst clashes occurred in the Jebalya refugee
camp in Gaza where troops opened fire on marchers, killing a
17-year-old youth identified as Jiha Absi, who was shot in the
chest.
   A 10-year-old boy, Aid Hamdani, was wounded by a bullet in the
left ankle, and Rami Timraz, 13, was struck by a bullet in the left
leg, they said.
   Witnesses said Hamdani smiled and flashed a V-for-victory sign
as he was taken into the emergency room at Gaza's Ahli Arab
Hospital.
   Hospital officials said eight other protesters were beaten or
hit by rubber bullets in the camp where violence persisted
throughout the day despite a military curfew.
   The second fatality occurred in the village of Azmut near the
West Bank city of Nablus where soldiers opened fire on about 200
marchers.
   A 15-year-old boy was hit by a bullet in the chest and died
later of his wounds, and two other people also suffered bullet
wounds, Arab reports said.
   The army confirmed a fatality in the village after the clash but
said the body was being examined to determine the cause of death.
   Details on the other wounded were not immediately available.
   In incidents Sunday, five Arabs were wounded in other protests
in the towns of Kalkilye and Idna near Hebron on the West Bank, the
army said.
   Soldiers also clamped curfew restrictions on the Kalandia
refugee camp north of Jerusalem after an Israeli passenger was
injured when the car he was riding in was stoned on a main highway.
   In a leaflet issued last week by PLO underground leaders of the
uprising, the 16th since the rebellion began, organizers said the
Moslem holiday should be used to protest ``the Arab and Islamic
silence'' in response to the violence.
   The day also marked a month since the slaying of PLO Chief
Yasser Arafat's deputy Khalil Wazir, who grew up in Gaza and was
also known as Abu Jihad.
   Wazir was killed in Tunisia. Israeli sources have said Israeli
security forces were responsible. The Israeli government has not
commented.
   Also today, a left-wing legislator urged further army
investigations into findings that at least one Israeli teen-ager in
a paramilitary training course beat Arab prisoners in a West Bank
jail.
   The legislator, Yair Tsaban of the socialist Mapam party, said
the incident occurred between Feb. 7-12 when a group of teen-agers
from a high school in southern Israel was brought to a base near
the West Bank city of Ramallah.
   Tsaban said the army put a military sergeant on trial for
allegedly encouraging the beatings, but that it was unclear whether
the officer was punished.
   ``I am demanding that this investigation be completed and that
this story be taught in the schools so that it won't happen
again,'' Tsaban said.
   On Sunday, thousands of Israelis attended ceremonies marking the
21st anniversary of the capture of Jerusalem's Arab sector.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir vowed Jerusalem would remain
Israel's capital forever and said his government would never give
up the territories, occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Shamir spoke at a ceremony on Ammunition Hill, site of one of
the fiercest battles in which Israel's army seized East Jerusalem
from Jordan.
   Although Jerusalem is Israel's declared capital, few countries
recognize it as such.
</TEXT>
