<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Ireland     05-16 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ireland,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Informer Freed After Serving Six Years Of Life Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish Republican Army informer was released
from prison after serving less than six years of a life sentence
for murdering three Protestants, the Northern Ireland Office said
today.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King used his ministerial power
to free Kevin McGrady at the end of April, King's office reported.
   McGrady surrendered to police in January 1982 after becoming a
born-again Christian while hiding from police in the Netherlands.
He confessed to the 1973 murders of three Protestants and was
sentenced to life imprisonment.
   Later that year he was the key government witness in a case
involving several former associates in the outlawed IRA. Seven men
were convicted of murder and other crimes on fthe basis of
McGrady's uncorroborated testimony.
   The spokeswoman, speaking on the customary condition of
anonymity, could not give a specific reason for the early release,
but said King would have taken into account McGrady's cooperation
with the authorities.
   ``He (King) must also be satisfied that there is adequate reason
to believe the person will not commit another violent crime,'' she
said.
   Press Association, the domestic British news agency, said
McGrady has left the country. The Northern Ireland Office would not
comment on his whereabouts.
   The IRA is fighting a guerrilla war to oust the British from
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite it with the
mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
