<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Abortion     05-16 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Abortion,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling Allowing Abortions for Prison Inmates in
New Jersey Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that pregnant prison inmates have the right to free abortions if
they cannot afford them.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by
prison officials in Monmouth County, N.J., that no such right
exists if an abortion is unnecessary to preserve an inmate's life
or health.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last Nov. 25 _ in a
decision binding on all local, state and federal prisons in New
Jersey, Delaware and Pennsylvania _ that inmates have a
constitutional right to even elective, non-therapeutic abortions.
   The appeals court barred enforcement of a Monmouth County
Correctional Institution policy that required inmates to get a
court order allowing them to get a non-therapeutic abortion. The
policy also required the inmates themselves to pay for such
abortions.
   ``The challenged regulation fails to provide inmates with a
meaningful opportunity to exercise their constitutionally protected
right to choose to abort their pregnancies,'' the 3rd Circuit court
ruled.
   A 1973 Supreme Court decision legalized abortion, based on the
right of privacy. The court said women have a fundamental
constitutional right to choose to end their pregnancies.
   But the court since has ruled that the federal government and
states are not obligated to pay for even medically necessary
abortions sought by women on welfare.
   Women behind bars present a special case because the high court
has ruled that the Constitution's Eighth Amendment, banning cruel
and unusual punishment, requires prisons to provide adequate
medical care.
   In the New Jersey case, the appeals court ruled that a federal
judge was justified in ruling that the inmates ``demonstrated a
likelihood of success on their Eighth Amendment claim that denial
of abortion-related services constitutes deliberate indifference to
a serious medical need.''
   The appeals court rejected the county's argument that its
responsibility to an inmate requesting a non-therapeutic abortion
is the same as its responsibility to one who wants a facelift for
purely cosmetic reasons.
   The 3rd Circuit court stopped short of ruling that denial of
abortion funding for inmates also is unconstitutional, but it did
order Monmouth County authorities to pay.
   ``County defendants shall assume responsibility for insuring the
availability of funding for all inmate abortions. If alternative
means of funding are non-existent, the county must assume the full
cost of all inmate abortions,'' the appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, prison officials said, ``The
Eighth Amendment clearly does not protect all medical needs; the
test is one of medical necessity, not simply that which may be
considered desireable.''
   The appeal warned against ``the somewhat anomalous situation of
allowing a person who cannot otherwise obtain an elective abortion
to obtain one by virtue of being temporarily confined in the county
jail.''
   The case is Lazaro vs. Monmouth County Correctional Institution
Inmates, 87-1431.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pelton     05-16 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pelton,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Pelton Espionage Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand the
espionage conviction of a U.S. spy agency employee who sold
surveillance secrets to Soviet agents.
   The justices, without comment, turned away arguments that Ronald
W. Pelton was denied a fair trial when convicted of selling
classified information about his agency's electronic eavesdropping
programs.
   Pelton, 46, worked for the National Security Agency for 14 years
as a technician before quitting in 1979. Prosecutors said he
contacted Soviet agents shortly thereafter.
   Following a federal trial in Baltimore two years ago, Pelton was
convicted of espionage, conspiracy to commit espionage, attempted
espionage and unauthorized disclosure of classified information. He
was sentenced to three life terms plus 10 years.
   Pelton testified that the Soviets paid him more than $35,000
over a period of years. His activities were exposed by a Soviet
defector.
   His conviction was upheld by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals last Dec. 18, sparking the appeal acted on today.
   In it, Pelton's lawyers attacked the constitutionality of a 1978
federal law, the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
   The law allows government agents to obtain court warrants
authorizing wiretaps and other forms of surveillance with less
proof of suspected wrongdoing than police generally are required to
show before obtaining such warrants.
   ``It is Mr. Pelton's position that (the law) is unconstitutional
because it allows unreasonable governmental intrusion upon personal
security contrary to the proscription of the Fourth Amendment,''
his appeal said.
   The Constitution's Fourth Amendment bans unreasonable searches
and seizures.
   FBI agents secretly tape-recorded conversations between Pelton
and the Soviets with whom he was doing business.
   Although the Supreme Court has never ruled definitively on the
1978 law's constitutionality, three federal appeals courts have
upheld it.
   Pelton's appeal raised an alternate challenge to his
prosecution. It said that even if the 1978 law is valid, it should
not be allowed to authorize governmental investigations ``conducted
primarily in contemplation of criminal prosecution.''
   The appeal contended that the law was designed only to help the
government answer threats to the national security _ and not to
help prosecute those who pose such threats.
   The case is Pelton vs. U.S., 87-6433.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
