<HEAD>Court Will Review Texas Death Row Inmate's Murder Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review Texas
death row inmate Phillip Tompkins' 1981 murder conviction for
killing a woman in Houston.
   The justices said they will study arguments that Tompkins was
denied a fair trial because, among other things, prosecutors
excluded potential jurors who are black.
   Tompkins was convicted of killing Mary D. Berry, who was last
seen alive leaving her Houston job on Jan. 25, 1981. Her body was
found two days later _ bound and gagged and tied to a tree.
   Police, who said Ms. Berry was not abused in any other way,
listed suffocation as the cause of death.
   The case is Tompkins vs. Texas, 87-6405.
