<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Windfall     05-16 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Windfall,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide If New Jersey Unfairly Forcing Oil Companies to
Pay Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in an important case for
state treasuries, today agreed to decide whether New Jersey
unfairly is forcing 13 major oil companies to pay millions of
dollars in taxes.
   The court said it will review a ruling that allows New Jersey
officials to deny state tax deductions for what the companies pay
in federal windfall profits taxes.
   Lawyers for the oil industry, mining interests and natural gas
producers say the New Jersey case could have broad impact in
encouraging other states to adopt similar taxes.
   Reagan administration lawyers recommended that the high court
review the New Jersey case, stating, ``We have not ourselves come
to a conclusion on the question.''
   The oil companies, which operate numerous refineries in New
Jersey, challenged a state business tax law that disallows a
deduction for windfall profits tax payments.
   The companies said the state tax is unfair because the windfall
profits tax is based on oil production, none of which takes place
in New Jersey.
   The windfall profits tax was imposed after President Carter
announced he gradually would remove controls on domestic crude oil
prices beginning in June 1979. The price controls were put in place
by President Nixon in 1971.
   Through the windfall profits tax, the federal government seeks
to recover billions of dollars in extra profit the oil companies
realize by the jump in oil prices resulting from decontrol.
   For example, in mid-1979 the controlled price of previously
discovered oil was $5.86 a barrel and the price of newly discovered
oil was $13.06 a barrel. The uncontrolled world price then was
approaching $20 a barrel, and would reach $30 a barrel before
dropping dramatically in recent years.
   The windfall profits tax is imposed on production at the
wellhead rather than on net profits or income calculated on gross
sales and net profits as measured at the pump.
   The windfall profits tax, which has produced more than $78
billion in federal revenue, will remain in effect until December
1990 or until it yields $227.3 billion in revenue.
   The New Jersey Supreme Court upheld the state tax last June,
saying it does not discriminate unfairly against the oil companies.
   The oil companies paid an extra $88.5 million in taxes to New
Jersey from 1980 through 1984 because they were not allowed to
deduct the windfall profits taxes.
   The companies said six other states also disallow income tax
deductions for windfall profits taxes. They are Georgia, Iowa,
Minnesota, New York, South Carolina and Wisconsin.
   The tax challenge was mounted by Amerada Hess, Atlantic
Richfield, Conoco, Cities Service, Exxon, Phillips Petroleum,
Chevron, Mobil Oil, Union Oil of California, Gulf Oil, Shell Oil,
Tenneco Oil and Texaco.
   The cases are Amerada Hess vs. Division of Taxation, 87-453, and
Texaco vs. Division of Taxation, 87-464.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Scientology     05-16 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Scientology,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reaffirms Denial of Tax Exemption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand rulings that
denied the Church of Scientology of California federal tax-exempt
status for three years.
   The court, without comment, turned away arguments that, among
other things, stripping the church of its tax exemption for the
years 1970-72 ``threatens the rights of all churches to proselytize
through the sale of religious literature.''
   The religion of Scientology was founded by L. Ron Hubbard, who
died in 1986.
   Scientologists believe they can progress toward spiritual
awareness through private sessions in which members' skin responses
to questions are monitored by an electronic device called an
E-meter, which Hubbard invented.
   Hubbard's collective writings comprise the religion's scriptures.
   For the tax years at issue in this case, the Church of
Scientology of California was the ``Mother Church'' of all
Scientology churches in the United States.
   The Internal Revenue Service in 1957 officially recognized the
Church of Scientology of California as a tax-exempt religious
organization, but revoked that exemption in 1967.
   In 1977, the IRS told the church it owed $1.43 million in taxes
and late-filing penalties for the years 1970, 1971 and 1972.
   The church sued the IRS in U.S. Tax Court, which upheld the IRS
tax assessment.
   The tax court ruled that, under the Internal Revenue Code, the
church was not entitled to tax-exempt status for the three years at
issue because some of the church's revenues ``inured to the benefit
of'' Hubbard and his wife, Susan.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that ruling last
July 28.
   ``The cumulative effect of Hubbard's use of the church to
promote royalty income (through sale of copyright materials),
Hubbard's unfettered control over millions of dollars of church
assets, and his receipt of untold thousands of dollars worth of
`debt repayments' strongly demonstrate inurement,'' the appeals
court said.
   The federal tax code gives tax-exempt status to religious or
charitable organizations if ``no part of the net earnings of which
inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.''
   Payment of reasonable salaries to church officials doe not
amount to inurement.
   In the appeal acted on today, the church argued that the appeals
court ruling ``is an unconstitutional intrusion into churches'
internal affairs.''
   The case is Church of Scientology of California vs. IRS, 87-1377.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pilot     05-16 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pilot,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Reinstatement of Fired Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand an
arbitrator's reinstatement of an airline pilot fired for allegedly
flying drunk.
   The justices, without comment, refused to use the case of former
Northwest Airlines pilot Larry W. Morrison to study the power of
federal courts to overturn labor arbitrator's awards deemed
contrary to public policy.
   In deciding a case from Louisiana last year, the court adhered
to previous rulings that limit severely such federal court power.
   The court unanimously ruled that an arbitrator's award may be
overturned on public policy grounds only when the award creates an
explicit conflict with laws or legal precedent.
   Last month, the justices backed out of reaching a ``public
policy grounds'' decision in the case of a Postal Service letter
carrier reinstated after he was fired for failing to deliver more
than 3,500 pieces of mail.
   In the pilot's case, Morrison was fired for violating his
employer's policy against drinking alcoholic beverages within 24
hours of flying.
   A Northwest pilot for 16 years, Morrison was given a blood test
more than two hours after serving as a co-pilot on a jetliner
flight carrying 79 people from Las Vegas to San Francisco on Aug.
1, 1982. His blood alcohol level was enough to create a presumption
of intoxication under California law.
   Morrison, through the Air Line Pilots Association, challenged
his ensuing dismissal. The challenge said he was fired without
``just cause'' because his misconduct was ``the unavoidable
consequence of his alcoholism.''
   Northwest allows reformed alcoholics to be pilots. But the
airline said Morrison failed to seek help until his problem had
endangered lives, and so he had to be fired.
   Morrison has since completed a treatment program successfully.
The Federal Aviation Administration has ruled him eligible to
resume piloting commercial aircraft.
   An airline arbitration board in 1984 ordered Northwest to
reinstate Morrison but U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green here
reversed that ruling in 1985.
   She said Morrison's reinstatement would be contrary to public
policy.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here reversed the trial
judge's ruling last year.
   The appeals court interpreted a key 1983 ruling by the Supreme
Court to mean that an arbitrator's award contravenes public policy
only if the award itself violates a law or compels unlawful conduct.
   In seeking Supreme Court review, Northwest lawyers said the
appeals court's ruling in Morrison's case conflicts with other
federal appeals court interpretations of the justices' 1983
decision.
   Northwest's appeal argued that the ruling in Morrison's case is
based on a ``crimped view'' of the public policy exception created
in the 1983 decision.
   The case is Northwest Airlines vs. Air Line Pilots Association,
86-1548.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
