<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Catalogs     05-16 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Catalogs,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules States May Tax Costs of Producing Catalogsin Louisiana
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States may tax the costs of producing
merchandise catalogs mailed directly to in-state residents even
when the catalogs are published in other states, the Supreme Court
ruled today.
   The court unanimously rejected a department store chain's
attempt to avoid paying taxes for catalogs received by its
Louisiana customers.
   Writing for the court, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said
Louisiana's imposition of a ``use tax'' on catalogs produced for
the New Orleans-based D.H. Holmes Co. does not interfere unduly
with interstate commerce.
   ``The Louisiana tax structure does not discriminate against
interstate commerce,'' Rehnquist wrote. ``The use tax is designed
to compensate the state for revenue lost when residents purchase
out-of-state goods for use within the state. It is equal to the
sales tax applicable to the same tangible personal property
purchased in-state.''
   The chief justice also noted that Holmes, with 13 department
stores in Louisiana, initiated the catalog deliveries to improve
its sales and name-recognition among Louisiana residents.
   He said the department store chain's ``significant presence'' in
Louisiana provided what lawyers call the required ``nexus'' _
contact with the state _ to justify the tax.
   ``There is `nexus' aplenty here,'' Rehnquist said.
   The court rejected arguments that because Holmes never actually
possessed the catalogs, it never really owned them _ and therefore
should not be subject to the tax.
   D.H. Holmes Co. also operates stores in Mississippi, Alabama and
Florida but 82 percent of its catalogs are mailed to about 400,000
Louisiana customers.
   The state tax imposed on Holmes is based on 82 percent of the
catalogs' value. The company paid more than $2 million to produce
the catalogs for three years.
   Today's decision upheld state court rulings that the tax is
valid.
   The case is D.H. Holmes Co. vs. McNamara, 87-267.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
