<HEAD>Dukakis Gains Ground as Iowa Democrats Pick Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
continued to gain steam among Iowa Democrats, winning the bulk of
delegates selected at congressional district conventions.
   Dukakis won 12 of the 34 delegates at stake over the weekend,
while backers of Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt elected nine
delegates who are technically uncommitted.
   Gephardt won the state's Feb. 8 precinct caucuses, but has since
dropped out of the race. Many of the nine uncommitted delegates are
expected to endorse Dukakis.
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' sole remaining active opponent, won
seven delegates, while Illinois Sen. Paul Simon collected six.
Simon has put his campaign on hold, but is still technically an
active candidate and eligible for delegates.
   Iowa Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder predicted Dukakis'
margin would grow during the month leading to the party's state
convention on June 25, when 18 more delegates will be selected.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Maine Dems Round Out National Delegation, But Status Uncertain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maine's Democrats have given front-runner
Michael Dukakis 11 more delegates towards the party's presidential
nomination, although a dispute remains over whether the state's
delegates will be seated at the national convention.
   The three-day state Democratic convention that ended Sunday left
nine delegates pledged to Jesse Jackson or uncommitted.
   The convention left unsettled a controversy over a difference
between state party rules with the national Democratic
delegate-selection guidelines that could prevent the Maine
delegation from taking a place at the convention in Atlanta.
   Nevertheless, party Chairman Rick Barton pronounced the event a
success.
   ``We came in as a large group of people and we left united,'' he
said.
