<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ParalyzedAmerican     05-16 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paralyzed American,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Gymnast Remains Paralyzed After Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old American who hurt her neck during a
gymnastic competition 11 days ago remains paralyzed but is
conscious, a sports official said today.
   Ryoji Itsukaichi, spokesman of the Japan Gymnastics Association,
said the condition of Julissa Gomez of Blue Springs, Mo.,
``remained almost unchanged'' since the May 5 accident.
   He said she was receiving oxygen because she has been unable to
breath regularly, and that her arms and legs are paralyzed.
   Itsukaichi quoted a doctor at the Tokyo University hospital as
saying ``it is too early to say whether she can recover from the
injuries, but since she is young, she may have a chance.''
   Miss Gomez damaged her cervical vertebrae while warming up for
the vault competition at an international gymnastics tournament
held here in conjunction with the Tokyo International Sports Fair.
   After a long runup, Miss Gomez failed to plant her feet firmly
on the springboard in front of the vault apparatus. She was
propelled into the vault head first, and carried to the other side,
where she fell on a small space of bare floor between the vault and
the mat, according to the gymnastics association.
   The technique she was attempting, in which a gymnast does a back
flip to the springboard, was introduced about 10 years ago and,
through difficult, is widely used by female gymnasts, an
association spokesman said recently.
   Last Wednesday, doctors fitted her with a tight body jacket and
inserted metal pins in the right and left sides of her skull to
secure the position of her neck.
   Itsukaichi said if her condition stabilizes, she may be flown to
the United States. But doctors say it is too dangerous to move her
now.
   The official said Miss Gomez still can not talk because of the
respirator.
   She communicates with her parents, who flew to Japan after the
accident, by blinking her eyes, Itsukaichi said.
   In this way, her parents have been able to ask her if she is in
pain or what kinds of music she wants to listen to, he said.
   Miss Gomez's grandmother and younger sister also flew to Tokyo
last week.
   According to the athletic association, Miss Gomez, named to the
U.S. junior national team in 1986, began training as a gymnast at
age 5. She became interested in gymnastics after seeing Nadia
Comeneci compete in the 1976 Olympic Games.
   Before the accident, she scored a 9.6 in the vault and was
leading her team in that event.
   A 4-foot-7-inch, 73-pound high school freshman, Miss Gomez was
born in San Antonio, Texas, and resides with her father in Blue
Springs.
</TEXT>
