<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Memorial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0582,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faith, Prayers, Counseling Will Help Families</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, `Additional
counselors...', to add quote from student at high school. Picks up
9th graf, `On Sunday...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI D. SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only instruction being given today at
Radcliff Middle School was in how to cope with grief as
schoolchildren gathered to mourn classmates killed in a fiery bus
accident.
   ``Today we've got to be more concerned with feelings than
education,'' said principal Charlie Jones as school opened.
   Saturday night's crash of a church bus, which burst into flames
after it collided with a pickup truck, killed 27 people including
16 children from the middle school listed as missing and presumed
dead.
   Additional counselors were on hand to help students face the
empty desks of classmates killed in the crash.
   ``I'm just trying to use good common sense and I'm trying to
make it an hour at a time,'' Jones said. ``It's going to be hard to
mesh this big a tragedy to meet everybody's different problems.''
   Enrollment at the school totals 775 pupils, most of whom seemed
to be present today, Jones said. He described them as ``pretty
quiet, not as much emotion as I figured.''
   The victims included 13 of Radcliff Middle School's
eight-graders, one seventh-grader and two sixth-graders. Three
other middle school pupils were hospitalized and three were at home.
   Additional counselors are also going to be available at North
Hardin High School, said Principal Ray Story. He said teachers will
be encouraged to allow the students to talk about the accident.
   ``It's silent, and that's the hardest part ...,'' said Lori
Coffey, an 18-year-old senior, after school opened at North Hardin
High. ``You walk down the hall and see the hurt, but no one is
saying anything.'' The high school lost three students in the crash.
   On Sunday evening, more than 700 friends and relatives turned
out for a subdued service at the Assembly of God Church. Some of
the 40 people injured in the crash attended the service, which
attracted a standing-room-only crowd.
   ``At an hour like this, there's not much you can say,'' said
Martha Tennison, wife of the Rev. W. Don Tennison, pastor of the
Assembly of God Church. ``You can just be there for them.
   ``Our faith in God will be just as strong or stronger than it
has ever been,'' she said after the service.
   ``Our hope in God is an anchor to the soul,'' said Dan
Mattingly, who led the evening prayers. ``We're in the midst of a
storm and we need an anchor.''
   The bus, with 67 aboard, was packed with teen-agers returning
from Kings Island amusement park north of Cincinnati. The trip was
an annual outing for the youths, who raised money for the event
through car washes and mowing lawns.
   Many friends and family members said their faith would help them
cope with their tragedy.
   ``I don't have any answers for you this morning,'' Mrs. Tennison
said during an informal service Sunday morning. ``I can't figure it
out. I wish I had the answers. I don't.''
   She said the task at hand was to gather strength to share with
the families of the dead.
   ``If there's ever been an hour when they needed us the most,
it's now. We'll be there for them,'' she said.
   One church member said the community also would band together
through its military ties. Radcliff, population 20,000, is adjacent
to Fort Knox, a military installation where many of the families
work.
   ``Our congregation is about 80 percent military families,'' Fred
Rishel said. ``We're close in the military, and we're close in the
church.''
   Condolences poured in by telephone Sunday from churches as far
away as Germany.
   A Roman Catholic priest also helped out at the evangelical
church, celebrating Mass early Sunday to help console gathering
members.
   ``The whole community is in a state of shock,'' said the priest,
the Rev. Leo Craycroft. ``We are praying for the families and doing
whatever we can to support them.''
</TEXT>
