<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal of 90-Year-Old Boston Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to help a
90-year-old Boston man who faces prison for refusing to testify
before a federal grand jury reportedly investigating organized
crime in New England.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Harry
Sagansky, who said imprisonment could kill him.
   Sagansky, twice convicted more than 20 years ago of illegal
bookmaking, was arrested last year in an FBI investigation of the
underworld organization of the late Raymond Patriarca, long-time
reputed New England crime boss.
   Sagansky was held in contempt for refusing to testify before a
grand jury after he was granted immunity from prosecution.
   He has been ordered imprisoned until he breaks his silence.
Supreme Court Justice William J. Brennan on Feb. 29 allowed
Sagansky to remain free pending review of his appeal.
   Federal prosecutors said Sagansky would be incarcerated in a
federal prison medical facility in Springfield, Mo., and said he
would be flown there accompanied by a nurse to protect his health.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected Sagansky's
arguments that putting him in prison will endanger his health and
could kill him.
   A federal court ``must have the means to enforce its lawful
order of contempt,'' the appeals court said. It added, ``We must
not lose sight of the fact that, although the witness labels it a
`cliche argument,' it is nonethless true that the witness himself
holds the key to his freedom. The government is validly seeking his
testimony, not his confinement.''
   Sagansky was imprisoned for 20 days in January after he refused
to testify, but then was released pending further appeals. He also
has said he has been the target of unlawful electronic surveillance
by the FBI.
   The case is Sagansky vs. U.S., 87-1590.
</TEXT>
