<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Jackson comments today; pick up 4th graf
pvs bgng ``We've come...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Jesse Jackson
appealed again today for fairness from the Democratic Party, saying
``fairness is a reasonable expectation.''
   Jackson has complained in recent weeks that his delegate total
is not proportional to his hard-won share of the popular vote in
primaries to date.
   ``Fairness is a reasonable expectation. Reciprocity is a
reasonable expectation. We expect to treat the party fair because
we expect to be treated fairly by the party,'' he told reporters
here.
   Asked what he would do if he did not win the nomination, Jackson
replied:
   ``We hope to have enough popular vote and delegates (for the
nomination),'' he said. ``And then we'll determine the ticket of
our party and the platform of our party and the priorities of our
party.''
   Jackson made a quick swing through New Jersey Sunday and today
before heading to Oregon for a final day of campaigning in advance
of the state's primary on Tuesday.
   On Sunday, under the massive dome of the Hopewell Baptist
Church, Jackson drew on religious themes of hope and faith as he
vowed to keep up his campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   ``We've come too far to turn around now,'' he told the mostly
black crowd. ``In our own lifetime we've moved from the back of the
bus to three steps from the White House.''
   Jackson said he was the only candidate committed to sweeping
economic reforms that would benefit working people.
   ``This is not about black fish and white fish but about big fish
and little fish,'' Jackson said, to applause.
   Jackson called for raising the minimum wage, working to bring
women's wages in line with those of men, earmarking defense funds
to education instead and providing universal health insurance. He
also outlined plans for providing affordable housing and day care.
   He attacked the Reagan administration's foreign and domestic
policies, including Vice President George Bush, the apparent
Republican nominee, in each criticism.
   Jackson faulted the administration for a failed ``courtship''
with Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and for allowing
U.S. companies to move out of the country in order to pay cheaper
wages.
   Jackson appealed for votes in the New Jersey primary, which is
June 7.
   ``No valley is too deep when our minds are made up,'' he said.
``We're winning every day. That's what makes the New Jersey race so
important. It's a matter of pulling your weight in New Jersey.''
   At the state Democratic convention in South Orange, N.J.,
Jackson noted pointedly that he, unlike rival Michael Dukakis, has
garnered few big-name endorsements.
   ``I haven't inherited any voters. I've earned every vote I've
gained,'' he said.
   Dukakis also appeared at the Democratic event, and the two met
briefly.
</TEXT>
