<HEAD>Moslem Factions Trade Fire In Beirut Slums; Syrians Poised To
Intervene</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADs with 12 grafs to UPDATE with more dead, Amal
counterattack. PICKS up 11th graf, ``No gunmen ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias today
blasted each other with howitzers, mortars and rockets in the slums
of south Beirut, defying a Syrian order to cease fire.
   Police said the Syrian-backed Amal militia staged a
counterattack, forcing the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God, to retreat from one section of the 16-square mile shantytown.
   During the last 10 days of combat, Hezbollah has pushed Amal
from large parts of the slums.
   Police said 14 people were killed and 120 wounded in the
hostilities Sunday and today, raising the overall toll to 225 dead
and 706 injured since fighting for control of the slums broke out
May 6.
   Eighteen Western hostages, including nine Americans, are
believed held in the slums by factions linked to the Hezbollah.
   Police said Syrian commanders had massed several thousand troops
and hundreds of tanks and armored vehicles around the main gateways
into the labyrinthine slums today.
   ``We're ready to go in, but zero hour hasn't been set yet,''
said a Syrian colonel commanding the main highway to the airport,
which was proclaimed reopened to normal traffic today for the first
time in 11 days.
   On Sunday, Syria's military intelligence chief in Lebanon, Brig.
Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, ordered Hezbollah and Amal to lay down their
arms.
   ``Our forces will shoot without hesitation any gunman on the
street and in buildings. Your lives will be spared if you comply,''
he said.
   ``It was imperative for Syria to take the decision to rescue the
people from the bloodbath,'' he told a news conference.
   Before the Amal counterattack, police said Hezbollah had seized
control of 90 percent of the slums. Hezbollah only held about
one-third of the 16 square-mile area on May 6. It was not
immediately known if Amal secured any districts in today's
counterattack.
   Radio stations reported that Amal's leader, Justice Minister
Nabih Berri, had decided to withdraw his militiamen.
   ``No gunmen should be allowed to remain in the suburbs and
Beirut, now that a legitimate force is taking charge of security,''
Berri was quoted as saying in a reference to the Syrian army.
   Hezbollah, which has fielded 3,000 fighters, has not responded
to the Syrian plan. But the fundamentalists' spiritual leader,
Sheik Mohammad Hussein Fadlallah, on Sunday called the Syrian
buildup ``an act of intimidation.''
   He said ``all the suburbs will be destroyed if the Syrians
attempt to enter by force,'' indicating that Hezbollah would resist
the Syrians.
   Kenaan cut off a reporter who asked whether the Syrians would
seek to free the foreign hostages. ``There is a disaster in the
area. People are suffering distress that we will try to end,'' he
said.
   The Christian-run Voice of Lebanon radio said, without naming a
source, that the hostages are now held in the basement of the
Iranian Embassy in a seaside neighborhood outside the battle zone.
   ``This report is untrue,'' an embassy spokesman said. He
declined to be named.
   The weekly Ash-Shiraa magazine reported earlier that the
captives were moved during the fighting from an exposed Hezbollah
barracks to the home of Hezbollah spokesman Sheik Ibrahim Amin in
the less vulnerable Haret Hreik neighborhood. The report could not
be verified.
   Police said most of the 250,000 people who lived in the slums,
mostly poor Shiites, have fled since the fighting erupted.
</TEXT>
