<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene     05-16 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene,0860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Peanut Production not Peanuts, While US Is Soypreme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soybean has an Asian-sounding name, with
its origins rooted in long-ago China. And the peanut has a real
American punch to its name, raising images of baseball parks and
street vendors.
   But the United States is the leading soybean producer, while
China is a distant third behind Brazil.
   China, meanwhile, is the biggest peanut producer, with India
second and the United States third, according to Agriculture
Department analysts.
   In all, global production of oilseeds in 1987-88 is expected to
be a record 203.7 million metric tons, up 5 percent from last
season, says the department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
Projections indicate output may rise further in 1988-89.
   Based upon various USDA reports issued last week, including the
May 10 supply-and-demand projections for 1988 harvests, the United
States will continue to hold a comfortable lead in soybean
production.
   Of the 203.7 million tons of oilseeds produced in the world,
soybeans will comprise 101.1 million tons, or almost half the
global harvest. The U.S. soybean share is more than 51.8 million
tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of soybeans.
   Brazil, the leading soybean competitor for American farmers, is
expected to provide 17.6 million tons. China's harvest was
estimated at about 12.1 million tons, with Argentina next at 9
million tons.
   Globally, cottonseed is the second-rated oilseed at almost 30.7
million tons of production in 1987-88.
   China is the cottonseed leader at 7.1 million tons, followed by
the United States, 5.23 million, and the Soviet Union, 4.49 million.
   Several of the remaining major oilseeds _ peanuts, sunflowerseed
and rapeseed _ are fairly close in production totals, ranging from
19 million to 23 million tons.
   Peanut production in 1987-88 is estimated at 19.3 million tons.
China leads with 6.17 million tons, followed by India at 4.35
million, and the United States a distant third with 1.64 million
tons.
   In listing the remainder of the major oilseeds, country rankings
get a bit blurred because some of the USDA figures are reported
regionally instead of by individual countries.
   For example, the top producer of rapeseed clearly is China, with
production reported at 6.73 million tons. But the second-ranked
producer is the 12-nation trading bloc of the European Economic
Community, or EEC, shown at 5.92 million tons. Canada, with 3.85
million tons, is third. Global rapeseed production was put at 22.9
million tons.
   A similar situation was shown for sunflowerseed. The Soviet
Union is easily the world's leading producer with 6.08 million tons
in 1987-88, while once again the EEC comes in second with 3.73
million. Argentina was third with 2.8 million tons forecast. World
output was reported at 20.3 million tons.
   The United States did not appear at all in the rapeseed
production figures, and was listed at 1.18 million tons of
sunflowerseed in 1987-88.
   Another oil source is flaxseed, with a world output of 2.34
million tons this season. Canada leads with 790,000 tons, followed
by Argentina, 550,000, and India, 400,000. The U.S. production was
reported at 190,000 tons.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. cotton inventories could show a modest
rise in the 1988-89 marketing year if Agriculture Department
projectons hold up.
   Although the department's first official estimate of 1988 cotton
production won't be ready until August, analysts say the harvest
could be around 14 million bales, down from almost 14.8 million
bales in 1987.
   With a modest decline in exports expected in the marketing year
that will begin on Aug. 1 _ probably dropping to 6 million bales
from 6.6 million this season _ and a drop in demand by domestic
textile mills, total U.S. cotton use is expected to decline by
about 1 million bales in 1988-89.
   Thus, despite the projected smaller harvest, the U.S. cotton
inventory by Aug. 1, 1989, could grow to 6.2 million bales from 5.5
million forecast as the carryover this Aug. 1.
   Globally, the same thing is happening. Department projections
put the world's cotton production in 1988-89 at 83.5 million bales
and total consumption at 82 million bales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong's brandy imports jumped 47 percent
last year and lower import duties which became effective in March
are expected to add further momentum, according to an Agriculture
Department trade report.
   The department's Foreign Agricultural Service said the rise in
Hong Kong's brandy imports could lead to further sales
opportunities for U.S. suppliers.
   France is the main supplier, providing 95 percent of last year's
imports of 8.43 million liters, the agency said in Foreign
Agriculture magazine. China was second, with 206,220 liters,
followed by South Africa, 53,591; Greece 52,957; and the United
States, 26,504.
   A liter is slightly more than a quart.
   The report said the Hong Kong import duty was reduced to $55 in
Hong Kong currency per liter from $67 prior to March 2, 1988.
Officials said one U.S. dollar was equal to 7.8 Hong Kong dollars.
</TEXT>
