<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-BackPay     05-16 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Back Pay,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Seven Pennsylvania Mechanics Entitled to Two Years
Back Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that seven
mechanics at a Wolmelsdorf, Pa., factory are entitled to two years,
not three, back overtime pay.
   The court's 6-3 decision resolves conflicting lower court
interpretations of a provision of the federal Fair Labor Standards
Act.
   The law currently sets for covered employees the minimum wage of
$3.35. It also generally requires employers to pay one and one-half
times an employee's regular rate for overtime hours _ those in
excess of 40 per week.
   The Labor Department sued the Richland Shoe Co. in 1984,
contending that it had been violating the federal labor law by not
paying overtime until a mechanic had worked at least 48 hours in
any week.
   The seven mechanics primarily were responsible for repairs and
maintenance of equipment at Richland's plant, which makes footwear
and other leather products.
   Under the federal law, a lawsuit seeking unpaid overtime
compensation is subject to a two-year statute of limitations. But a
three-year deadline is authorized for a ``willful'' violation of
the overtime-payment requirements.
   In other words, workers wrongly deprived of overtime pay may be
able to collect two years or three years worth of back overtime
payments after suing their employer.
   U.S. District Judge Daniel H. Huyett ruled that Richland's
violation of the Fair Labor Standards Act had been willful. He said
that determining willfulness ``requires nothing more than that the
employer has an awareness of the possible application'' of the
federal law.
   The New Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
previously had announced such a standard for determining
willfulness under the labor law.
   But the Philadelphia-based 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed that portion of Huyett's ruling that awarded the mechanics
three years of back overtime pay.
   The 3rd Circuit court said the Richland's violation of the law
could not be ruled willful unless it was shown that Richland knew
it was doing so or displayed a reckless disregard for whether it
was violating the law.
   That ruling seemingly meant the mechanics were entitled to two,
not three, years worth of back overtime pay.
   Writing for the high court today, Justice John Paul Stevens said
the 3rd Circuit court's interpretation of willful is the correct
one.
   ``The standard ... that the employer either knew or showed
reckless disregard for the matter of whether its conduct was
prohibited by the statute is surely a fair reading of the plain
language of the act,'' Stevens said.
   Justices Thurgood Marshall, William J. Brennan and Harry A.
Blackmun dissented. They said the 5th Circuit court's
interpretation should be adopted.
   The case is McLaughlin vs. Richland Shoe Co., 86-1520.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
