<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0575,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Finds Bodies Of Two Pilots; Tanker Still Ablaze After Larak
Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for grafs 15-16 pvs, beginning ``Air Force
Lt....'' to update with Pentagon officials saying no battle damage
seen on helicopter. Picks up 17th graf pvs ``Leslie and Hill...'' </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out today aboard one of five
tankers damaged in an Iraqi air raid on Iran's Larak Island oil
terminal.
   A Pentagon spokesman in Washington, meanwhile, said the wreckage
of a U.S. helicopter had been found along with the bodies of its
two crewmen.
   The aircraft was reported missing in the Persian Gulf after a
battle last month in which U.S. forces sank or disabled six Iranian
ships.
   Officials were still trying to determine today how many people
died in the Iraqi raid Saturday on the Larak terminal in the Strait
of Hormuz at the southern end of the gulf.
   The attack set fire to the Spanish supertanker Barcelona, the
Cypriot-flag tanker Argosy, the Liberian-flag supertanker Seawise
Giant, British tanker Burmah Endeavour, and the Iranian tanker
Khark.
   The Seawise Giant and the Argosy were badly damaged in fires
that raged out of control for many hours. The Burmah Endeavour and
the Khark sustained minor damage, officials reported.
   The Barcelona was beached to prevent it sinking. Although the
fire aboard it appeared to have been extinguished Sunday, it
reignited and Iranian-led salvage teams were fighting the flames
today, according to gulf shipping executives who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said the
bodies of 16 of the Seawise Giant's crew have been recovered, one
seaman was killed aboard the Barcelona and two crewmen were killed
aboard the Argosy. It said three crewmen remained missing from the
Barcelona.
   But gulf-based shipping executives said only one crewman aboard
the Seawise Giant was killed, with three missing, and that one man
aboard the Barcelona was killed, with three other crewmen missing.
   The Iraqi raid, the third on Larak in seven months, was aimed at
throttling Iran's economic lifeline, its oil exports, to force
Tehran to the negotiating table and end its 7{-year-old war with
Iraq.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Cyprus, on Sunday quoted a senior
Iranian air force officer as saying the U.S. Navy aided the Iraqi
warplanes attacking Larak by jamming Iranian radar and radio
communications for nine minutes.
   U.S. officials said U.S. warships patrolling the gulf were not
involved with the Larak raid.
   The bodies of the two U.S. Marine Corps pilots and the wreckage
of their helicopter were located in the southern Persian Gulf on
Sunday, the Pentagon said, nearly a month after they disappeared
during U.S.-Iranian clashes.
   In Washington, Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman,
said the bodies of Capt. Kenneth Hill, 33, of Thomasville, N.C.,
and Capt. Stephen Leslie, 30, of New Bern, N.C. were recovered from
the Marine Corps AH-1 Cobra.
   Air Force Lt. Col. Charles Manicer, a spokesman for the U.S.
Central Command, said the remains of the gunship will be destroyed
in place rather than pulled out of the water. He said he did not
know when the wreckage would be blown up.
   Pentagon officials said the initial report from Navy divers in
the gulf indicated they had yet to spot any ``battle damage'' on
the wreckage of the helicopter that would prove it crashed after
being hit by gunfire or a missile.
   ``So far, there is no discernible evidence of battle damage,''
said one official, who insisted on anonymity. ``But they're still
going over it as best they can.''
   Leslie and Hill were the only American casualties in the
fighting April 18, when U.S. naval forces destroyed two Iranian oil
platforms and sank or disabled six naval craft. Iran said at the
time that its forces shot down the helicopter.
   Tehran said 44 Iranians were killed during the clash.
   The fighting began after U.S. forces earlier that day destroyed
two Iranian oil platforms in retaliation for a mine explosion in
the gulf four days before that damaged the USS Samuel Roberts and
wounded 10 sailors.
   The Navy had officially called off the search for the helicopter
and declared the men killed in action. The wreckage was located by
a chartered salvage tugboat in the general area where the clashes
occurred, salvage experts said.
</TEXT>
