<2ND_LINE>AM-Library Board,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eisenhower, Kennedy Kin Named to Presidential Library Advisory
Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grandson of one president and the daughter
of another were named Monday to a new advisory committee on
presidential libraries established by the archivist of the United
States, Dr. Don Wilson.
   The advisory committee will be a nine-member group whose job it
will be to form a closer alliance with the National Archives on
joint public programs and exhibitions. It also will work toward
increasing private support for the presidential library system,
said John Fawcett, head of presidential libraries.
   David Eisenhower, who recently wrote ``Eisenhower at War'' about
his grandfather, Dwight D. Eisenhower, is one member. Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, daughter of John F. Kennedy is another.
   They and the others will serve three-year terms. The National
Archives operates and maintains eight libraries housing the papers
of presidents Herbert Hoover, Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman,
Eisenhower, Kennedy, Lyndon Johnson, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter.
   Other members of the committee are Martin J. Allen Jr., chairman
of the Gerald R. Ford Foundation; George M. Elsey, president
emerityus of the American Red Cross; William J. vanden Heuvel,
president of the Franklin and Eleanor Institute; Tom Johnson,
publisher and chief executive officer of the Los Angeles Times;
Robert J. Lipshutz, counsel to Carter; Jeremiah Milbank, president
of the J.M. Foundation; and Frederick J. Ryan Jr., assistant to
President Reagan.
</TEXT>
