<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan-Reconstruction Bjt   05-16 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Reconstruction, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace In Afghanistan Will Require Massive Reconstruction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If peace ever returns to the mountains
and deserts of Afghanistan, the war-ravaged country will require
one of the most massive reconstruction efforts since World War II.
   The first stage will be the relocation of about 3 million Afghan
refugees from Pakistan and 2 million from Iran. Western observers
believe that 4 million more Afghans are refugees inside their own
country.
   Anthony Land, head of the Peshawar, Pakistan, office of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, said the return will be the largest
human migration in the organization's history.
   Inside Afghanistan, 10 years of civil war between the communist
government and Moslem insurgents, the last 8{ years with Soviet
military involvement, have left much of the country in ruins.
   Pakistanis, Western diplomats, guerrillas and refugees seem to
agree that even if the fighting stops in Afghanistan, the country
will never be the same.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, chairman of the seven-party guerrilla
alliance based in Pakistan, estimated that 60 percent of the houses
in Afghanistan have been destroyed, along with an equal percentage
of arable land.
   ``The whole country is in ruins,'' said the guerrilla leader.
``Canals and irrigation systems are badly damaged or destroyed.''
   Hekmatyar said the Afghans' ability to restore the irrigation
systems will be crucial to avoid mass starvation once the refugees
return.
   U.N. agencies and several countries have started making plans
for Afghanistan's reconstruction, but they say it is too early
gauge the project's exact size or expense.
   One of the first and most dangerous tasks will be clearing mines
planted or scattered across the countryside by Soviet-Afghan
aircraft.
   U.S. diplomats estimate there may be 3 million of them. The
guerrillas say the number is closer to 5.5 million.
   Then comes what officials predict will be a massive infusion of
emergency food and shelter, medical supplies, seeds and farm
implements.
   Some officials believe that fields left fallow under years of
blazing sun will be too hard to be worked by the Afghans'
traditional wooden plows.
   Few officials care to venture what all this will cost, but the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Jean-Pierre Hocke, recently
mentioned a figure of $300 million. Western diplomats in Islamabad
have guessed up to $1.5 billion dollars.
   When the refugees return is anybody's guess, but several
interviewed in the camps of Pakistan's northwest frontier province
said they won't venture back until all Soviets are gone and the
Marxist Kabul government has fallen.
   ``I will go first and see what is left of my home and my farm,''
said Isayal Ghairad, 34, who lives with his wife, two daughters and
son in the sun-baked Munda No. 6 camp, a half-hour's drive from
Peshawar.
   He said he will not send for his family until he is certain he
can feed and house them.
   U.N. and Pakistani officials agree they won't see the refugee
exodus begin until after next spring's thaw.
   A squabble has already broken out over which government the
reconstruction aid should be channeled through: the existing Kabul
regime, Islamabad, or the guerrillas, who are creating a government
of their own.
   ``Looking at Afghanistan, we see no efforts of any kind from the
other side for preparations to receive refugees,'' said a Pakistan
Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking on the usual condition that he
not be named.
   Kabul's own Foreign Ministry spokesman responded with his own
broadside broadcast by official Radio Kabul.
   ``These groundless allegations, which are being made in order to
mislead public opinion, are far from the truth and are counted as
another design for creating obstacles in the way of the return of
the refugees ... ,''the radio quoted him as saying.
   He said the measures taken were ``political, social and
economic,'' but he gave no details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
