<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PTLBuyers     05-16 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Buyers,0394</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>PTL Plan Would Sell Off Assets</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL expected to file a revised
reorganization plan in U.S. Bankruptcy Court this afternoon that
essentially puts the $200 million, 2,200-acre evangelical empire on
the auction block, officials said today.
   PTL wants to sell Heritage USA in Fort Mill, or at least enough
of it to pay off its debts, and then lease the property required to
carry on its church and network television ministries, according to
a draft of the plan.
   Several proposed buyers already have surfaced, including George
Shinn, a sports entrepreneur from Charlotte, N.C.
   Judge Rufus Reynolds ordered PTL last month to devise an orderly
plan of liquidation of its assets to pay its debts. The ministry
had failed to raise enough money to meet its operating expenses and
pay the first installment of its debt as specified under the
original reorganization plan filed in December.
   Under the revised plan, Reynolds would appoint a board of three
businessmen, possibly headed by PTL Vice President M.C. ``Red''
Benton, to preside over PTL as a self-liquidating trust, said David
West, PTL director of public relations.
   PTL's assets, including a hotel and convention center, a water
park, a residential development and about 1,700 acres of
undeveloped land a few miles south of Charlotte, are worth an
estimated $160 million to $200 million. The organization's debts
are estimated to range between $75 million and $130 million.
   Whatever money or property remained after debts were paid would
go back to the non-profit arm of the ministry, Heritage Ministries,
which would operate the church and television network, the
spokesman said.
   The Charlotte Observer reported Sunday that several groups
apparently are planning to compete with Shinn in bidding on
Heritage USA. The newspaper reported that at least one group of
creditors, dubious about Shinn's willingness to provide up-front
cash in his bid to buy PTL, is seeking a buyer more to its liking.
   Another offer is expected from a new Salt Lake City corporation,
Tango Trading Co. The company, whose principals include former PTL
Vice President Dale Hill, has announced that it will submit a bid
to buy Heritage USA.
   PTL has been in financial straits since founders Jim and Tammy
Bakker left the ministry last year amid a sex-and-money scandal.
</TEXT>
