<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Records     05-16 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Records,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Prisoners Entitled to Inspect Pre-Sentence Reports in
California Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prisoners are entitled to inspect
substantial portions of their pre-sentence investigative reports
prepared by the government, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   The 5-3 ruling in two cases from California was labeled ``a
bombshell'' by dissenters who said it may trigger a flood of new
requests for government reports under the Freedom of Information
Act (FOIA).
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote the majority opinion,
denying sweeping authority sought by the Reagan administration to
withhold pre-sentence reports from prisoners.
   Rehnquist said the government's privilege against disclosing
some confidential information does not apply with the same force
when the request for files is made by the subject of the report
rather than someone else.
   Federal laws ``speak so strongly against the existence of a
privilege on the part of the government when the request is from
the subject of the report that we think it accsed from that which may be
withheld will be
time-consuming and expensive.
   Officials also argued that giving the information to inmates
will have a chilling effect on individuals questioned by
investigators who fear their identities will be dislcosed.
   The case is U.S. vs. Julian, 86-1357.
</TEXT>
