<HEAD>Senator: Questions Will Haunt Any Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 9 grafs to UPDATE with latest Fitzwater comments on
negotiations with Noriega; Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Why does.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's chief spokesman said today
he cannot predict when U.S. discussions with Panamanian officials
might lead Manuel Antonio Noriega to give up power.
   ``I can't comment on any course of action,'' spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said, although he backed away from characterizing U.S.
discussions with Noriega as ``plea-bargaining.''
   Fitzwater said he had used the term last week, as had White
House chief of staff Howard Baker want to repeat it.
   The administration's reported willingness to drop U.S. drug
trafficking indictments in a deal to get Noriega out of power has
been widely criticized by members of Congress, U.S. att, but he did notorneys
and
law enforcement groups.
   Fitzwater said today that Reagan ``certainly is aware of'' the
criticism of proposals to dismiss indictments brought against
Noriega in Miami and Tampa, Fla., but refused to discuss the
strategy for dealing with the Panamanian strongman.
   ``We can't say what the give and take is,'' he said. ``We can't
predict time (for Noriega's departure). We can't discuss what they
are talking about, what the options are and how long it will ommittee has
``some evidence'' that
wrongdoing on the part of U.S. officials in Panama is behind the
administration's efforts to dismiss the indictments.
   But, he said, ``obviously we don't have enough that we've seen
fit to make it public or that we feel that we should talk about
publicly and I haven't for that reason.''
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., a member of the Appropriations
subcommittee on defense and foreign operations, disagreed with the
reports that Noriega had some information on U.S. wrongdoing.
   ``The fact is that that's election-year politics,'' D'Amato said
on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation.''
   President Reagan, meanwhile, was asked Sunday on his return to
the White House after a weekend at Camp David, Md., whether a deal
had been struck with Noriega. ``I can't comment,'' he said.
   Reagan administration officials have said they were ``plea
bargaining'' with the Panamanian military chief and de facto ruler
about possibly dropping the drug indictments.
   A top State Department official, Michael Kozak, has been engaged
in secret negotiations with Noriega in Panama. Administration
sources said last week that the military chief was told that if he
left Panama for a year, perhaps in August, the indictments would be
dropped.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III on Friday presented arguments
to Reagan against dismissing the charges, according to U.S.
Attorney Leon Kellner of Miami, a prosecutor who obtained one of
the indictments.
   On Sunday, Robert Merkle, another U.S. attorney who secured
indictments against Noriega, said that a deal with Noriega ``would
make it impossible for me to maintain any credibility not only in
my own community ... it will make it difficult for me to look my
own kids in the eye and tell them to `just say no' to drugs.
   ``I would probably begin to say `just say maybe' because this is
the sort of equivocation I think which is absolutely
unacceptable,'' he said.
