<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleSatellite     05-16 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Satellite,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellite For Space Shuttle Mission Delivered To NASA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $100 million communications
satellite was delivered here Monday to be readied as the cargo for
the first post-Challenger space shuttle mission.
   The Tracking and Data Relay Satellite, TDRS-3, is a twin of a
payload destroyed when Challenger exploded shortly after launch on
Jan. 28, 1986. The shuttle fleet has been grounded since the
accident, with Aug. 22 now the target date for the next flight.
   TDRS-3 arrived here by C-5 cargo plane after a flight from
California. It was built for NASA by TRW's Space and Technology
Group in Redondo Beach.
   The new satellite is to be deployed from the cargo bay of
Discovery during the first day of the upcoming shuttle mission. It
will join the partially functional TDRS-1, launched from a shuttle
in April 1983.
   The satellites, a total of six of which are being built by TRW,
provide a communications link between ground stations and the
shuttle and other satellites orbiting the Earth.
</TEXT>
