<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-16 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you think a beauty pageant for turtles and
tortoises is new, you're the slow one.
   The New York Turtle And Tortoise Society sponsored the 14th such
extravaganva Sunday as 115 reptiles bid to be chosen belle of the
shell.
   They ranged in size from less than an inch to a 30-inch leopard
tortoise. All were primped for the judges as they posed in tanks
and other containers.
   As they slithered, slid and sometimes slept, about 350 members
of the society and their guests compared their health, longevity,
uniqueness and length of time in captivity, said Jim Van Abbema,
editor of the society's monthly newsletter.
   The winner is part of a turtle species from Panama.
   ``It had been in captivity for seven years and its health, shape
and configuration was flawless,'' Van Abbema said.
   Despite the fun Sunday, Van Abbema said the society remains
primarily a conservation organization and frowns on such things as
turtle races.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laundered money has a new meaning to the
Cincinnati employees of Jacor Communications.
   They spent two days cleaning honey from money that had come from
a ``Rolling In The Dough'' promotion at WYHY-FM, a Nashville,
Tenn., radio station owned by Jacor.
   Ten people had covered themselves with honey May 3, rolled over
$100,000 spread in an empty swimming pool, and took home whatever
stuck to them.
   The winners picked up $7,644 in the stunt, said WYHY-FM General
Manager Mike Kenney. But Jacor was stuck with $92,356 in gooey $1
bills.
   When the cash was returned to a Cincinnati bank May 4, the U.S.
Treasury Department was not amused.
   Jacor was ordered to clean, press and stack the cash by 5 p.m.
May 5, or corporate officers would face felony charges for defacing
currency, said Frank Wood, the company's president and chief
operating officer.
   Employees began the round-the-clock laundering operation under
the eye of an armed private security guard.
   Bills were washed in pillowcases and tumbled dry. The wrinkled
bills were steam ironed before being returned in time to meet the
deadline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TAYLOR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To a lexicon already crowded with such
phrases as lucky duck, sitting duck, lame duck and even dead duck,
a group of Taylor residents wants to add another _ speeding duck.
   DuckFest, a day of community activities May 21, will include a
race for humans called the ``Duck Waddle,'' a duck egg relay and
other activities befitting a town where the high school sports
teams are the Fighting Ducks. But duck racing is the event that has
captured imaginations.
   The racing ducks will zip down wire-enclosed, 16-foot runways.
While the birds run, handlers are allowed to encourage them by
crawling along a ramp above the runway and making any kind of noise
they figure will motivate their racers.
   But if the verbal encouragement rolls off their birds' backs,
handlers are stuck. The rules say that once started, a duck can't
be touched.
   The Taylor competition is being patterned after the Great
American Duck Race held each year in Deming, N.M., where hundreds
of racing ducks and up to 20,000 spectators have gathered.
   Rules require that each racing duck be named. Among a long list
of suggestions: the intimidating moniker ``Winner or Dinner.''
</TEXT>
