<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DukakisNotebook     05-16 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Notebook,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Campaign Notebook: Dukakis Invokes Stars, Charisma, Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one ever accuses Michael Dukakis of being
a spellbinding campaign speaker. But every once in a while the
Democratic presidential front-runner comes up with a line that
makes ears perk up.
   Perhaps energized by a crowd of more than 2,000 people at a
weekend street market here _ his biggest crowd in some time _
Dukakis found words that managed to meld a multitude of his themes.
   In three sentences, he reminded voters of the Reagan
administration's ties to Panama's accused drug-trading Gen. Manuel
Noriega, of its reported attempt to cut a deal dropping Noriega's
federal indictment, and of Dukakis' entirely unrelated call for a
law requiring notice to workers before companies close plants. And
at the same time he took a swipe at expected Republican opponent
George Bush.
   ``I understand the vice president was in Portland,'' Dukakis
said. ``And I understand that he said he thought the president
ought to veto the new trade bill because it contains a provision
that gives American workers 60 days notice before they're thrown
out in the streets.
   ``This from an administration that's apparently prepared to give
Noriega 90 days notice before they work out a deal.''
   His staff was pleased as punch. ``I know a new line when I hear
one,'' said Alice Travis, national political co-ordinator.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts governor provided examples of his less
successful oratorical attempts, too, on his recent West Coast
campaign swing.
   Looking tired and jet-lagged by sunset Friday in San Diego,
Dukakis raised the issue of charisma.
   He's often accused of a severe charisma deficiency, and he tries
to make a positive of it by saying he offers competence instead.
But he mentions the word ``charisma'' so often as to suggest that
the whole idea nags at him.
   He sometimes contends that at least his wife Kitty finds him
charismatic and passionate. Standing before a small group of
Democratic activists gathered for poolside cocktails, Dukakis took
the claim another step.
   ``We've had a lot of discussion in this campaign about
charisma,'' he said. ``Well, out here they think I'm charismatic.
Right?''
   He was met with silence, then chuckles.
   Recovering, he invoked his ethnic roots.
   ``Anyway,'' he said, ``charisma is a Greek derivative.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With all the talk of Nancy Reagan and astrology, Dukakis has
developed his own interest in the subject.
   Putting away his staff's concerns that California might prove
the wrong place to do it, Dukakis poked fun at the Reagans by
referring to the stars.
   ``I don't know a horoscope from a telescope,'' he said often.
   He would add that he had decided to learn, and had taken a
reading of the stars for himself and Attorney General Edwin Meese
III.
   ``In both cases, it says we're going to be changing positions
soon,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On Friday the 13th, the Dukakis campaign was beginning to wonder
if perhaps there might be something to the stars and superstitions.
   Arising in a fashionable hotel just off San Francisco's Union
Square, Dukakis campaign trip director Jack Weeks was chagrined to
find there were no buses to take the two busloads of traveling
press in the motorcade to the morning campaign event.
   There was a difference of opinion over who was to blame. But
Weeks quickly made a call to a local cab company, and the
reporters, photographers and network crews were soon piling into a
fleet of taxis and heading off to a high school in the city's
suburbs.
   One group _ from a television network _ proved luckier than the
rest. They managed to hail a long, black limo.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' trip to the West was his first with Secret Service
protection. He was the last presidential candidate to accept the
government bodyguards, and their arrival brought new rules and
restrictions to Dukakis' entourage.
   Campaign staffers began sporting new lapel pins, of a unique
design that signal to the informed who the wearer is.
   They also began spouting new phrases and words, like ``sweep the
bags,'' which doesn't mean clean them but assures the luggage is
unarmed and non-threatening, and ``EOD,'' which staffers explain as
an impenetrable acronym for the guys who do the sweeping.
   ``We're learning a new language,'' press secretary Mark Gearan
said.
</TEXT>
