<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Bias     05-16 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bias,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier to File Job-Discrimination Charges in
Colorado Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
people to file job-discrimination charges against employers by
allowing flexibility for meeting some deadlines imposed by a
federal anti-bias law.
   The justices, by a 5-3 vote, agreed with the Reagan
administration and revived a Colorado sex discrimination case that
was dismissed because deadlines for filing the complaint were
missed.
   The complaint was filed by Suanne Leerssen of Aurora, Colo., who
was fired on June 10, 1983, by Commercial Office Products Co.
   Ms. Leerssen filed a sex discrimination complaint against the
company with the federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
289 days later, on March 26, 1984.
   The 1964 Civil Rights Act says generally such charges must be
filed with the EEOC within 180 days of the occurrence of the
alleged discrimination. But the law also gives someone charging job
bias up to 300 days to file with the EEOC if the proceedings
initially are instituted with a state or local civil rights agency.
   In a related provision, the law says no charge may be filed with
the EEOC for 60 days from the time the case is filed with a state
or local civil rights agency. That provision is intended to give
the agency time to resolve the dispute while the EEOC steps aside.
   Colorado civil rights officials previously had agreed with the
EEOC that, in effect, the federal agency did not have to wait for
the 60 days to expire before intervening in cases like that of Ms.
Leerssen.
   Most states have similar work-sharing agreements with the EEOC.
The state agencies initially process certain types of claims and
the EEOC initially handles others.
   But the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that despite
the state-federal agreement the EEOC must wait the full 60 days
before intervening.
   Adding 60 days to the 289 days Ms. Leerssen had waited to take
action against her employer meant that the EEOC's hands were tied
until 349 days had elapsed from her firing. And that is too late
for the EEOC to meet the 300-day limit, the appeals court said.
   The Supreme Court today overturned the appeals court ruling.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, writing for the court, said the
300-day deadline was not missed because the EEOC had tacit approval
to act immediately, without waiting 60 days. He said Colorado
officials had waived the 60-day waiting period under their
agreement with the EEOC.
   The Reagan administration had said the 10th Circuit court
ruling, if adopted nationwide, could have forced dismissal of
thousands of discrimination complaints on a technicality.
   The case is EEOC vs. Commercial Office Products Co., 86-1696.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
