<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Candidates-Money Bjt   05-16 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Money, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Finance People Raise Money for Primary Foes, Fall
Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and George Bush, within sight
of nomination and the end of their own fund-raising needs, are
turning their attention to retiring the debts of one-time rivals
and raising money for their parties.
   Bush has agreed to a request from Senate Republican Leader Bob
Dole to help pay off his debt, said Bush deputy finance director
Fred Bush. Dole's debt stood at $1.8 million as of the end of
March, but he has received some $600,000 in federal matching funds
since then.
   Within two weeks, Bush will send out a mailing to his 15,000
top-dollar contributors seeking funds for the Kansas senator, said
the treasurer, who is not related to the vice president.
   On the Democratic side, such fund-raising will be done under the
auspices of the Democratic Party, not the Dukakis campaign,
although Dukakis will participate in any events, said his treasurer
Bob Farmer. Former opponent Albert Gore Jr. has the largest debt
outstanding, at more than $1.5 million.
   ``Governor Dukakis respects and likes the other candidates,''
Farmer said, but added, ``I think that because there are still
delegates outstanding, we would not want anyone to think we were
trading delegates for money. It would be more appropriate if
(Democratic Party) Chairman (Paul) Kirk put the thing together.''
   Democratic National Committee spokesman Mike McCurry said no
date has been set for the unity fund-raiser.
   In the vice president's case, Fred Bush said, the Dole mailing
``shows good faith on the vice president's part ... I think the
Dole people will help us as well.''
   He said there had been no request for help from the campaign of
Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., whose treasurer Scott Mackenzie said the
campaign expects to pay all of its remaining bills by the end of
June.
   However, the campaign still needs to raise money for close-down
costs and compliance with Federal Election Commission regulations,
which will come to under $1 million, said Mackenzie.
   ``If we could get the vice president to do a unity function or
sign a letter to his contributors on our behalf that would
certainly help,'' Mackenzie said in a telephone interview.
   Both Dukakis and Bush are beginning to refocus their
fund-raising machines on helping their parties build warchests for
the November general election.
   The candidates each will get $46 million from the
taxpayer-supported federal fund to campaign for the general
election, and cannot spend more than that amount.
   But election law also allows the parties to spend $8.3 million
to help their nominees, and they can also finance state-based
efforts which indirectly help the presidential ticket.
   With events last month, Bush raised the maximum $27 million that
primary candidates are allowed to spend under election law.
   He plans to help the GOP raise the $8.3 million, plus another
$14 million that will go to state election funds for November, said
Fred Bush.
   He said more than $1 million has already been raised for that
effort, and four large fund-raising events, at $10,000 per couple,
are planned for June. They should bring in between $4 and $5
million.
   Farmer said the Dukakis fund-raising team of 30 will embark on
general election efforts after hitting the $27 million primary
ceiling next month.
   Farmr, who has overseen Dukakis' admirable finance effort, will
remain as treasurer and if Dukakis wins the nomination as expected,
will work with the party to raise funds for both the presidential
campaign and for such state efforts as voter registration, local
races, and other party-building activities.
   Noting that the Republicans traditionally have had millions more
to spend than the Democrats, Farmer said, ``My goal would be to
create a level playing field for Democrats and Republicans'' and
raise ``as much as it takes to win.''
   Farmer said if Dukakis is the nominee, he anticipates expanding
on the system he used to raise money for Dukakis in the primary
season _ a network of 950 finance committee members who each
pledged to raise $10,000.
   Seven hundred raised the $10,000 each, and 150 raised $20,000 or
more, he said.
   ``Traditionally people went out and found a few fatcats and
depended on them to raise money. We have tried to create a
grassroots (effort) all over the country,'' Farmer said.
   In addition, Farmer said he foresees helping to raise money for
the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, and the Democratic gubernatorial
bids.
</TEXT>
