<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     05-16 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Welcomes Soviet Pullout From Afghanistan; Vows To Back Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States welcomed the withdrawal
Monday of Soviet troops from Afghanistan and renewed its pledge to
support Moslem rebels as they fight to take control of the Kabul
government.
   ``The resistance has made clear its intention to continue the
struggle for self-determination against the illegitimate Kabul
regime,'' the State Department said. ``As we have said, we fully
support the resistance and their goal of an independent
Afghanistan.''
   The statement did not make clear whether the United States
supported the rebels in a civil war with the pro-Soviet government
or also in attacks on Red Army forces as they depart from the
war-torn country.
   The Soviet commander, Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov, said Saturday in
Kabul that the Russians would defend themselves against rebel
attacks. ``Certainly the retribution will be severe,'' he said.
   The Afghan rebels have stockpiled U.S. weapons, including
shoulder-fired Stinger missiles, while the Soviet have armed the
Afghan army. President Najib has denounced the rebels, who are
called ``freedom fighters'' by the Reagan administration, as
``terrorists'' and ``barbarians'' and ``fanatics who laughingly
preach a holy war.''
   On Monday, a convoy of 1,300 Soviet soldiers left Kabul and
headed for home. Gunfire rang out in the distance during a farewell
ceremony _ an ominous reminder that the civil war rages on.
   Gen. Gromov said Saturday that a quarter of the Soviet troops
would be pulled out of the country by the end of the month. An
estimated 115,000 Soviet troops are in the country backing the
government against the guerrillas.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said ``we welcome
the start of the withdrawal. ... This is a historic occasion,
opening up the possibility for the early restoration of
Afghanistan's independence and self-determination.''
   He said he hoped all Soviet forces would be withdrawn ``well in
advance'' of the Feb. 15 deadline set in agreements signed by
Afghanistan, Pakistan, the United States and the Soviet Union.
   The U.S. official made a point of the fact the rebels had not
signed the cease-fire accord. Redman also stressed the continuing
and frequent U.S. contact with the Mujahedeen.
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said in a separate
statement that U.S. support for the guerrillas ``remains
steadfast.''
   The leader of a Moslem rebel faction vowed on Sunday to seize
Jalalabad, a major strategic city, as soon as an estimated 6,000
Soviet troops withdrew.
   ``We'll continue our jihad (holy war). We are fighting against
an idea,'' said Mahmood, a commander in the radical Hezb-I-Islami
guerrilla faction, who spoke from his headquarters in Peshawar,
Pakistan.
   Soviet troops are expected to complete their retreat from
Jalalabad in two weeks and be replaced by up to 12,000 Afghan army
troops.
   Guerrillas and Western observers estimate that about 1.5 million
Afghans have died in the war. The U.S. State Department estimates
Soviet casualties since 1979 at 33,000 to 38,000, more than
one-third of whom were killed in eight years of fighting.
   An estimated 2.9 million Afghan refugees are in Pakistan and an
estimated 2.3 million are in Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
