<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   05-16 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Two Arabs on Day of Mourning, Widespread Beatings
Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and
killed two Arab youths on Monday and wounded at least nine
protesters in widespread clashes on a ``Day of Mourning'' for Arabs
killed in the Palestinian uprising.
   The violence took place during a heat wave described as the
worst in 18 years. The temperature Monday in Tel Aviv was 108
degrees. It also came on Id el Fitr, the Moslem holiday marking the
close of the holy month of Ramadan.
   Hospital officials in Gaza City reported treating at least 46
Arabs for beating injuries.
   The respected liberal daily Haaretz quoted reserve soldiers
returning from duty in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip as
complaining that beating and humiliating Arabs had become routine
army practice.
   The soldiers said a common tactic was stripping Arabs during
interrogation.
   In towns and villages throughout the occupied lands, Arabs
followed instructions issued in the latest Palestine Liberation
Organization leaflet to mourn victims of the uprising by praying
for them in mosques and laying wreaths on their graves.
   Protests erupted during marches as Moslem worshipers emerged
from prayers waving outlawed Palestinian flags, chanting
nationalist slogans and hurling stones at troops.
   The worst clash occurred in the Jabaliya refugee camp, a hotbed
of Palestinian nationalism on the outskirts of Gaza City.
   Troops opened fire when worshipers marched to a cemetery and
began throwing stones. A 17-year-old youth was killed and three
others, including a 10-year-old boy, were wounded, hospital
officials said.
   In Azmut, a village near the West Bank city of Nablus, troops
opened fire when a disturbance broke out during another Arab march,
the army said. Hospital officials said a 15-year-old boy was killed
and two people were wounded.
   The fatalities brought the Arab death toll during the uprising
to at least 190, according to U.N. figures. An Israeli teen-ager
and one soldier have died.
   In Jabaliya, witnesses said about 800 marchers made their way
from three mosques in the camp to the cemetery. As troops appeared,
some marchers began throwing stones.
   ``The soldiers started shooting everywhere,'' said 12-year-old
Rami Ahmed Demraz, who lay in Gaza City's Ahli Arab hospital with a
gunshot wound in his leg.
   Jabaliya resident Atas Abu Oshed, an 18-year-old tailor, said
two army helicopters dropped tear gas on the marchers and later
dropped baseball-sized stones on houses.
   After the morning march, Oshed said troops searched the camp for
stone-throwers, breaking into houses and beating refugees.
   ``They kicked in the door, pulled me out from behind my sewing
machine and and started to beat me with riot sticks,'' said Oshed,
who lay in a hospital bed with a bandage around his head. ``My
sister tried to help me and they beat her to the ground, knocking
her unconscious.''
   Doctors at the Ahli Arab hospital said they admitted six
Jabaliya residents with beating injuries Monday, and the city's
Shifa hospital said it admitted 20 more from the camp and an
additional 20 from other parts of Gaza.
   Yusef Hashim Kadus, 21, from Jabaliya, said 10 soldiers stopped
him as he was leaving his house and started hitting him with rifle
butts and riot sticks studded with pointed objects. Red welts
covered his back.
   Nabil Said Lubad, 22, lay nearby with a bloodied, bruised and
swollen left eye and red abrasions and black-and-blue welts on his
arms and legs. ``The troops asked me if I threw stones,'' he said.
``I said `no,' and they just kept beating me with riot sticks and
an iron pipe.''
   Residents of Beit Hanoun, a small village near Jabaliya, said
troops clashed with Arab worshipers following early morning prayers
there.
   Jaber Mohammed Kaffarneh, 24, whose two broken arms were in
casts from the wrist up, said he was surrounded by 20 soldiers.
   ``They hit me on the arms and all over my body with a tire
jack,'' said Kaffarneh, whose head and left leg were swathed in
bandages. He said he was beaten for an hour and thrown in a garbage
dumpster.
   Left-wing legislator Yair Tsaban urged the army to probe
allegations that at least one Israeli teen-ager in a paramilitary
training course beat Arab prisoners in a West Bank jail.
   Tsaban told The Associated Press the incident occurred between
February 7 and 12 when a group of high school students were brought
to a detention center near Ramallah.
</TEXT>
