<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 05-16 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0587,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drenched Schoolgirls Greet Pope In Paraguay</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs, pope arrives in Paraguay. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs ``The pope spoke...'' DELETES last five grafs as
redundant. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today began a
three-day visit to Paraguay, last stop on his South American tour.
His jet touched down in a torrential rainstorm as drenched
schoolgirls in white smocks chanted a greeting.
   President Alfredo Stroessner, who has ruled this nation for 34
years, awaited the pontiff inside an airport boarding area
protected from the rain.
   John Paul, who on departure from Rome on May 7 called his 12-day
trip to Uruguay, Bolivia, Peru and Paraguay ``a mission against
hate, violence and lies,'' arrived at 1:30 p.m. aboard a DC-8
jetliner of Peru's state airline Aeroperu.
   Gen. Stroessner's government tried last week to alter the papal
schedule in Paraguay by canceling a meeting with opposition
leaders, a move the Vatican said was unprecedented.
   The government later backed down. But the papal visit has
spotlighted deteriorating ties between the Roman Catholic Church
and the rightist government, whose members often describe clerical
critics as communists and subversives.
   In turn, clerics frequently attack alleged government
corruption, election fraud and human and civil rights violations.
   The church has criticized the decision to allow only
state-controlled radio and television to cover papal activities in
Paraguay, where about 97 percent of the 3.8 million population is
Catholic.
   In Peru on Sunday night, the pope called for an end to political
violence that has claimed 10,000 lives in recent years.
   ``May your homeland ... be a place where exploitation, violence
and terrorism do not leave their tragic sequels of oppression and
death,'' John Paul told a group of intellectuals and businessmen in
Lima, Peru's capital.
   The pope spoke in a Catholic seminary where last week leftist
guerrillas seeking the overthrow of Peru's civilian president, Alan
Garcia, interrupted a Mass and called for an armed revolution.
   In a farewell speech in Lima this morning, the pope reiterated
his concern over Peru's growing political violence.
   ``I cannot silence the sadness that invades my pastor's heart on
confirming that this noble Peruvian nation continues to suffer the
lash of violence.
   ``Attacks and crimes continue to leave pain and death in so many
homes of this country,'' he said.
   When John Paul first visited Peru in 1985, he appealed to
leftist insurgents to put down their arms. But the violence is
worse than ever.
   He recalled that appeal this morning.
   ``Before leaving this beloved soil of Peru, I renew the call I
made in February 1985 to those responsible for so much pain and
death.''
   Officials said leftist insurgents were responsible for four
dynamite blasts in Lima on Saturday that preceded the pope's
arrival. There were no reported injuries, but the explosions
knocked out electricity in a large section of the city.
   At a Mass Sunday in a park on outskirts of Lima, the pope
appealed to an estimated 1.5 million Peruvians to build ``a
civilization of love.''
   ``A civilization, which, resting on this foundation of love for
the person who is near us _ our neighbor _ will transform ... the
whole world,'' he said.
   During a meeting with Peru's bishops, he spoke of the ``blind
and insensitive violence'' plaguing the nation, Peru's poverty and
the country's major role in the South American drug trade.
   Peru is a major source of the coca leaves that yield cocaine.
   In a taped message broadcast on Peruvian radio, he referred to a
1986 prison uprising by members of the Maoist Shining Path
guerrilla movement. The army killed more than 250 guerrillas in the
clash.
   ``I know of the painful tensions which have cost lamentable
blood quotas, and I know of your sufferings and needs, which in
spite of noble and generous efforts on the part of authorities,
have not been overcome,'' he said in the message to prison inmates.
   An estimated 20,000 troops and police in riot gear sealed off
downtown Lima and guarded public buildings and hotels after the
bomb blasts Saturday.
   Heavy security was particularly evident when the pope called on
Peru's president Sunday in the government palace. As Garcia led
John Paul through a garden, they passed two armored personnel
carriers, soldiers carrying submachine guns and a special
anti-terrorist team in red berets.
</TEXT>
