<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Heat     05-16 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Heat,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worst Heat Wave In Two Decades Ignites More Than 100 Fires</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A desert wind raised temperatures across Israel
to more than 100 degrees Monday in the country's worst heat wave in
nearly two decades. More than 100 forest fires were reported, and
the death of an Austrian tourist was blamed on heat stroke.
   The hottest spot was Jericho, where the temperature reached 113,
according to the Israeli Meteorological Service. It was 109 in the
northern region of Galilee and 108 in Tel Aviv and Haifa. Jerusalem
registered 97 degrees.
   With the heat wave in its third day, health officials urged
people to stay indoors as much as possible and drink 12 to 16
glasses of water a day.
   On Saturday, temperatures in Jericho reached 116 degrees,
surpassing the record 115 degrees in May 1970, said Marco Marcel, a
forecaster at the meteorological service.
   The soaring temperatures were caused by a ``sharav,'' or hot
desert wind from north Africa, Marcel said.
   A 55-year-old tourist, Hubert Riegler of Vienna, died Saturday
after suffering heat stroke while hiking along the Dead Sea south
of Jerusalem, police said.
   Another death was indirectly blamed on the heat Sunday in Ramat
Hasharon, a Tel Aviv suburb.
   Police said a 35-year-old Israeli burned to death when he tried
to start an electric generator and the machine burst into flames.
The accident happened during a power outage caused by electricity
use estimated at 23 percent above normal.
   In the northern Galilee region, firefighters battled 50 blazes
Monday that had burned for more than 24 hours, Israel radio said.
Small planes were used to spray water on the flames. Another 50
fires have been put out in the past two days.
   About 350 residents were evacuated from the tiny village of
Moshav Ya'ara in the Galilee because of spreading flames, the radio
said.
   Fires destroyed six houses in the Mitzpe Kelil settlement,
burned through about 350 acres of trees and caused at least
$500,000 damage, radio and news reports said.
   The Jerusalem Post reported one happy result of the heat. It
said that prices for tomatoes, which soared 115 percent last month,
would soon come down because a large part of the crop was ripening
prematurely under the hot sun.
</TEXT>
