<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Beating     05-16 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Beating,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Probes Report of Teen-Ager Beating Arab in Army Camp</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Monday an investigation had been
launched into reports that an Israeli teen-ager in a paramilitary
youth corps severely beat an Arab prisoner after being encouraged
to do so by an army sergeant.
   The incident reportedly occurred in February, but details were
only published Monday.
   The daily Hadashot printed an interview with a 16-year-old Yuval
Aflalo from the southern town of Yeroham. Yuval was quoted as
saying he felt ``great enjoyment' after beating an Arab prisoner
``to a pulp'' with a wedge of iron. The prisoner required
hospitalization.
   ``I tell you, if I had had a submachine gun in my hands at that
moment, I would have killed him,'' the teen-ager was quoted as
saying.
   About 100,000 Israelis of high school age belong to the Gadna, a
paramilitary youth corps. Its members are taught to use weapons,
navigate and camp in preparation for entering the army at 18 for
three years' compulsory service.
   Hadashot said the teen-ager from Yeroham was one of 60 high
school students from the town's Gadna corps who spent a week at an
army base near Ramallah in the West Bank in February.
   Education Minister Yitzhak Navon said on Israel radio that a
sergeant at the Ofer camp near Ramallah invited three Gadna youths
``to come and see Arab detainees.''
   Navon said only two of the teen-agers went along and one ran
away when he saw the prisoners.
   ``Only one (teen-ager) was left. Apparently the sergeant
encouraged him to strike. How many times, I don't know. For that,
there is a committee investigating.'' Navon said. ``Presuming that
the details are correct, then this certainly is a grave affair.''
   Col. Uri Manos, who heads the Gadna, said the youth quoted in
Hadashot exaggerated his role.
   But he said the army was probing allegations that a soldier at
the base took two other teen-agers to the detention center and that
one of them may have struck a prisoner.
   Meir Tsaban, a lawmaker of the Socialist Mapam Party who
revealed the incident to Israeli newspapers, said in a telephone
interview that he learned of the incident in March after teachers
at Yeroham High School said they heard students boasting about
participating in beatings.
   Tsaban said the army told him it had put a sergeant on trial for
the incident and had issued orders barring the youth corps from
being brought to bases in the West Bank where Arab prisoners are
held. Tsaban didn't name the sergeant.
   Tsaban said he decided to publicize the case because he felt the
army investigation had been inadequate. ``The probe was
unsuccessful, and it was not even clear whether the sergeant was
punished,'' he said.
   The Haaretz daily quoted reservist troops who recently
compeleted duty in the occupied territories as complaining that
physical abuse and harassment of Arabs ``has become the norm.''
   In keeping with army policy, the newspaper did not publish the
names of the complaining soldiers. It said harassment ranged from
strip searches to beatings and vandalizing homes.
   The newspaper quoted one of its reporters who witnessed an
incident Sunday at the El Amari refugee camp near Ramallah.
   According to the witness, soldiers beat a detainee ``although he
did not resist arrest'' and that one soldier threw a stone at the
detainee's mother as she pleaded for his release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
