<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSPoll     05-16 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Poll,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Poll: 37 Percent Favor Condom Handouts in School</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release after 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half the Americans in a poll in January
said high school pupils should be taught that condoms can prevent
the spread of AIDS, and more than a third said schools should give
out condoms, Parents Magazine reported Monday.
   Eighty-seven percent of the 1,008 adults polled said they were
not worried or only slightly worried that they may get AIDS. Among
the roughly 200 who had teen-age children, a smaller majority _ 60
percent _ were not worried or only slightly worried about their
children getting AIDS, the poll said.
   Forty-nine percent of all the adults polled said high school
pupils should be taught that condoms are effective in preventing
the spread of AIDS, and 37 percent said schools should make condoms
available to pupils who want them, Parents Magazine reported.
   The poll was conducted by telephone Jan. 15-27 among a random
national sample, the magazine said. The margin of error was three
points.
</TEXT>
