<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RubberStrike 2ndLd-Writethru a0645 05-16 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rubber Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0645,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URW Strikes Firestone, Set To Strike Goodyear</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `Goodyear's URW ...,' with one graf to
CORRECT that margin was not 54 percent but that vote was 54 percent
against contract.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 15,000 workers were poised to strike
Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. as a walkout by 4,700 union members
against Firestone Inc. continued today in six states.
   On Sunday, the last of 11 United Rubber Workers locals at
Goodyear plants to vote rejected a union request to reconsider a
rejected contract proposal, defeating the union's attempt to set a
pattern for an industrywide pact.
   The union set a strike deadline of noon Tuesday for 11 Goodyear
plants in nine states.
   Mike Stanley, president of URW Local 878 in Union City, Tenn.,
said he and other union representatives have been called to Akron
to talk with Goodyear officials Tuesday morning.
   The Firestone strike began Sunday after negotiators in Cleveland
failed to reach an agreement by a 12:01 a.m. deadline. The walkout
affects plants in Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.; Oklahoma City;
Noblesville, Ind.; Russellville, Ark., and its tire headquarters in
Akron.
   No new talks have been scheduled, URW and Firestone spokesmen
said.
   Union leaders said Firestone officials refused to abide by the
pattern set in the tentative Goodyear contract.
   ``They did not present to us the cost-of-living allowance
provisions Goodyear granted, and there was no provision in there
for fully paid hospital insurance,'' said URW President Milan Stone.
   ``We believe that our proposal contains a number of
improvements, and in terms of Firestone's position in the industry
is equal in value and in cost to the URW settlement proposal,''
George W. Aucott, the company's executive vice president, said in a
statement.
   The third of the nation's Big Three tire makers, Uniroyal
Goodrich Tire Co., came to terms last month in a contract allowing
for the company's special needs as a result of the recent Goodrich
and Uniroyal merger.
   In the Goodyear contract, the main dispute was the lack of pay
raise in the pattern agreement, which included job security
provisions.
   Fifty-four percent of Goodyear's URW members rejected the
tentative contract on May 1. Six of the 11 Goodyear locals approved
the pact, but they did not represent a majority of the the
company's membership in the union. Under URW bylaws, ratification
must come from a majority of the membership as well as a majority
of the locals. So the union asked the locals to reconsider.
   On Sunday, the union local in Danville, Va., voted 479-339 not
to reconsider, forcing the URW to set a strike deadline.
   The vote followed a visit last week by Goodyear Chairman Robert
Mercer Jr., who urged local leaders to reconsider the proposed
contract.
   In addition to Danville, the strike would affect plants in
Akron, St. Marys and Marysville in Ohio; Gadsden, Ala.; Union City,
Tenn.; Madisonville, Ky.; Lincoln, Neb.; Topkea, Kan.; Sun Prarie,
Wis.; and New Bedford, Mass.
</TEXT>
