<HEAD>Soap Opera Actress Is A Survivor Of Violent Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Christine Tudor, who plays Gwyneth
Alden on the soap opera ``Loving,'' began drinking at age 12 and is
the survivor of a violent past.
   In the May 21 issue of TV Guide, Ms. Tudor said she grew up
``angry .... Drinking fast became my way of dealing with the guilt
and torment.'' She is the youngest of five children of an alcoholic
father.
   The actress who grew up in working-class South Baltimore said
before her father left the family when she was 9, her life was
``filled with the emotional baggage of poverty, of late-night
arguments that brought violence and police intervention at home.''
   She skipped school and failed seventh grade. When she returned
to school, she met a remarkable teacher, Grace Guarino. By the end
of the eighth grade, Ms. Tudor had stopped drinking and street
fighting and was an honor student.
   Today, she spends 20 hours a week helping troubled youths,
working in the non-profit Youth at Risk Program of the Breakthrough
Foundation. She also organized the YAR Celebrity Development, where
about 50 celebrities have worked with troubled youths.
</TEXT>
