<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Sokolov     05-16 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Sokolov,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Yale Professor Loses Bid to Keep Citizenship in Nazi Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Yale University professor who the
government asserts wrote ``vicious attacks on Jews'' for a
Russian-language newspaper controlled by the Nazis during World War
II lost a Supreme Court appeal Monday aimed at saving his U.S.
citizenship.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that Vladimir
Sokolov of Milford, Conn., may be stripped of his citizenship, the
first step toward deportation.
   Sokolov, who came to the United States in 1951, became a
naturalized citizen in 1957.
   Sokolov's attorney, Kevin W. Smith of Hamden, Conn., said his
client retired about eight years ago from Yale, where he taught
Russian literature.
   Government prosecutors contend that Sokolov's citizenship was
gained illegally because he falsely stated upon entering this
country that he had not ``assisted the enemy in persecuting civil
populations.''
   Sokolov, 75, was born in Orel, Russia. After Nazi Germany
invaded the Soviet Union during World War II, he worked as a writer
for Rech, a Russian-language paper.
   Government lawyers say that during his employment, Sokolov
``wrote numerous articles containing vicious attacks on Jews,'' for
which he won medals for ``bravery'' and ``merit'' from the Nazis.
   Sokolov fled the Soviet Union when the German Army retreated,
government lawyers said.
   He later wrote for Berlin-based newspapers that also featured
virulent propaganda against Jews, the government said.
   The case is Sokolov vs. U.S., 87-323.
</TEXT>
