<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CashMachine     05-16 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cash Machine,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Just 2 People Have Volunteered to Pay Back Overflow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Of 45 people who made off with a total of $4,500
extra from a bank cash machine that went berserk last month, just
two have volunteered to return any of the money.
   ``I was surprised they did come in and very happy they were
going to give me the money right away,'' Amelia Saavedra, the
branch manager of the savings and loan that was hit for the loss,
said Monday.
   ``I was very surprised, pleasantly surprised, to say the least.''
   Those two were told to keep the money in their accounts so it
could be automatically deducted when they are billed, according to
Robert Nolan, a spokesman for First Federal Savings and Loan
Association of Rochester.
   The association's branch at First Avenue and 14th Street spewed
forth the money on April 24 as users of the cash machine called
their friends to alert them that when $5 bills were requested, $20
bills were given.
   ``I called everybody I knew,'' an unidentified writer told New
York Newsday at the time.
   The cash machine transactions are automatically recorded, so the
association has a record of everyone who mistakenly received the
$20 bills. Each of the 45 people who got extra money has had or
will have the money deducted from their accounts, Nolan said.
   ``To my knowledge, we have had no protests,'' Nolan said Monday.
   The bank branch is part of a network that dispenses cash for
other banks, so the network will credit First Federal once the
accounts cough up the lost money.
   An employee of the bank had mistakenly put a canister of $20
bills into the slot for $5 bills. Theoretically, the most a
customer could get was $800 if he asked for $200.
   The clerk who loaded the machine incorrectly will not be
disciplined or reprimanded.
   ``It was an innocent chain of human events,'' Nolan said, and
procedures have been instituted to prevent it from happening again.
   The profiteering customers will not be prosecuted and there is
no investigation under way into the matter, according to Colleen
Roche, a spokeswoman for the Manhattan district attorney's office.
   Meanwhile, Nolan said the bank could stand the temporary loss.
   ``We're a $4.7 billion association,'' Nolan said. ``I don't
believe it affected the cash flow.''
</TEXT>
