<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-16 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Planes Attack 12 Tanker in 18 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq reported its 12th attack on an
Iranian tanker in 18 days Monday, and Persian Gulf shipping
executives said they had reports of 10 crewmen killed.
   At Iran's Larak island terminal in the Strait of Hormuz, salvage
teams fought a fire still burning on a Spanish supertanker from an
Iraqi raid Saturday.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit of London said two more names
were added to the death toll of the Saturday raid, in which five
tankers were hit. Lloyd's said 19 were dead and three missing. Gulf
shipping agents put the numbers at two dead and six missing.
   A dispatch from the official Iraqi News Agency said air force
planes made ``accurate and effective hits'' Monday on a ``big naval
target,'' the standard Iraqi term for a tanker owned or chartered
by Iran. It said all planes returned safely.
   Executives said the tanker was hit near Iran's main oil export
terminal, Kharg Island in the northern gulf, but said they did not
have the name of the vessel or further details. They said there
were reports of 10 crewmen dead.
   Iran uses the tankers to ferry oil from Kharg to makeshift
terminals on Larak and Sirri Island, in comparatively safer waters
450 miles down the gulf. Iraq raids the ships in an attempt to cut
off the oil revenue Iran needs to finance the war, which began in
September 1980.
   Of the dozen raids Iraq has reported since April 29, six have
been confirmed independently.
   U.S. military officials said the wreckage of a Marine Corps
helicopter gunship found in the southern gulf would be ``destroyed
in place'' by underwater explosives because it could not be
salvaged. The bodies of the two pilots were recovered Sunday.
   The Navy announced plans for a warship to drop a wreath in the
central gulf Tuesday, the first anniversary of an Iraqi missile
attack on the guided missile frigate USS Stark in which 37 sailors
were killed. It was hit by two Exocet missiles fired by an Iraqi
pilot who mistook it for an Iranian ship.
   Shipping executives said the 325,000-ton Spanish supertanker
Barcelona continued burning and ``listing heavily,' two days after
the Iraqi raid on the Larak, but the vessel had been beached and
was not expected to sink.
   Iraqi jets flew a 1,500-mile roundtrip to hit Larak, where
foreign ships load oil brought down the gulf by shuttle tankers. It
was the third and most damaging Iraqi attack on the facility in
seven months.
   In addition to the Barcelona, the other ships damaged were the
world's largest vessel, the 564,739-ton Liberian-flag Seawise
Giant; the 457,841-ton British-flag Burmah Endeavour; the Argosy, a
152,004-ton Cypriot tanker, and the 231,712-ton Iranian-owned Khark.
   Iran has accused the United States of complicity in the raid,
claiming American warships jammed radar and radio communications
for nine minutes. U.S. officials deny the allegations.
   Some diplomatic and shipping industry observers, noting the
attack on Larak was among several recent military reversals, say
the Iranian military is under growing pressure to restore its
credibility.
   Last month, Iraq recaptured the Faw Peninsula, which Iran had
occupied since 1986, and the U.S. Navy destroyed two Iranian oil
platforms and sank or damaged six naval craft April 18. The
helicopter gunship was lost that day and Iran claimed to have shot
it down.
   Iran has threatened to avenge the setbacks.
   Iranian speedboats or frigates customarily attack a neutral
commercial vessel, most often in the southern gulf, for each tanker
hit by the Iraqis. More than 500 ships have been raided by both
sides since the war began.
</TEXT>
