<HEAD>Cuomo Wants Jackson To Meet With Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, trying to ease
tensions, will arrange a meeting between presidential hopeful Jesse
Jackson and New York's Jewish leaders, it was reported Monday.
   Cuomo said the meeting would be sometime after the presidential
primaries end on June 7, the New York Daily News reported.
   During the campaign leading up to New York's April 19 primary,
Jackson refused to meet with Jewish leaders. He has antagonized
Jews by supporting Palestinian rights and referring to New York
City as ``Hymietown'' during his 1984 campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Cuomo, who met with Jackson for an hour on Friday in San
Francisco, said the black leader was concerned that Jewish leaders
would use any such meeting to attack him.
   ``I told him I would set it up personally and he could rely on
me to set up a group that was sincerely interested in communicating
and wasn't going to take advantage of him politically or any other
way,'' said Cuomo during an interview Sunday morning.
