<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MenOnly     05-16 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Men Only,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Will Be Asked To Drop `Men Only' Provision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona voters will decide this November
whether to drop an unenforced constitutional provision that bars
women _ like Gov. Rose Mofford _ from holding the state's top
offices.
   The Senate voted 27-to-0 Monday for a proposed constitutional
amendment to remove language that restricts the top offices to men.
The House already has passed the proposed amendment, so the Senate
vote automatically places the issue on the November general
election ballot.
   The constitution technically now allows only men to be governor,
secretary of state, attorney general, school superintendent and
treasurer.
   Women have held those jobs for years, including Mrs. Mofford,
who had been secretary of state since 1978 and succeeded to the
governorship on April 4 when Gov. Evan Mecham was convicted on two
impeachment counts by the Senate.
   Senate Minority Leader Alan Stephens said Monday he wonders what
will happen if voters reject the amendment. However, the federal
constitution supersedes the state document in any case.
   Assistant Minority Leader Lela Alston predicted the proposed
amendment will be approved. Nonetheless, she added, Arizona has
often been accused of being a backward state and the vote may show
``the level of real discrimination against women. It will be an
interesting vote.''
   A rejection of the amendment would be ``a terrible, terrible
thing to have,'' Ms. Alston said.
</TEXT>
