<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     05-16 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Chief Pushes for Plant-Closings Plan in Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland moved to
muster support Monday for the beleaguered plant-closings provision
of the omnibus trade bill, calling it ``the human element'' in the
1,000-page package.
   ``Fairness alone dictates that workers have the right to know
about employer decisions that so drastically alter their lives,''
Kirkland said in attacking President Reagan's threatened veto of
the bill.
   ``His veto would rip the heart out of the bill by denying
workers and their communities the opportunity to avert or ease the
human catastrophe that occurs when employers move elsewhere,''
Kirkland said. He called the provision ``the human element'' in the
massive measure.
   The AFL-CIO has been running radio commericals around the
country and holding news conferences in selected cities as part of
a veto override campaign. They have focused on a provision of the
bill that would require companies with 100 or more employees to
give 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs
   Kirkland urged lawmakers to fight any effort to soften or drop
the plant-closings provision as a way of making the measure more
palatable to the White House. He said the labor federation would
oppose any version of the trade bill without the provision.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, sent the bill to the White
House on Friday and the president has 10 days not including Sundays
to act upon it or allow it to become law without his signature.
That means the expected veto might not come until early next week.
   White House spokesman B.J. Cooper said he could not forecast
precisely when Reagan would veto the bill but added, ``I don't
think we'll bump up against the last day.''
   The centerpiece of the bill would overhaul the system under
which the United States imposes trade sanctions to retaliate
against international violations and aid American industries
threatened by stepped up overseas competition.
   Reagan has cited the plant-closings provision and Alaska oil
export restrictions in threatening to veto the measure. He has been
saying the labor-supported feature would blunt rather than sharpen
the nation's edge in global markets.
   The bill cleared the Senate 63-36 on April 27, three votes short
of what Democratic leaders believe would be needed to override a
Reagan veto.
   In gathering support, the administration has been saying that,
once the president's veto were sustained, a modified version with
more moderate provisions could be whisked through with little
difficulty.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., has issued a
warning almost every day since April 27 that there can be no quick
action on a modified version of the trade bill if Reagan's veto is
sustained.
   Kirkland said the labor federation would withdraw its support if
the plant closings provision were sacrified to obtain the
president's signature. He did say in response to a question that he
would not actively campaign against such a measure.
</TEXT>
