<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-BingoFraud     05-16 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Bingo Fraud,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grandmother Cleared of Illegally Winning $2 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 74-year-old woman described by
prosecutors as ``everyone's favorite granny'' was acquitted Monday
of swindling a newspaper out of a bingo jackpot worth nearly $2
million.
   Phyllis Hanlon wept outside the courtroom in this city in
northwest England after a jury found her innocent of winning the
tabloid Sun's 1-million-pound ($1.89 million) top prize by fraud.
   ``Thank God it's all over,'' she said. ``It is the end of a
nightmare that seems to have gone on forever.''
   According to testimony, the fraud was perpetrated by printer
Arthur Sagar, whose job was to insert a winning bingo card into
every batch of 1,500 distributed to readers.
   Sagar gave winning cards to friends in return for a share of the
winnings, the prosecution said. The one he gave Mrs. Hanlon won her
more than $24,500, and she won the jackpot in a draw among 80
winners.
   Two other women, Mary Young, 44 and her mother-in-law, Margaret
Warde, 75, were cleared of charges of obtaining prizes of $18,900
each by conspiracy.
   What happens to the jackpot Mrs. Hanlon won in January 1985
remains to be decided by the courts. She said she had given about
one-third of the money to relatives and others, including two
daughters, and bought a home for $189,000.
   ``I was very happy to win it, but it brought me both happiness
and sadness,'' she said.
   The women were acquitted after the prosecution failed to
convince the jury they knew the winning cards were stolen. They
were described as ``impeccably respectable,'' with no criminal
records.
   Sagar, Mrs. Hanlon's son-in-law Kenneth Fairbrother, and two
other accomplices, John and Susan Marshall, pleaded guilty and were
to be sentenced Tuesday.
   Mrs. Hanlon said she gave Sagar and Marshall a total of 100,000
pounds, not as a reward for the winning card but because she felt
sorry for them.
   Judge Reginald Lockett told members of the jury they might
consider Mrs. Hanlon ``foolish, but you are not trying her for
that. ... May she have been duped, deluded and used shamefully by
others? If so she is, on my directions, not guilty.''
</TEXT>
