<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Broadcast     05-16 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Broadcast,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex-And-Violence Watchdog Announced; Critics Claim Censorship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Monday it was setting up
a new watchdog body to monitor sex and violence in broadcasting,
and it denied allegations that it was paving the way for censorship.
   The Broadcasting Standards Council was promised by the
Conservative Party in an election manifesto pledging to clean up
sex and violence in TV, radio and videos.
   It will be headed by Sir William Reese-Mogg, 59-year-old former
editor of The Times of London, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd told
Parliament.
   The opposition Labor Party claimed the council would be used to
stifle criticism of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government.
   The government has clashed frequently with the British
Broadcasting Corp. and the Independent Broadcasting Authority,
usually over documentaries dealing with national security or
Northern Ireland.
   The temperature heated up in recent weeks after both
corporations broadcast films challenging the official version of
events in Gibraltar March 6, when British anti-terrorist agents
shot to death three Irish Republican Army members who allegedly
were plotting to plant a bomb.
   The films, which suggested the victims could have been captured
alive, were broadcast despite expressions of outrage from Mrs.
Thatcher and pleas for them to be suppressed until after the
inquest in Gibraltar.
   ``The waters of the relationship between the government and the
broadcasters are a bit choppy at the present time,'' Hurd said, but
insisted the council's task was to deal with sex and violence, not
politics.
   Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of the opposition Labor Party,
called it an ``entirely authoritarian wedge.''
   ``The programs which the government objects to are not concerned
with sex, violence and taste, but concerned with the government's
political convenience. This body will eventually be expanded to
inhibit those who dare to criticize this administration,'' he said.
   Hattersley attacked the choice of Reese-Mogg, whom he accused of
playing ``an ignoble part'' in suppressing a program on Northern
Ireland when he was a BBC vice chairman.
   The council's most controversial power will be to preview
imported TV material before it is aired. Many broadcasters have
objected strongly, saying it opens the way for censorship and will
allow Reese-Mogg to stamp a conservative bias into television.
   Reese-Mogg says he asked for the right to preview programs, but
denies he intends to censor politically sensitive material.
   Government officials argue that the BBC and IBA have failed to
satisfactorily defend standards of decency on the two networks each
controls.
   Hurd said the council would be set up immediately and receive
legal powers when these were approved by Parliament.
   He said its functions would be to draw up a code of standards in
consultation with broadcasting, cable and video authorities,
monitor and report on the present intake of foreign material,
consider complaints and publicize its findings, and conduct
research into whether televised sex and violence affects behavior.
</TEXT>
