<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusCrash-School Bjt   05-16 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-School, Bjt,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Try to Cope with Grief from Tragic Bus Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Principal Charlie Jones thumbed through the
dark blue 1988 yearbook of Radcliff Middle School on Monday,
pointing out 16 of the children who died in one of the worst bus
accidents in U.S. history.
   At page 14, the end of the yearbook's eighth-grade section,
Jones paused. ``This page was hard hit,'' he said, gently touching
the smiling pictures of Denise Vogland, Amy Wheelock, Kristen
Williams and Chad Witt.
   At least four schools were represented on a church bus that
crashed Saturday as it returned a First Assembly of God youth group
and adult chaperones from the Kings Island amusement park north of
Cincinnati.
   Twenty-seven on the bus died when a pickup truck being driven in
the wrong direction on Interstate 71 plowed headon into the bus,
causing its fuel tanks to rupture and setting the bus ablaze.
   Sixteen people including the pickup driver, Larry Mahoney of
Worthville, remained hospitalized.
   The middle school was hardest hit, with three pupils still
hospitalized besides the 13 eighth graders, one seventh grader and
two sixth graders who were listed as missing and presumed dead.
Three other middle school pupils escaped with less serious injuries.
   The school's enrollment is 775 and ``I'm still not sure what the
effect will be of losing 16 kids, minimum,'' Jones said. ``Sixteen
kids out of our school and all of them quality, model kids.''
   Amy Wheelock, for example, was ``Miss Everything,'' Jones said.
She was captain of the cheerleaders and ``probably the most admired
girl at school.
   ``The thing that hurts me, that I can't get out of my mind, is
that we talk about leaders of tomorrow. These kids were leaders,''
Jones said.
   At nearby North Hardin High School, students were ``doing as
well as they can under the circumstance,'' said Principal Ray Story.
   Three of the school's boys _ senior Richard Gohn, freshmen
Joshua Conyers and Anthony Marks _ were among those believed dead
and eight other students remained hospitalized.
   Reporters were not allowed inside the high school, but Lori
Coffey, an 18-year-old senior, said it ``was silent.''
   ``That's the hardest part because you walk down the hall and see
the hurt but no one's saying anything,'' Ms. Coffey said. ``Most
people are in shock. Things like this don't happen at our school.''
   With an enrollment of 1,800, ``the North Hardin family is a big
family,'' Story said. ``It doesn't matter that it's a large family.
When any one member is missing, it affects the whole family.''
   The schools opened on schedule Monday, but emphasis was on grief
management rather than instruction.
   One of the bus crash survivors, sophomore Allen Tennison, said
he was back in school because ``the only way I know how to deal
with this is to talk about it.''
   ``There's times when I'm home and I look at pictures of my
friends and it hits me. But I've been numb all weekend,'' said
Tennison, the 15-year-old son of the church's pastor, Rev. Don
Tennison.
   The youth described the group on the bus as close-knit, everyone
knew everyone else.
   Signs of the tragedy were all over Radcliff, a booming town in
northcentral Kentucky just outside the Fort Knox Army base.
   Every flag that could be found in the city was at half staff and
sympathies were spelled out on marquees and display signs at
businesses and restaurants up and down the main business district.
   The message at the SunShine Cafe summed them up: ``Our hearts go
out to the families.''
   Counselors and chaplains were standing by at the high school and
teachers were encouraged to talk about the tragedy with any student
who felt the need, Story said.
   At the middle school, Jones said he and his faculty were ``just
trying to use good common sense and trying to make it an hour at a
time.''
   ``Today's a learning process, whether we want to know it or
not,'' Jones said. ``It's a tough learning process, but it is a
learning process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
