<DOCNO> AP880516-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1807EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForestSubsidies     05-16 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Subsidies,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Nations Said Depleting Forests With Subsidized
Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many developing countries have lost billions
of dollars through timber subsidies and giveaways that accelerate
destruction of tropical forests, a research organization said
Monday.
   ``Many of these countries have put the timber resource up for
grabs,'' said the author of the study, economist Robert Repetto.
``They collect in royalties and taxes much less than the timber is
worth. The ecological effect has been the extensive, wasteful,
rapid destruction of resources.''
   Repetto is a member of the staff of the World Resources
Institute, which studies environmental issues. In the past three
years the institute has published similar reports critical of
subsidies in developing countries for energy, water and pesticides.
   Monday's study reviewed several studies of below-cost sales of
timber by the U.S. Forest Service from the 191 million acres of
national forests. Though the service shows revenues exceeding
expenses by more than $500 million year, Repetto estimated that
once all costs are counted, the sales have been losing at least $85
million a year.
   Monday's study was meant to complement one by the institute in
1985 advocating reforestation efforts in developing countries.
   About 27 million acres (an area slightly larger than Virginia)
of forest are being lost in developing countries each year,
according to United Nations estimates. About two-thirds of it is in
the ``closed'' forests typical of the tropics where extensive
development of tree crowns prevents sunlight from reaching the
ground.
   ``The traditional assumption has been that deforestation makes
economic sense even if it makes environmental nonsense,'' said
James Gustave Speth, president of the institute. ``The work today
... punches a big hole in this traditional assumption.''
   Researchers examined 10 countries: China, Indonesia, the
Phillipines, Malaysia, Brazil, Ghana, Gabon, the Ivory Coast,
Liberia and the United States.
   In the Phillipines, for example, they found that royalties,
export taxes and other fees captured for the government only
one-sixth of the above-normal profits _ what economists call
``economic rent'' _ from the timber harvest in the years 1979-1982.
The five-sixths not captured amounted to about $860 million.
   To develop jobs, Indonesia, as well as other countries, exempts
sawn timber and plywood from export taxes and provides other tax
concessions to mills. But the mills use logs so inefficiently that
``in 1983, plywood exports worth $109 at international prices per
cubic meter of logs processed cost the rupiah equivalent of $133 to
produce, a sacrifice of potential gains possible only because of
the government's financial incentives and its forgiveness of log
export taxes,'' the report said.
   The Ivory Coast taxes plywood exports at 1 percent or 2 percent
and log exports at 25 percent to 45 percent. For the iroko species,
according to the report, this means ``more than $50 in taxes are
foregone for every $25 of extra foreign exchange earnings generated
when a cubic meter of log is processed into plywood.''
   Brazil provides so many concessions to cattle ranches carved out
of the Amazonian rain forest that over 15 years the typical rancher
can earn 2{ times his initial investment, even though the value of
the total ranch investment, counting the government's contribution,
would shrink by half.
   The 470 subsidized ranches had converted 6.4 million acres from
forest to pasture by 1983. Since there are 50,000 unsubsidized
ranches in the Amazon, the report questioned whether the subsidies
are worthwhile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmallKidnapping     05-16 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Kidnapping,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Small's Kidnapper Had `Cold, Calculated' Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kidnapping and murder of a prominent
local businessman who suffocated after being buried alive was part
of a ``cold, calculated'' plan to collect a $1 million ransom, a
prosecutor said Monday.
   Assistant Attorney General Michael Ficaro told jurors in opening
arguments that Daniel J. Edwards, 31, abducted Stephen Small on
Sept. 2 because he was ``trying for the big score,'' and that
Edwards ``never intended Stephen Small to live.''
   But defense attorney Sheldon Reagan told jurors it was a
``tragic, but accidental death.''
   He said evidence would show no signs of injury to Small, and
that the wooden box in which he was buried contained water, candy
bars, lights and a faulty air supply system.
   The state is seeking the death penalty against Edwards.
   Edwards and Nancy Rish, 26, were arrested two days after Small's
abduction and hours before police found his body in a wooded area
between Kankakee and the Indiana border.
   Miss Rish, who lived with Edwards in Bourbonnais, also has been
charged with murder and kidnapping. Her trial date has not been set.
   Ficaro said evidence would show that Small, great-grandson of
former Illinois Gov. Len Small and a member of a prominent media
family, was restoring a Frank Lloyd Wright house last summer, while
Edwards was busy ``building the nightmare that brings us to this
court today,'' a coffin-size plywood box.
   The prosecutor said the jury would hear a tape recording Edwards
made of Small telling his family he had been kidnapped and where to
take the $1 million ransom.
   Ficaro said Edwards' fingerprints were found inside the wooden
box and on plastic pipe at the burial scene, but Edwards' biggest
mistake was assuming ``it takes a long time to trace a phone call.''
   Police traced a ransom call to a public telephone in nearby
Aroma Park, where a witness saw Edwards, Ficaro said.
   Police said Small was lured from his restored home after
midnight Sept. 2. The caller, identifying himself as a policeman,
asked Small to come to another house he owned because it had been
burglarized.
   Before dawn, Nancy Small received a call saying her husband
would be found in a box if the ransom were not paid. Late in the
day, a call with delivery instructions was unclear. The person
later promised to call back, but the family received no other calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
