<HEAD>Actress Chooses Percentage Over Up-Front Money in Perfume Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Dynasty'' star Joan Collins is hoping that a
sweet smell will be a success _ because she gets a percentage of
the proceeds.
   Parlux Fragrances Inc. of Manhattan announced Monday that Miss
Collins has signed a contract to start a line of fragrances next
year.
   She was chosen, according to Parlux chief Gerard Semhon,
``because as a Hollywood personality she is the ultimate at this
point. She is the most visible, probably in the same league as
Elizabeth Taylor.''
   The name of the new product is undisclosed pending some legal
technicalities but will include Miss Collins' name, Semhon said.
   Miss Collins accepted a down payment of less than six figures
against future royalties of 5 percent of the net proceeds, Semhon
said. A spokeswoman for the company said first year sales are
expected to be about $10 million.
   Semhon said he was able to persuade the actress that the
start-up costs would be large and any large initial payment to her
would be a liability.
   But Semhon declined to reveal exactly how much Miss Collins was
paid because ``She's very proud. She doesn't want people to know
she accepted less than someone else.''
