<HEAD>Metalworker Given Maximum Sentence For Murder In Ethnic Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A metalworker was convicted of murder Monday and
sentenced to the maximum 15 years in prison in connection with
ethnic rioting that killed at least 32 people in the Azerbaijani
city of Sumgait.
   Talekh Salekh Ogli Ismailov was convicted of premeditated murder
by a tribunal headed by a member of the Supreme Court of
Azerbaijan, the official Tass news agency reported. He was the
first person convicted in the February riots.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda reported last week that
Ismailov was accused of intentionally killing someone during the
unrest ``from hooligan motives.''
   Tass said legal proceedings were continuing against other
defendants accused of participating in the rioting that broke out
Feb. 28 in Sumgait, an industrial city on the Caspian Sea. No other
details of the trials were reported.
   The disorder was sparked by a campaign in neighboring Armenia
for annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. The
majority of the people in the small, mountainous region are
Christian Armenians, and Armenians say they are repressed by
Azeris, who are Moslems.
   Armenian activists said bands of Azeris hunted down and killed
Armenians during the riot in Sumgait.
   More than 80 people have been charged with criminal offenses in
the rioting, in which 26 Armenians and six Azeris died and 200
people were injured.
