<HEAD>Feedlot Cattle Up 4 Percent From Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as
of May 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 7.5 million head,
up 4 percent from a year ago and 6 percent from two years ago, the
Agriculture Department said Monday.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in April totaled 1.61 million head,
up 5 percent from a year ago but 1 percent below two years ago.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported at 1.53 million head, down 9 percent from a year
ago and 2 percent below April 1986.
   As of May 1, feedlot inventories were larger than a year earlier
in five states and down in Arizona and Texas. The states account
for about three-fourths of the nation's beef production.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of May 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
