<2ND_LINE>AM-Sorzano Resignation,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Aide on Latin Affairs Resigning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Sorzano, a top Latin American affairs
aide to national security adviser Colin Powell, will leave his post
at the end of the month, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said Monday.
   Sorzano, who was born in Cuba and is known for his strong
support for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, declined in a telephone
interview to discuss his reasons for leaving after 16 months at the
NSC.
   But The Washington Times quoted a senior official as saying
Sorzano is leaving because deputy national security adviser John
Negroponte considered Sorzano's views to be ``too hardline'' and
``insulted him in staff meetings.''
   Sorzano was senior aide to then-United Nations Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick during President Reagan's first term.
</TEXT>
