<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MaternityLeave     05-16 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maternity Leave,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Official Remains Hopeful of Resolving Maternity Leave Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Justice Department official said Monday
he remains hopeful that a senior attorney involved in a maternity
leave dispute with the department will return to work despite her
vow not to come back.
   But Assistant Attorney General John Bolton, who heads the
department's criminal division, said a schedule cannot be arranged
until attorney Joan Bernott provides information to enable the
department to determine what duties she can perform.
   ``I said to her we will do nothing to jeopardize her health,''
said Bolton, who has offered Ms. Bernott the possibility of working
part-time.
   Bolton had ordered Ms. Bernott to return to work May 31 or
submit additional medical information from her doctor giving a
reason why her leave should be extended to mid-August.
   On May 4, Bolton rejected her request, which is supported by a
note from her doctor, to extend her leave without pay to Aug. 15.
Ms. Bernott, who went on maternity leave Jan. 25, is seeking seven
months instead of the usual three months to four months leave.
   Last week, Bolton extended her leave to May 31 pending receipt
of more information from her doctor.
   But Ms. Bernott said Monday she'll probably get fired.
   ``I'm not going to go back against my doctor's advice and my own
best judgment,'' she said on CBS-TV's ``This Morning'' program. ``I
think I'll be AWOL, which will subject me to disciplinary
proceedings and discharge.''
   Bolton refused to speculate on what steps may be taken if Ms.
Bernott fails to return to work, but he said he remains hopeful she
will comply with the request for additional medical information.
   Ms. Bernott, 42, obtained a letter from her physician, Dr.
Sandra M. Chase, on March 28 saying she needed an additional four
months of recuperation from a difficult pregnancy.
   ``Return to work now, in my opinion, represents health risk to
this patient,'' the doctor said in a follow-up April 26 letter
submitted as a result of Bolton's request for more information.
   Ms. Bernott charged in the interview that Bolton has made
accusations and threats beyond his request for additional
information from her doctors.
   ``He is holding three letters from two of my physicians. And he
hasn't just denied my request for leave, he has issued reprisals
against me, accused me of fraud, asked me to sign waivers of
confidentiality of all my medical records,'' Ms. Bernott said. ``He
has demanded that my physicians answer 27 questions _ probing
details of their opinion and my medical condition.
   ``He has canceled a reassignment that had been arranged for me
about a year ago and has been in the works since then,'' she said.
   Bolton said the queries are consistent with information the
department normally requests in considering all any extended leave
request from an employee, including maternity leave.
   He also said he has left the door open on the subject of her
reassignment in the divison.
   Ms. Bernott, who has three children, was the department's lead
attorney in successfully defending the government against
litigation surrounding the use of the defoliant Agent Orange during
the Vietnam War.
   Bolton said the civil division faces an enormous workload and
that it was vital that its 25 senior attorney positions _ one of
which is held by Ms. Bernott _ be staffed fully.
</TEXT>
