<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Youth,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Tells Youths He'll Try for Better U.S.-Soviet Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told a group of American and
Soviet high school students Monday he hopes to work for greater
people-to-people contacts between the two superpowers.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, greeted about 50 students gathered
in the White House East Room after the president made brief remarks.
   The president noted that the young members of the organization
known as Direct Connection had held a summit meeting recently in
Helsinki, Finland, and that they had taken positions on several
issues.
   ``You agreed to a set of resolutions on ways to develop better
communication and understanding, to protect the envirionment and to
press for increased cooperation between our countries,'' he said.
   ``Now I hope to expand our cooperative exchanges with the Soviet
Union to increase the cultural, educational and people-to-people
contacts, like yours, that are indispensable,'' Reagan said. ``And
I want you to know that I'll read your proposal carefully and take
it to heart as I leave for Moscow for my next meeting'' with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, he said.
   The members of the Direct Connection group held a youth summit
in Helsinki last week, then traveled to Moscow where they met with
Gorbachev and other Soviet officials.
