<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Copper-7Trial Bjt   05-16 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copper-7 Trial, Bjt,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IUD Trial: Civil Suit Opens against Contraceptive Device Maker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The once widely used Copper-7
intrauterine contraceptive device was back on trial Monday, and
plaintiffs' attorneys said they were armed with internal documents
never before used against the G.D. Searle & Co. product.
   The Minneapolis law firm Robins, Zelle, Larson & Kaplan, which
represented plaintiffs in earlier litigation against Dalkon Shield
maker A.H. Robins Co., settling 198 cases for a total of $38
million, also is representing the plaintiffs in the case against
Searle.
   Robins Zelle, which is representing more than 30 other women in
separate Copper-7 lawsuits, has said evidence introduced in the
firm's first trial against Searle is expected to set a foundation
for lawsuits to come.
   U.S. District Judge Robert G. Renner questioned potential jurors
Monday to hear the suit brought by Esther R. Kociemba, 29, of the
Melrose area northwest of here, and her husband, William. Opening
arguments were planned Tuesday.
   While 17 other cases involving the Copper-7 nationwide have gone
to trial, attorney Roger P. Brosnahan has said his law firm will
introduce internal company documents not used in those trials.
Those documents, he said, will show that Searle marketed the IUDs
without regard for women's health and safety.
   Searle, which won 14 of the earlier cases, has denied that its
IUD caused any injury to the women. One of the cases lost by Searle
is on appeal.
   When they filed the suit in October 1984, the Kociembas asked
for $500,000 in compensatory damages and $500,000 in punitive
damages, plus court costs, for injuries Mrs. Kociemba allegedly
suffered as a result of using a Copper-7 IUD for just under 1{
years in 1977 and 1978. The couple later amended their lawsuit to
ask for an unspecified amount.
   According to the suit, Mrs. Kociemba has experienced
infertility, illnesses, ``great pain, suffering and mental
anguish'' that have continued since she had the IUD removed in
November 1978.
   More than a dozen attorneys for Robins Zelle have been going
through documents involved in the Searle IUD cases for more than
three years in preparation for the trial, Brosnahan said.
   ``We have gone through some 500,000 or more documents,'' he said.
   In addition, the law firm began taking the depositions of Searle
employees, former employees, outside testing groups and expert
witnesses named on Searle's behalf about 2{ years ago, he said.
   ``There have been 60 or 70 of those depositions, which consume
about 15,000 pages of transcript,'' Brosnahan said. ``Very few of
the documents and none of the deposition testimony was ever used in
the previous trials.
   ``So, in our judgment, it will be the first real trial involving
the Copper-7,'' he said.
   Spokeswoman Kay Bruno at Searle headquarters in Skokie, Ill.,
disputed that, saying Searle doesn't view the suit as much
different from earlier suits brought against the company. Many of
the documents have been used in previous court cases, she said.
   Searle withdrew the Copper-7 and its other IUD, the TATUM-T,
from the U.S. market and stopped manufacturing the two items in
January 1986, citing the cost of litigation and the unavailability
of liability insurance. However, the IUDs still are available in
foreign countries.
   Bruno said more than 800 lawsuits involving the IUD have been
filed against Searle. Of those, many have been settled out of
court. She said about 500 suits still are pending against the
company.
   The Copper-7, a small device made of plastic and copper, was
approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in 1974 and
Searle sold between 300,000 and 400,000 IUDs in the United States
annually before withdrawing the product from the U.S. market.
   In the Kociemba Copper-7 trial, Brosnahan said Robins Zelle
attorneys believe they can establish through the testimony of
Searle employees and former employees and through the company's
internal documents that Searle was not honest with physicians or
the public about potential problems related to the Copper-7.
   ``We think the evidence will clearly show that the company was
not telling the doctors or the women what they knew and, in fact,
were telling them things that were contrary to what they knew or
had every good reason to know,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
