<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldBank-Women     05-16 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-Women,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Increases Aid for Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank announced new programs Monday
to aid women in eight countries where male interests traditionally
dominate.
   The countries are Kenya, Nigeria, Zimbabwe, India, Bangladesh,
Pakistan. Morocco and Mexico.
   ``You will see pathfinding investments on behalf of women in a
wide range of activities _ in education generally, in both formal
and informal training for employment, in agricultural extension and
financing, in health and family planning services and in
environmental protection,'' said Barber B. Conable, president of
the World Bank.
   The bank is the chief source of aid to nearly 120 Third World
countries. It makes loans of $17 billion a year and is planning an
increase to well beyond the $20 billion level in the 1990s. The
United States is the largest shareholder, joined in contributions
by more than 30 others.
   Conable said there will be added support for women in other
countries as well as the eight singled out.
   He was speaking to the Overseas Education Fund of the League of
Women Voters. It gave him and his wife, Charlotte, an award in
recognition of help to women in poor countries.
   ``What you will see, and what I hope you will take part in, is a
determined drive not just to overcome discrimination and the
poverty it reinforces but to put women at the forefront of the
fight against poverty in the developing world,'' he said.
   He saw a change in policies toward women in the Third World.
   ``In access to education, to credit, to basic health services,
we are in the midst of a revolution, but one that still leaves
women too far behind,'' Conable said.
   ``So the revolution we must continue is the one that closes the
gap between men and women in the Third World by creating
opportunities for both sexes.''
   Help for women in the Third World has been the subject of a
clash between the Reagan administration and some members of
Congress. A bill supported by Democratic legislators would order
the U.S. Agency for International Development to make sure its
training programs abroad enroll as many women as men.
   AID Administrator Alan M. Woods opposes the bill on the ground
that it would hamper his agency's programs in countries that
traditionally deny many rights to women.
</TEXT>
