<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TabathaFuneral     05-16 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tabatha Funeral,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Not A Time For Mourning: Pastor Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISONVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen ministers backed by a gospel
choir and soloists bade farewell to transplant patient Tabatha
Nicole Foster on Monday, urging those who followed the child's
struggle to consider the love she had for life.
   Attendants waved fans to revive several people in the
congregation of about 300 during the emotional service for the
toddler who had been the longest Survivor of a five-organ
transplant when she died Wednesday.
   The Rev. Robert L. Cottoner, pastor of the family's Oak Grove
Baptist Church here, based a eulogy on 1 Corinthians, Chapter 13:
   ``So faith, hope, love abide, these three; but the greatest of
these is love.''
   ``Keep the faith, hold on to the hope, but love will bear every
burden,'' Cottoner said as members of the congregation clapped and
shouted: ``That's all right. Yes sir.''
   ``You'll find that faith testifies, hope pacifies but love
satisfies,'' Cottoner said. The service was held at First Baptist
Church moved from Oak Grove, where Tabatha's mother, Sandra Foster,
was choir director, to accommodate more guests.
   Family members and friends later placed flowers atop the child's
small, white casket before the burial.
   The 3-year-old died at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh after
an infection caused her heart, kidneys and liver to fail, hospital
officials said. The toddler, born with an intestinal deformity,
received the transplant during a 15-hour experimental operation
that ended Nov. 1.
   Contributors from across the country, including President Reagan
and singer Frank Sinatra, gave more than $300,000 to help the
family pay medical bills.
   The Rev. Sue Corlett, chaplain at Kosair Children's Hospital in
Louisville while Tabatha was treated there, attended the service
along with six nurses who had cared for the child.
   ``This is real difficult for us to see her dead because she was
always so alive,'' Corlett said. ``There are 90- and 100-year-old
people who didn't live as much as she did.''
   ``She touched everyone that got involved,'' Beverly Brangers, a
nurse at Kosair, said as she wiped tears from her eyes at the
cemetery. ``You couldn't help but love her.''
   Cottoner urged the congregation not to mourn for the girl.
   ``This is a time for rejoicing. After all the things she's
endured, she's resting peacefully,'' the minister said. ``It's time
for us to rejoice that another of God's children has been called
from labor to refreshment.''
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson, preoccupied by a church bus crash that
killed 27 people outside Carrollton during the weekend, sent a
representative and a message to the family.
   ``Seldom has such a young life had such a mighty impact on a
state and a nation,'' the statement said. ``Tabatha fought a strong
and cheerful battle on behalf of us all.''
</TEXT>
