<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru a0664 05-16 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens of Extremists Refuse to Leave Golden Temple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with number of troops in siege
and 42 slain in Sikh attacks elsewhere in Punjab. Pick up 15th graf
pvs: Sarabjeet Singh...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces on Monday bombarded
lookout towers in the Golden Temple with incendiary bombs and fired
machine guns to try to dislodge dozens of radical Sikhs.
   Police said more than 50 militants remained in the compound,
which has been surrounded by more than 2,800 police and troopers
for a week. The 400-year-old temple is the Sikh religion's holiest
shrine and center of a violent campaign for a separate Sikh nation
in Punjab state.
   At least 35 people, most of them Sikh militants, have been
killed.
   Elsewhere in Punjab, 42 people were killed in attacks by Sikh
extremists in different attacks in a 24-hour period, United News of
India reported.
   A paramilitary officer involved in the Golden Temple siege said,
``We will have to starve them out or think of other alternatives. I
think we will be here for quite some time.''
   He spoke with reporters while seven of the 146 Sikhs who
surrendered Sunday appealed to their comrades to give up.
   ``Please come out with your hands up,'' Skatter Singh said
through a loudspeaker. ``The officers are good to us. None of us
has been troubled.''
   Sporadic gunfire was the only response from militants inside the
20-foot-high walls.
   Skatter Singh belongs to the Khalistan Commando Force, one of
several Sikh separatist groups with offices in the Golden Temple
compound. Khalistan is what the Sikhs would call their nation.
   The seven made their appeals during two pauses in army firing at
two 18th century brick towers in the compound.
   At dusk, a new saffron-colored Khalistan flag fluttered from the
window of one soot-covered clock tower at the northern entrance to
the temple complex.
   On Monday evening, commandoes of the Black Cat anti-terrorist
squad were seen moving into a dining hall in front of the towers.
   Sources said an underground passage links the dining hall and
towers. They said about five militants were thought to be in the
basement of the towers.
   United News of India gave this report of the killings by Sikh
extremists in Punjab Sunday night and Monday:
   Gunmen opened fire on crowds in Samana town, killing 18 people
and wounding 18. In Samrai village, five people were shot to death.
   Sikh terrorists in a car fired at a doctor's clinic in Mukerian
town, killing a 2-month-old child and another person. The owner of
the clinic, Dr. Kewal Krishan, was wounded.
   At least 17 other people were killed in scattered attacks in the
northern state.
   The deaths raised the number of people killed in attacks blamed
on Sikh radicals to at least 1,002 this year. Most of the victims
were Hindus but some were Sikh moderates.
   Sarabjeet Singh, deputy police commissioner in Amritsar, said at
least 40 Sikh radicals were in the Golden Temple's inner sanctum,
which is surrounded by a vast pool and approachable only by a
marble walkway.
   ``We do not want to hurt the sentiments of the Sikh community by
doing anything that might harm the Harimandir Sahib (inner
sanctum),'' said Chaman Lal, inspector general of police in Punjab
state. ``But at the same time, we are trying to convey to them (the
militants) that we mean business.''
   Devout Sikhs would view any attempt to storm the inner sanctum
as desecration.
   Prime Minister Indira Gandhi sent the army into the Golden
Temple in 1984 to drive out Sikh extremists and was assassinated by
Sikh bodyguards five months later. More than 1,200 people were
killed in the assault.
   Militants have fought a terrorist war since 1982 for a Sikh
nation.
   Sikhs make up only 2 percent of India's 800 million people and
claim discrimination by Hindus, who account for 82 percent. Sikhs
are a majority in Punjab state.
   K.P.S. Gill, police chief of Punjab, told a news conference
Monday that 146 people surrendered Sunday, not 151 as another
official reported earlier.
   Gill said 17 had been freed, one committed suicide and 128 were
held on charges ranging from waging war against the state to
illegal possession of arms.
</TEXT>
