<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DramaCriticsAward     05-16 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drama Critics Award,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Drama Critics Honor `Joe Turner's Come and Gone'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' by August Wilson
was chosen Monday as best new play of the 1987-88 theater season by
the New York Drama Critics Circle.
   ``The Road to Mecca'' by South African playwright Athol Fugard
was picked as best foreign play, while ``Into the Woods,'' a fairy
tale musical by Stephen Sondheim and James Lapine, was named best
musical.
   It was the third time Wilson has won the best play award,
getting the honor in 1984 for ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' and
again in 1987 for ``Fences.'' Sondheim and Lapine are also previous
winners, taking the musical award in 1984 for ``Sunday in the Park
with George.''
   ``Joe Turner,'' currently running at the Ethel Barrymore
Theater, is set in a Pittsburgh boarding house in 1911. The drama
concerns the children of slaves coming to terms with their past.
   Memebers of the New York Drama Critics Circle include Clive
Barnes and Marilyn Stasio of The New York Post; John Beaufort, The
Christian Science Monitor; Michael Feingold and Julius Novick, The
Village Voice; William Henry III, Time; Richard Hummler, Variety;
Howard Kissel, Don Nelsen, and Douglas Watt, the New York Daily
News; Mimi Kramer and Edith Oliver, The New Yorker; Jack Kroll,
Newsweek; Michael Kuchwara, The Associated Press; Jacques le Sourd,
Gannett Newspapers; David Lida, Women's Wear Daily; William Raidy,
the Newhouse group; Frank Rich and Mel Gussow, The New York Times;
John Simon, New York; Allan Wallach, Newsday; Edwin Wilson and
Sylviane Gold, The Wall Street Journal.
</TEXT>
