<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Africa     05-16 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Africa,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Soviet Officials To Discuss Southern Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top U.S. and Soviet experts on African affairs
will meet in Portugal on Wednesday to prepare for discussions
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on
southern African issues later this month, an administration
official said Monday.
   The American delegation will be led by Assistant Secretary of
State Chester A. Crocker and the Soviet side will be headed by
Anatoly Adamishin, a deputy foreign minister.
   U.S. officials, asking not to be identified, said they expect
southern African issues to be thoroughly discussed at the summit
meeting in Moscow in two weeks.
   Moscow and Washington have been supporting opposite sides in
Angola's 13-year-old civil war.
   The administration has been seeking a negotiated settlement that
will lead to both a Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola and
independence and black majority rule in neighboring Namibia,
administered by South Africa.
   Crocker and Adamishin discussed the southern African question
last month in London before an unprecedented four-way meeting
involving officials from the United States, South Africa, Angola
and Cuba.
</TEXT>
