<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AllAcademic     05-16 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-All Academic,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top High School Students Urged To Stump for Education Back Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr. exhorted 20 of
the nation's top high school seniors Monday to ``stir 'em up'' back
home on behalf of education spending and opportunity for all
children.
   Weicker, R-Conn., said neither the Reagan administration,
Congress nor the public at large was sufficiently committed to
education.
   Addressing an awards luncheon for USA Today's All-USA Academic
First Team, Weicker charged that none of the current presidential
candidates has made education a cornerstone of his campaign,
despite ``a few perfunctory statements'' by Vice President George
Bush about wanting to be ``the education president.''
   ``I certainly welcome that within my own party. It will be the
first one in a long time,'' the maverick Republican said.
   ``Those of you that are the winners, do me a favor when you get
back home. Stir 'em up. Stir 'em up. Tell 'em, `Whatever
opportunity has been given me isn't shared by that much of the
nation.' Make certain that all of our children have that special
education ... that brings opportunity,'' Weicker said.
   ``You ask that candidate that stands up, `Are you for
education?' And don't be satisfied when that candidate says, `I'm
for education.' Are you willing to pay for that education?''
Weicker said.
   ``It's easy to be against drugs, and it's easy to be for
education. It's not so easy to pay for the war on drugs or pay for
education,'' Weicker said.
   The All-USA team was chosen by a panel of 10 educators from more
than 900 students nominated by their high school principals. The
contest, in its second year, is co-sponsored by the National
Education Association and the National Association of Secondary
School Principals.
   The winners, all seniors, were 10 boys and 10 girls with average
grades of 3.97 on a scale of 4.0, and average scores of 1,413 on
the Scholastic Aptitude Test and 31.3 on the American College Test.
   For most, their accomplishments outside the classroom, recited
by USA Today Editor John C. Quinn at a banquet at the newspaper's
headquarters, were as formidable as their grades.
   The winners were:
   _Pamela Abshire of Salem (Va.) High School, a licensed pilot who
has conducted research on how plants develop immunity from crown
gull tumor.
   _Deborah Cheng of Rolla (Mo.) Senior High School, who has
studied the effects of heavy salts on plants and microorganisms.
   _Charles Doran of Walt Whitman High School in Bethesda, Md., who
developed a new concept in statistical math.
   _Nathan Gilliland of Northwest High School in Omaha, Neb., who
