<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending     05-16 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal Allowing Death Penalty for Drug Dealers Still Under
Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, trying to wrap up work on a
Pentagon budget bill, refused Monday to eliminate a proposal
permitting the death penalty for drug dealers who are convicted of
killing people.
   The Senate voted 68-27 not to table, and thus kill, the death
penalty proposal offered by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   ``The American people are entitled to this protection,'' said
D'Amato. ``I think we have to find a clearer message for those who
deal in drugs. ... The death-dealing drug lords fear no one.''
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and other opponents noted that
D'Amato's amendment had nothing specifically to do with the
Pentagon budget and should be considered in another forum. Senate
rules do not require that amendments be germane to pending
legislation.
   But Levin also opposed the amendment because he said studies
have shown that people sometimes are wrongly convicted of crimes.
   ``The main reason I'm opposed to capital punishment is that you
cannot correct your mistakes,'' Levin said. ``Time and time again,
we've found that we've convicted the wrong man.''
   Levin's unsuccessful move to kill D'Amato's amendment left the
D'Amato plan in limbo. It has not been adopted and thus is still
one of the unresolved issues as the Senate tries to finish work on
the Pentagon bill.
   Opponents of D'Amato's plan have threatened to filibuster his
amendment in an effort to prevent a vote on it.
   The Senate is tentatively scheduled to take a final vote Tuesday
morning on the bill, which authorizes $299.5 billion in Pentagon
spending for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   Senate passage of the Pentagon budget would send it to a
House-Senate conference committee, where it would have to be
reconciled with the separate defense budget approved last week by
that chamber.
   The House bill does not contain any provisions similar to
D'Amato's death penalty plan and addition of the proposal could
hold up final action on the Pentagon budget for months, said Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   ``We won't be able to get a defense bill with this amendment on
it,'' said Nunn, adding that he supported the amendment.
   He explained that addition of the D'Amato amendment would mean
that a conference committee would have to involve the House
Judiciary Committee, which has jurisdiction over such legislation
in that chamber. That committee opposes the plan.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas responded that ``50
percent of the American people list drugs as the number one
problem. ... They don't care about our little jurisdictional
disputes.''
   D'Amato first offered his proposal last week, shortly after the
Senate voted overwhelmingly to grant new powers to the military to
enter the fight against illegal drug trafficking.
   D'Amato said, ``I am not suggesting this idea is a panacea,''
but he noted, ``I think it will help.''
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., echoed Levin's opposition, noting that
``our history has a number of instances where innocent persons have
been executed. ... I suggest this is not the way to go.''
   In other decisions Monday, the Senate:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Voted 63-30 to table, and thus kill, an amendment by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., which said the United States could not follow the
terms of the agreement in which the Soviet Union agreed to pull
troops out of Afghanistan unless President Reagan sent the
agreement to the Senate as a formal treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
