<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Wealth     05-16 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Wealth,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Millionares Down to Just One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, which two years ago
included three millionaires among its members, apparently has just
one remaining _ Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
   The court's newest member, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, fell
short of millionaire status. He listed assets in 1987 at somewhere
between $348,000 and $920,000.
   Kennedy joined the court earlier this year.
   According to financial disclosure reports released in compliance
with the Ethics in Government Act, O'Connor listed her net worth
for 1987 as at least $1.3 million.
   The law requires only broad ranges of value for the reporting of
assets. It does not require that any asset worth less than $1,000
be listed, nor the value of personal property items and the
official's primary residence.
   O'Connor listed assets for herself and her husband, attorney
John O'Connor, worth between $1.3 million and $2.3 million or more
in 1987. For 1986, she had listed family assets worth between
$913,000 and $1.9 million.
   Former Chief Justice Warren E. Burger and former Justice Lewis
F. Powell, a pair of millionaires, retired during the past two
years.
   Among the more noteworthy information included in this year's
disclosure forms:
   _Justice Antonin Scalia received $12,000 in honoria as payment
for speaking to various organizations. He also earned $13,500 from
Louisiana State University and $1,300 from Tulane University for
summer teaching jobs. Scalia also received a gift, a $350 pair of
cowboy boots, for serving as a B'Nai B'rith dinner speaker in
Albuquerque, N.M.
   _Justice William J. Brennan received a $3,500 advance from a
book publisher for a compilation of his speeches that is in the
works.
   _Justice Thurgood Marshall, as he has in past years, swore that
his only asset is a savings account worth between $15,000 and
$50,000.
   The court's eight associate justices are paid $110,000 a year.
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist's annual salary is $115,000.
   Here are the listed 1987 assets of the court's members:
   _Rehnquist, $136,000 to $380,000, up from the $116,000 to
$210,000 listed for 1986.
   _O'Connor, $1.3 million to $2.3 million or more, up from
$913,000 to $1.9 million.
   _Scalia, $65,000 to $150,000, down from $120,000 to $285,000.
   _Kennedy, $348,000 to $920,000.
   _Brennan, $141,000 to $485,000, up from $120,000 to $395,000.
   _Marshall, $15,000 to $50,000, unchanged.
   _Justice John Paul Stevens, $177,000 to $385,000, up from
$50,000 to $165,000.
   _Justice Harry A. Blackmun, $225,000 to $680,000, up from
$195,000 to $645,000.
   _Justice Byron R. White, $145,000 to $250,000 or more, up from
the $20,000 to $60,000 listed for 1986. White's listed assets for
1985 were between $145,000 and $400,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
