<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AstroPoll     05-16 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Astro Poll,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Get the Aquarians While More Libras Lean to GOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aquarians tend to consider themselves Democrats
and Libras are more likely than others to lean toward the
Republican Party _ but don't tell the plurality of Americans who
reject astrology.
   The latest entry in the political debate over the influence of
the stars comes courtesy of Public Opinion magazine, a bimonthly
publication of the American Enterprise Institute for Public Policy
Research in Washington.
   Picking up on the discussion sparked by disclosures that
astrological considerations have played a role in President
Reagan's schedule, Public Opinion compiled data from past polls
including these tidbits:
   _Democrats drew 47 percent of Aquarians but just 32 percent of
Libras in surveys done from 1985-87 by the National Opinion
Research Center.
   _Another 32 percent of Libras considered themselves Republicans,
but only 28 percent of Aquarians and just 25 percent of
Sagittarians backed the GOP.
   _Their sign aside, 47 percent of adults polled by the Roper
Organization in 1985 said they did not believe in astrology. Thirty
percent weren't sure, while 23 percent believed in the influence of
the stars.
   Public Opinion figured the breakdown of party identification
according to astrological sign by separating the Democrats,
Republicans and independents by birth date.
   Why bother? ``Because we never miss an opportunity to get Public
Opinion magazine's name in the press,'' said Graham Hueber, the
assistant editor.
</TEXT>
