<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HorseRingworm     05-16 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Ringworm,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ringworm Discovered in Two BLM Corrals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ringworm has been diagnosed in about 800
horses owned by the Bureau of Land Management at two corrals in
Nevada and Nebraska, the bureau said Monday.
   The contagious but treatable fungus disease was found in about
700 horses at contractor-operated corrals at Lovelock, Nev., and as
many as 100 more at Bloomfield, Neb., bureau spokesman Tim Locke
said.
   Each corral holds about 2,700 horses, Locke said. Together they
hold the major portion of the 8,600 horses the bureau has rounded
up from public lands in the West. The BLM is trying to find
suitable owners to adopt the horses.
   The bureau has continued to transfer horses from its corrals,
``But I can assure you unequivocally that none has been moved
without the veterinarian's OK,'' Locke said. Bureau policy is that
no horses are moved without a vet's approval ``and our policy is
being followed,'' he said.
   The bureau, he said, notified the Agriculture Department's
veterinarians for Nevada, and was advised by veterinarian Ron
Anderson ``to treat it. At this time he is not imposing a
quarantine,'' as some advocacy groups had asked.
   At Bloomfield, Locke said, ``the situation is under control.''
   Jim Clapp of Singletown, Calif., head of the Wild Horse
Sanctuary, said he saw horses with strangles, infections of the
lymph nodes, on a visit to Lovelock last week, but Locke said he
had no reports of that.
</TEXT>
