<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0742 05-16 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Meets With Shultz, Other Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS four grafs to update with US expressing concern over
Israeli tactics for subduing West Bank unrest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
explored avenues for Arab-Israeli peacemaking during talks Monday
with Secretary of State George P. Shultz, other government
officials and members of Congress.
   Peres went to Shultz's home for breakfast and met him again at a
luncheon hosted by Israeli Ambassador Moshe Arad. Also present at
the luncheon were Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, White House
chief of staff Howard Baker and leaders of Congress.
   The State Department said it did not have any information about
the morning meeting, except that the two leaders discussed Shultz's
moribund plan for Arab-Israeli peace talks. Israeli officials said
neither Shultz nor Peres wanted to divulge details of their talks,
which were to continue Tuesday.
   At a luncheon toast, Shultz praised Peres' ``creativity'' in
seeking to advance peace talks. Shultz, who has scheduled his
fourth shuttle of the year to the Mideast next month, said Jordan
and Israel had neither rejected nor accepted his peace plan.
   Quoting a favorite Peres analogy, Shultz said the violent
situation in the region is ``like a pregnant woman _ it cannot
continue to be pregnant for long.''
   Peres, in his remarks, called on Shultz to press for acceptance
of the U.S. initiative, saying there were many obstacles in its way
``but the alternative is more serious. ... I prefer an imperfect
peace to a perfect war.''
   Peres supports the Shultz plan, but his rival in Israel's
coalition government, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, opposes the
blueprint. Jordan's King Hussein has also expressed reservations,
Syria has rejected the plan and Egypt is the only country to
support it openly.
   Peres was also meeting with members of Congress to discuss the
peace process, the five-month Palestinian rebellion in the
Israeli-occupied territories and planned U.S. arms sales to Saudi
Arabia.
   Dozens of members from both the Senate and House have expressed
reservations about the administration's plan to sell the Saudis a
$325 million support and maintenance package for electronic
surveillance AWACS planes and $200 million worth of Bradley
fighting vehicles.
   The congressmen are upset with the Saudis for their clandestine
purchase of Chinese-made intermediate range missiles, which could
hit Israel.
   Peres' meetings with Shultz and with President Reagan on
Tuesday, which are not expected to produce movement on the stalled
peace plan, are viewed by Israelis as a bid by Peres for U.S.
support in advance of Israel's fall election campaign.
   Peres, head of the Labor Party, will face off against Shamir,
leader of the right-wing Likud bloc.
   Shamir opposes the Shultz plan because it envisions oversight by
the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council _
the United States, China, the Soviet Union, England and France.
Shamir fears the five powers would coerce Israel to give up Arab
lands it captured in the 1967 Mideast war.
   In another development Monday, Assistant Secretary of State for
Human Rights Richard Schifter told a Peres aide the United States
was concerned that Israel's tactics to subdue the five-month
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip were
getting harsher, said an Israeli official.
   Schifter told Israeli Foreign Ministry Director Yossi Beilin
that ``he was concerned the exceptions were becoming the norm,''
said the official, who asked not to be named.
   Israel has repeatedly said cases of abuse against Palestinians
were unauthorized exceptions and the soldiers committing them would
be punished. Some 180 Palestinians have been killed in the rioting,
and thousands have been wounded by tear gas, clubs and bullets.
   Schifter himself declined to comment on the meeting. U.S. public
criticism of Israel's tactics has been muted, in keeping with a
belief that addressing the problem in private diplomatic contacts
is more effective.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Peres went, 2nd graf previous</HEAD>
