<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra     05-16 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Names McFarlane as Unindicted Co-Conspirator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former national security adviser Robert C.
McFarlane was identified Monday as an unindicted Iran-Contra
co-conspirator in Oliver L. North's motion to be tried separately
from his three co-defendants.
   The legal status of McFarlane, who pleaded guilty to misdemeanor
charges of withholding information from Congress about secret
Reagan administration aid to Nicaraguan Contra rebels, was
mentioned in a footnote to North's request for a separate trial.
   The names of the unindicted co-conspirators in the case have
been sealed by the court.
   The defense brief, along with naming McFarlane, identifies the
other unindicted co-conspirators as Fawn Hall, North's former
secretary at the National Security Council; Joe Fernandez, a former
CIA agent also known as Tomas Castillo, and Marine Lt. Col. Robert
Earl, North's aide at the NSC.
   Hall and Earl are cooperating with the investigation by
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh under grants of immunity from
prosecution.
   Neither McFarlane's lawyer, Leonard Garment, nor James Wieghart,
a spokesman for Walsh, would comment on the defense revelations.
   North, former national security adviser John M. Poindexter, and
arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard
V. Secord, all asked to be tried separately on charges stemming
from their involvement in the diversion of U.S.-Iran arms-sale
profits to the Contras.
   In their motions for separate trials, the defendants said they
wanted to use the congressional testimony of their co-defendants to
prove their innocence.
   A joint trial of all four defendants would unfairly prejudice
the case against them because all the defendants, except Secord,
testified before Congress under limited grants of immunity from
prosecution, the defense said.
   ``The court must grant each defendant a separate trial to
protect both the Fifth Amendment right of defendants North,
Poindexter and Hakim to be tried before a jury that has not been
exposed to their immunized testimony or its fruits, and the Sixth
Amendment right of each defendant to use the immunized testimony of
his co-defendants and its fruits in his defense,'' North's lawyers
said in their brief.
   The lawyers for North, a former NSC aide, noted a further
complication involving McFarlane, who returned to the Iran-Contra
committee last year for additional questioning following North's
appearance.
   The defense noted that Walsh acknowledged in a staff memo last
summer that McFarlane's testimony ``was likely tainted'' because it
was given ``in direct response to Lt. Col. North's immunized
testimony.''
   ``The IC (independent counsel) has also made clear that
McFarlane, an alleged unindicted co-conspirator, will be a key
prosecution witness,'' the North brief said. ``Lt. Col. North's
co-defendants are certainly entitled to cross-examine McFarlane
about his tainted testimony.''
   McFarlane was identified in the defense brief as an unindicted
co-conspirator in the conspiracy to defraud the government count
that charges all four defendants. The brief says Ms. Hall,
Fernandez and Earl are also unindicted co-conspirators in that
count of the indictment.
   McFarlane, who resigned as national security adviser in late
1995, traveled with North to Tehran in May 1986 on a plane that
delivered spare parts for Hawk missiles. McFarlane carried a Bible
signed by President Reagan and a cake in the shape of a key that
were presented to the Iranians in the negotiations to free hostages
held in Lebanon in exchange for arms sales to Iran.
   McFarlane, who is also cooperating with Walsh's investigation,
could receive a prison sentence of up to four years and a $400,000
fine for his guilty plea to misdemeanor charges of withholding
information from various congressional committees that inquired
into covert aid to the Contras during a ban on direct U.S. military
assistance.
   In other developments in the case, the prosecution made another
stab at obtaining nearly 3,000 pages of diaries that North kept
while he was at the NSC.
   The recently retired Marine lieutenant colonel last week invoked
the Fifth Amendment when the diaries were subpoenaed by a Senate
Foreign Relations subcommittee.
   Walsh, who has unsuccessfully tried to subpoena the material,
asked that they be produced as part of pre-trial discovery for
``any and all notebooks, journals or ledgers kept by the
defendants.''
   The request also included documents of financial transactions
involving a series of companies used by Hakim and Secord to broker
arms to the Iranians and to ferry materiel to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Walsh also accused the defense of ignoring U.S. District Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell's order to specifically challenge the application
of the Classified Information Procedures Act to the case.
   The law sets out procedures for disclosure of secret government
documents during a criminal trial. Walsh has amassed some 300,000
pages of classified documents in his investigation.
   Walsh contended that the defense ``did not attempt to
substantiate the specific problems'' they had identified with
complying with the law raising instead ``hypothetical and abstract
arguments'' about the law's constitutionality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
