<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish     05-16 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicans On Both Sides Fear Return To Sectarian War of 1970s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bloody attack on a pub
patronized by Roman Catholics inspired fear Monday among Catholic
and Protestant politicians of a return to the sectarian warfare of
the 1970s.
   The Protestant Action Force, an outlawed paramilitary group,
claimed responsibility for the lunchtime shooting Sunday at the
Avenue Pub in downtown Belfast.
   Three people were killed and six wounded in an attack
reminiscent of those in the 1970s by Protestant paramilitary gangs
that opened fire at random on Catholic-owned pubs, businesses and
homes.
   Politicians on both sides appealed for calm after Sunday's
attack.
   ``I don't want any innocent Protestants to be killed as a result
of this,'' said Patrick McBride, whose 27-year-old brother Paul was
one of the three slain Catholics.
   Brian Feeney, a city council member for the Social Democratic
and Labor Party, a moderate Catholic group, said he feared the
murders were an attempt to revive the sectarian war.
   ``There has to be a rapid and visible response from the police
to protect people from these murderous exploits,'' he said. ``The
whole object of this exercise is to instill maximum terror in the
Catholic community, drive them off the streets back into their own
ghettos.''
   Cecil Walker of the Official Unionist Party, the largest
Protestant political group, said the killers were bent on
``creating havoc and sectarian strife in the community ... creating
pandemonium and chaos.''
   Ed Maloney, a co-biographer of The Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of
the hardline Protestant Democratic Unionist Party, said Protestant
paramilitary groups have targeted Catholic nationalists for 10
years but Sunday's shooting ``smacks of the early and mid-1970s, an
indiscriminate attack whose targets could only be innocent
Catholics.''
   The deaths of McBride, Damien Devlin, 24, and Stephen McGahan,
27, bring to 28 the number of civilians killed this year. At least
2,646 people have died since sectarian violence began in August
1969.
   In County Tyrone on Monday, a part-time soldier in the largely
Protestant Ulster Defense Regiment was seriously injured by a
booby-trap bomb on a farm where he worked.
   The Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to drive the
British out of predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland, claimed
responsibility. There was no indication of a connection with the
Belfast shooting.
</TEXT>
