<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-DukakisPolls     05-16 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Dukakis Polls,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Put Dukakis Ahead of Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis leads George Bush by 10
points in their likely presidential contest, in part on the
strength of voters who say the Democratic Party is better able to
handle key issues, a poll said Monday.
   The 1,382 adults interviewed in the CBS News-New York Times poll
listed drugs, unemployment and the federal deficit as the country's
most important problems, and said Democrats were better able to
handle them.
   Partly as a result, CBS News reported, 49 percent said they
would vote now for Dukakis, the Democratic front-runner, to 39
percent for Bush, who has clinched the Republican nomination. Ten
percent were undecided.
   Another new poll, by Louis Harris & Associates, gave Dukakis a
7-point lead. Such polls are not predictive of a contest so far off
as the November general election, but they can provide a general
sense of voter sympathies.
   The CBS-Times poll said 35 percent of the respondents had an
unfavorable view of Bush, to 33 percent favorable. Dukakis' rating
was better: 38 percent unfavorable, 14 percent unfavorable.
   However, Dukakis was less known; 21 percent said they had not
heard enough about him, and another 26 percent were undecided about
their opinion of him. For Bush, all but 10 percent had heard
enough, and 21 percent were undecided.
   Dukakis outscored Bush in several categories. Thirty-eight
percent though of Bush as ``too attached to special interests,'' to
only 17 percent who thought that of Dukakis.
   Fifty-five percent said they would be uneasy with Bush's
approach to a difficult international crisis; 42 percent said that
of Dukakis. Fifty-five percent said Bush was tough enough to make
hard choices, but 65 percent said that of Dukakis. And 49 percent
said Bush was ``hiding something that the public ought to know''
about the Iran-Contra affair.
   Respondents to the poll said the Republicans would be better at
dealing with the Soviets and at keeping America strong, but those
were not cited by a sizable number of responents as key issues.
   The most frequently cited issue was drugs, and a plurality of 37
percent said the Democrats were better able to handle the problem.
An even bigger share, 51 percent, said Democrats were better able
to handle unemployment.
   The CBS-Times poll was conducted by telephone with a random
nationwide sample of adults from May 9-12 and had a margin of
sampling error of 3 points.
   The Harris poll, of 2,138 voters, put the hypothetical race at
50 percent for Dukakis, 43 percent for Bush and 7 percent
undecided. That poll was done in two segments, April 1-5 and May
5-10, and also had a 3-point error margin.
</TEXT>
