<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan-Attacks 1stLd-Writethru a0701 05-16 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Attacks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Three In Connection With Deadly Blasts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 3 grafs, report of U.S. Embassy advisory; picks up
4th pvs `Police said'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALAH ZARROUG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men with Lebanese passports were
caught while trying to get rid of weapons after attacks that killed
seven people and wounded 21, including three Americans, police said
Monday.
   The attacks Sunday night occurred at the Acropol Hotel and
nearby Sudan Club. Diplomats, relief workers and journalists
frequent the hotel, and the club is reserved for nationals of
Britain and Commonwealth countries.
   Sudanese sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
U.S. Embassy advised Americans not to leave their homes. American
clubs in Khartoum had been closed, they said.
   Police said the dead at the Acropol, their bodies mangled by a
bomb that blew the tin roof off the two-story building, included a
British family of four who had been in Sudan for two months, a
waiter and a Sudanese army officer.
   There was no word on the identity of the three Americans injured
at the hotel.
   ``Limbs of those who were killed ... were scattered on the floor
of the restaurant after the explosion,'' said Col. Mutasim Osman
Karim, an explosives expert.
   An unidentified foreigner died during the attack later on the
Sudan Club, said a police statement rad Monday over the
government's Radio Omdurman.
   The statement said the suspects, who carried Lebanese passports
but were dressed in the traditional white robes of the Sudanese
when captured, were identified by witnesses as participants in the
assaults.
   Passers-by helped capture the suspects outside the Sudan Club
after the attack as they ``tried to get rid of the clothes they
were disguised in,'' the statement said.
   Police said the suspects attempted to ditch submachine guns,
ammunition and other items ``that provide material evidence of
their involvement in the attacks.''
   Karim said evidence at the club indicated the terrorists used
grenades and automatic weapons in their raid there.
   The men came to Sudan masquerading as Lebanese businessmen, the
statement said. It was not announced whether they had connections
with terrorist groups or other organizations.
   Karim said the explosives appeared to be Soviet-made.
   In London, a spokesman for the British Foreign Office: ``We have
no means at the moment of knowing if it is an attack aimed at
British interests, or whether it is wider than that.'' He spoke on
condition of anonymity, in accordance with British practice.
   No motive has been advanced for the attacks, which occurred as
Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi swore in a new Cabinet.
   In London, a private British relief charity, Ockenden Venture,
identifed the British family as Chris Rolfe, 35, his wife Clare,
37, and their children Thomas, 3, and Louise, 1. The charity said
the Rolfes were helping drought victims in eastern Sudan.
   A European man who said he witnessed the Acropol attack reported
the blasts blew the roof off the two-story building and smashed a
hole in the floor a yard wide.
   ``I'm angry because the ambulances weren't rushed to the scene
immediately,'' said the witness, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``I think some of the dead could have been rescued if
the ambulances had come earlier.''
   Tahnassis Pagoulapos, the Acropol's manager, said ambulances
arrived an hour after the explosions.
   The official Sudan News Agency said a large number of foreigners
and diplomats were in the hotel at the time of the blasts,
including a senior U.S. diplomat whom it did not identify.
   The news agency said two Canadians and a Dutchman also were
wounded. It did not name them or give nationalities of the other
wounded.
   Waiters at the Sudan Club said they heard an exchange of fire
near the entrance. ``All of us just went under the tables,'' said a
waiter, who did not give his name.
   Both the United States and Britain warn their citizens not to
travel in southern Sudan, where civil war has raged for five years,
and to take caution when traveling in other parts.
   An American communications technician was shot and gravely
wounded near the Libyan diplomatic mission on April 16, 1986.
   Hours earlier, U.S. jets raided Tripoli and Benghazi in what
Washington described as retribution for Libyan support of
international terrorism.
   The United States blamed Libya for the Khartoum attack, but
there were no arrests.
</TEXT>
