<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0731 05-16 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Dismisses Jackson's Complaints; Robertson Bows Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 10th graf pvs, bgng: Dukakis was, with
CBS-Times poll; stands for AM-Primary Rdp listed on AM-News Digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis on Monday dismissed rival Jesse
Jackson's claim that he is being treated unfairly, saying ``we all
knew what we were doing and what we were running against.'' Pat
Robertson put his Republican presidential campaign on hold, bowing
to the inevitability of George Bush's nomination.
   On the eve of the Oregon primary, Jackson renewed his appeal for
fairness. At a stop in New Jersey, Jackson said he has helped elect
many congressmen by ``registering more Democrats than anybody else
in history'' and deserves a ``return on my investment.''
   ``We're not discussing generosity. We're discussing
reciprocity,'' Jackson told about 200 cheering supporters in Newark.
   But Dukakis, tending to gubernatorial business in Massachusetts,
said the preacher-turned-politician was well aware of the realities
of the Democratic nominating process.
   ``This is a campaign for delegates as well as votes,'' said
Dukakis, who expects to win the lion's share of 45 delegates at
stake in Oregon. ``We all knew what we were doing and what we were
running against.''
   Jackson has been unable to translate his popular vote support
into equivalent backing from the party leaders and politicians
known as ``super delegates.'' He trails Dukakis in The Associated
Press total delegate count _ 1,610 to 956 _ as well as the super
delegate tally _ 203 to 52.
   Jackson urged the super delegates to be fair to his candidacy
and close the gap in the delegate count.
   ``Super does not mean following the tail wind,'' he said.
``Super means bucking the head wind.''
   Front-runner Dukakis, who told New Jersey Democrats on Sunday
``I smell victory in the air,'' received some encouraging news from
a Harris poll that found him leading Bush in a trial heat of the
likely presidential contest.
   Dukakis was backed by 50 percent of the 2,138 likely voters
surveyed in telephone interviews April 1-5 and May 5-10. Bush was
favored by 43 percent of those polled and 7 percent were undecided.
The poll had a margin of error of 3 percent.
   And a CBS-New York Times poll suggested Dukakis had a 10-point
lead over Bush, 49 percent to 39 percent, with 10 percent
undecided. THe poll of 1,382 voters was conducted by telephone May
9-12, and had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
   Bush, who clinched the nomination with his win in the
Pennsylvania primary last month, lost his only remaining rival on
Monday as Robertson officially suspended his campaign.
   The former television evangelist said he would resume control of
his financially-troubled Christian Broadcasting Network, which he
left to run for president.
   ``Today I suspend my candidacy for the Republican nomination in
1988 but I do not now nor will I ever suspend my advocacy of
conservative and moral principles,'' Robertson told reporters near
his home on the grounds of CBN University in Virginia Beach, Va.
   ``George Bush has won the nomination. I applaud his magnificent
effort and warmly endorse his candidacy,'' he said.
   Robertson also said he filed incorporation papers for a new
political action committee, ``Americans for the Republic,'' a group
to be used as a ``rallying point for future political action.'' But
he said of his own possible bid in 1992, ``That remains a moot
question until the 1988 election. I hope Mr. Bush is elected and
then re-elected again in 1992.''
   Bush spent the day campaigning in Washington state, where he
defended himself against charges that one of his top aides was
involved in a Contra supply operation.
   ``That is old news,'' the vice president said. ``I'd hate to
think it is politically motivated material. You get sick and tired
of saying, `I've told the truth' ... You get bombarded by these
insinuations and tired stories.''
   Newsweek reported Sunday that arms dealer Richard J. Brenneke
said in a sworn deposition to a Senate Foreign Relations
subcommittee that Bush's national security adviser, Donald Gregg,
was the Washington contact for the operation, known as ``Arms
Supermarket.''
   ``It's just pure unadulterated ... I have got to watch my
language,'' Bush said as he toured the Weyerhaeuser Technology
Center in Federal Way, Wash., with a Yale classmate from 1948 and a
member of his national finance committee, George Weyerhaeuser.
</TEXT>
