<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Pakistan     05-16 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Pakistan,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India, Pakistan Agree to Take Steps to Stop Arms and Drug
Trafficking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India-Sikhs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India and Pakistan agreed Monday to take
steps to contain Sikh terrorism, arms smuggling and drug
trafficking along their lengthy border, according to an Indian
official.
   ``I hope our Pakistani friends can translate our hopes into
action,'' Home Secretary C.G. Somiah said. He spoke at a news
conference at the end of three days of talks with a Pakistani
delegation.
   India has accused Pakistan of training and helping Sikh
extremists who are fighting for a separate homeland in Punjab state
in northern India. Pakistan has denied the charge.
   The Pakistani delegation was led by Interior Secretary S.K.
Mahmud.
   A statement issued at the conclusion of the talks said the two
countries agreed to have joint border patrols in ``selected
sensitive areas of the Punjab sector of the India-Pakistan border.''
   It said officers from their border forces would hold joint
meetings once a month to ``effectively deal with all illegal
transborder movements.''
   India and Pakistan will assist each other in investigating drug
trafficking and arms smuggling and in handing over people to give
evidence in criminal cases, the statement said.
   ``We placed substantial evidence of different kinds of help they
(Pakistan) are rendering to terrorists in Punjab,'' said Somiah,
who headed the Indian negotiators.
   He said the evidence was based on interrogation of Sikh
militants, photographs of arms and ammunition recovered in Punjab,
and visits to Pakistan by Sikh militant leaders living in other
countries.
   ``The Pakistani delegation denied its complicity ... but they
assured us that positive action will be taken,'' Somiah said.
   He was asked if progress has been made since the last round of
talks on border cooperation were held in December 1986. Somiah said
those talks ``have not resulted in lessening of any activity.''
   Predominantly Hindu India and Moslem Pakistan have fought three
wars since 1947 when the subcontinent gained independence from
Britain. Sikhism is an offshoot of the Hindu religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
