<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Union     05-16 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Union,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Labor Federation Calls For Work Stayaways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's largest black
labor federation on Monday called for a three-day worker stayaway
June 6-8 and for regular weekly demonstrations to protest recent
government crackdowns.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, which claims 691,000
dues-paying members, said its weekend special session was ``marked
by a mood of worker militancy and anger.''
   The session, attended by 1,500 delegates, was called in response
to the government's February decision barring the federation from
taking part in political activity and banning 17 other
anti-apartheid groups from functioning in any capacity.
   Federation officials also are angered by a proposed Labor
Relations Amendment that would severely curtail unions' ability to
stage legal strikes and would make them liable for damages suffered
by a company that is the target of a strike.
   The federation statement Monday called for June 6-8 to be days
of ``peaceful demonstration.'' The federation cannot explicitly
call for a strike, but similar pleas in the past resulted in
widespread worker stayaways.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions also called for
``stepping up demonstrations in all organized factories every
Tuesday.'' The statement did not elaborate, but would appear to
call for brief weekly demonstrations or sit-down strikes.
Federation officials could not be reached by telephone for
additional comment.
   Under current law, management can fire workers even when they
are staging legal strikes. The new bill would expand the powers of
management and government to prevent or halt strikes.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
