<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls For Fairness As Likely Primary Defeats Loom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with Oregon appearance</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson stepped up his appeal for
fairness from the Democratic Party on Monday and said he deserved
credit for ``registering more Democrats than anybody else in
history.''
   ``We're not discussing generosity. We're discussing
reciprocity,'' Jackson said to the cheers of about 200 supporters
at a breakfast address.
   The Democratic presidential contender spoke out against party
rules that have made his delegate total disproportionately smaller
than his share of the popular vote. He called for ``one person, one
vote,'' and asked the so-called ``super delegates'' to close the
gap in the delegate count. Jackson trails front-runner Michael
Dukakis by more than 650 delegates.
   Super delegates are elected leaders and party officials who
comprise almost a third of the number needed to win nomination at
the July convention in Atlanta. Super delegates have been moving
steadily into Dukakis' column.
   ``Super does not mean following the tail wind. Super means
bucking the head wind,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson told New Jersey campaign leaders that he has helped
elect many senators and representatives by ``registering more
Democrats than anybody else in history'' and that he deserved a
``return on my investment'' in the party.
   Jackson claims credit for registering 2 million new voters in
1984 and after, many of them black.
   He implied that his work registering voters helped elect New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, a former professional basketball player
who has pledged his support for Dukakis.
   ``You don't become senator because you could shoot a basketball.
You become a senator because people invested in you,'' said Jackson.
   Jackson continued his theme of the last several days for
``reciprocity'' from the party, but said his appeal for fairness
was not a veiled threat.
   ``My focus now is not to be accusatory, but to make our basic
appeal, which is one of reasonable expecations: fairness,'' Jackson
said at a news conference after his speech.
   Later, Jackson flew to Oregon to make a primary-eve appeal for
votes. There are 45 delegates at stake in the state's primary on
Tuesday.
   ``I want to win in Oregon on tomorrow and take that momentum to
California, debate Bush three times, and send Reagan and Bush out
of Washington on the same plane,'' he said at an airport rally in
Eugene.
   ``If I make the most sense to you, vote for me,'' Jackson urged
the crowd. ``If I win, you win.''
</TEXT>
