<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CastleFire     05-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Castle Fire,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic German Castle Damaged in Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>USINGEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators ruled out arson as
the cause of a major fire at the 13th-century Kransberg Castle, the
wartime headquarters of Nazi air force chief Hermann Goering,
officials said Monday.
   The castle is now used as a school for U.S. Army noncommissioned
officers.
   Friday night a fire started in the attic and was contained to
one wing, said Sgt. Glenda Taylor, spokeswoman for the 5th Army
Corps in nearby Frankfurt.
   She said about $600,000 in damage was caused, but there were no
injuries.
   No one was in the castle at the time, but U.S. soldiers were on
the castle grounds at Usingen, 18 miles north of Frankfurt, and
called German firemen, she said.
   Capt. Robert Jones, another 5th Corps spokesman, said
investigators ruled out arson. ``Preliminary reports suggest it was
an electrical fire,'' he said. ``The wiring in the castle dates
back to the 1930s.''
   Jones said West German authorities were still investigating.
   Goering had his World War II headquarters and residence at the
castle.
   U.S. occupation forces took it over in 1945 and it was used as a
temporary Allied jail for Albert Speer, Adolf Hitler's architect
and armaments chief, and other captured German officials before
their war crimes trials in Nuremberg.
   In 1946, Goering committed suicide inside his Nuremberg jail
cell two hours before he was to be hanged as a war criminal.
</TEXT>
