<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance     05-16 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weekend Nets Five Boats in Zero Tolerance Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five boats, including the yacht that once carried
former presidential candidate Gary Hart and model Donna Rice, were
confiscated during weekend enforcement of the ``Zero Tolerance''
drug policy, the Coast Guard said.
   About a quarter-ounce of marijuana was found in two garments on
the Monkey Business, and the largest amount of contraband found on
any of the other boats was two marijuana cigarettes, the Coast
Guard said.
   No arrests were made in the seizures by the 7th Coast Guard
District, which extends south from North Carolina to include the
Caribbean Sea and eastern Gulf of Mexico. The names of people
connected with the boats were not released by the Coast Guard.
   The Kick n Back, a Chris Craft boarded in Lake Worth Inlet late
Friday, was seized after one gram of marijuana was found in a
plastic bag in plain sight, according to a Coast Guard statement.
   The Monkey Business, a $2,500-a-day, 82-foot charter yacht, was
boarded about 22 miles northwest of the Bahamian island of Bimini.
   The boat, estimated to be worth more than $1 million, was bound
back to Miami when it was seized at 10:30 a.m. Saturday with three
men and one woman aboard. The owner was not among them.
   At 4 p.m. Sunday, the Mercator, carrying four people, was
boarded 90 miles southwest of Key West. It was taken for one-tenth
of an ounce of pot found on board, the Coast Guard said.
   Late Sunday afternoon, a Coast Guard boarding party confiscated
a 26-foot open fishing boat 15 miles east of Fort Lauderdale after
half a gram of marijuana was found on board. The boat had two
people on board, the Coast Guard said.
   In the final weekend seizure, the Skyliner, was carrying seven
people when it was seized 30 miles south of Savanah, Ga., at 9 p.m.
Sunday. A boarding party found two joints on the boat, officials
said.
   The Zero Tolerance program is a two-month-old federal policy
that allows the government to seize any boat, plane, car or other
means by which any measurable amount of an illegal drug is
conveyed. The government can auction the property and keep the
profits unless its owners prove they have no connection to the
marijuana.
</TEXT>
