<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0710 05-16 0891</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0710,0912</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Masses Troops To Enter Slums; Battles Rage Despite its
Orders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Two grafs SUB for last graf pvs, The agency ... UPDATING with
later Iranian action.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria massed troops and tanks Monday for
a push into Beirut's southern slums after Shiite Moslem militias
defied a cease-fire order from the Syrian army and dueled with
howitzers, mortars and rocket launchers.
   There was no word on when the Syrians would enter. Lebanese army
sources said the Syrians were taking their time in hopes the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, which controls nearly all the slums, could
be persuaded not to resist.
   Police said the Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the
Syrian-backed Amal militias fought through the day in the enclave
where 18 Western hostages, including nine Americans, are believed
held by pro-Iranian extremists.
   They said Amal, driven to the slum fringes in 11 days of combat,
made a counterattack Monday that forced Hezbollah to retreat in the
Shiyah neighborhood.
   ``It's a significant development but not enough to turn the
tables on the victorious Hezbollah,'' said a police offical, who
spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance with regulations.
``Only the Syrians can crush Hezbollah.''
   Police said 14 people were killed and 120 wounded in fighting
Sunday and Monday, raising the toll to 225 dead and 706 wounded
since fighting for control of the 16 square miles of slums began
May 6.
   Most of the hostages are believed held by kidnappeers linked to
Hezbollah, and the United States indicated Monday it would be
willing to talk with the captors.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman, asked about reports
that the hostages had been moved from the slums, said: ``I don't
have anything to say about their whereabouts. We would only be
concerned obviously if this kind of fighting were to endanger the
hostages.''
   He said Washington was pleased by a call from the spiritual
guide of Hezbollah, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, for
negotiations about the hostages and said: ``We will talk to anyone,
to any group, to any government, about the well-being and release
of the Americans still held hostage in Lebanon.''
   In Beirut, the Iranian Embassy repeated its denial of a report
by the Voice of Lebanon, a Christian radio station, that most of
the hostages had been moved to the embassy grounds outside the
battle zone.
   Syrian commanders deployed thousands of soldiers and hundreds of
armored vehicles at the gateways to the labyrinthine slums beside
the Beirut airport.
   Mem and machines began massing two days ago under Brig. Gen. Ali
Deeb and Brig. Gen. Hisham Moalla, said to be Syria's toughest
generals.
   They commanded crackdowns on fundamentalist Moslems in the Hama,
Syria, in 1981 in which up to 30,000 people were reported killed,
and in north Lebanon's port of Tripoli in 1985.
   Deeb and Moalla had two armored brigades entrenched in sand
dunes around the airport Monday with their artillery and tank
cannons trained on the slums.
   The Syrians also want the predominantly Shiite 6th Brigade of
the Lebanese army to go in with them to minimize the risk of coming
under Hezbollah fire, the sources said.
   ``If there is a chance of confrontation, then the Syrians will
change their tactics. They will level the slums with artillery
before moving in,'' one military source said. He spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The sources estimated the Syrian buildup at about 7,500 soldiers
and 500 tanks and armored vehicles.
   Syria's military intelligence chief, Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan,
ordered Hezbollah and Amal to lay down their arms, warning: ``Our
forces will shoot without hesitation at any gunman in the street or
in buildings. Your lives will be spared if you comply.''
   Amal's leader, Nabih Berri, who is also Lebanon's justice
minister, has declared support for a Syrian entry into the slums.
   Radio stations said he had decided to disband his 6,000-strong
militia in the suburbs and neighboring west Beirut, saying: ``No
gunmen should be allowed to remain in the suburbs and Beirut, now
that a legitimate force is taking charge of security.''
   Fadlallah said Sunday that ``all the suburbs will be destroyed
if the Syrians attempt to enter by force.''
   That would sharpen the strain on an alliance between Syria and
Iran, which has been imperiled by Hezbollah's efforts to dominate
the 1.2 million Shiites in Lebanon.
   The Syrians have 25,000 troops based in northern and eastern
Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   They also deployed 7,500 troops in west Beirut in February 1987
to curb three years of militia violence.
   But in an apparent effort to avoid a collision with Iran, the
Syrians did not venture into the slums then.
   Iran's acting foreign minister, Ali Mohammed Besharati, was in
Damascus on Monday for talks with Syrian officials on the Lebanon
crisis, Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency reported in a dispatch
that was monitored in Cyprus.
   Besharati later went to Beirut and met separately with Fadlallah
and Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin, head of the supreme Shiite
council, the sect's highest religious body, in the presence of
Iran's ambassadors to Syria and Lebanon.
   A statement from the Iranian Embassy said Besharati was trying
to resurrect a four-man committee representing the presidents of
Iran and Syria as well as Amal and Hezbollah to end the slums war.
</TEXT>
