<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BattleshipPort     05-16 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Battleship Port,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S.F. Mayor Seeks New Plan To Base USS Missouri; Navy Secretary
Says No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of San Francisco asked the Navy on
Monday to revise its plans for basing the battleship Missouri in
his city, but the civilian head of the service later rejected the
idea.
   Navy Secretary William Ball told Mayor Art Agnos that he expects
the city to fulfill commitments made last year to help pay for
dredging and facilities for the battleship, or else the Missouri
and its battle group won't be coming to the city, a Navy spokesman
said late Monday.
   Cmdr. Jeff Zakem, the spokesman, released a statement saying:
``The fulfillment by the city and county of San Francisco of the
commitments in the memorandum of understanding was necessary in
order to proceed with the Navy's plan for homeporting a battleship
battle group in San Francisco.
   ``Secretary Ball advised the mayor of his disappointment that
the agreement negotiated in August 1987 would not be honored by the
city. In the Navy's view, the terms of the memorandum of
understanding with the city were such that San Francisco and the
bay area would have received substantial economic benefits from
homeporting ....''
   Agnos told reporters Monday he would like to see the Navy base
the huge battleship itself at some other nearby port while placing
the smaller escorts at a rebuilt Hunters Point shipyard as
originally planned.
   The smaller warships would not require the extensive dredging
needed for the battleship, easing environmental concerns, the mayor
said.
   Moreover, the city would like the Navy to renegotiate the
memorandum of understanding so that a more balanced mix of
industry, office and residential buildings can be developed at
Hunters Point.
   The Navy has balked at that idea, saying the activation of a
naval station there for the Missouri battle group would not allow
civilian businesses to stay but that the city would benefit through
the creation of new jobs and economic activity to support the fleet.
   Pentagon officials who asked not to be named said Monday the
proposal by Agnos might kill for good the assignment of a
battleship battle group to San Francisco.
   But Reps. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., and Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.,
endorsed the mayor's efforts, saying the Navy should consider a
compromise.
   ``I want to commend him for taking a positive approach,'' Boxer
said in an interview Monday.
   ``He's not anti-Navy, as some people have suggested,'' Pelosi
said. ``We want Hunters Point to be developed in an environmentally
sound manner.''
   Agnos assumed office on Jan. 8, replacing Dianne Feinstein, who
had been a strong proponent of basing the ship in San Francisco.
   The Navy originally planned to get the Missouri in San Francisco
by 1990. That schedule has slipped because of congressional budget
cuts. At the same time, the Navy has been waiting to see whether
Agnos would honor the earlier memorandum.
   Beyond the extra dredging required for a battleship, Agnos said
the Navy's original plan would force the eviction of 200 small
businesses with 1,000 employees and payrolls totaling $20 million.
   A Pentagon source said Monday he wasn't sure the service would
be interested in renegotiating last year's agreement to accommodate
Agnos.
   ``San Francisco signed an agreement with the Navy; we didn't
force them to do that,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
