<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jamaica-Quake     05-16 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jamaica-Quake,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Earthquake In Eight Days Hits Jamaica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minor earthquake shook Jamaica early
Monday, the second quake in eight days, but no injuries or damage
were reported, officials said.
   The temblor was felt strongest in Kingston, the capital, and St.
Andrew Parish.
   The Seismic Research Unit at the University of the West Indies
said the earthquake registered 3.6 on the Richter scale, with its
epicenter off northeast Jamaica at latitude 18.2 degrees north and
longitude 76.4 degrees west, at a depth of 6.2 miles. It struck at
5:34 a.m. EDT.
   A May 9 earthquake in Jamaica lasted 90 seconds and measured 4.2
on the Richter scale, one of the strongest in Jamaica in 30 years.
A student was injured then when she jumped in panic from the second
story of her school.
   The Richter scale measures energy released by quakes as recorded
on seismographs. A quake registering 4 is capable of causing
moderate damage.
</TEXT>
