<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Noriega     05-16 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Noriega,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Asks Senate to Oppose Any Deal To Drop Charges Against
Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole asked the
Senate on Monday night to oppose any U.S. deal with Manuel Noriega
which would involve dropping criminal charges against the
Panamanian strongman.
   ``The American people are never going to understand if we
dismiss indictments against Noriega,'' the Kansas Republican told
his colleagues as he introduced a non-binding resolution opposing
any deal in which charges are dropped.
   There have been numerous reports in recent days that Reagan
administration officials were negotiating an agreement with Noriega
where he would voluntarily step down and relinquish power if the
United States would drop federal drug trafficking indictments that
were brought against him in February by grand juries in Miami and
Tampa, Fla.
   Dole's proposal was a ``sense of the Senate'' resolution which
he introduced as an amendment to a pending bill authorizing
Pentagon spending for the fiscal year which begins Oct. 1.
   The Senate originally considered voting on the resolution Monday
night, but delayed a vote until at least Tuesday when Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee, objected.
Nunn said he wanted to talk with members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee.
   Dole said he had no personal knowledge about the accuracy of the
reports of the proposed deal, but he referred to them as a ``golden
parachute'' for Noriega.
   ``If we send this signal, it's going to undermine the so-called
war on drugs,'' said Dole. ``Let Noriega go, but let's don't send
him off with a legal golden parachute.''
   Golden parachute is often the term used to describe benefits and
severance pay offered to top business executives when they are
fired or resign.
   ``We all want Noriega to go,'' said Dole. ``We all agree that
should be a high priority of American policy in Panama. But it is
not the only priority for American policy.
   ``If we let Noriega off the hook on the drug indictments that
have been brought against him _ no matter what the motive _ we have
sent a very regrettable message to the world,'' added Dole.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., called the proposed deal
``scandalous'' and said ``all we're doing is rewarding him, we're
giving him a pardon.''
   ``This administration is doing itself in,'' said D'Amato, who
then went on to praise President Reagan as a ``good man, a
courageous man.''
   ``I don't think the American people want us to drop these
charges and give testimony to the effectiveness of the (Colombian)
drug cartel and Manuel Noriega,'' said D'Amato.
   Nunn said he believes that ``you don't indict a leader of a
foreign country unless you know how you're going to follow through
on it ... apparently we did not have ways to go about it, plans for
extradition.''
   ``Certainly, we've dug ourselves into a hole now,'' said Nunn.
Dropping the charges ``is sending a very bad signal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
