<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Cuban     05-16 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Cuban,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Cuban Cyclist Jailed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Cuban cycling team who
sought American help in defecting to the United States was jailed
in this northern city Monday, the newspaper El Norte reported.
   It said Roger Vazquez Vazquez, 25, abandoned his team after a
race in Mexico City last week and went north hoping to defect to
the United States.
   Vazquez was detained Sunday as he tried to pass through a
federal migration checkpoint at Nuevo Laredo, 16 miles south of the
U.S. border city of Laredo, Texas, according to the newspaper.
   The U.S. Consulate in Monterrey declined to comment on the
report that Vazquez asked for U.S. political asylum.
   ``We are not permitted to comment on any individual case like
that. There are just too many potential ramifications,'' said
consulate spokesman Bob Brown.
   But he said U.S. policy in such cases is ``to give them
assistance if possible.''
   The Federal District Attorney's Office in Monterrey said it had
no information on the case.
   A secretary at the Loma prison where Vazquez reportedly was held
said prison directors were out of the office Monday and unavailable
for comment.
   El Norte quoted migration officials in Nuevo Laredo, who were
not identified, as saying Vazquez was in Mexico legally but was not
authorized to go to the border.
   It said Vazquez came last week to Monterrey, 135 miles south of
Laredo.
   Without identifying its sources, the newspaper said cyclists
from Monterrey who had met Vazquez in Mexico City gave him refuge
and took him to the U.S. consulate where his case was being
considered.
   Vazquez became impatient and tried to leave the country on his
own, the report said.
   El Norte reported Nuevo Laredo officials said Vazquez would be
sent to Mexico City and the Interior Department would resolve the
case.
</TEXT>
