<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-16 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Big And Little, Rattle The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The powerful thunderstorms and showers rattled the East and
South on Monday, pelting much of the South with hail.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended Monday from western New York
across Pennsylvania, the Virginias, the Carolinas, Kentucky,
Georgia and Alabama, as well as central Texas and the northern and
central Pacific Coast by mid-day.
   Georgia authorities said a University of Georgia freshman was
struck and killed by lightning while playing golf and an Atlanta
construction worker was crushed when a building under construction
was knocked down by high winds.
   Golf ball-size hail fell in New York at Naples, Pen Yann and
Branchport and at Hancock, Md.; Berkeley Springs, W. Va.;
Fayetteville, Ga.; and in central Texas near Austin, the weather
service said.
   Smaller hail also was reported in Laurel Park, Kernersville and
Hendersonville, N.C.; Pelham, Ala.; Chesnee, S.C.; Atlanta,
Cornelia, Riverdale, Jonesboro, Hamton and Newman, Ga., and near
Austin, Texas.
   Hail also fell on Dayton and Little Valley, N.Y.
   Denver tied its high temperature record for May 16 and reached
89 degrees. The record was set in 1964.
   Havre, Mont., reached 92 degrees and broke its high temperature
record for the date, 91 degrees, set in 1901.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 98 degrees at Needles, Calif. The
nation's low temperature Monday morning was 25 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Tuesday's forecast called for showers and occasional
thunderstorms from the northern and central Atlantic states into
the southern Appalachians, as well as Florida, and from the
northern Rockies across the Northern Pacific coast.
   Predicted highs would reach the 60s for New England, the
northern Appalachians and the Great Lakes, from the northern
Rockies across the northern half of the Pacific Coast, near 70
along the California coast, near 90 degrees for the Southern
Plains, the 90s from southwest Texas through the desert Southwest,
and in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
