<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PoetLaureate 1stLd-Writethru a0828 05-16 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poet Laureate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0828,250</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to change year position of poet laureate was
created</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nemerov Named Poet Laureate at Library of Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize and National Book Award winner
Howard Nemerov was named Monday as poet laureate of the United
States, becoming the third person to hold that job since it was
created in 1985.
   Nemerov's appointment was announced by James H. Billington, the
Librarian of Congress.
   ``Howard Nemerov has given America remarkable range of poetry
from the profound to the poignant to the comic,'' said Billington.
   ``It is a happy moment for poetry that Howard Nemerov will
become our new ambassador for the `republic of letters,''' he added.
   Billington also cited Nemerov, 68, for his work as ``an
outstanding critic, essayist, fiction writer and teacher.''
   Nemerov _ currently a distinguished professor at Washington
University i8n St. Louis _ will succeed Richard Wilbur and Robert
Penn Warren in holding the endowed chair created by Congress in
1936 for the position of Consultant in Poetry to the library.
   In that capacity, Nemerov will give a public poetry reading and
lecture, advise the library on its literary programs and recommend
new poets to be included in the library's archive of recorded
poetry and literature.
   Nemerov previously served as a consultant in poetry to the
library in 1963.
   Nemerov won both the Pulitzer Prize and National Book Award in
poetry in 1978. Among his collections of poetry are ``Image and the
Law,'' ``Guide to the Ruins,'' ``Mirrors and Windows'' and ``War
Stories.''
   Nemerov, who was born in New York City and was graduated in 1941
from Harvard University, has taught at Hamilton College, Bennington
College, Brandeis University and Hollins College.
</TEXT>
