<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings     05-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Execution Date Set For Simmons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of two murders and accused of
14 others should be executed June 27, a judge said Monday after
granting R. Gene Simmons' wish to waive his right to appeal his
death sentence.
   Simmons, 47, was convicted last week of two deaths in a Dec. 28
shooting rampage in Russellville. He is due to stand trial July 18
for the deaths of 14 members of his family, whose bodies were
discovered by police at his home.
   If no one intervenes to delay the execution, it would be one of
the swiftest in modern U.S. history. But a woman whose daughter and
grandson were killed says she wants Simmons tried again ``before
he's put to sleep.''
   No one has been executed in Arkansas since 1964.
   John Burnett, a Little Rock attorney who chairs an eight-member
committee that considers cases for intervention by the Arkansas
chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union, said no decision had
been made about the Simmons case.
   He said possible intervention would probably be discussed by the
committee.
   Charlotte Croston, the mother of Renata Simmons and her son,
Trae, who were among those found at the Simmons home, said with
tears streaming from her eyes she wanted Simmons to stand trial for
killing his relatives.
   ``I'd like for him to suffer a little bit before he's put to
sleep,'' she said. ``I don't know if he believes in the hereafter,
but the last laugh is on him because he's going to suffer a lot
more then. I want him to die. I just want him to face justice in
this life before he does.''
   Immediately after being convicted Thursday of killing Kathy
Kendrick and James Chaffin and trying to kill five other people,
Simmons asked his trial judge, Circuit Court Judge John Patterson
to expedite his execution.
   After he was sentenced, Simmons calmly read a brief statement,
in which he said that ``anything short of death would be cruel and
unusual punishment.''
   ``I only ask for what I deserve,'' he said. ``Let the torture
and suffering in me end. Please allow me the right to be at peace.''
   Patterson said he scheduled Monday's hearing to satisfy himself
that Simmons was mentally competent to waive his right to appeal.
   Patterson reminded Simmons during Monday's 35-minute hearing
that ``any time prior to execution, you have the right to change
your mind and appeal. Do you understand that?''
   Simmons said he understood and did not think he would change his
mind, adding ``nobody better hold their breath.''
   Simmons said the decision ``actually was made on the 28th of
December'' _ the day he went on a shooting rampage that killed two
and wounded four in Russellville.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
