<DOCNO> AP880516-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Africa     05-16 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Africa,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet and U.S. officials to hold talks on southern Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top U.S. and Soviet negotiators on
southern Africa will meet in Lisbon this week to discuss the civil
war in Angola and South Africa's control of Namibia, a U.S. Embassy
official said Monday.
   Chester Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, and Anatoly Adamishin, a Soviet deputy foreign
minister, will open the talks Wednesday, embassy spokeswoman Susan
Clyde said.
   She said only Soviet and U.S. officials are expected to take
part in the talks, with Crocker due to arrive in the Portuguese
capital on Wednesday and leave Thursday or Friday.
   The Soviet and U.S. envoys have met several times recently to
discuss ways of ending the conflicts in southern Africa. President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev are expected to
discuss the issue at their Moscow summit opening May 29.
   Earlier this month in London, Crocker presided over the first
face-to-face negotiations among representativs from Angola, South
Africa and Cuba.
   Cuba has an estimated 40,000 military personnel in Angola,
helping that country's Marxist government fight rebels of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola _ UNITA. The
United States and South Africa back UNITA.
   South African and Angolan officials met Friday in Brazzaville,
the capital of Congo, and a second meeting among the four countries
that met in London is expected to take place in Brazzaville within
two weeks.
   Adamishin arrived in Lisbon Monday. He recently visited Angola,
Cuba and the United States.
   In another development Monday, Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos said Angola accepted the principle of a gradual
withdrawal of the Cuban military personnel from his country.
   Dos Santos, in an interview with the official Angolan news
agency ANGOP, said the United States is refusing to recognize
Angola diplomatically until the Cubans have left. He said that
position was ``absurd'' and ``without any logical explanation.''
   The ANGOP report, monitored in Lisbon, quoted the president as
saying Namibian independence and the end of the Angolan war would
be decisive steps toward peace in southern Africa and the abolition
of racial segregation in South Africa.
   Namibia, also known as South-West Africa, is a territory between
Angola and South Africa that has been administered by South
Africa's white-dominated government since the end of World War I
under a League of Nations mandate.
   South Africa has rejected repeated demands by the United Nations
that Namibia be independent. One South African condition is the
removal of Cuban troops from Angola.
   Guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization
(SWAPO) are fighting South Africa for control of the territory.
   SWAPO has bases in southern Angola and South Africa frequently
has sent troops into Angola.
   Angola received its independence from Portugal in November 1975
and UNITA was defeated in the battle for power by the Marxist
Popular Liberation Movement of Angola.
</TEXT>
