<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ferries     05-16 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferries,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Struck Company Plans To Resume Dover-Calais Ferry Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ferry Pride of Kent made the voyage
from Dover to Calais, France, on Monday in a move to resume the
first passenger service on that route by P and O European Ferries
Ltd. since a strike began 15 weeks ago.
   A company official said the Pride of Kent left Dover at 10:45
a.m. (5:45 a.m. EDT) on an unscheduled sailing and returned at
about 2 p.m.
   ``It is another step in the progressive reintroduction of our
services and ships,'' said a P and O spokesman, who was not
identified in line with British custom. He acknowledged that ``not
many people'' were on board.
   Another P and O official, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the company intended to resume normal passenger
sailings on the Dover-Calais run, the busy and shortest route
between England and the Continent. He said the company would
provide three round-trip sailings daily.
   P and O made its first effort to break the strike with sailings
between Dover and Zeebrugge, Belgium, beginning May 1. Its ferries
carried mainly freight and a few passengers.
   It began operating freight ferries between Dover and Calais on
Friday.
   Rival ferry companies resumed full operations Friday after
members of the National Union of Seamen decided to give up their
secondary action in support of P and O's striking workers.
   The P and O strikers are protesting changes in work schedules
that the company is instituting as cost-cutting measures. P and O
said the measures are needed to make the line competitive by the
time the Channel Tunnel opens in 1993, providing a direct
railroad-car route between Britain and France.
</TEXT>
