<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     05-16 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Allowed Back Into Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general secretary of the
opposition Christian Democratic Party, Ivan Romero, returned to
Panama on Monday, 10 days after he was expelled from the country.
   His return came on the same day that Commerce Minister Mario
Rognoni called ``lunacy'' the U.S. demand that Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega resign. Rognoni told a news conference here, ``Just as the
United States does not negotiate over hostages, neither do we.''
   Romero had come back on May 6 from an international conference
of Christian Democratic leaders in Miami, but was detained upon
arrival by police and held overnight.
   Party President Ricardo Arias Calderon said Romero was beaten
during an interrogation before being put on a plane back to Miami
the following day.
   On Monday, Romero told about 40 supporters who showed up to
greet him: ``This kind of action makes us tougher for the fight we
will keep up until the end.''
   The Christian Democrats oppose Noriega, who as head of the
15,000-member Defense Forces is also de facto leader in Panama.
Noriega has been under U.S. indictment in Florida since February on
drug trafficking and money laundering charges.
   The Reagan administration has been pressuring the general to
relinquish power, applying economic sanctions and freezing
Panamanian bank accounts in the United States.
   Rognoni called U.S. pressure ``a new form of state terrorism,''
and said: ``Today the world has changed and it is a brand new world
for Panama.''
   He outlined an economic recovery plan designed to definitively
and drastically reduce Panamanian dependence on the United States,
including the pursuit of new markets and sources of investment
outside North America, which has always been Panama's major
economic partner.
   ``What has happened because of the economic aggression has come
to help the Panamanian people, because it has taught them they
cannot trust or depend on the United States as a true friend,'' the
commerce minister said.
   He said secret talks here in recent weeks between State
Department envoy Michael Kozak and Noriega's representatives are
positive ``because we did not call them, we did not ask them to
come. They came on their own, which means they must be
re-evaulating and rethinking their policies toward Panama.''
   He said the discussions did not amount to negotiations because
``the U.S. can drop the indictments and lift the sanctions
unilaterally, without having to negotiate with anyone.''
   Asked if Kozak and Noriega's people were talking about Noriega's
abandoning his post, Rognoni replied: ``The United States makes a
mistake when it thinks that because of its power, because of its
arrogance or capacity to exert force, it can tell a country who
should be its president or who should be its chief of firemen or
police.
   ``To ask that a commander retire, or what's more, that he leave
the country, as if he were on some kind of parole, is lunacy.''
   Rognoni said the talks between Kozak and Noriega's
representatives included three main areas: political implications
of the crisis, economic effects of U.S. sanctions and the affairs
of Noriega with the U.S. Department of Justice.
   Rognoni said ``a full review'' of U.S.-Panamanian relations was
needed.
   ``I doubt very much that the U.S. thinks that after all they
have done all they have to do is send a secret envoy and everyone
will kiss and make up,'' he said.
   ``We need to negotiate whether we feel comfortable with the
threat from the U.S. that at any moment they can block our accounts
and close our banking center and destroy our economy depending on
the whims of whoever is in office in the U.S.
   ``And we have to rethink and retalk with them if we are going to
allow them to use their military bases in Panama for whatever
purpose in Central America without our knowledge and approval,'' he
added.
   The United States maintains about 10,000 soldiers along the
Panama Canal. According to the 1977 Panama Canal Treaty, complete
control of the waterway and the bases is to be handed over to
Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
