<HEAD>Leftist Exile Is Arrested Upon Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATING throughout with new material, based on actual arrest
upon return. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday arrested a prominent
leftist political exile, Maria Elena Carrera, who challenged a
banishment order issued by Chile's military regime and slipped back
into the country.
   Mrs. Carrera, a former senator and a prominent member of the
Socialist Party, was arrested at the house of a friend. She had
been staying there since her clandestine return to Chile last
Friday via a mountain road from neighboring Argentina.
   The arrest occurred after she went to Santiago's appeals court
to file a document claiming she was ``exercising my right to live
in my country.'' She had lived in exile since shortly after the
September 1973 military coup that brought Gen. Augusto Pinochet to
power and made him president.
   A brief government communique said she will be charged with
illegal entry into Chile. If convicted, she faces up to 15 years in
jail.
   Mrs. Carrera is on a list of about 400 Chileans banished by the
military regime for political reasons.
</TEXT>
