<HEAD>adv 24</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, May 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, May 24, the 145th day of 1988. There are 221
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On May 24, 1844, Samuel F.B. Morse transmitted the words, ``What
hath God wrought!'' from Washington to Baltimore as he formally
opened America's first telegraph line.
   On this date:
   In 1819, Queen Victoria was born in London.
   In 1830, the first passenger railroad in the United States began
service between Baltimore and Elliott's Mills, Md.
   In 1881, some 200 people died when the Canadian ferry Princess
Victoria sank near London, Ontario.
   In 1883, the Brooklyn Bridge, linking Brooklyn and Manhattan in
New York, was opened.
   In 1935, the first night game in major league baseball was
played at Cincinnati as the Reds beat the Philadelphia Phillies,
2-1.
   In 1941, the German battleship Bismarck sank the British
dreadnought Hood in the North Atlantic.
   In 1962, astronaut Scott Carpenter became the second American to
orbit Earth as he flew aboard Aurora 7.
   In 1976, Britain and France opened trans-Atlantic Concorde
supersonic jet service to Washington.
   In 1980, Iran rejected a call by the World Court in The Hague to
release the American hostages.
   In 1984, a court in El Salvador found five former national
guardsmen guilty of murdering four U.S. churchwomen in December
1980.
   In 1986, the Union Jack was flown in Israel for the first time
in 38 years as Margaret Thatcher became the first British prime
minister to visit the Jewish state.
   Ten years ago: Addressing a special United Nations General
Assembly session on disarmament, Vice President Walter F. Mondale
said the United States would be willing to help set up electronic
early-warning systems in other countries to help prevent regional
conflicts.
   Five years ago: New Yorkers marked the 100th birthday of the
Brooklyn Bridge. The celebration included a parade that featured
antique wagons, public officials in Victorian garb, marching bands
and floats, as well as a massive fireworks display.
   One year ago: San Franciscans marked the 50th birthday of the
Golden Gate Bridge three days early. An estimated 225,000
pedestrians filled the span, while hundreds of thousands of others
crowded near the entrances to the bridge.
   Today's birthdays: Former congressman Wilbur Mills, D-Ark., is
79. Singer Bob Dylan is 47. Actor Gary Burghoff is 45. Actress
Priscilla Beaulieu Presley is 43. Singer Rosanne Cash is 33.
   Thought for today: ``Bad men are full of repentance.'' _
Aristotle, Greek philosopher (384 B.C.-322 B.C.)
</TEXT>
