<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, May 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, May 25, the 146th day of 1988. There are 220
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On May 25, 1787, the Constitutional Convention convened in
Philadelphia after enough delegates had shown up for a quorum. In
the months that followed, the delegates drew up the Constitution.
   On this date:
   In 1803, American essayist and poet Ralph Waldo Emerson was born
in Boston.
   In 1810, Argentina began its revolt against Spain.
   In 1935, baseball great Babe Ruth hit the 714th and final home
run of his career, for the Boston Braves, in a game against the
Pittsburgh Pirates at Forbes Field.
   In 1946, Transjordan (now Jordan) became a kingdom as it
proclaimed its new monarch, King Abdullah Ibn Ul-Hussein.
   In 1961, President John F. Kennedy asked the nation to work
toward putting a man on the moon by the end of the decade.
   In 1963, the Organization of African Unity was founded, in Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia.
   In 1976, U.S. Rep. Wayne L. Hays, D-Ohio, admitted having had a
``personal relationship'' with Elizabeth Ray, a committee staff
member who claimed she'd received her job in order to be Hays'
mistress.
   In 1977, the motion picture ``Star Wars,'' written and directed
by George Lucas and starring Mark Hamill, Harrison Ford and Carrie
Fisher, opened in theaters.
   In 1979, 275 people died in America's worst air disaster when an
American Airlines DC-10 crashed at Chicago's O'Hare airport.
   In 1985, more than 11,000 people were killed as a hurricane and
tidal wave devastated Bangladesh.
   In 1986, an estimated 7 million Americans, including President
and Mrs. Reagan, participated in ``Hands Across America,'' forming
a line across the country to bring attention to and raise money for
the nation's hungry and homeless.
   Ten years ago: The Montreal Canadiens captured their third
consecutive Stanley Cup as they defeated the Boston Bruins, 4-1, in
the sixth game of their quest for the National Hockey League
championship.
   Five years ago: Navy Lt. Cmdr. Albert Schaufelberger, a military
attache in San Salvador, was assassinated. A group known as the
FMLN later claimed responsibility
   One year ago: A jury in New York acquitted former Labor
Secretary Raymond J. Donovan and seven other construction
executives of fraud and grand larceny.
   Today's birthdays: Lyricist Hal David is 67. Jazz musician Miles
Davis is 62. Author Robert Ludlum is 61. Former opera singer
Beverly Sills is 59. Broadcast news executive Ron Nessen is 54.
Country singer-songwriter Tom T. Hall is 52. Country singer Jessi
Colter is 45. Actress-singer Leslie Uggams is 45. Actress Karen
Valentine is 41. Actress Connie Sellecca is 33.
   Thought for today: ``The newspapers are full of what we would
like to happen to us and what we hope will never happen to us.'' _
John Fowles, English author.
</TEXT>
