<HEAD>adv 27</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Friday, May 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, May 27, the 148th day of 1988. There are 218
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On May 27, 1937, the Golden Gate Bridge connecting San Francisco
with Marin County, Calif., opened. Only pedestrian traffic was
allowed the first day. Between 6 a.m and 6 p.m., more than 200,000
people crossed the span.
   On this date:
   In 1647, the first recorded American execution of a ``witch''
took place in Massachusetts. (The method involved was not burning
at the stake, but hanging.)
   In 1818, American reformer Amelia Jenks Bloomer, who popularized
the garment that bears her name, was born in Homer, N.Y.
   In 1837, American gunfighter and frontiersman Wild Bill Hickok
was born in Troy Grove, Ill.
   In 1911, the 38th U.S. vice president, Hubert H. Humphrey, was
born in Wallace, S.D.
   In 1929, aviator Charles Lindbergh married Anne Spencer Morrow
in Englewood, N.J.
   In 1935, the Supreme Court struck down the National Industrial
Recovery Act.
   In 1936, the Cunard liner Queen Mary left England on its maiden
voyage.
   In 1941, amid rising world tensions, President Franklin D.
Roosevelt proclaimed an ``unlimited national emergency.''
   In 1941, the German battleship Bismarck was sunk by the British
navy off France, with a loss of 2,300 lives.
   In 1949, author-cartoonist Robert L. Ripley, of ``Ripley's
Believe It or Not!'' fame, died in New York.
   In 1964, independent India's first prime minister, Jawaharlal
Nehru, died.
   In 1977, the City of New York fined ``human fly'' George H.
Willig $1.10 _ one penny for each of the 110 stories of the World
Trade Center he'd scaled the day before.
   Ten years ago: Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei A. Gromyko held
separate meetings in Washington with President Jimmy Carter and
Secretary of State Cyrus R. Vance to discuss proposals aimed at
limiting strategic weapons.
   Five years ago: A federal grand jury indicted former
Environmental Protection Agency official Rita M. Lavelle for
contempt of Congress. Lavelle was later acquitted of the contempt
charge, but was convicted in a separate trial of perjury.
   One year ago: The Rev. Jerry Falwell, responding to comments by
Jim Bakker, denied that he had hoodwinked Bakker into giving up
control of the PTL ministry.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Vincent Price is 77. Novelist Herman
Wouk is 73. Former Japanese Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone is 70.
Actor Christopher Lee is 66. Former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger is 65. Actress Lee Meriwether is 53. Actor Louis Gossett
Jr. is 52. Actor Bruce Weitz is 45. Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
is 44. Actor Todd Bridges is 23.
   Thought for today: ``Our greatest glory consists not in never
falling, but in rising every time we may fall.'' _ Oliver
Goldsmith, British poet and dramatist (1728-1774).
</TEXT>
