<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 28,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>adv 28</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Saturday, May 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, May 28, the 149th day of 1988. There are 217
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On May 28, 1934, the Dionne Quintuplets _ Annette, Cecile,
Emilie, Marie and Yvonne _ were born to Elzire Dionne in Callender,
Ontario.
   On this date:
   In 1533, England's Archbishop declared the marriage of King
Henry VIII to Anne Boleyn valid.
   In 1863, the first black regiment from the North left Boston to
fight in the Civil War.
   In 1929, the first all-color talking picture, ``On with the
Show,'' opened in New York.
   In 1937, President Franklin D. Roosevelt pushed a button in
Washington signalling that vehicular traffic could cross the newly
opened Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco.
   In 1937, Neville Chamberlain became prime minister of Britain.
   In 1940, during World War II, the Belgian army surrendered to
invading German forces.
   In 1957, the National League gave its approval for the Brooklyn
Dodgers and New York Giants baseball teams to move to Los Angeles
and San Francisco.
   In 1972, the Duke of Windsor, who had abdicated the English
throne to marry American divorcee Wallis Warfield Simpson, died in
Paris at age 77.
   In 1977, 165 people were killed when fire raced through the
Beverly Hills Supper Club in Southgate, Ky.
   In 1982, Pope John Paul II began the first-ever papal visit to
Britain with an appeal to Britain and Argentina to end their
fighting over the disputed Falkland Islands.
   In 1984, President Reagan led a state funeral at Arlington
National Cemetery outside Washington for an unidentified American
soldier killed in the Vietnam War.
   Ten years ago: Al Unser became the fifth man to win the
Indianapolis 500 a third time, claiming his latest victory in three
hours, five minutes and 54.99 seconds at an average speed of
161.363 mph.
   Five years ago: Leaders of the world's major industrialized
democracies arrived in Williamsburg, Va., for an economic summit
hosted by President Reagan.
   One year ago: Mathias Rust, a 19-year-old West German pilot,
landed a private plane in Moscow's Red Square, having evaded Soviet
air defenses. (Rust, later convicted by a Soviet court for his
daring feat, remains imprisoned.)
   Today's birthdays: Actress Carroll Baker is 57. Singer Gladys
Knight is 44. Actress Sondra Locke is 41.
   Thought for today: ``What makes us discontented with our
condition is the absurdly exaggerated idea we have of the happiness
of others.'' _ Anonymous.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
