<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-MostWanted Adv17   05-16 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Most Wanted, Adv 17,0694</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, May 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Television's `Wanted' Show Gets Its Man</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're wanted, watch out. NBC's ``Unsolved
Mysteries'' or Fox Broadcasting's ``America's Most Wanted'' may
send the police to your doorstep.
   Jerry Strickland was arrested in connection with a 1987 Michigan
murder when 20 people recognized him after seeing ``Unsolved
Mysteries'' last February.
   Strickland was watching when he was arrested. He told police it
was his favorite show.
   One fugitive, James Charles Stark, was found on the basis of a
promo for an upcoming episode of ``America's Most Wanted.'' Stark,
convicted three times as a sex offender, was wanted in the murder
of a girl in Banning, Calif., and for the rape of a woman in nearby
Hemet.
   ``America's Most Wanted'' was the highest-rated show on the Fox
network in the most recent rating period.
   Fox contends that 13 dangerous criminals are behind bars today
as a result of profiles in the first 12 weeks of ``America's Most
Wanted.''
   Robert Stack, host of ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' said four cases
have been resolved as a result of that show.
   ``This is a public service,'' said Stack. ``It works. Television
is such a saturation medium. It's like Marshall McLuhan's global
village. People blame television for passive viewing. This is
active viewing, with two-way communications. You can help solve a
mystery.''
   Both shows feature re-enactments of the crimes, often with some
of the real people who were involved.
   ``This program demonstrates that people don't have to resort to
vigilantism to help catch criminals,'' said John Walsh, host of the
Fox show. Walsh has become a national spokesman for victims since
his son, Adam, was abducted and killed seven years ago. The TV
movies ``Adam'' and ``Adam: His Song Continues'' told his story.
   ``I think these shows are also popular because people are fed up
with the level of violence in this country,'' said Walsh.
``Washington is now the murder capital of the United States. Can
you imagine, the nation's capital, and it's ahead of Miami, Detroit
and New York in murders!''
   Walsh, whose diligence got Congress to pass legislation to aid
in the location of missing children and set up a center in
Washington, said, ``I think people realize this is a great country
and we have great resources and there's no reason for violence.
People are sick of it.''
   The basic difference between the shows is that ``America's Most
Wanted'' deals only with fugitive criminals. ``Unsolved Mysteries''
gets into all types of unsolved events and missing persons.
``America's Most Wanted'' is a weekly show on the Fox network.
``Unsolved Mysteries'' appears as an occasional special on NBC, the
next scheduled for Wednesday, May 25.
   ``Many of our stories deal with normal people in abnormal
situations,'' said Stack, best known for his role as Eliot Ness on
``The Untouchables'' television series a generation ago.
   ``I don't have much sympathy for hoodlums,'' he said. ``I would
never allow a hoodlum to be sympathetic on `The Untouchables.' They
recently made a movie about Frank Nitti and made him to be a normal
person. These were psychotic killers.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   A LETTER IN THE MAIL _ Viewers for Quality Television is asking
Brandon Tartikoff, president of NBC Entertainment, to save ``A Year
in the Life.'' The organization previously helped rescue CBS'
``Cagney & Lacey'' and ``St. Elsewhere.'' VQT director Dorothy
Swanson said in a letter to Tartikoff that canceling the show would
be tantamount to ``a form of book burning, because `Year' is like a
good novel, we `read' a chapter each week, and we aren't finished
with this novel yet.'' ...
   COMEDY FEST _ Canadian comic actor John Candy will be host July
23 of the sixth annual Montreal International Comedy Festival to be
carried live on HBO. Other participants will be announced later.
Candy, who recently co-starred with Steve Martin in ``Planes,
Trains and Automobiles,'' is an alumnus of ``SCTV.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tues PMs, May 17
</TEXT>
