<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-I Adv29-2Takes   05-16 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I, Adv 29-2 Takes,1081</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 6 b&w
photos, 1 sketch, 1 logo. ColorFoto subscribers get 6 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Every kid with a cane pole and a can of worms
knows the joy of fishing. One of four Americans fish for fun. Among
them, the self-anointed elite are the 6.4 million fly fishermen. To
them, hooking a trout can be like a religious experience, and their
numbers are growing along with their passion. This is the first of
three articles.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENNIS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Johnny France remembers it, he was a boy
roaming wild in the Bear Trap Canyon when he first saw her.
   ``She was standing up on her hind legs, staring straight down
into the river as it swirled around her. Every once in a while her
big paw would shoot out, splashing her, but she kept coming up
empty-handed, either missing completely, or the slippery trout
would wiggle out of her grasp. After a very long time, completely
frustrated and still hungry, that old sow grizzly let out an angry
growl, shook herself off, and walked away in disgust.''
   France likes to tell that tall tale to the fly fishermen he
guides down the Madison River of Montana. It is his home-grown
homily about the humblings of nature on man and beast, his tactful
way of saying fly fishing is the Great Leveler _ it is merciless
toward CEOs, yuppies, one-horse cowpokes, and grizzly bears alike.
   France especially likes to spin his yarn on days when the fish
aren't biting.
   ``2,994 TROUT PER MILE!'' exclaims the State of Montana in
half-page advertisements in fishing magazines, adding its own
codicil for Doubting Thomases: ``Honest...average from five
selected Montana rivers.''
   The ad implies that fishing is so easy in Montana even a child
can do it. But a fly fisherman puts away childish things, like
night crawlers and grasshoppers.
   ``Boys should learn about trout after they have learned about
girls,'' wrote Geoffrey Norman in ``A Fisherman's Seasons.''
``Trout, and trout rivers, are sensuous and unpredictable. They
frustrate more than they reward, and they have a way of making you
feel inadequate.''
   So to be a fly fisherman is to surrender to the complexities of
30,000 fly patterns, the more than 130 different fly rods sold by
the Orvis company alone, and all the nuance and subtlety of the
sport. It is, sometimes, to be skunked, to go home with an empty
creel and dreams of the one that got away.
   ``Whenever we touched the banks of the Yellowstone (River) great
numbers of trout were seen of enormous size, swimming in water
which was so clear that every motion of the fish could be
distinctly seen...Selecting my lightest fly rod, my reel and line
were soon attached...The trout were there, I knew, and I expected
to hook one the instant the flies struck, but I was doomed to
disappointment _ there was no response...I tried every color in my
book, but to no purpose...I spent an hour without a single rise,
and at length gave it up.''
   Thus wrote Gen. William Strong in 1875 during a military
expedition through the Yellowstone country of Montana and Wyoming.
   American Indians fished for food long before Plymouth Rock, but
fly fishing was imported by British and European immigrants.
There's evidence it was practiced for sport on Eastern rivers as
far back as the Revolutionary War.
   In much of the Old Country most good fishing streams are
privately owned with no public access. Democracy gave all citizens
the right to fish the United States' public waters. That equality
explains why one in four are now fishermen. Anybody with a pole, a
line, and a hook, and who buys a license, can fish on 729 million
acres of federal, state, and municipal public lands.
   But on some days, when the wind isn't just right, or the light
is wrong, or the Great Fish God simply decrees, `No, not in this
space and time,' there will be no taut lines, stopped hearts, or
sparkling rainbows flashing through the air.
   The true mystery of fly fishing is why any trout, salmon,
steelhead (a sea-going rainbow trout), bass, or bonefish is ever
caught by a man or woman dressed up in rubber britches.
   ``It kinda makes you wonder why a fish would pick you,'' mused
France, a 47-year-old cowboy and former sheriff who's fished his
whole life.
   ``Why, with all the billions of bugs flying around and under the
water, would a big brown trout decide to eat mine?''
   Because France knows how to ``read'' water, how to match live
mosquitoes with the dead feathers and hair he ties on his hook, how
to predict the time and distance in a fish's life.
   To know what he knows is a quest which sets millions of men and
more and more women off in search of perfect equipment, perfect
rivers, the angler's equivalent of biblical tomes, and companions
with whom to share the passion and wonder which envelops an angler
the instant he hooks his first fish on an artificial fly.
   ``It was an employment for his idle time, which was then not
idly spent,'' wrote fly fishing's first guru, Izaac Walton, in
``The Compleat Angler.''
   ``...A rest to his mind, a cheerer of his spirits, a diverter of
sadness, a calmer of unquiet thoughts, a moderator of passions, a
procurrer of contentedness...and that it begat habits of peace and
patience in those that professed and practiced it.''
   Three centuries later Norman Maclean published a slim volume
containing a novella and two short stories titled ``A River Runs
Through It'' which has become another classic of the genre.
   ``In our family, there was no clear line between religion and
fly fishing,'' Maclean wrote. ``We lived at the junction of great
trout rivers in western Montana, and our father was a Presbyterian
minister and a fly fisherman who tied his own flies and taught
others. He told us about Christ's disciples being fishermen, and we
were left to assume, as my brother and I did, that all first-class
fishermen on the Sea of Galilee were fly fishermen, and that John,
the favorite, was a dry-fly fisherman.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-I Adv29-1stAdd   05-16 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I, Adv 29-1st Add,0897</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>ENNIS, Mont.: dry-fly fisherman.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dry flies being, in the lexicon of the sport, the equivalent of
the shoot-out at the OK Corral because they are little fake bugs
which float on top of the water and dare a fish to show itself when
it comes after them.
   Wet flies, which are made of more absorbent materials, sink
below the surface and therefore aren't considered as much fun by
purists.
   And purists there are, by the hundreds of thousands. Unlike
plunk and dunkers who use live bait or shiny lures to spin-cast for
catfish, bluegills, yellow perch, and black crappie, fly fishermen
are elitists.
   It isn't money that sets them apart from other fishermen,
although kings and presidents have commonly been fly fishermen.
   Never mind that today a serious (or just plain rich) angler can
spend thousands on equipment and costume.
   No, say fly fishermen, theirs is an intellectual exercise as
much as a physical workout. It is a sport where no one keeps score,
an avocation demanding as much concentration as a hostile takeover
or a friendly merger.
   ``Calling fishing a hobby is like calling brain surgery a job,''
said Paul Schullery, author of the new book ``American Fly Fishing:
A History.''
   The curious may collect hundreds of volumes on the subject,
dating from ``A Treatise on Fishing With A Hook,'' attributed to
Dame Juliana Berneres in 1496, to Tom Rosenbauer's ``Reading Trout
Streams,'' which is still in print.
   Some of America's noted writers (Ernest Hemingway, Zane Grey)
and artists (Winslow Homer, N. C. Wyeth) labored to transmit to the
unenlightened the joy and frustrations of fly fishing.
   Research can sometimes carry zealots to the outside of the
envelope. Professional angler A. J. McClane has wet a line in 141
countries and lived with Eskimos and Pygmies to learn techniques.
Author and publisher Nick Lyons, wearing goggles, once submerged
himself in a full bathtub to get a trout's-eye view. He said he
didn't learn much.
   The more the mystery deepens, the more the magic beckons.
   Some fly fishermen, especially after a great day on a fine
river, guess that the attraction is linked to man's primeval
origins. They wax poetic about the thrill of the hunt, the
one-on-one battle with a wild creature. Sometimes they compare the
experience to love.
   ``I've guided on the New Fork River (of Wyoming) for 25 years
but I've never landed a trophy on her,'' lamented Jack Dennis Jr.,
of Jackson, Wy. ``There's a certain mystery to that river, like
wondering whatever happened to the girl you loved in high school
but didn't marry.''
   Increasingly, fly fishermen say the thrill of catching a trout
or a steelhead is nearly matched by releasing it to hook again some
other day. On the sections of rivers designated gold medal and blue
ribbon by various agencies, barbless hooks and catch-and-release
regulations are the norm rather than the exception.
   Because cold-water game fish need clear, clean water to survive,
they can often be seen gliding just below the surface. Every year
nearly 180,000 visitors to Yellowstone National Park peer over the
edge of Fishing Bridge, where angling is outlawed, to watch the
fish go by. Just watch.
   The Roman poet Martial (A. D. 40-104) may have been the first to
use a feathered hook to land a saltwater fish. A hundred years
later Macedonian fishermen reportedly were catching trout on fake
flies.
   Through the ages, fishermen landed countless catches using all
kinds of artificial creations. Fly tying itself became an art.
   In 1658 Richard Franck, who served in Oliver Cromwell's army,
noted that the salmon ``delights in the most gaudy and Orient
colors you can choose.''
   Mary Ellen Orvis Marbury, whose father, Charles Orvis, founded
the nation's oldest mail-order company in 1856, was the first
person to organize and categorize fly patterns used in the United
States. She exhibited her own hand-tied flies at the Columbian
World Exposition in Chicago in 1893.
   Today's artificial flies imitate anything from a tiny egg to
snails. Hundreds are on display at the American Museum of Fly
Fishing in Manchester, Vt., which houses the history of the sport
in the New World.
   Men, women and children who wade into a trout stream do it for
their own reasons. But all are bound by unifying skeins. There is
peace in such places, the outer peace of scenery, the inner peace
of reflection.
   For a fly fisherman standing knee-deep in a swiftly flowing
stream of melted snow or a crystalline lake, there is harmony with
earth and sky, a condition increasingly rare in this high-tech,
high-density world.
   Never mind if it's raining. Never mind if the wind blows. Glory
be if it's bracing blue skies, if the trees on the bank are tender
green or autumnal gold, if the breeze is a caress.
   Never mind if the trout aren't biting or the salmon aren't
running. They did yesterday. They will tomorrow. If there's one
commandment all fly fishermen believe in, it is the optimism of
tomorrow.
   For that is the day they will finally land all the ones that got
away.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Next Sunday: Guarding the Waters</HEAD>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
