<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-I-Fireworks Adv29   05-16 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I-Fireworks, Adv 29,0719</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAYLING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More and more often, the peace and
tranquility of world-class trout streams near here are being
invaded by the distant shriek and explosion of military training.
   It's a collision of two worlds, both economically vital to the
2,000 residents of this northern Lower Peninsula town surrounded by
woods and winding rivers.
   Northeast of town is Camp Grayling, the nation's second-largest
National Guard training post. There, men and women from across the
country train for battle.
   Also to the northeast are branches of the Au Sable River,
classified by outdoors magazines as being among the top fly fishing
streams in the nation. There, men and women seek the serenity of a
shallow river twisting through wooded hills, a favorite habitat of
the trout.
   For nearly 75 years, the two sides have coexisted in relative
harmony. But recently, as the post expands its mission to include
some wintertime training and resort development expands its
holdings, they have butted into each other.
   Within five miles of some small communities, made up partly of
summertime cabins along the Au Sable and Manistee Rivers, are
ranges the Guard periodically bombards with artillery and
air-to-ground shells.
   The Guard mostly uses marker bombs, with a small explosive
charge and plenty of dye to show where a bomb hit. Sometimes, the
real thing _ bombs containing up to 500 pounds of explosives _ are
used.
   ``The Guard activity, the night firing and everything else that
goes on totally destroys the ambiance of the fly fishermen on the
river,'' says Dan Alstott, president of the AuSable Manistee Action
Council, a coalition of conservationists and other groups.
   The branches of the Au Sable, which means ``to the sands'' in
French, wind their way east to Lake Huron.
   Rusty Gates, president of the Anglers of the Au Sable, runs the
16-room Gates' Fishing Lodge on the river, where the trout season
runs from late April through October. Fish may be caught and
released anytime during the year, however.
   ``We've had flames 150 feet high right across the river'' after
Guard bombs started fires, Gates says, adding that he has briefly
evacuated his business three times because of the fires.
   ``They'll be shooting air-to-ground incendiary rockets and
everybody else can't burn trash,'' he says.
   Alstott's group has filed a lawsuit challenging the scope of
training at the camp and seeking to enforce the original agreement,
in 1913, under which only the Michigan militia could train at the
camp.
   One problem is low-flight corridors established years ago,
before multi-engined jets, which are a lot nosier. ``We get
complaints about wrecking peace and quiet,'' says Lt. Col. Brian
Downey, spokesman for the Michigan Guard.
   Occasionally, residents near the ranges report cracked windows
and fallen plaster after an exercise. If an investigation
establishes the damage was caused by the training, the Guard pays
for the repairs.
   One of the bombing ranges is near Guthrie Lake, on the northwest
border of the camp. This spring, Otsego Lake Township Assessor
Lorrie Chapman cut the value of houses off the lake itself by 50
percent.
   ``More than likely,'' she said, ``it's because of the bombing at
the bombing range.''
   To keep the noise down and to streamline training, Downey said a
new computerized mock war zone will be built farther inside the
camp's boundaries.
   Downey said as part of the Army's ``Total Force'' concept, the
Multi-Purpose Range Complex combines tank, infantry and helicopter
training with computerized targets. The range will be nestled
between two rises in the land, which should cut noise, he added.
   Gates' group strongly opposes the complex, saying it lies in the
Au Sable watershed area and, in addition to noise, may result in
pollution of the river because of the explosives.
   In Grayling itself, many in the business community welcome the
Guard. At this summer's peak, about 8,000 troops will train at the
camp.
   ``It's an advantage,'' says Mary Holden, manager of a small
downtown hotel. ``They've kept us in business for years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishing-I-People Adv29   05-16 1031</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I-People, Adv 29,1054</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-I</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jimmy Carter as president needed to get away for a while
before he went to Camp David with Israeli Prime Minister Menachem
Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, his thoughts turned to
fly fishing.
   ``When I was president, Rosalynn and I fly fished out West,'' he
says. On the pre-Camp David trip, ``I took along with me the
briefing books that I would be using to prepare myself for the
Mideast negotiations, so it was a combination of delightful
surroundings, good companions...and also just clearing my mind when
I was ready to embark on one of the major challenges of my
presidency.''
   He now fly fishes throughout the world, but loves to come home
to north Georgia to the little log cabin he furnished with his
handmade wooden furniture.
   ``The cabin is within 20 feet of Turnip Town Creek, which has a
fairly good native population of rainbow trout. It's the perfect
environment for writing in placid, beautiful surroundings, in
almost total isolation. When Rosalynn and I are there, which is
never enough, it makes for good thoughts and productive days.''
   The former president has written a new book, ``An Outdoor
Journal: Reflections and Adventures,'' recalling favorite fishing
experiences. Writing it, he said, was ``a labor of love.''
   Jack Hemingway: ``I bet I was the only American in World War II
who parachuted into Occupied France with a fly rod. I used it,
too.''
   The son of legendary fisherman and writer Ernest Hemingway now
lives in Ketchum, Idaho, between angling excursions to distant
parts of the globe. But some of his most vivid memories are of his
happy days on clear rivers with his father.
   ``When I was 6, before I'd ever picked up a fly rod, I spent one
whole summer watching him fish the Clark's Fork River of the
Yellowstone,'' Hemingway says. ``Finally, at the very end, when I'd
spent the whole summer building up the need to fish, my father
taught me how to cast.''
   Author of ``Misadventures of a Fly Fisherman,'' Jack Hemingway
says his love for the sport has lasted throughout his life. Not so
for his late father.
   ``Dad had a big nice trunk, outfitted with all his rods and
reels and tackle, everything he had collected over his years of fly
fishing'' remembers Hemingway. ``Right after that wonderful summer
on the Clark's Fork, in the fall of 1939, he had the trunk shipped
by railway express, and they lost it. He never trout fished again.
I think it was as if he felt he'd have to start all over again and
it just wasn't worth the trouble.''
   Paul Volcker: ``I took my wife fishing on our honeymoon and she
hasn't been since,'' says the former chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board.
   Volcker now teaches at Princeton University and is chairman of a
New York investment banking firm. When he resigned from the Fed
last year, he said he planned to go fishing.
   ``I went maybe eight times last summer, I ought to be doing
more,'' says Volcker, who's cast for trout in Scotland, England,
and Yugoslavia. ``You're out with nature and all that stuff. It's
nice to be more or less alone, testing your wits and skill. But I'm
a real amateur.''
   In the winter, he ties his own flies at his Manhattan home and
plots a warm weather assault on distant rivers, perhaps in New
Zealand or Montana. ``From now on I'm going to grab fishing
whenever I can get it.''
   Linda Morgens: ``On the first date with my future husband my
train into New York was late, so he occupied his time by going to
Abercrombie & Fitch and buying some artificial flies. He was very
surprised when he showed them to me and I started identifying them.
Our mutual enthusiasm for fly fishing was certainly a plus.''
   Mrs. Morgens is a veteran member of Trout Unlimited's board of
directors and chairs the nominating committee.
   ``Both my parents were fishermen _ my mother once held a blue
marlin record _ and since I was an only child I spent a lot of time
doing male sort of things with them. I grew up before the women's
lib thing, so fishing taught me how to do things on my own, taught
me I could go off alone without needing any help. In those days
there weren't that many things which could teach women to be
independent, but fly fishing was one of them.''
   Mrs. Morgens and her husband, Ned, live in South Norwalk, Conn.
   Curt Gowdy, who for 20 years hosted The American Sportsman on
ABC: ``When we'd go fishing, my dad would say, `Curtis, remember
the buffalo. There were millions of them before the white man wiped
them out for money. That could happen to trout, too.' So from the
very beginning, when I learned to fly fish at the age of 8, I was
always a catch-and-release fisherman.''
   He fishes almost everywhere now, and wherever he goes he
preaches conservation.
   Gen. John Pietrowski, commander in chief of the United States
Space Command and the North American Aerospace Command, puts in
crowded workdays in his Colorado Springs headquarters, ``but
sometimes in the evenings I can slip away, up into the mountains,
and fly fish.
   ``I always like to match wits with a trout. It's great when you
win, but the alternative isn't desirable. It's very humbling to
come home empty-handed.''
   William Horn, assistant secretary of the interior, is partial to
fishing in Montana, Alaska and Wyoming, but spends more time
fishing on the East Coast. ``Before I was working and got married
and had kids I went fly fishing 40 or 50 times a year,'' he says.
``Now I'm lucky if I go 15 times a year. But I dream about it a
lot.''
   ``I like companions who have the same appreciation for the
sport's traditions and ethics as I do, and who provide just enough
subtle competition on the stream to make it intriguing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
