<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--NewArchbishop Adv29-2Takes   05-16 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--New Archbishop, Adv 29-2 Takes,0927</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He's now the nation's highest ranking black
Roman Catholic prelate as Atlanta's new archbishop. Like the pope,
Eugene Antonio Marino is regarded as a conservative in theology and
a liberal on some social issues. His first challenge, he says, will
be to gather ``all the sheep into the fold, regardless of color. I
intend to make this clear by the way I exercise my ministry rather
than by anything I say.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After Sunday Mass at the Roman Catholic church
across from the Martin Luther King Jr. memorial, parishioners were
discussing Atlanta's new archbishop, Eugene Antonio Marino.
   ``He's a bishop who happens to be a black man, the way Doug
Williams is a black man who happens to be quarterback of the
Washington Redskins,'' ventured Victor McLemore, a black lawyer who
is president of the parish council at Our Lady of Lourdes.
   ``You mean Bishop Marino already is a winner?'' said Father
Joseph Cavallo, the white pastor of the parish that for 75 years
has been the mother church for Atlanta's black Catholics.
   At Sacred Heart parish on the opposite edge of the downtown
business and hotel district, where Los Angeles manager Tom Lasorda
takes up the collection when the Dodgers are in town, the
predominantly white congregation broke into applause when it was
announced from the altar that Atlanta would have the nation's first
black archbishop.
   There was loud clapping too at the Cathedral of Christ the King
out on Peachtree Road in Buckhead, Atlanta's yuppieland, where
parish council member Richard Farnsworth hailed the appointment as
``fitting for a city so prideful of its race relations.''
   Still in ``deep shock'' over his new job, Marino arrived in town
with an episcopal motto of ``Feed My Lambs'' that told a little
about his priorities for the poor and homeless and a
self-deprecatory joke that told a lot about himself:
   ``This may have come about through misdirected prayer. Some
people were praying for a new archbishop and some were praying even
more fervently for a strong backup quarterback for the Falcons.
Somebody up there sent in the wrong Marino. Instead of Dan from the
Miami Dolphins they got Eugene from the D.C. diocese.''
   His installation on May 5 became the hottest ticket in town.
While the Atlanta Braves were drawing fewer than 4,000 after
opening the season with 10 losses, l0,000 sought admission to the
ceremony, which already had been switched from the cathedral to the
Civic Center, seating 4,600.
   Because of the pro basketball playoffs, the archdiocese was
unable to rent the Omni, where the Democrats will hold their
national convention in July and where the 54-year-old archbishop
might have matched rock star Michael Jackson in playing to a full
house.
   Born in Biloxi, Miss., where he was an altar boy and rode his
bike to ring the 6 a.m. Angelus bell at Our Mother of Sorrows, the
nation's now highest ranking black prelate is realist enough to
know there are vast problems and some murmurs of dissent lurking
beyond the applause.
   The Atlanta archdiocese stretches north to the South Carolina
line and covers 69 counties, some of them lily white and pocketed
with remnants of the Ku Klux Klan. The corporate queen city of the
Sun Belt also witnessed in recent years a white flight to the
northern suburbs just beyond the reach of the gleaming,
graffiti-free subway line.
   In some precincts, Marino's arrival is regarded as proof
positive of what cab driver Ray Herston of Smyrna tells his
passengers: ``Atlanta is a black city. They got Andy Young for
mayor, a black city council president, a black chairman of Fulton
County, and now a black archbishop.''
   In an overall population of 3.7 million, of which about 1
million are black, the archdiocese counts 156,000 Catholics. Just
under 10,000 are black.
   While acknowledging that his appointment gives the Catholic
Church more visibility in the black community and ``is a sign of
hope for all minorities,'' Marino recognizes that his first
challenge will be to gather ``all the sheep into the fold,
regardless of color. I intend to make this clear by the way I
exercise my ministry rather than by anything I say.''
   With Cubans moving in large numbers from Miami and Tampa into
booming Atlanta, the archbishop wishes he had learned more Spanish
at home.
   When his father, Jesus Maria Marino, a baker in Puerto Rico,
migrated to Biloxi and married Lottie Bradford, the family, which
soon numbered eight children, adopted Mississippi's black culture.
   Her father had helped build Our Mother of Sorrows Church, which
like Our Lady of Lourdes in Atlanta, is a national parish with no
regular boundaries serving the black community.
   There was no telephone in the house when Marino was growing up,
``but there were always people poorer than we were.'' He came
``straight home'' from the parish grammar and high school, and
knelt in the living room with the family each evening to recite the
rosary. He credits a strong Catholic upbringing with putting him on
the road to the priesthood at age 18. ``That,'' he adds with a
gentle laugh, ``and the watchful eyes of six sisters,'' one of whom
is now a nun in Baltimore.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
