<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--NewArchbishop Adv29-1stAdd   05-16 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--New Archbishop, Adv 29-1st Add,0882</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: in Baltimore.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Marino joined the Josephites, a community of blacks and whites
founded in England after the American Civil War to evangelize the
emancipated slaves. Members have included anti-war activist Philip
Berrigan and Biloxi bishop Joseph Howzt among the 12 current
American black bishops at the head of a diocese.
   ``I never thought I'd see this in my lifetime: a black bishop in
Biloxi and now a black archbishop in Atlanta,'' Marino says.
   A few weeks after his ordination on June 6, 1962, young Marino
went into a Biloxi coin laundry with his sister, Katherine, without
seeing the ``Whites Only'' sign in the window. ``I won't say we
were thrown out,'' he wryly recalls, ``but we left in kind of a
hurry.''
   During his 14 years as an auxiliary in Washington, Marino was a
tireless advocate before congressional committees for civil rights,
the poor, homeless and unborn, and alternatives to prison.
   A jogger and physical fitness fan, he often stopped by the
Calvert winter shelter for homeless men across from St. Matthew's
Cathedral on his way to doing the ``super circuit'' of exercise
machines at the YMCA on the corner.
   The new archbishop will find the homeless on the increase in the
bustling ``Big Peach,'' where gentrification, upgrading blighted
neighborhoods with condos and town houses for yuppies and ``DINKS''
(double income, no kids) is making housing too expensive for even
blue-collar whites and blacks.
   From his pastoral work in the nation's capital, Marino is no
stranger to urban crime, the drug scene and youth gangs, which are
also on the rise with Atlanta's economic growth. He testified
movingly before a legislative committee about drugs ``turning our
cities into a nightmare of fear: l3-year-olds carrying automatic
weapons, killing for a jacket or a radio.''
   As vicar general of his order and later as secretary of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, Marino gained the
reputation of being ``a priest's priest.'' Colleagues having
problems with alcohol, church discipline or doctrine often confide
in him. His skills here will be tested early in Atlanta.
   A scandal erupted when a grand jury returned an indictment on
charges of molesting four altar boys against a priest who was
quietly allowed to return to his home diocese in England. Similar
cases of pedophilia in recent years have resulted in payments of
millions of dollars to victims by the dioceses of Orlando, Fla.,
New Orleans and St.Paul-Minneapolis.
   Just before Marino took over, an associate pastor in the same
parish as the indicted priest was disciplined by church authorities
and had to apologize from the altar after preaching at Mass that
the pope was ``dead wrong about celibacy.'' The associate pastor
suggested that contributed to the child molestation charges against
his colleague and was responsible for l4 priests leaving the
archdiocese in the past six years.
   Marino's appointment automatically makes him a national black
leader at a time when the Democrats, media-spotlighted by a
powerful Jesse Jackson delegation, will convene in the city that
enshrines civil rights landmarks such as King's grave and the
Ebenezer Baptish Church and is home to Coretta King, Andrew Young,
Julian Bond and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
   Marino played a large role in arranging the meeting of Pope John
Paul II with black leaders in New Orleans last fall and is one of
the authors of ``What We Have Seen and Heard,'' a pastoral letter
by American black bishops on the status of minorities in the church.
   Like the pope, whom he greatly admires, he is regarded as
conservative in theology and liberal on some social issues.
   During the 19-year reign of Archbishop Thomas Donnellan, who
died in October, the Atlanta archdiocese tripled in population and
the number of parishes grew to 65, more than double.
   ``When Archbishop Donnellan came, St. Patrick's Day was big, but
now I think there'll be a different emphasis,'' mused Cavallo.
``Certainly the church will be more comfortable in the black
community, where before it was more or less by invitation.''
   Despite cross burnings and even church burnings in the past,
Catholics have always been regarded as a lucky omen in Atlanta.
   On that November day in 1864 when Gen. William Sherman's troops
burned the hotels, the jail, the slave market, freight yards,
warehouses and almost eveything else in Atlanta, including the
fire-house, Immaculate Conception Catholic Church was saved after
the Rev. Thomas O'Reilly warned that Irish draftees in Union blue
would mutiny at such a sacrilege. Sherman took the threat so
seriously he spared the Episcopal, Methodist, Presbyterian and
Baptist churches, and also city hall, which luckily was close by.
   And the great Atlanta fire of May 21, 1917, stopped short of the
business dictrict when Catholics wetted down the roof of Sacred
Heart Church with all available holy water.
   Come what may, Marino is grateful to be absolved from that
enduring airline joke: ``Bound for heaven or hell, change at
Atlanta.''
   ``I've changed planes at this airport countless times,'' he
says, ``but from now on out all my flights will either originate or
terminate at Atlanta.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
