<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--New Archbishop</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta's Eugene A. Marino has made history as the first black
Roman Catholic archbishop in the United States, but the United
States had its first black Catholic bishop more than a century ago.
   Bishop James A. Healy was named to head the diocese of Portland,
Maine, in 1875.
   Listed here, with their year of appointment, are the other
current black Catholic bishops in the United States:
   The Most Rev. Harold R. Perry, auxiliary bishop of New Orleans,
1965.
   The Most Rev. Joseph Lawson Hoe, bishop of Biloxi, Miss., 1977;
previously auxiliary bishop of Natchez-Jackson, Miss., 1972.
   The Most Rev. Joseph A. Francis, auxiliary bishop of Newark,
N.J., 1976.
   The Most Rev. James P. Lyke, auxiliary bishop of Cleveland, 1979.
   The Most Rev. Emerson J. Moore, auxiliary bishop of New York,
1982.
   The Most Rev. Moses B. Anderson, auxiliary bishop of Detroit,
1982.
   The Most Rev. Wilton D. Gregory, auxiliary bishop of Chicago,
1983.
   The Most Rev. J. Terry Steib, auxiliary bishop of St. Louis,
1983.
   The Most Rev. John H. Ricard, auxiliary bishop of Baltimore,
1984.
   The Most Rev. Carl Fisher, auxiliary bishop of Los Angeles, 1986.
   The Most Rev. Curtis Guillory, auxiliary bishop of
Galveston-Houston, Texas, 1988.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
