<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--BulgingBrasilia Adv29-2Takes   05-16 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Bulging Brasilia, Adv 29-2 Takes,0931</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The idea was to build a new capital city to open
up and populate Brazil's empty central region. That it did. The
gleaming, futuristic city also lured throngs of miserably poor
peasants hoping to find jobs. Nobody counted on the resulting
overcrowding in a perimeter of satellite cities. Brasilia, as one
official puts it, is now ``a fantasy island surrounded by misery.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was called the Capital of Hope and
the Capital of the Future when it was built 28 years ago, a
modernistic city rising from scratch in the middle of a dry and
barren prairie 750 miles from the sea.
   Today Brazil's capital has become both a capital of despair and
a paradise of plenty, a city of wretched poverty and gleaming
opulence.
   Some say Brasilia is the victim of its own success.
   ``Brasilia was a modern option and was useful because it did
what it set out to do: decentralize the country, build new highways
and transfer the seat of government,'' says Oscar Niemeyer, the
architect of the slick-white linear buildings that are Brasilia's
landmarks.
   ``But Brasilia also symbolizes the spirit of Brazil, which is
discriminatory and lacks social justice,'' adds Niemeyer, now 81.
``Only a revolution will solve our problems.''
   Built to sustain 2 million people by the year 2000, Brasilia's
Federal District already has a population of 1.7 million. By the
end of the century, that number is expected to swell to 4 million,
a population the city cannot support under present conditions.
   ``When it was planned, the growth of the city was not imagined
by anyone,'' says Federal District Gov. Jose de Oliveira Aparecido.
``It is now like a beautiful woman wearing old clothes. It needs to
be modernized.''
   Today, Brasilia has the social ills of other large Brazilian
cities: overcrowding, shantytowns, land invasions, homeless
children and traffic jams.
   A lack of water, magnified by a dry season which sponges
soothing humidity from the air, adds to Brasilia's woes.
   Although Brasilia was planned to house the powerful who run the
political and administrative machinery, the poor are now the
majority.
   Lured by the very promise of the city's founders, the poor come
in tattered clothes and plastic thongs to escape the drought and
famine of the northeast.
   ``They come to find their dreams, but when they get here they
realize it's not the promised land,'' Aparecido says.
   Unable to survive in a city where only the affluent can afford
to live, they end up in one of Brasilia's 11 ``satellite cities,''
located 15 to 80 miles away.
   Federal congresswoman Maria de Lourdes Abadia has called
Brasilia ``a fantasy island surrounded by misery.''
   Ceilandia, one of the poorest satellite cities, didn't exist in
1970 and today has nearly half a million people.
   A promised land-reform program to distribute fertile land to 12
million landless peasants is stalled, attracting even more to the
Capital of Hope.
   Brazil, a developing nation larger than the continental United
States, has 143 million people and the world's eighth-largest
economy. But 70 percent of its people live in dire poverty and earn
less than $45 a week in a country which last year had inflation of
366 percent.
   Unoccupied cultivable land is scarce, and most of it belongs to
just 4 percent of the population, as it has for centuries.
   ``Without land, without money or technology to improve their
lives, the rural workers will continue to invade the city,''
Niemeyer says.
   Brasilia was erected in a flash of resolve. It was the campaign
platform of President Juscelino Kubitschek, who took office in
1956, to create a ``capital that would unite the whole nation.''
   Four years later, on April 21, 1960, as Kubitschek promised,
Brasilia was inaugurated.
   At the time, the capital was Rio de Janeiro, a tropical city of
spectacular mountains and beaches and a vibrant nightlife.
   Few wanted to move to an artificial, barren city full of red
dirt and brush land. Brasilia, far inland in the state of Goias,
didn't even have one river or spring.
   But there was no choice. Many foreign embassies were threatened
with losing accreditation if they didn't move to the new capital.
   ``There was no way of avoiding it. The lungs of Brazil are in
Brasilia. It is center of national power,'' says Aparecido, often
criticized because he spends much time visiting other capitals,
such as Paris and Rome.
   Last year, largely through Aparecido's efforts, Brasilia became
the youngest city to be named by the United Nations as a Patrimony
of Mankind, a cultural and historical heritage.
   Shaped like an airplane, Brasilia's nucleus is called the
``Pilot Plan,'' the design of architect and urbanist Lucio Costa,
now 86.
   In Brasilia's ``cockpit'' is the government, the futuristic
marbled buildings which carry the unmistakable swirling seal of
architect Niemeyer.
   Visitors are drawn to the marbled and spacious presidential
palace, where President Jose Sarney on most Fridays makes a grand
exit, walking down a swooping ramp to his limousine.
   The twin-towered, white-domed Congress, where lawmakers are
writing a new constitution inside chambers connected by underground
tunnels, becomes on weekends a playground for children who climb
the domes like ants on a hill.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
