<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--BulgingBrasilia Adv29-1stAdd   05-16 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Bulging Brasilia, Adv 29-1st Add,0817</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>BRASILIA, Brazil: on a hill.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Like rows of disciplined soldiers, identical government
ministries line a wide esplanade that leads into the residential
and commercial sectors.
   In the wings of the Brasilian ``plane'' are businesses and
apartments, called the ``superquadras,'' or superblocks, identified
only by letters and numbers. Most superquadras have their own large
supermarket and smaller bread shops, a Brazilian version of
stop-and-go shopping.
   Landscape artist Roberto Burle Marx relieved Brasilia's cool
uniformity with a mosaic of gardens and trees. The idea was to
accentuate the wide horizons and open sky of a city that had no
hills, forest or sea.
   Brasilia was not planned for pedestrians. By car, it is easy and
fast to drive down its avenues and looping highways.
   But it is difficult and slow to get around if you are one of the
million who pour in daily from the satellite cities to work. There
aren't enough buses, fares are expensive and the ride can be
dangerous. Bad drivers as well as poorly maintained buses account
for 200 accidents a month.
   Maria dos Santos, a maid who works in Brasilia, earns $70
dollars a month. She she spends half that to take three buses into
the city.
   Besides the satellite cities, some 10 ``favelas,'' Portuguese
for ghettos or shantytowns, have recently sprung up, including one
a couple of miles from the Alvorada Palace where Sarney resides.
   An empty lot, usually government property, is an invitation for
squatters to build cardboard houses. Recently, 900 descended on a
plot next to a trendy apartment building.
   With no water or electricity, the settlement was a health hazard
as well as an eyesore. Eventually police on horseback torched the
shacks and dispersed the squatters.
   To keep migrants away, the government has begun paying families
to return to their home states. In its initial stage, few are
taking up the offer.
   The cost of living in Brasilia is about the same as in Rio or
Sao Paulo, but the quality of life can be better for the well-to-do
in Brasilia.
   For example, in the residential area surrounding an artificial
lake, a three-bedroom house with a pool rents for about $1,000 a
month. In Rio, it would be double that.
   Apartments in Brasilia rent for about $200 to $600 a month,
depending on the desirability of the block.
   Aparecido boasts Brasilia ``has the best quality of life of any
city in Brazil. Where else can you have such space for so little?''
   That applies only to the elite.
   In Ceilandia, a simple one-bedroom house with just a kitchen and
bath rents for about $50 a month _ about as much as the occupant
could hope to earn.
   Brasilia has expensive restaurants and cheap restaurants,
nothing in between, with prices at the fine restaurants varying
from $20 to $40 for two people.
   Middle-level professionals such as university professors and
bankers earn $800 to $1000 a month, a lot by Brazilian standards. A
member of Congress, however, gets $7,000 a month, tax exempt.
   For fun, the poor stay in their satellite cities. If they come
in, they can hang out in one of the many corner bars which sell the
popular and cheap sugar cane liquor called ``cachaca,'' or go to a
movie. A meal at a simple restaurant can be less than $5 a person.
   The affluent go to one of the dozen tennis, golf or sailing
clubs along the lake which charge a membership of $60 to $100 a
month.
   Since every other lakeside house has a swimming pool,
entertaining at home is popular. There's not much else to do, with
few museums, theaters and concerts available for either the poor or
rich.
   Niemeyer and Costa have plans for new residential areas to take
the weight off the district's overloaded plane.
   Some officials say Brasilia's most crucial problem is lack of
water.
   The main dam built in the 1960s to supply water for 350,000
people is serving at least twice that many. The artificial lake
used as a humidifier and for sewage drainage is polluted and
infested with hardy weeds.
   For nearly six months a year, Brasilia's humidity levels dip to
below 20 percent. Last year, levels dropped to 7 percent. The
average at the Sahara desert is 13 percent, what the World Health
Organizaton says is the limit for humans.
   Water rationing is now standard during the dry season, but city
water officials foresee harder times.
   ``We need funds to buy technology to clean up the lake and build
another dam and another lake'' says Valdo Roholf, vice president of
Brasilia's water company. ``We say it will be cheaper than building
a new capital.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
