<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv29   05-16 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 29,0946</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trouble with Gary, according to actor
Peter Horton, is that he doesn't want to face the fact that he's
not going to be another Homer or Milton.
   Gary Shepherd, Michael's oldest friend and best man at Michael's
marriage to Hope on ABC's ``thirtysomething,'' simply doesn't want
to grow up. He's a free spirit, and he's having too much fun.
Besides, he's terrified.
   At the moment, Gary is having a fantasy. Dressed as a Viking,
sword in hand, he is confronting the tenure board at the
Philadelphia college where he is a classics professor.
   Horton stands on a tall ladder, beside the raised camera,
looking down at the tenure committee grouped around a conference
table. Technicians blow smoke about the room to enhance the
dream-like atmosphere.
   ``In my fantasy this is the way I'd love to treat the tenure
committee,'' he explains later. ``I come in like Errol Flynn and
bellow, `I challenge you all!' I've been turned down for tenure.
   ``I've been teaching for seven years but I haven't been
conforming to the policies of the institution, so they won't give
it to me. It has to do with Gary growing up. It's eminently
satisfying but it's not a very realistic way to react. When you're
a kid you're passionate for idealism, but you have to temper it as
you grow up or your idealism is useless.''
   Horton notes that in real life he was kicked out of Principia
College in Illinois for a similar attitude. He later finished at
the University of California at Santa Barbara. ``My best course was
Milton's `Paradise Lost,''' he says. ``My worst course was Biology
202. I never studied `Beowulf' until I got this role.''
   The crew is at the Wilshire Ebell Theater to film the sequence
for the show, which focuses on a group of so-called ``yuppies'' and
has become a favorite of college students and the upwardly mobile
thirtyish generation. For the past season, it was tied for 46th
place and among new shows it was tied for eighth place.
   The show also stars Ken Olin as Michael, Mel Harris as Hope,
Timothy Busfield, Polly Draper, Melanie Mayron and Patricia Wettig.
It was created by Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick.
   The episode, which was telecast earlier this month, ended with
Gary losing tenure and appealing the decision.
   Gary is a passionate teacher whose speciality is the classical
epic, such as ``Beowulf'' and ``The Iliad.'' Unfortunately, it
doesn't have much relevance to today's world. He would like to be
like one of his classical heroes, but his discipline melts when
there's an opportunity to go to bed with a pretty coed.
   ``Gary represents the character in all of us who is afraid to
grow up,'' says Horton, who has long blond hair and a thick growth
of stubble on his chin. ``I think the main reason for that is that
he's afraid to admit the end of his potential. When you're growing
up you have a fantasy of what your potential is, but at some point
you have to come to terms with it. He has to face the fact that
he's not going to be a Homer or a Milton or a Mozart. Or even a
college professor.
   ``He's very intelligent and on some levels very wise. He sleeps
around, but he's honest about it. He has his own morality. There's
a much deeper reality to everyday living. How do you define
yourself? Are you able to be a loyal friend and love people? Gary
is a much better friend to Michael than I am to my friends.''
   In the show, Gary and Michael were high school friends who went
to college together. They were involved in politics and
demonstrations.
   ``But as we got older he went into the corporate world and I
tried to stay the same,'' says Horton. ``That provides a lot of the
tension in our relationship. He has a sense of guilt for his
perception that he has forsaken his youthful ideals. On the other
hand, he has become a responsible adult and is a constant reminder
to me of what I should be doing.''
   Horton was born in Bellevue, Wash., but his father's shipping
business took him as a youngster to Hong Kong, Japan, Thailand and
the Philippines. ``I remember once in Bangkok a monkey came flying
out of a tree and landed on my shoulders,'' he says. ``I was in
heaven. We spent some time on cargo ships. Once we hit a big storm
and my sister and I put socks on our hands and feet and slid all
over the place.''
   He got his degree in music composition and planned to become a
conductor. ``I got into acting by accident,'' he says. ``I
auditioned for a repertory company in Santa Barbara as a pianist. I
needed the money. I ended up studying with them and stayed for nine
months.''
   Horton appeared in three movies before ``thirtysomething,'' and
in his short career has done almost as much directing as acting. He
has directed several episodes of the series, an ABC Afterschool
Special, a segment of the movie ``Amazon Women on the Moon,'' and
has several projects in development.
   ``I thought I was going to be a conductor,'' he says. ``But
directing is a lot like conducting.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
