<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Rambo Adv22-2Takes   05-16 0950</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Rambo, Adv 22-2 Takes,0981</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv22</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rambo III Revises Rambo II's Rewrite of Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time we saw him, he had a question.
``Do we get to win this time?''
   And you did, Rambo II _ with a knife, a bow and arrow and just a
little help from a Vietnamese girlfriend. Three years later comes
``Rambo III,'' and the Vietnam War according to Sylvester Stallone
has come full circle.
   Captured by Soviet forces in Afghanistan, Rambo's mentor, Col.
Trautman, explains that wars against determined opponents on their
home ground cannot be won.
   ``We've already had our Vietnam,'' Trautman snarls. ``Now you're
gonna get yours.''
   With that tip of the beret to those gritty guys in the Viet
Cong, Rambo is off to Afghanistan on another private war _ and
maybe nothing's changed at all.
   ``Rambo still thinks that way,'' said Stallone, who also writes
the scripts. ``It's just different characters, see?''
   ``Rambo III'' features more of the cartoonish
``Roadrunner''-style violence of its predecessors, with the
slow-talking, fast-shooting fighting machine joining horse-mounted
holy warriors to subdue Soviet armor.
   It's the same invincible John J. Rambo that delighted President
Reagan at the time of the TWA hijacking in Beirut in 1985. ``After
seeing `Rambo' last night, I know what to do the next time this
happens,'' Reagan joked.
   ``That's wrong,'' Stallone says hotly. ``Rambo goes in to end
conflicts, not initiate them. He didn't go in to kick the Russians'
butts, he went in to get his friends out.''
   David Morrell, the former Iowa State English professor who
introduced Rambo in the novel ``First Blood,'' says he also was
offended by Reagan's jest.
   ``I can't say I was amused,'' Morrell said, ``because I was
distressed by the interpretation of the character. But I was
bemused because it's a way of being told how powerful the character
is. So I was gratified by that.''
   ``Rambo: First Blood Part II'' grossed $150 million in U.S.
theaters, spawned a line of fighting dolls and fearsome squirt guns
and made ``Rambo'' a part of the language.
   Reagan's joke marked the first time that any Associated Press
story from Washington mentioned Rambo, but other references
followed. Reagan invoked Rambo again on behalf of tax reform in
September 1985, but mostly Rambo became a term of abuse hurled by
Democrats.
   ``I see where Rambo is now `it' with the young,'' former vice
president Walter Mondale said three years ago, complaining of a
``Rambo streak'' in the White House. ``War is great. You can shoot
and won't be shot. Complexity is blown away by simple violence.''
   Stallone and Morrell, who recently came to New York to promote
the film, both say Rambo is a man of peace, not a jingoistic
murderer but a celluloid descendant of the frontier gunslinger
forced into one last battle.
   ``I find it incredible,'' Stallone says, his voice rising,
``every time some local atrocity occurs where a man puts on fatigue
pants and takes a rifle and goes into a shopping center, it's
`Rambo murderer slays three.'
   ``Rambo doesn't kill innocents. ... He's never killed unarmed
children.''
   In 1985, a 17-year-old in Missouri who had seen ``First Blood''
half a dozen times put on camouflage gear, picked up a kitchen
knife and a pistol and attacked his neighbors. He was convicted of
assault, burglary and armed criminal action.
   ``I can philosophically put it into this bag, that this child
was an accident waiting to happen,'' Stallone says. ``If it wasn't
Rambo, it was going to be another fictional character, which he
would just use as his _ I don't know _ his primer cord.''
   ``I keep close watch of this, and I know of only six cases in
which the Rambo character was blamed for violent events,'' says
Morrell. Three were in the United States, he said, and the others
in England, Australia and Canada.
   ``When I look into these things, what happened was that we were
dealing with psychotics, people who were unbalanced. If it hadn't
been one thing, it would have been that their Rice Krispies didn't
snap, crackle and pop properly in the morning.''
   So what does Rambo stand for? That depends, in part, whether
it's the books or the films.
   Morrell, who had Rambo criticizing U.S. policy in Central
America in his book of ``Rambo II,'' had suggested setting the $63
million ``Rambo III'' in Nicaragua.
   Stallone nixed that, in part because he didn't want another
jungle picture. But if Rambo fears anything, it's controversy.
   ``Until that conflict is really over, or until the line of
demarcation is drawn . . . then I can't jump into that,'' Stallone
said of Nicaragua.
   Afghanistan, however, was one place where Congress and Reagan
agreed on who wore the black hats.
   ``You have 300 million Russians vs. 12 million Afghans who are
undernourished, underarmed, undertrained and they are holding their
own. Finally, after 8{ years they are receiving some assistance,''
Stallone said.
   ``But Rambo doesn't go in to fight Russians. When they accuse me
or my characters of red-bashing, that is irresponsible, because he
never says, `I'm gonna get that dirty commie.' It never came out of
his mouth.''
   Gee, maybe it was all the exploding Russians in ``Rambo II'' or
the hulking Soviet boxer in ``Rocky IV'' that gave the impression
that Stallone harbors strong feelings about Moscow.
   ``I used to think I did,'' he said. ``I understand `glasnost,'
and the Soviets' need to do this. ... I'm all for `glasnost.' I
think the military branch is totally out of line, and they've made
mistakes, and this is their Vietnam.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Rambo Adv22-1stAdd   05-16 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Rambo, Adv 22-1st Add,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: their Vietnam.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps the real villain in Rambo's world is the U.S. government.
   In ``First Blood,'' which became a film in 1982, Rambo wages war
against a sheriff who was a decorated hero of the Korean War. The
story ends with an innocent American town in flames.
   In ``Rambo II,'' he was stranded in enemy territory by a
cynical, lying, high-level bureaucrat who was covering up the
presence of American prisoners in Vietnam.
   The worst that can be said of the U.S. Embassy official in
``Rambo III'' is that he's a little brusque.
   Morrell regards the Rambos II and III as exhibitions of special
effects.
   ``Nobody is pretending that this is great art,'' he says.
   When ``Rambo III'' was screened for critics here, Tri-Star
Pictures filled out the audience with adolescent males who cheered
the title, cheered the first glimpse of Stallone's face, cheered
Rambo's knife and cheered his bow and arrow.
   A head goes through a windshield. ``Yeah!'' Trautman is strung
up by his arms. ``Hahaha!'' Rambo turns a Soviet soldier into an
exploding yo-yo. ``YEAH!''
   ``Who are you?'' the Soviet commander radios. ``Your ... worst
... nightmare,'' Rambo grunts, and the kids dig it.
``Ooooooooooooooo!''
   As absurdities piled up, even the critics were laughing at mass
slaughter.
   In the first book, which had a body count in excess of 200 _
compared to two or three deaths in the first film _ Morrell had
this explanation for Rambo:
   ``He had killed a great many people, and he could pretend their
deaths were necessary because they were all a part of what was
pushing him, making it impossible for someone like him to get
along. But he did not totally believe it. He had enjoyed the fight
too much.''
   Stallone feels the impulse to violence. Even his Lincoln Hawk,
the gentle, arm-wrestling father in ``Over the Top,'' cracked a few
jaws and crashed a truck into a mansion.
   ``I find myself frustrated when words prove futile,'' Stallone
says. ``You're philosophically right, and you're morally right, and
you somehow cannot get your way _ you don't get respect, you don't
get listened to, so you become frustrated.
   ``Yes, I feel that way a lot,'' Stallone admits, ``but I take it
out usually in my scripts.
   ``Like, when you say the `exploding yo-yo,' the Soviet who
explodes, the reason is _ rather than just have him die or be hung,
to have him self-immolate, that to me is kind of a blatant message
that that kind of evil doesn't deserve a resting place.''
   The Rambo of the books has a Hamlet streak, to kill or not to
kill. But Stallone's Rambo won't talk about self-defense or just
wars. His audience, he says, doesn't want lectures.
   ``They know the essence of the character, and they know what he
does best and they want to get to it,'' he says.
   Stallone is already thinking about ``Rambo IV,'' scouting the
globe for a crisis where one mean dude could lend a hand.
   ``Panama is leading up to be a very interesting situation,''
says Stallone, who regards Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega as the
perfect villain.
   ``Could you cast a better man? Seriously? I mean, he's God-sent
_ good guy, bad guy, the face, the look, his own private army, the
drugs _ I mean, the canal itself, the importance. Incredible!
That's a scenario.''
   So back to the jungle?
   ``Yeah, go down and teach him how to breakdance,'' Stallone
growls. ``Have a little rap session at Noriega's house this
weekend.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Adv for Sunday, May 22</HEAD>
