<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Rambo-Crenna Adv22   05-16 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Rambo-Crenna, Adv 22,0688</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Rambo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Richard Crenna Accidentally Becomes Rambo's Mentor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It all started when Kirk Douglas walked out
on a movie just before the cameras rolled. Now Richard Crenna finds
himself in what could amount to a lifetime job: as mentor-father
figure to the invincible Rambo.
   ``I don't know why (Douglas) left the film, and it's really not
my business,'' recalls Crenna. ``I was sent the script of `First
Blood' and called to the wilds of British Columbia. That was a very
fortuitous call for me.
   ``It's been a real experience, finding myself in this kind of
film and, if you will, this kind of social phenomenon coming out of
the Rambo series.''
   Richard Crenna is no stranger to the show world. At 61 he has
clocked a half-century as a performer, starting as a radio actor at
11.
   ``I was playing six or seven running roles at the same time;
once I did nine,'' he recalled.
   He is a veteran of films (``The Sand Pebbles,'' ``Body Heat'')
and television (``Our Miss Brooks,'' ``The Real McCoys''), but
nothing prepared him for the impact of the ``Rambo'' movies
starring Sylvester Stallone.
   ``The audience's perception of you is related to what you are on
the screen,'' he observed. ``I've been a chameleon in my career;
the audience never knows where they're going to find me. They lift
a rock and there's Crenna.
   ```Rambo' has brought a new kind of recognition. When you're
walking down the streets of New York and you're in a series like
`The Real McCoys,' people want to take you home and give you a
barbecue. When you play an authority figure as I did in the
`Slattery's People' series, they say, `Good afternoon, Mr. Crenna,
are you enjoying your trip?'
   ``Now I'm getting hard hats 14 stories up yelling down, `Hey,
Rich, what's happenin'? Where did you leave Rambo?'''
   Crenna's role as Col. Trautman has been both complementary and
contrasting to John Rambo: the logical, level-headed commander, and
the impetuous fighting machine. Trautman usually shows up before or
after the action, but not in ``Rambo III.''
   ``In this film for the first time, Rambo and Trautman are in
action together,'' Crenna said. ``I was forewarned by Sly, who
called several months before we started and said, `You better get
in shape, Crenna, because I'm going to show you what it's like to
do what I have to do.'
   ``I said, `No, you're kidding, I'm too old to be running up and
down mountains.' He said, `Get in shape.' So for three months I got
in shape, and thank God I did. Because it was a very, very
difficult picture.''
   ``Rambo III'' filmed for 5{ months in Israel, Thailand and Yuma,
Ariz., and the experience reinforced Crenna's awe for Stallone's
dedication: ``He gets up at 5 every morning to work out so he can
stay in shape. In `First Blood' he worked in 40-below weather
wearing a tank top. The temperature reached 130 in the Negev on the
last picture.''
   A conscientious actor, Crenna has tried to bring dimension in a
film series not noted for character development: ``I approach
everything I do with enthusiasm and an attempt to bring honesty to
the character. I try to make Trautman first and foremost a human
being. Then I put on the green beret. Hopefully, I put a human
being under the beret.''
   Viewing his 50 years as an actor, Crenna marveled: ``I don't
know how I've survived. Tenacity, for one thing. Also the fact that
I've never been a so-called `movie star.' I've always considered
myself a working actor; that's what I do for a living.
   ``That's enabled me to discover a lot of things about myself and
my craft. Hopefully, I'll be able to continue until they put me in
a chair, take me out to the home and set me on the lawn.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
