<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--CryingBabies-Sleep Adv19   05-16 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Crying Babies-Sleep, Adv 19,0264</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Healthy Babies Really Can Sleep All Night</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Crying Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virtually all children free of major medical or
neurological problems have the ability to sleep well, says Dr.
Richard Ferber.
   Ferber, a sleep expert at Children's Hospital, says that beyond
the first six months of infancy, almost every youngster is capable
of going to bed at an appropriate hour, falling asleep within
minutes and staying asleep until a reasonable hour in the morning.
   In his book ``Solve Your Child's Sleep Problems,'' (Simon &
Schuster, $7.95) Ferber lists these additional facts and opinions
about children's sleep:
   _A newborn sleeps 16 or 17 hours a day, while a 1-year-old gets
about 14 hours. By age 3 until adolescence, children gradually need
less sleep. A 12-year-old should get about 10 hours. Needs vary
from child to child.
   _The majority of children don't like to sleep in total darkness,
and there is no reason they should. A night light or hall light
helps children get their bearings if they wake up, especially after
a dream.
   _Children should be put on a regular sleeping schedule. Don't
let a 2- or 3-year-old decide what time to go to bed.
   _Once babies are about 3 months old, they no longer need to be
fed at bedtime and several times during the night. If babies beyond
this age awaken several times and must be fed to go back to sleep,
feeding is causing a sleep problem.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
