<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--SpaceJunk Adv19   05-16 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Space Junk, Adv 19,0592</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 19, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Earth's Orbit Is a Junkman's Dream</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Soviet Union launched Cosmos 1941 on
April 27, it added to the productive satellites in orbit but also
contributed 28 pieces to the junk that circles the Earth.
   Every time a rocket slices through the atmosphere to the void
beyond, it adds to the litter. Some of the 7,110 pieces in orbit
are destined to travel around the globe for all time.
   The United States and Soviet Union are the principal
contributors of man-made objects in space, which range in size from
a screwdriver dropped by a space-walking astronaut to the Soviet
Mir space station.
   Somewhere out there, too _ if they haven't re-entered the
atmosphere and burned up _ are 10 or 12 screws about [-inch in
diameter, missing when the 1984 shuttle mission returned from
repairing the Solar Max satellite.
   Another object that racked up millions of miles before it
finally burned up was the thermal glove that floated out of Gemini
4 in 1965 while Ed White had the hatch open for the first space
walk by an American.
   The U.S. Space Command in Colorado tracks all objects in space
and all countries are obligated to inform one another about their
launches.
   Six days after the Cosmos 1941 launch, in a weekly update, the
space command said 3,246 of the 7,110 pieces they were tracking by
radar came from the Soviet Union. The trackers said they detected
28 new pieces and that eight others had ``decayed'' _ re-entered
the atmosphere _ for a net gain of 20 pieces.
   The United States was responsible for 3,148 pieces, the European
Space Agency, 481; Japan, 82, and France, 40.
   The totals are nearly always three pieces of space debris for
every working satellite. More than half the debris comes from more
than 90 satellites that have exploded unaccountably, according to
Don Kessler, project scientist for debris studies at NASA's Johnson
Space Center.
   Dangerous chunks of shrapnel, whizzing through space at 22,000
mph, also come from spent rocket bodies that shatter when residual
fuels come in contact with each other. ``A 3-millimeter particle
has as much kinetic energy as a bowling ball going 60 miles an hour
and if it hit an electrical component, it would probably cause that
system to cease functioning,'' Kessler said.
   Space shuttle Challenger returned from a mission in June 1983
with a chip in the middle window on the right side of the cockpit.
Chemical analysis showed the culprit was a flake of the paint used
on rockets and payloads. The window had to be replaced.
   Space station planners ``are faced with a considerable design
problem'' because of the junk, Kessler said, and have added 2,000
pounds of shielding to each of the six modules that will be
occupied by astronauts.
   The explosions of satellites or rockets often aren't detected
for a year or more after they occur, he said. A French-made Ariane
rocket blew up nine months after it deposited its cargo in space.
The fragments of that explosion, probably caused by
overpressurization of gases, number 450.
   After six U.S. Delta rocket second stages exploded _ the last in
1981, three years after it was launched _ the manufacturer fixed
the flaw that caused the blasts, leaks in tanks holding fuels that
burn when they combine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Fungus Adv19   05-16 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Fungus, Adv 19,0549</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, May 19, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Finding New Tools for Agriculture in a Moldy Mess</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a federal laboratory just up the road from
the University of Georgia sit dozens of Pyrex beakers filled with
moldy Spoon Size Shredded Wheat.
   The mess in the beakers is the work of a self-described
simple-minded Briton who finds in his fungi the stuff of an
agricultural revolution: natural compounds that can do the work of
harmful chemicals.
   Hank Cutler is a plant physiologist at the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Richard B. Russell Research Center, a high-rise that
borders the university campus but which few students ever visit.
   To describe his work, Cutler likes to explain how discovery of
penicillin from the penicillium mold turned medicine away from the
use of dangerous metals for drugs and toward the use of natural
antibiotics. ``The same sort of thing is happening in agriculture.
Perhaps now we need agricultural chemicals that are biodegradable
and don't impact the environment.''
   Cutler grows fungi, often using as his medium Spoon Size
Shredded Wheat; with its little cross-hatch pieces, the cereal
seems to work just fine for growing mold. Just add a little yeast
and sugar.
   He later filters the mold to fine compounds that might have some
biological action of their own.
   ``There may be 30, 40, 50 compounds in there, and I've got to
get out the one that's active. That's the art. I see something
interesting in that gunk, and I say, `How the hell am I going to
get it out of there?'''
   Some of the compounds he's found include:
   _Cyclopenin, a chemical from penicillium mold that acts as a
tranquilizer on baby chicks. ``It contains the same structural
elements as diazepam,'' the drug sold as Valium, Cutler said. It
also retards growth in some plants.
   _Cyclopenol, which kills the fungus that caused the great Irish
potato famine and still attacks crops.
   _Cytochalasin-H, which controls flowering in certain plants.
   Cutler's latest discovery is a compound he grew from special
wine grapes and dubbed cinereain.
   ``It's not terribly active, but I bet that it will have
significant pharmaceutical activity'' because structurally it
resembles other compounds used in the pharmaceutical industry, he
said. ``That's a hunch. ... I'm probably dead wrong. But I can
guarantee you it's got biological activity.''
   Cutler's findings on cinereain will be published next month by
the Japanese journal Agricultural and Biological Chemistry. ``I
like to publish on their turf, because I then know that I'm highly
competitive,'' he said.
   Cutler, who's made a career of studying fungi, the last 20 years
in Georgia for the USDA, fears the United States is falling behind
the Far East in agricultural biochemistry. American agriculture has
been liberal with non-biodegradable farm chemicals; Japan, with its
land constraints, has turned to chemicals that don't harm the
environment.
   ``I believe very strongly that within the next five to seven
years we will be importing Japanese agricultural chemicals based on
natural products,'' he said, ``and we'll be wringing our hands _
just like the automobile _ and saying, `Gee whiz, what happened?' ''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-QuittingSmoking Adv19   05-16 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--What's New-Quitting Smoking, Adv 19,0255</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Anti-Depressant May Be Latest Help for Would-Be Ex-Smokers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doxepin, a drug used to treat depression, may be
the latest way to help people quit smoking, a new study suggests.
   Smokers who took doxepin before and during abstinence showed
less craving, anxiety, restlessness and difficulty in concentrating
than those who took a placebo, said researcher Neil Edwards of the
University of Tennessee.
   After eight weeks, nine of 12 doxepin users continued to abstain
from smoking, compared with only one of 13 on the placebo,
according to Edwards, who described the results at a recent
American Psychiatric Association meeting.
   He undertook the study after three psychiatric patients who took
doxepin for depression mentioned they had quit smoking without
withdrawal symptoms.
   The crucial time for relapse extends for a year after quitting,
so studies will have to run at least that long to assess doxepin's
effectiveness, Edwards said. Other treatments also have been
effective in the short term.
   All the subjects had smoked at least five years and averaged 38
cigarettes a day. ``They were significant smokers,'' Edwards said.
   Both groups received individual counseling at weekly sessions,
he said.
   Edwards, whose study was financed by the university, said the
biochemical mechanism for the effect of doxepin in ex-smokers is
not known. Drowsiness, dry mouth and constipation are common side
effects of the drug.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv19   05-16 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 19,0649</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for May 19 in summary form.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby that wakes up and howls at night often is
frustrated by an insolvable problem: how to fall back to sleep.
   Dr. Richard Ferber of the Center for Pediatric Sleep Disorders
says virtually all healthy, full-term infants can sleep through the
night by age 5 or 6 months. Babies who wake up and cry can usually
develop good sleep habits in three or four nights, or at worst a
week or two.
   The most widely recommended strategy for restoring peace is to
let the child cry. Another is to check on the baby periodically but
resist the urge to give it a bottle. Then there's the relatively
new ``scheduled awakening'' method that involves rousing a child
before it normally wakes you.
   Ferber recommends creating a sleep routine for your child that
he can follow without you being there in the middle of the night.
Start by putting the child to bed while he is awake, in a
reasonably dark, quiet room without being rocked or given a back
rub or pacifier.
   If he cries, wait five minutes, then return and let him know he
hasn't been abandoned. But don't pick him up. If he still cries,
wait 10 minutes and go in briefly. The next time, wait 15 minutes.
Look in every 15 minutes until he falls asleep. Each night, add
five minutes to the waiting periods.
   Inability to get back to sleep is the most common cause of
nighttime crying. Others include ear infections, breathing
difficulties, toilet training, a new bed, starting day care or
fighting between the parents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Soviet Union launched Cosmos 1941 on
April 27, it added one productive satellite in orbit and 28 pieces
of junk.
   Every rocket that slices through the atmosphere to the void
beyond adds to the litter, which totals 7,110 pieces, according to
the U.S. Space Command in Colorado, which tracks each chunk. The
United States and Soviet Union are the principal contributors, with
3,148 and 3,246 pieces, respectively.
   The trash has included paint flakes, screws and even the thermal
glove that floated out of Gemini 4 in 1965 on America's first space
walk.
   Space station planners ``are faced with a considerable design
problem,'' because of the junk, says Don Kessler, project scientist
for debris studies at NASA's Johnson Space Center. They've added
2,000 pounds of shielding to each of the six modules that will be
occupied by astronauts.
   ``A 3-millimeter particle has as much kinetic energy as a
bowling ball going 60 miles an hour,'' Kessler says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a laboratory just up the road from the
University of Georgia, Hank Cutler is using beakers of Spoon Size
Shredded Wheat to grow fungi that provide natural compounds to do
the work of harmful chemicals.
   To describe his work, Cutler, a plant physiologist at the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's Richard B. Russell Research Center,
explains how discovery of penicillin from the penicillium mold
turned medicine away from the use of dangerous metals for drugs and
toward the use of natural antibiotics.
   ``Perhaps now we need agricultural chemicals that are
biodegradable and don't impact the environment,'' he says.
   Already, he's identified cyclopenin, a chemical similar to
Valium that acts as a tranquilizer on baby chicks and retards
growth in some plants; cyclopenol, which kills the fungus that
caused the Irish potato famine; and cytochalasin-H, which controls
flowering in certain plants.
   Cutler fears the United States is falling behind the Far East in
agricultural biochemistry. American agriculture has been liberal
with farm chemicals; Japan, with its land constraints, seeks
biodegradable chemicals.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
