<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Researchers Encouraged By Bone Marrow Technique</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers say they're encouraged by a new
method of fighting one of the main obstacles facing leukemia
victims who need bone marrow transplants: a disease in which the
transplanted marrow attacks the body.
   Graft-versus-host disease is the reverse of the reaction wherein
the body rejects a transplanted organ. Dr. Roy Wu of the National
Cancer Institute says more recipients die from GVHD than from
relapses of their leukemia.
   In the new method, Johns Hopkins Oncology Center researchers
used a centrifuge to remove T-lymphocytes, immune system components
that trigger rejection, then implanted cell-rich marrow necessary
for the production of healthy blood and for successful grafts. They
also administered cyclosporin, an anti-rejection drug that doctors
had been using as part of leukemia treatment.
   The 12-month survival rate for patients treated with cyclosporin
is only about 35 percent. Dr. Albert Donnenberg, of Johns Hopkins,
says 50 percent of patients receiving the new treatment survived
the year. Patients who began the new treatment while in remission
for leukemia had a 63 percent survival rate compared with 39
percent for patients who were in early relapse.
   Donnenberg says it is too early to claim success because the
center has not done a controlled study in which two groups are
treated and studied.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Stress Seems to Play Major Role in Viet Vet Health Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of more than 15,000 American soldiers
indicates that Vietnam veterans were almost twice as likely to
report medical problems as those who served elsewhere, and suggests
the difference may be stress-related.
   ``Vietnam veterans also showed more anxiety and depression in a
battery of psychological tests,'' says the Vietnam Experience
Study. ``Stress can produce anxiety, depression and a variety of
somatic (physical) symptoms.''
   The Centers for Disease Control conducted phone interviews with
7,924 GIs who served in Vietnam in 1965-1971 and 7,364 who served
elsewhere. Extensive physicals were given to a subsample of 2,490
Vietnam veterans and 1,972 others.
   The study found no physical indications of exposure to Agent
Orange and said ``perceived exposure'' to herbicides is linked with
psychological problems and with reported health problems that did
not show up in physical exams.
   Vietnam veterans were almost twice as likely (19.6 percent to
11.1 percent) to report health problems. Yet, doctors who did not
know the military history of the two groups examined them and could
detect few medical differences.
   The Vietnam veterans have a higher incidence of alcohol abuse,
anxiety and depression, greater hearing loss and a measurably lower
sperm count. Fifteen percent suffered symptoms of combat-related
post traumatic stress disorder.
   The study was ordered by Congress as part of veterans benefit
bills passed in 1979 and 1981.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Mummy Under Glass to Test Preservation Method</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARINA DEL REY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists plan to entomb a
3,000-year-old mummy dubbed Lady X to test a hermetically sealed
display case designed to prevent the decay of Egypt's mummies and
other antiquities.
   The glass-walled cases will be filled with inert nitrogen gas,
silica gel to keep relative humidity at 30 percent to 40 percent,
and a special powder to destroy any oxygen. Temperatures will be
kept at 68 to 72 degrees Fahrenheit.
   Lady X, believed to have been a commoner, was found near Luxor
in the 1960s and was the first mummy sent out of Egypt since the
remains of Pharaoh Ramses II were taken to Paris in 1976 for
radiation treatment to halt fungal decay.
   She will rest for one to three months in the new display case as
a test.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Heart Recipients Have Difficulty Adjusting to New Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart transplant recipients need help learning
to get the most out of life, say researchers who found that more
than half the patients in a new study suffered mood disturbances
and many faced family problems.
   Side effects of post-surgical medication, including headache,
burning pains and reduced sexual performance, cause some of the
problems, according to Peter Shapiro and Donald Kornfeld of
Columbia University's College of Physicians and Surgeons in New
York. The two studied 73 heart recipients.
   One study group of 30 patients was interviewed up to a year
after surgery; another group of 43 were studied up to six years
after the transplant.
   Thirty-seven patients had mood disturbances such as
demoralization and difficulty adjusting to post-transplant life;
four cases suffered major depression. Fifteen had mood swings,
irritability and argumentativeness. Symptoms began the first few
weeks after surgery and receded as dosages of anti-rejection drugs
were tapered off.
   Twelve patients had family or marital troubles, such as children
running away from home or picking fights with their parents. The
problem was especially common with teen-age sons who resented the
father's trying to re-assert a role of disciplinarian after the
disabling heart condition was over.
   Sixteen patients complained of decreased memory.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Focus Turned From Replacement Artificial Heart to Assist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government, after spending $239.31
million trying to develop a completely artificial human heart, is
turning its attention to smaller pumps that can assist, rather than
replace, a failing heart.
   ``There are still a lot of problems'' that cannot soon be solved
with a total heart replacement device, according to Dr. Claude
Lenfant, director of the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute.
Every attempt at replacing human hearts has resulted in a patient
dying of either infection or stroke caused by blood clots that
develop within the mechanical heart.
   The National Institutes of Health now will support only four
grants for development of a self-contained, long-term ``single
ventricular'' device, which would be inserted into the left
ventricle of the heart, the chamber that endures most of the work
stress in the four-chambered human heart.
   The grants will go to Thermedics Inc. of Woburn, Mass.; Abiomed
of Danvers, Mass.; Nimbus Inc. of Sacramento, Calif., and Novacor
of Oakland, Calif.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 19</NOTE>
