<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Outlook     05-16 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Outlook,0909</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Outlook</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting and holding a job in the 1990s is
going to be easier than it was this decade as the population ages
and the labor force grows more slowly.
   But getting the good jobs in the fastest-growing fields such as
health services, data processing and management, will require more
education, training and a willingness to develop new skills
periodically, according to experts.
   ``The growth will be predominantly among those occupations
generally requiring post-secondary education,'' says Janet L.
Norwood, commissioner of the Bureau of Labor Statistics. ``The
greatest decline will be in those jobs generally requiring less
than a high school education.''
   About 38 percent of the 20 million new jobs that the American
economy is expected to create between now and the year 2000 will
require at least one year of college or more, according to
government projections.
   The greatest demand will be for skilled technicians and service
workers, particularly in the computer and medical fields, followed
by managers and sales workers in the skyrocketing number of small
businesses. Together, they will account for half of the new jobs by
the end of the century.
   Not needed are more farmers and private household, forestry and
fishing workers. Employment in all of those fields is expected to
decline from its current level by 3 percent to 6 percent over the
next 12 years.
   And for other less-skilled occupations, such as manual laborers,
operators or assembly line workers, job growth is projected to
climb only a total of 2.5 percent by 2000, in contrast to an 18
percent projected employment growth in the economy as a whole.
   ``It is going to be a lot rougher than it used to be for people
without a high school education,'' says Richard Belous, a labor
market economist for The Conference Board, a business research
group financed largely by Fortune 500 companies.
   ``There has always been a premium on education, but that premium
is increasing,'' Belous said. ``Even traditional industries for
blue-collar workers, such as mining and construction, are becoming
more skill-based, requiring people who can deal with
numerically-controlled equipment, computers and blueprints.''
   Because of the increasing complexity of hospital care, the
biggest demand for any single occupation will be registered nurses,
whose average pay now ranges between $20,000 and $27,000 a year.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics projects employment of nurses
will grow 44 percent, or by 612,000, between now and 2000, but
cautions that some career paths will be restricted to those with
bachelor's degrees in the field.
   A dramatic increase in the need for workers exists in all of the
health fields. Among them, job growth is expected to rise 30
percent for dentists, 63 percent for dental hygienists, 75 percent
for medical record technicians, 38 percent for physicians, 65
percent for radiologic tecnologists and 87 percent for physical
therapists.
   Job growth in the relatively young field of physicians
assistants, now with only 26,000 people in it, is expected to climb
57 percent over the next decade.
   And the demand for legal assistants will double, reflecting what
Belous sees as an increasing trend among professionals in all
occupations to turn more of their workload over to
paraprofessionals as the demand for their services increases.
   ``Relatively speaking, these jobs provide good salaries, job
mobility and careers for people who lack the resources or
inclination to attend college for four years,'' he said.
   ``Even the prestigious law and accounting firms are under coming
under such intense cost pressures from their clients that they are
turning more of the routine work that used to be done by senior
partners over to paralegals and para-accountants,'' Belous said.
``The model we're gravitating towards is the dentist's office where
the majority of the patient's time is spent with the hygienist.''
   For college graduates, the biggest job growth will occur among
physicians, an increase of 188,000 by the year 2000; electrical and
electronics engineers, up 192,000, and lawyers, up 191,000.
   The marketing, advertising and public relations fields also will
see a job growth of about 32 percent, according to the government,
as domestic and foreign competiton among buinesses intensifies.
   And employment of social workers is expected to increase by 33
percent in response to the needs of a growing and aging population.
   The computer fields will be the other biggest area of growth,
with the demand for programmers expected to rise 70 percent, or by
335,000, over the next 12 years and for systems analysts by 75
percent of 251,000.
   However, as with most of the new jobs, the prospects for winning
employment will be the best for programmers and systems analysts
with college educations.
   ``Applicants with less than a bachelor's degress and no
experience are likely to face strong competition,'' the Bureau of
Labor Statistics says.
   Familiarity with and knowledge about computers is going to be
more of a prerequisite for jobs in most other fields as well, says
Belous.
   ``Everyone is going to have to become more comfortable with
computers,'' he says, ``even though they are becoming more
`friendly.' And because the days of womb-to-tomb in one corporation
are over, the best advice I have is to always have a current resume
on a floppy disk. It's going to be a much more mobile job
environment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
