<DOCNO> AP880516-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Classof'88     05-16 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Class of '88,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Class of '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College graduates this year are finding
jobs more easily than the Class of '87, but often with companies
that wouldn't have recruited on campus in the past, according to
placement experts.
   Job candidates also are facing more tests for drug use and
honesty.
   ``We see a very bright outlook for this year's graduates,'' said
Alan E. Yost, assistant executive director of the Bethlehem-based
College Placement Council. ``We are in an expanding economy.''
   Pennsylvania State University students, for example, had nearly
26,000 on-campus interviews this year with business, industry and
government representatives, up from 23,325 last year, said Ralph
DeShong, associate director of career development and placement.
   Temple University had 10 career days on campus when employers
could meet and interview students, said Neil Gutman, director of
career development. In past years it had just six, he said.
   ``The most significant factor for us has been the considerable
increase in less well-known employers,'' Gutman said.
   Pizza companies, a dairy and delicatessen association, and
discount building supply companies are among the employers that
have come to look for management prospects, Gutman said.
   These are employers that wouldn't have been here a few years
ago, he said.
   The trend in part reflects changes in major corporations that
today employ service or consulting firms for work once performed
in-house, Yost said. ``They're bringing fewer people in through the
broad front door,'' he said.
   Last fall's stock market chill appears to have had little effect
on this spring's job prospects.
   ``It did not go unnoticed. We had some students who were
concerned about it,'' DeShong said. ``But we can't say that it has
had an impact. Nor are we hearing students say that offers have
stopped.''
   In its latest survey of salary offers, the College Placement
Council reported employers are offering more money to graduates in
most disciplines.
   Offers to electrical engineering graduates as of March averaged
$2,410 monthly, a 1.4 percent increase since last July; accounting,
$1,975, up 9 percent; and marketing and distribution, $1,742, up
2.7 percent.
   Social workers were being offered an average of $1,420, up 9
percent; communications workers $1,619, up 7.1 percent; and
management consultants, $2,228, up 3.3 percent.
   Offers were lower for graduates in only a few academic
disciplines, such as economics, $1,817 monthly, down 7.8 percent
from last July; chemistry, $2,059, down 3.4 percent; and aerospace
and aeronautical engineering, $2,322, down 0.9 percent.
   Offers as financial analysts averaged $1,940, down 12.4 percent;
banking $1,687, down 10.7 percent; and transportation and
distribution, $1,824, down 2.7 percent.
   But to start earning a paycheck, graduates often must undergo
more rigorous screening than their predecessors.
   In a November 1986 survey of 497 employers, the council found
28.2 percent required tests for drug or alcohol abuse. The council
estimates nearly 60 percent of all employers now use such tests,
Yost said.
   The main reasons cited for drug screening in 1986 were safety
and security, he said.
   ``Students have adjusted fairly well to that,'' said DeShong.
``It's obviously a concern to business, industry and government.''
   Employers are also checking other aspects of employees'
backgrounds more thoroughly.
   ``They seem to be backing off from the lie-detector test, but
there's a pickup in the tests for honesty,'' Yost said, adding that
credentials get a more thorough review today as well.
   ``The employers are getting a lot more cautious about bringing
people aboard,'' Yost said. ``Given the litigiousness of society,
and what a contract implies, they want to be awfully sure going
in.''
   Where students went to college has limited bearing on their
careers.
   A prestigious degree may help a student get the first job, but
not the second one, Yost said.
   ``You can't go into your job and base your performance on your
undergraduate grade point average,'' DeShong said. ``Sooner or
later it's going to come down to productivity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
