<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-SPE--Careers:Nursing     05-16 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Nursing,0785</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Nursing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A national shortage of nurses has brought out the imagination in
hospital and state recruiters, who are trying enticements from
higher salaries to recruitment dinners, from pay bonuses for new
nurses to highway billboard advertising.
   Some 300,000 nursing jobs are unfilled nationwide, with hospital
nursing vacancies nearing 20 percent, according to the American
Nurses Association.
   The federal Bureau of Labor Statistics says the biggest demand
for any single occupation between now and the end of the century
will be registered nurses, whose average pay now ranges between
$20,000 and $27,000 a year. The agency projects the employment of
nurses will grow 44 percent or by 612,000 between now and 2000, but
cautions that some career paths will be restricted to those with
bachelor's degrees in the field.
   While some hospitals have had to close wards because of the
shortage, others are coming up with at least temporary solutions.
   Thousands of foreign nurses have been recruited from overseas in
an effort to ease the shortage in the United States, although that
program has run into some problems with immigration officials
regarding temporary visas.
   In St. Joseph, Mo., the actor who plays the grandfatherly Dr.
   Auschlander in television's ``St. Elsewhere,'' joined a
recruiting drive by Heartland Hospital East. Norman Loyd stars in a
10-minute video to be distributed nationwide in Heartland's search
for nursing personnel. ``Having him in it will be an
attention-getter _ something we hope will catch the eye of nurses
who might be looking for a position,'' said Debi Yancer, associate
director of patient care services.
   
   The video will be shown at career days, placement fairs and at
recruitment dinners that have been spurred by the nationwide
shortage of nurses.
   A plan to train welfare recipients to be registered nurses has
gotten the go-ahead from the administration of Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
G. Thompson, despite criticism from some nurses.
   
   The proposal drew criticism from representatives of the nursing
profession and lawmakers who called it demeaning because it seemed
to ignore the education, skills and dedication needed to become a
nurse.
   The plan is to be implemented through the Wisconsin Employment
and Training Program, commonly called ``workfare.''
   ``We're about 1,000 nurses short in this state. We've got 80,000
to 90,000 people on welfare,'' said state Sen. Joseph Strohl.
``We've got to have 1 percent that have the necessary ingredients
to become a nurse.'' Under the plan, counties that administer job
counseling will encourage welfare recipients to enter nursing
programs at vocational schools. The state will pick up the cost of
tuition and day care, Strohl said.
   Another Wisconsin plan to ease the nursing shortage involved
forgiving some student loans of nurses who go to work in hospitals
or nursing homes.
   In Stafford, Conn., Johnson Memorial Hospital leased a billboard
overlooking a part of an interstate highway, advertising:
``Attention health-care professionals. If you worked at Johnson
Memorial Hospital, you would be home by now.''
   Some hospitals have begun a ``nurses-for-hire'' program, for
nurses who travel the country working a few months at one hospital
before moving on to another.
   In Cincinnati, the Good Samaritan Hospital School of Nursing is
offering a registered nurse refresher course for those who have
been out of practice for five or more years.
   ``Nurses who left the profession to have families are often
hesitant to come back becuse they fear not understanding new
procedures,'' says Carol Perlman, School of Nursing assistant
director of program development. ``The course will help nurses gain
confidence in dealing with new technology, offer an opportunity to
gradually get back into nursing, and get re-acquainted with their
skills and knowledge of patient care.''
   The American Association of Critical-Care Nurses (AACN), which
says 82 percent of the nation's hospitals report a shortage of
critical care nurses, has published a recruitment booklet, a poster
and two videos in an attempt to lure nurses into the career.
   ``Critical care nurses provide a vital role in the quality of
hospital health care, from patient treatment, rehabilitation and
recovery to family support and counseling,'' says Jeanette
Hartshorn, president of AACN and a registered nurse.
   ``It is estimated that by the year 2000,'' she says, ``hospitals
will only care for the most seriously-ill patients. The number of
critical care beds has continued to rise, but the demand for
specially-educated and technologically sophisticated nurses has not
been able to meet the demand; and the demand continues to
increase.''
   A critically ill patient is defined by AACN as one with real or
potential life-threatening health problems.
  
</TEXT>
