<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:WithNursing-Billboard     05-16 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: With Nursing-Billboard,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: With Nursing-Billboard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN MILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual recruiting effort proved that
a job seeker can make progress while stuck in a traffic jam.
   Johnson Memorial Hospital in Stafford earlier this year leased a
billboard overlooking a busy section of Interstate 91 in Hartford
for two months, advertising openings on its nursing staff.
   The hospital was feeling the impact of the nationwide nursing
shortage, and had been forced to turn patients away or refer them
to other hospitals, officials said.
   The billboard read: ``Attention health-care professionals. If
you worked at Johnson Memorial Hospital, you would be home by now.''
   Stephen E. Torla, vice president of human resources at Johnson
Memorial, said the billboard resulted in five vacancies being
filled and inquiries about employment were received from as far
away as Missouri and New Jersey.
   The billboard was ``good as far as employee moral, good as a
recruitment tool, and good exposure,'' Torla said, adding that
there are still some nursing vacancies at the hospital.
   Elizabeth A. Nelson, vice president of financing at Johnson
Memorial, said the hospital is considering renewing the billboard's
lease to attract other hard-to-find employees such as laboratory
technicians, respiratory therapists and operating room technicians.
   Judith Insinga, planning analyst for Gov. William A. O'Neill's
task force on the nursing shortage, said the Connecticut Hospital
Association reported last December that 11.8 percent of the jobs
for registered nurses in the state are now vacant. That's nearly
1,000 jobs, Insinga said.
   Lynn Steck, national creative director for Patrick Media Group,
which designed the billboard for Johnson Memorial, said other
hospitals are leasing billboard space to draw attention to the
health-care services they offer.
   Patrick Media Group, a billboard advertising company based in
Scranton, Pa., with offices in Hartford, projects that by the end
of 1988, hospitals are projected to rank 11th among the company's
top 25 advertisers listed according to dollar expenditure, she said.
   ``Outdoor ads are a 24-hour-a-day medium which allow the
audience to be moving. It's something you can't turn off,'' Steck
said.
   Meanwhile, Johnson Memorial and other Connecticut hospitals are
using other lures to get and keep nurses.
   Johnson Memorial offers to pay nurses double-time on weekends or
pay for 40 hours if they agree to work four nine-hour shifts.
   Also, the hospital will pay the tuition of an employee who has
worked for a year or more who wishes to train as a nurse's
assistant or a licensed practical nurse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Librarians     05-16 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Librarians,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Librarians</HEAD>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: A version of this story moved previously.)</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As computer data bases, cassettes and compact
discs join newspapers, magazines and books, the United States is
confronting a shortage of public librarians to help sort the flood
of information. ``A large number of librarians will be retiring in
the next five to 10 years and there aren't the numbers coming in to
replace them,'' said Margaret Myers, a personnel expert with the
American Library Association.
   
   She said library schools had 3,538 graduates in 1986, fewer than
half the 8,091 degrees in 1979.
   
   The shortfall comes as the public needs librarians trained to
help ``make sense of ... the new books, data bases, videocassettes,
specialist magazines and countless other media that debut daily,''
Ms. Myers said recently.
   Children's librarians, school media specialists, catalogers and
minority service personnel are in particularly short supply,
experts say. Some openings go unfilled. Others are staffed by less
qualified workers.
   ``In some geographic areas it's a crisis _ New York, Boston, the
East Coast,'' said ALA President Margaret Chisholm. ``There's such
a shortage that it is really affecting services.''
   
   Among the causes cited for the shortage are new corporate
opportunities, an overall increase in the number of public library
jobs and low pay for librarians.
   
   Average starting salaries for New York City librarians with
masters degrees in library science are $22,500, said library
spokeswoman Lauren Moye. A national survey of 1986 library school
masters graduates indicated starting salaries averaged $20,874.
   School librarians averaged $28,390 last year, reference workers
in public and academic libraries were paid an average $23,552 in
1986, and staff in special libraries, including corporations,
averaged $28,943 in 1985, according to studies.
   
   ``Librarians in the West and Southwest tend to make higher
salaries,'' said Ms. Myers. ``Lowest salaries are in the
Southeast.''
   Once one of the few professions open to women, public and school
library careers are now just one of many options.
   
   ``Libraries and nursing cannot compete with law and banking,''
said Ed Szynaka, library director in suburban Pasadena. ``You could
start with a five- figure salary in law that could be as high as
you would ever get in a library career.''
   
   Those who stick with library training are finding better pay
working in corporate libraries and data bases, rather than public
libraries. The corporate openings listed at ALA meetings outstrip
the number of interviewees, said Myers.
   
   A California Library Association report predicts 1988 will bring
364 public, academic and specialized librarian openings, 256 of
them in public libraries. Next year, 446 openings are expected
statewide.
   While the survey projected 60 percent of the openings will be in
public libraries, only 28 percent of the 162 library school
students responding to the survey want public library work.
Thirty-five percent prefer academic libraries and 26 percent
special libraries.
   ``Salaries are better in the private sector than in the public
sector,'' said Mary Sue Farrell, executive director of the state
library association. ``Salaries are better at GTE or IBM than
working for the City of San Francisco.''
   
   Along with the need for children's librarians, the survey also
pinpointed ``an underrepresentation of minorities in the profession
as compared with the population of California, especially among
Hispanics and blacks.''
   With shortages of both children's and school librarians, experts
are worried that young people may not gain the skills needed to
sort information gained from reading books or magazines, typing
queries on a computer terminal, using a microfiche reader, or
viewing from a compact disc. ``If you have a school of 3,000 kids
and you don't have a librarian there, that's a problem,'' said
Bonnie O'Brian, the Los Angeles school library
   supervisor. ``Almost every job people are going into has to do
with information. The only place they can learn that is in the
school library media center.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
