<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Secretaries     05-16 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Secretaries,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Secretaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY700</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Technology is changing the image of the office secretary.
   A recent survey of 500 American corporations found that 61
percent of the employers hire secretaries with word processing
skills and 57 percent expect secretaries to use personal computers
within two years.
   The survey was conducted by Indianapolis-based ITT Educational
Services Inc., an ITT Corp. subsidiary and a private trainer of
professional secretaries.
   ``Filing and dictation are no longer considered primary
secretarial skill requirements. A secretary in today's workplace
needs to be proficient in world processing, reprographics,
communication distribution and electronic mail,'' said Rene
Champagne, president of ITT Educational Services.
   ``Those secretaries who possess the skills needed to keep up
with new technologies are becoming invaluable to their employer.''
   ``Employers are perceiving secretaries in a new light,'' says
Eleanor P. Vreeland, president of the Katharine Gibbs School, which
conducted a survey of Fortune 500 and other companies. ``The
presence of automation in every office enables secretaries to
devote more time to administrative responsibilities, thus offering
companies a more productive employee.''
   Katharine Gibbs School Inc. is a network of 11 private business
secretarial schools in the Northeast.
   In the Gibbs survey, 51 percent of the respondents acknowledged
a significant increase in the secretary's level of administrative
responsibility; 48 percent saw the need for computer literacy as
another major change.
   Ninety-three percent of the companies surveyed by the
secretarial school agreed that the role of the secretary is
different than it was five years ago. Seventy-five percent said
secretaries must have knowledge of word processing.
   The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that 300,000
secretarial positions will become available through the 1980s and
80,000 of these will go unfilled because of a lack of unqualified
secretaries.
   ``Good secretaries are hard to find for a number of reasons,''
Miss Vreeland said. ``The baby bust has resulted in fewer people in
the work force, there are more career options open to women, and
the rapid growth of small- to mid-sized businesses has caused
fierce competition for secretaries between companies, especially in
the Northeast.''
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics projects a 9.6 percent increase
in secretarial jobs from 1984 to 1995, despite the spread of office
automation.
   Jobs for secretaries, stenographers and typists increased by an
average of 3.3 percent a year between 1982 and 1987, below the rate
for total employment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
