<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Teachers     05-16 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Teachers,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Teachers</HEAD>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: A version of this story moved previously.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public school teachers now earn $28,031 on
average and in 10 states the typical teacher earns more than
$30,000 a year, the National Education Association reports.
   The average classroom teacher, with 15 years of experience, got
a 5.6 percent pay raise last year that boosted her or his salary by
$1,477 from the 1986-87 level of $26,534.
   The union did not estimate how much salaries will rise this
fall, but if teachers get another 5.6 percent increase, they will
be earning $29,600 on average for the 1988-89 school year.
   Teacher salaries have risen sharply in the 1980s amid widespread
concern about lagging standards in the classroom and waning
interest among college students in entering the profession.
Recently, however, with starting salaries topping $20,000 in some
places, interest in teaching has picked up.
   Secretary of Education William J. Bennett, in a critique on the
impact of school reforms, said teacher salaries have risen 20
percent after adjusting for inflation since 1980-81.
   But the NEA said that over the past decade, including the steep
inflation years of the late 1970s, teacher salaries are up only 7.3
percent after inflation.
   The union said there were 2,275,209 classroom teachers in the
public schools this year, 25,251 more than in 1986-87.
   The entire instructional staff, including principals,
supervisors and specialists, numbered 2,589,148. That was up by
30,190, or 1.2 percent. The average salary for all instructors was
$29,203, up 5.3 percent from $27,722 last year.
   Most teachers work on nine- or 10-month contracts.
   Eighteen states and the District of Columbia pay teachers more
than the national average; 32 states pay less.
   NEA researchers said the $28,031 figure is an estimate based on
salary data compiled from all 50 states. It was up by $1,477, or
5.6 percent, from the union's revised average salary figure of
$26,534 for the 1986-87 year.
   Although only an estimate, the NEA salary figure is widely
cited, including by the U.S. Department of Education, as the most
accurate indicator of how much the nation's nearly 2.3 million
classroom teachers in the public schools are earning. It includes
American Federation of Teachers contracts.
</TEXT>
