<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Unemployment     05-16 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Unemployment,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Unemployment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment fell in April to 5.4 percent, the
lowest it has been since 1974, with export-led hiring on factory
assembly lines in the industrial heartland leading the latest spurt
of new jobs, the government said.
   The number of Americans at work rose by 606,000 in April while
those listed as unemployed fell by 191,000 to 6.6 million, dropping
joblessness 0.2 percentage points from March's rate of 5.6 percent,
the Labor Department said.
   The rate was the lowest since June 1974 when it also stood at
5.4 percent but at time when the nation was well into a steep
recesssion, in contrast to the current economic expansion.
   The Labor Department said in its report on the job market that
the average hourly wage nationwide in April rose to $9.22, a nickel
over March, for an average annual increase of 5.6 percent. That is
twice the 2.8 percent average increase in hourly wages for all of
1987.
   Growth in new factory jobs, which had been sluggish the previous
three months after rising dramatically in 1987, accounted for more
than one-fourth of the 175,000 increase in employers' payrolls in
April.
   Leading the surge were export-related industries such as
machinery and fabricated metal products. But production jobs in the
U.S. auto industry also climbed by 10,000, reversing wide-scale
layoffs in January and February.
   The jobless rate for adult men fell 0.3 percent points to 4.6
percent in April. For women, it remained unchanged at 4.8 percent.
   Hospital and business services and retail outlets such as stores
and restaurants which had been the hottest areas of job growth the
past year showed a total payroll gain of just 71,000 in April.
   The Labor Department said nearly all of the improvement in the
unemployment figures was among people who had been laid off from
their last jobs, as opposed to those who had quit or were seeking
employment for the first time.
   ``The number of unemployed job losers declined to slightly less
than 3 million and their proportion of the total jobless was at its
lowest point this decade, 44 percent,'' said Janet L. Norwood, the
commissioner of labor statistics.
   Growth in voluntary part-time jobs accounted for two-thirds of
the increase in the number of working Americans in April.
   ``We often fall into the trap of reacting negatively to any job
expansion that is not full time,'' Ms. Norwood told the
congressional Joint Economic Committee. ``But some one out of every
eight workers _ 15 million in all _ do not want full-time jobs.''
   The number of people working part-time because they could not
find full-time work actually fell by 150,000 in April to 5.2
million, still a ``level of concern,'' Ms. Norwood said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:LiberalArts     05-16 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Liberal Arts,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Liberal Arts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A liberal arts college degree often has meant prestige and
pride, but little pay in the real world. But there are some
indications that business is acknowledging that there is life after
liberal arts training.
   ``A liberally educated person is still the type of individual
needed at the highest level of corporate life,'' says Robert
Callander, president of Chemical Bank and a Dartmouth College
graduate.
   ``The technical skills are built upon this base. It is this
peculiar mix of sciences, mathematics, history and English that
produces a mind capable, in later life, of bringing mature judgment
to complex _ and sometimes great _ issues,'' he says.
   Many employers look for graduates with the writing and
analytical skills and broad-based education that liberal arts
provide, says Alan P. Goodman, career services director at the
Catholic University of America, in Washington, D.C.
   He says job-seekers should major in a liberal arts field and
take electives such as economics, management or computer sciences,
combine their studies with experience in student government and
work as a college student in a business environment.
   With this concept in mind, many colleges are seeking ways of
providing a broad-based education while preparing students for a
career.
   Many offer internships and cooperative education programs that
provide students with work experience outside the classroom.
   Concordia College, in Moorhead, Minn., offers a combination of a
liberal arts curriculum and vocational preparation _ learning and
earning. Students at Concordia are assigned to a faculty adviser
for involvement in cooperative education programs, internships, or
part-time work related to their major course of study.
   Buena Vista College, in Storm Lake, Iowa, has a program called
``Second Curriculum,'' in which students meet with a career adviser
to decide which extracurricular activities stress job-related and
personal development skills. For example, a student who plans to be
a lawyer found that involvement in the Student Activities Board
improved assertiveness and decision-making skills.
   Marymount Manhattan College in New York City offers a seminar
called Women in Management, which is offered for college credit to
honors students. It features professional women, from bankers to
ballet dancers, as guest lecturers speaking about their work.
   ``We didn't want to be only a career-oriented school,'' says Lou
Stanek, program director. ``We are convinced that the liberal arts
is the best training for leaders.''
   ``Too many students see college simply as a ticket to getting a
job when they graduate,'' says Al Splete, president of the Council
of Independent Colleges, a service organization for small liberal
arts colleges.
   ``Liberal arts graduates are problem-solvers and will be
successful because they have perception and can change as needed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:SummerJobs     05-16 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Summer Jobs,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Summer Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Summertime,'' the song says, ``and the livin' is easy.''
   But making a living may be something else, at least for students
who often work long hours for minimum wages during their summer
break.
   Some schools are trying to make it a little easier, by helping
students find work that pays more than undergraduates usually earn.
   At the University of Rochester, Rochester, N.Y., for example, a
``SummerReach'' jobs program offers employers subsidies from donors
for hiring students.
   The university pays 36 percent of the student earnings, with
money raised from donors who see their contribution creating jobs
at salaries that help offset high educational costs.
   ``People and foundations like to contribute to education, but
especially to students who want to help themselves,'' says James
Scannell, University of Rochester vice president for enrollments,
placement and alumni affairs. ``It's been relatively easy to raise
money for this program.''
   The program has placed nearly 100 students to date in job areas
such as community planning, engineering sales, public relations,
marketing and banking.
   Average summer earnings are estimated at $2,700.
   Similar programs are offered at Duke University and Cornell
University, among others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
