<DOCNO> AP880516-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Family     05-16 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Family,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY704</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of all American families have two wage earners,
according to Labor Department figures, and 67 percent have children
under the age of 14.
   In many cases, this has presented a difficult problem in
balancing career and family.
   Just ask Danielle Kennedy.
   ``I learned many valuable lessons about delegating
responsibilty, communication and negotiation right from my own
living room,'' she says.
   Kennedy, 43, began her first full-time career, in real estate
sales, when she was pregnant with her fifth child. She is now a
motivational lecturer, author of two books on selling and the
mother of eight.
   Many women, she says, look for a full or part-time career for
``the added sense of personal accomplishment that working can
provide,'' along with a flexibility in hours that allows for
involvement in family affairs and child raising. ``Many quickly
discover, however, that it takes quite a balancing act to be
successful at both,'' she says.
   For those who seek to balance these two worlds, she advises:
   _ Working parents need to give equal priority to important
family and business commitments. Establish a solid dividing line
between the time dedicated to work and home.
   _ Form well-defined goals and make a commitment to achieving
them. Include the family in the process of goal-setting. ``The most
important motivating factors in my work aren't `me' goals, they are
`we' goals,'' she says.
   She once promised ski lessons to her children if she reached a
certain sales quota. ``We put up a ski poster as a reminder of what
we were all working toward, and everyone pitched in with laundry,
cooking, and cleaning up after themselves.
   ``When a family achieves `we' goals, the message kids get is
that the big, bad world isn't so bad at all,'' she says. ``It's a
big, exciting, hopeful world.''
   Sales appears to be a career area that suits many working
parents, as it often offers flexible hours.
   Some 90 percent of direct sales consultants are women and more
than 80 percent work at it part time, according to the Direct
Selling Association, Washington, D.C. Turnover can be frequent, but
many have made direct sales a long-term career.
   Mitch Allphin, for example, is a Princess House home decorator
consultant, who earns $250 to $400 for 12-to-18-hour weeks.
   ``I never considered myself a good salesperson,'' she says,
``but I love showing off the crystal and demonstrating how to use
it for decorating.''
   She schedules her demonstrations at night, three or four
evenings a week, when her husband cares for the three children.
``He calls it his `quality' time with them,'' she says.
   She takes her business with her when she travels. ``There are no
assigned territories, so it's easy to keep the business going as we
vacation,'' she says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Choices     05-16 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Choices,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Choices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Salary was not the most influential factor in making a career
choice among business administration students, according to a
Carnegie Mellon University survey.
   The Pittsburgh school study found career path and advancement
were more important than salary, with 55 percent of last year's
graduating MBA class not accepting the highest paying job offered.
   One student eventually chose a job that paid $20,000 a year less
than one he was offered. Other salary differentials were about
$5,000.
   After career path and advancement, the work itself and use of
skills was considered most important, followed by geography, the
``comfort factor,'' and people. Salary ranked ninth.
   The study was conducted by Ed Mosier, director of Carnegie
Mellon's Career Opportunities Center, among some 100 business
school graduates who received two or more job offers.
   Mosier said that being ``wined and dined'' by prospective
employers did not greatly influence final decisions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
