<DOCNO> AP880516-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Planning     05-16 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Planning,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Planning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many young people make the mistake of applying for jobs before
they know what they really want to do, according to a career
planning consultant at a California college.
   Salary alone should not determine the choice of a career, says
Lane von Herzen, director of career planning at Scripps College in
Claremont, Calif.
   ``Be wary of choosing a career, or a particular entry-level job
offer, solely because of its comparative monetary reward,'' Von
Herzen cautions. ``The extra money won't be rewarding in the long
run if that's not the direction in which you really want to go.
   ``A career that offers less money, at least in the beginning,
may turn out to be more enriching for you in the fundamental sense
of career satisfaction.''
   Another pressure to be resisted, he adds, is the suggestion from
parents or peers that a career should be chosen because it's
prestigious.
   ``Remember that it's you _ not your parents or peers _ who is
going to be devoting your life to this pursuit,'' he notes.
``You'll be more fulfilled, and probably more successful, if you
make a choice based on your own interests, goals and values.''
   Von Herzen recommends that students engage in career-research
interviewing long before they enter the job market.
   By talking to people in their intended field, he advises, career
seekers can find out what the greatest satisfactions and drawbacks
are in that particular career, the present and anticipated
opportunities, and what kind of person it takes to be successful.
   ``Try to get a gut feeling of what it's like to earn your living
in this way,'' he adds. ``If at all possible, get yourself an
internship so you can experience that feeling first hand.''
   In preparing resumes, he says, job-seekers should be specific,
and ``instead of saying you've developed coordination skills, tell
what you've coordinated, or instead of saying you've mastered
time-management skills, say you earned 20 percent of your college
tuition while working two summer jobs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
