<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Pain     05-16 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Careers: Pain,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Pain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Women executives climbing the corporate ladder of American
business are finding that success in their careers literally can be
a pain in the neck _ and upper back _ according to a physical
therapist.
   In shouldering new responsibilities, the executives often work
under sedentary stress, sitting for hours in a fixed position
behind a desk writing reports, dictating letters and conducting
meetings, or interviewing job applicants.
   ``Caught up in their work, most women executives simply ignore
upper back pain and steam full speed ahead,'' says Margaret Seiler,
supervising physical therapist at the back pain clinic for
outpatients at Crozer-Chester Medical Center in Chester, Pa.
   ``But if you are working under stress for prolonged periods of
time, you should stop once in a while for a mental and physical
break,'' advises Ms. Seiler, who has developed a series of
exercises intended to take a person's mind off work problems,
increase upper body circulation and relieve the muscle strain that
causes upper back pain.
   The desk exercises can be done _ by men or women _ every two
hours, or as needed.
   For after-office therapy at home, Ms. Seiler advocates a sound
night's slumber to erase vestiges of work-related tension.
   ``A bed and its mattress directly affect the quality of sleep,''
explains the therapist. ``Some like a firm mattress, others a soft
one. But regardless of personal preference, a mattress should
provide support for the heavy parts of the body _ the hips and
shoulders _ and disperse bodyweight uniformly.
   ``And, of course, it should be comfortable.''
   The stress-breaker exercises developed by Ms. Seiler are aimed
at soothing upper back pain by relaxing tired, tense musles and
creating a warm, suffused body glow due to increased circulation,
she says.
   Although designed to be done while at the desk, ``they can also
be done at home while sitting on the edge of your bed _ and are a
good waker-upper to get you on your way to work feeling relaxed and
refreshed.''
   The exercises, each repeated five times and taking no more than
one minute apiece, are:
   _ Neck circles _ Point chin to chest, chin to each shoulder, ear
to each shoulder.
   _ Shoulder rolls _ Move your shoulders up, forward, back and
down. Relax and repeat.
   _ Shoulder lifts _ Raise your shoulders up, tighten and relax;
drop your shoulders, tighten and relax.
   _ Self hug _ Stretch arms across your chest, hug yourself, hold
for five seconds and relax; bend your elbows back, tighten for five
seconds and relax.
   _ Trunk stretch _ Sit tall, look straight ahead, press shoulders
back for count of five, relax for count of five.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
