<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Youth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent University of Michigan study indicates that over the
past decade young Americans _ faced with a crowded job market _ are
placing increased emphasis on job status, income and advancement.
   At the same time, they have become more conservative, quieter in
behavior and dress, and less extreme in political views and actions.
   According to a report on the continuing study by the
university's Institute for Social Research, ``young people today,
in contrast to those a decade or so earlier, are not faced with
crises such as the Vietnam war and the draft.
   ``Thus, they are freer to concentrate on the more immediate
issues in their personal lives _ their own hopes and plans.''
   For young people in general, the researchers noted, the goal of
finding steady work and succeeding in it has grown in importance
over the past decade.
</TEXT>
