<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>CAREERS: Books</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A random sampling of career-related new books cover the job from
start to potential finish:
   ``The Complete Job Search Book'' (Wiley), by Richard H. Beatty,
is written for those entering the job market and deals with
resumes, cover letters, employment sources.
   On the other side of the career coin is ``Surviving Corporate
Downsizing'' (Wiley). Subtitled ``How to Keep Your Job,'' this
150-pager offers advice from a California placement attorney on how
employees can ``keep their jobs by positioning themselves as
indispensable to the company team.'' Self-marketing is the key to
success and survival, says author Jeffrey G. Allen.
   ``Make Them Choose You'' (by James D. Kohlman; Prentice Hall)
contends to focus on the ``psychology of the interview _ the
criterion employers rely on most heavily when hiring new
employees.''
   And, once you have the job, there's ``Working It Out,'' by
Stephen Stasser (Prentice Hall), with self-quizzes that aim at
finding out how you really feel about your work.
</TEXT>
