<HEAD>CAREERS: Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Numerous cutbacks in executive jobs across the nation have
resulted in a heavy increase in unsolicited resumes and phone calls
to management recruiters over the past six months, reports a New
York executive search firm.
   `Every recruiter I know has experienced a sharp jump in the
number of calls and letters coming in _ even from people who still
have their jobs,'' says Phyllis Tama, vice president of Thorndike
Deland Associates.
   The cutbacks in recent months apparently have fostered
widespread anxiety among management ranks, according to the search
consultant, who added: ``Everybody seems to be doing contingency
planning.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania's Susquehanna University has added a
seven-week-long ``career planning'' class as a required sequence to
its core curriculum, which also includes classes on library
research, communication skills and interpersonal relationships.
Students must successfully complete the requirements in order to
graduate, according to the campus administration.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Students majoring in wood science and technology are finding
good job opportunities and starting salaries ranging from $18,000
to $25,000, according to Professor R. Bruce Hoadley of the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
   Hoadley says jobs for women are especially plentiful as gender
bias becomes less of a concern in the diverse wood products
industry, which requires a broad range of job skills and knowledge.
   Wood technologists, he explained, are concerned with converting
trees into wood and wood into products.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A five-year course of study has been launched at the University
of Rhode Island to give students an opportunity to become leaders
in international business.
   The pilot program merges the university's strong German language
curriculum with its engineering school, according to a spokesman.
   The standard four-year engineering program is combined with
specially designed German courses. In the first three years,
students take a separate German program, honing technical language
skills.
   This is followed by a one-year internship in a German-speaking
country, with the fifth year devoted to advanced German courses as
well as interdisciplinary engineering courses taught all in German.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Graduate Management Admission Council, an association of 81
graduate business schools, will offer its third annual series of
programs for blacks and Hispanics interested in an MBA degree.
   The free program, called Destination MBA, focuses on
opportunities for minorities in management careers and on how to
prepare for and get into graduate business school. It will be held
this year in Cincinnati (Sept. 24), New York (Oct. 1), Arlington,
Va. (Oct. 8), Dearborn, Mich. (Oct. 22), Chicago (Nov. 5), Los
Angeles (Nov. 19), and St. Louis (Dec. 3), and next year in San
Francisco (Feb. 4), Atlanta (Feb. 11), and Miami (Feb. 25).
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Non Commissioned Officers Association (NCOA) sponsors 22
one-day Job Fairs each year, to help ex-service people enter the
civilian work force.
   ``The Job Fairs are open to enlisted personnel and officers free
of charge, regardless of whether they are members of the NCOA,''
says Herbert M. Flanagan, director of NCOA's veterans employment
assistance.
   In addition, the NCOA conducts four-hour Job Seeker workshops at
military installations not covered by Job Fairs.
</TEXT>
