<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in April and
are up at a sedate annual rate of 2.9 percent in the first four
months of the year, the government says.
   The April increase in the Producer Price Index was down from a
0.6 percent March advance, leading many analysts to conclude after
Friday's report by the Labor Department that worries over inflation
had been overstated by the March increase. They said if the
volatile energy and food sectors were removed, the April price
advance was a minuscule 0.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1.9 percent rise in business sales in
March was the largest advance in more than a year, but the 0.3
percent rise in business inventories was the smallest since last
August, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Friday total business sales rose to
a seasonally adjusted $479.5 billion in March. It was the largest
advance in 13 months and followed an equally strong 1.1 percent
rise in February.
   Business inventories rose to $720 billion, the smallest rise
since last August. Inventories had grown by 0.4 percent in February.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of the economy seems almost
too good to be true less than seven months after the stock market
plunge, business leaders say.
   The Business Council, composed of 61 executives from the largest
U.S. corporations, predicted modest growth, low unemployment and
moderate inflation this year in a report issued Friday at its
meeting at the Homestead resort.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rush to beat widespread buyer-incentive
deadlines boosted sales of domestic-made car and light trucks 35.2
percent in early May compared with a year ago, industry analysts
say.
   Automakers sold 204,270 domestic-made cars and light trucks in
the eight-selling days from May 1-10, up from 151,131 in the
identical period a year ago, the companies reported Friday.
   General Motors Corp. sold 35.1 percent more cars and light
trucks, while Ford Motor Co. rose 31.5 percent and Chrysler Corp.
sales jumped 48.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Far-reaching trade legislation on its way to
President Reagan would hold nearly 10,000 imported auto franchises
in the United States hostage to the nation's trade disputes, a car
dealer group says.
   The American International Automobile Dealers Association said
Friday that it felt it was ``the first target for retaliation.''
   Robert McElwaine, president of the trade association, said the
imported automobile industry is large enough at $40 billion a year
to hurt the exporting country severely should the U.S. restrict
imports in a trade dispute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interstate Commerce Commission tentatively
has approved the proposed merger of the Union Pacific Corp. and the
regional Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad, sources said.
   The soyurces said Friday that the commission has scheduled an
official announcement of its decision for Monday.
   Agency and congressional sources, speaking on condition they not
be identified, said the commission had voted 4-0 to permit Union
Pacific to acquire the MKT system.
</TEXT>
