<HEAD>Iceland Devalues Its Currency By 10 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New lede to CLARIFY that traders were selling the kronur.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iceland devalued its currency, the
kronur, by 10 percent after panic selling of the kronur forced the
central bank to halt all currency trading.
   The government, which announced the devaluation on Sunday, said
the central bank had requested the move. It said the bank also
could devalue the kronur by a further 3 percent if that was deemed
necessary in the near future.
   The central bank halted all currency trading Friday after 25
percent of its foreign currency reserves dried up in frantic buying
of foreign currencies by individuals and companies anticipating a
20 percent devaluation of the kronur.
   The three-party coalition government announced the devaluation
after lengthy discussions over the weekend.
</TEXT>
