<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     05-16 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0441</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose slightly today in extremely light
trading, which brokers called a reflection of investor reluctance
to commit much money to a post-crash market that remains vulnerable
to sudden selloffs.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 2.16 points
to 1,992.71 by 11 a.m. EDT on Wall Street. Broader market indices
rose marginally.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by less than 2-to-1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 728 up, 453 down and 486 unchanged.
Volume on the Big Board totaled 79 million shares after the first
90 minutes.
   ``It is extremely quiet,'' said Philip C. Puccio, senior vice
president and manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read &
Co. in New York. ``Institutional buyers are virtually at a
standstill.''
   Nearly half the early trading volume came from dividend-capture
strategies in one stock, GTE, with more than 37.8 million shares
changing hands at 35], down ]. Aside from that, many investors just
stayed away, partly out of concern over the impact of the March
trade deficit statistics to be released Tuesday.
   Those figures, which have come to symbolize America's economic
weakness, have jolted the market in the past when they exceeded
expectations. Most economists believe the March number will fall
between $12 billion and $13 billion, down from $13.8 billion in
February.
   ``If the number comes in under double digits, I think this
market goes a lot higher,'' Puccio said. ``But investors don't want
to buy something today and look like idiots tomorrow. That's the
reason for the dullness.''
   William King, head trader at Nikko Securities International in
New York, attributed some early strength in the market to a
carryover from a mild rally on Friday, based on expectations that
rising interest rates have stabilized for awhile. But he said
anxiety about the trade numbers stalled the rise today.
   ``When you've had worse trade numbers the market has punished
you severely,'' King said. ``So if you err, you err on the side of
caution.''
   Besides GTE, the most-active NYSE issues included Staley
Continental, down { to 36] on volume exceeding 1.13 million shares.
The company accepted a sweetened takeover offer from Tate & Lyle of
$36.50 a share after finding no other serious bidders.
   Among active blue-chips, General Electric rose { to 39~, Boeing
fell 2 to 49{, American Express rose \ to 23| and Exxon fell \ to
44}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues rose 0.23 to
145.53. On the American Stock Exchange, the market-value index rose
0.08 to 298.02.
</TEXT>
