<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surging Soybean Futures Lead Grains Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the surging soybean
market leading the way.
   Soybean contracts opened at least 19 cents a bushel higher, the
strongest opening this year, as dry weather fears continued to
provide broad support, analysts said.
   ``It's a huge opening, and it's all based on the weather,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for the investment firm Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Less rain fell in the Midwest during the weekend than traders
had expected and the latest forecasts called for dry conditions to
prevail until at least mid-week.
   Soybean futures prices, now at four-year highs, are extremely
sensitive to weather factors because U.S. soybean stockpiles are
dwindling and a good crop is needed to meet the anticipated demand.
   ``If we had had good rains over the weekend, we'd be opening 20
or 25 cents lower,'' Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was 6 cents to 8{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.12 a bushel; corn was 4{ cents
to 7 cents higher with May at $2.04 a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to
5 cents higher with May at $1.60{ a bushel; soybeans were 19{ cents
to 23 cents higher with May at $7.39 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. The cattle
markets were awaiting this afternoon's release of the Agriculture
Department's monthly seven-state cattle-on-feed report.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .15 cent higher with June at
73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .55 cent lower
with May at 80.77 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .43 cent
higher with June at 53.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.15 cent to .40 cent higher with May at 54.80 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Friday while pork futures were
mostly lower.
</TEXT>
