<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-Trade     05-16 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Trade,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany's Trade Surplus Shrinks 21 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's trade surplus fell
21 percent to 8.2 billion marks in February from 10.4 billion marks
in the corresponding period a year earlier, the Federal Statistics
Office said Monday.
   The surplus was also down from 8.5 billion marks in January.
   The country's current account surplus, which includes trade in
merchandise, services, investment income and certain transfers,
stood at 5.2 billion marks, compared to 4.7 billion marks in
January, the statistics office said.
   The February trade report had been delayed for six weeks because
of the implementation of a new reporting system based on European
Community guidelines. The January report was four weeks later for
the same reason.
   The report said West German exports slumped 1.6 percent compared
to a year earlier, while imports rose 5 percent from the
year-earlier level.
</TEXT>
