<1ST_LINE>u f PM-HuttonProbe 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hutton Pays More Than $1 Million Fine For Money-Laundering Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf with 2 grafs of Shearson comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.F. Hutton & Co. paid more than $1
million in fines today for its guilty plea to three federal money
laundering charges involving its Providence office.
   Hutton attorney E. Lawrence Barcella Jr. signed the guilty plea
and turned a check for the fine over to U.S. Attorney Lincoln C.
Almond.
   The brokerage company was fined $10,000 for one count of
conspiracy and $500,000 on each of two counts of violating federal
cash transaction reporting laws.
   The plea follows the May 6 filing of criminal charges against
Hutton in U.S. District Court, accusing the company of failing to
report at least $532,000 in currency transactions at the Providence
office. Federal law requires that cash transactions of greater than
$10,000 must be reported to the IRS.
   The people for whom the transactions were allegedly made were
not named. Almond has said up to $1.2 million was involved, some of
it from organized crime figures and some from businesmen.
   In addition to the three felony counts against the firm, two
former brokers at Hutton's Providence office were also named in the
documents, known as a criminal information, filed in court.
   One of the brokers died shortly after the investigation began,
Almond said. Charges against the other broker, Brian J. Lareau, 46,
of Jamestown, R.I., were to have been filed last week.
   Hutton was acquired last year by Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc.,
and the company is now known as Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill said today that after the
merger with Shearson, all of Hutton's branches adopted the Shearson
policy of prohibiting cash deposits in any amount. This should help
deter any similar schemes in the future, he said.
   ``None of the people who were involved in any of the
transactions are with the company anymore,'' O'Neill said. ``We
don't see it as having any impact on the company.''
   Almond said he did not know of wrongdoing at other Hutton
offices and said there was no evidence anyone other than the two
brokers named May 6 had participated in the scheme.
   Under Securities and Exchange Commission rules, a felony
conviction of the company could result in the suspension of
investment services. Shearson said last month it expected to
receive waivers from the SEC that would allow it to continue
business.
   Last October, the SEC found Hutton had violated provisions of
the SEC law and rules relating to financial record-keeping and
reporting of currency transactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
