<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ForbesList     05-16 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forbes List,0456</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Forbes Says Heads of Communications Firms Got Biggest Raises in
1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief executive officers of communications and
media companies got the biggest pay raises in all major industries
in 1987, according to a national survey of executive pay published
by Forbes magazine.
   The median total compensation of the communications executives
rose to $1.19 million last year from $848,000 in 1986, a 40 percent
increase, Forbes said in its May 30 issue. Median total
compensation means half the executives made more than that amount,
and half made less.
   The survey covered the 800 chief executive officers who run the
nation's biggest publicly owned companies.
   Donald L. Pels, chief executive officer of Lin Broadcasting, was
the highest-paid CEO in the media industry last year with $17.40
million. John C. Malone, the head of Tele-Communications, was the
lowest-paid at $390,000.
   Thomas S. Murphy of Capital Cities@ABC received total
compensation of $801,000. Laurence C. Tisch, the chief executive
and president of CBS, got the median pay of $1.19 million.
   The communications and media industry placed second after
financial services, which had the highest-paid chief executives in
1987 for the third consecutive year, Forbes said.
   Although they earned the highest pay, CEOs in the financial
services industry also saw that compensation drop by a median 21
percent from 1986 levels, reflecting deteriorating conditions in
the securities industry.
   The median pay of financial services chiefs fell to $1.26
million last year from $1.60 million in 1986, the survey said.
   Alan C. Greenberg of Bear Stearns Cos. was the highest-paid CEO
in financial services last year with $5.71 million, while Jess T.
Hay of Lomas & Nettleton was the lowest at $506,000.
   After financial services and communications, the 10 highest-paid
industries in 1987 and their median pay for CEOs, according to
Forbes, were:
   _Aerospace and defense, $1.17 million.
   _Health, $1.163 million.
   _Beverages and tobacco, $1.162 million.
   _Food processing, $1.12 million.
   _Retailing, $1.05 million.
   _Apparel, shoes and textiles, $1.03 million.
   _Leisure and recreation, $1.02 million.
   _Conglomerates, $1.01 million.
   The 10 best-paid CEOs and their compensation, were:
   _Charles Lazarus, Toys R Us, $60.03 million.
   _Jim P. Manzi, Lotus Development, $26.34 million.
   _Lee A. Iacocca, Chrysler, $17.66 million.
   _Donald A. Pels, Lin Broadcasting, $17.40 million.
   _Paul B. Fireman, Reebok International, $15.43 million.
   _Richard W. Furlaud, Squibb, $14.04 million.
   _John F. Welch Jr., General Electric, $12.63 million.
   _William S. Edgerly, State Street Boston Corp., $10.11 million.
   _W. Michael Blumenthal, Unisys, $9.98 million.
   _James W. Conte, Community Psychiatric Centers, $8.61 million.
</TEXT>
