<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OECD-Projections     05-16 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OECD-Projections,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OECD Revises 1988, 1989 Growth Projections Upward</HEAD>
<HEAD>With OECD Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6 p.m. EDT; time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in the industrialized democracies
will be much quicker in both 1988 and 1989 than was thought at the
end of last year following the October markets crash, according to
OECD projections released Monday.
   The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
confirmed that it has revised upward its projection for real, or
inflation-adjusted, gross national product growth to 3 percent for
1988 from its December estimate of 2.25 percent.
   The growth rate for 1989 is now expected to be around 2.5
percent, compared with a previous estimate of 1.75 percent.
   The OECD, which is made up of the world's 24 most industrialized
nations, is now projecting that real growth in the United States
will reach 2.75 percent in 1988, slowing slightly to 2.5 percent in
1989. These figures were revised upward from the December estimates
of 2.5 and 1.75 percent, respectively.
   Growth rates in other major OECD member countries have also been
adjusted. West Germany is expected to experience a 2.25 percent
expansion in 1988, slowing to 1.75 percent in 1989, compared with
earlier estimates of 1.5 percent and 1.75 percent, respectively.
   Japan will have one of the strongest growth rates among the
major industrialized countries with a projected 4.25 percent this
year and 3.75 percent in 1989, the OECD said. This compares with
December forecasts of 3.5 percent and 3 percent, respectively.
   The latest OECD figures for inflation are little-changed from
those of the December 1987 outlook, with rates of 3.5 percent
expected for the 24 OECD member countries in 1988 and 3.75 percent
projected for 1989.
   On unemployment, the OECD sees the average rate for the
industrialized countries as a group at 7.5 percent in both 1988 and
1989, compared with previous estimates of 8 percent for 1988 and
8.25 percent for 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
