<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     05-16 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0395</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks drifted today in extremely light trading,
which brokers attributed to inflation anxiety and a persistent
reluctance to risk cash in the volatile post-crash market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which seesawed in
a narrow range through much of the session, was up 7.79 points to
1,998.34 by 3 p.m. EDT. Broader market indices were mixed.
   Traders said a sharp rise in the Commodity Research Bureau
commodity futures index contributed to an underlying fear of
inflation in the stock and bond markets. The index is considered a
key measure of inflation, which erodes the value of stocks and
bonds.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by about 3-to-2 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 814 up, 608 down and 496 unchanged.
Volume on the Big Board totaled 132.15 million shares with an hour
of trading left.
   More than one-third of the volume came from dividend-capture
strategies in one stock, GTE, with nearly 48 million shares
changing hands at 35|, down [. Aside from that, many investors just
stayed away, partly out of concern over the impact of the March
trade deficit statistics to be released Tuesday.
   Those figures, which have come to symbolize America's economic
weakness, have jolted the market in the past when they exceeded
expectations. Most economists believe the March number will fall
between $12 billion and $13 billion, down from $13.8 billion in
February.
   ``If the number comes in under double digits, I think this
market goes a lot higher,'' said Philip C. Puccio, senior vice
president and manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read &
Co. in New York. ``But investors don't want to buy something today
and look like idiots tomorrow. That's the reason for the dullness.''
   Besides GTE, the most-active NYSE issues included Staley
Continental, down { to 36] on volume exceeding 1.5 million shares.
The company accepted a sweetened takeover offer from Tate & Lyle of
$36.50 a share after finding no other serious bidders.
   Among active blue-chips, IBM rose ] to 110}, General Electric
rose } to 40[, Woolworth rose [ to 53 and Exxon fell \ to 44}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues rose .51 to
145.81. On the American Stock Exchange, the market-value index fell
0.19 to 297.75.
