<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-16 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Advance Limit On Weather Worries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and corn futures closed dramatically
higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade with some contracts up
the limit allowed for daily trading as dry weather fears kicked the
grain markets into a frenzy.
   Buyers dominated the market from the opening bell as traders
returned from a weekend that saw less rain than expected in most of
the Midwest's corn and soybean areas.
   New forecasts issued in the morning predicted dry conditions
until at least mid-week.
   Soybean futures prices, now at four-year highs, are extremely
sensitive to weather factors because U.S. soybean stockpiles are
dwindling and a good crop is needed to meet the anticipated demand,
analysts said.
   Some soybean and corn contracts were up the limit before noon.
Soybeans are permitted to rise or fall no more than 30 cents a
bushel per day, while corn futures are limited to moves of 10 cents
a bushel.
   With most soybean contracts for 1989 delivery trading above
$7.90 a bushel, trader Victor Lespinasse of Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. said $8 soybeans are likely.
   ``Then my goal is $10, assuming the weather remains a little
drier than normal, and then _ well, the all-time high was $12.90 a
bushel on June 5, 1973,'' he said. ``I was there.'' The Board of
Trade confirmed the date and price.
   At the close, wheat was 13 cents to 15 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.19 a bushel; corn was 8\ cents
to 10 cents higher with May at $2.07 a bushel; oats were 6\ cents
to 7} cents higher with May at $1.63} a bushel; soybeans were 28
cents to 30{ cents higher with the May contract, on which the daily
price limit has been removed because of the contract's upcoming
expiration, at $7.50 a bushel.
</TEXT>
