<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-16 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0171</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild burst of late-afternoon buying helped
boost the stock market today after a mixed session marked by
extremely light volume and post-crash investor apathy.
   Traders said rumors of a lower-than-expected March trade
deficit, a statistic to be released Tuesday morning by the Commerce
Department, helped Wall Street in the final few hours.
   ``It looks like they're expecting good figures,'' said Robert
O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Traders said a figure sharply lower than the anticipated $12
billion to $13 billion deficit would provide some much-needed
optimism for Wall Street, which has been plagued by a loss of
confidence since the crash seven months ago.
   The monthly trade deficit figures have come to symbolize the
American economy's competitive weaknesses and are closely watched
by the financial markets because they can influence the dollar's
value, interest rates and the Federal Reserve's monetary policy.
</TEXT>
