<1ST_LINE>u f AM-KodakSettlement Bjt   05-16 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak Settlement, Bjt,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Agrees to $150 Million Settlement in Instant-Camera Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. agreed Monday to reimburse at
least 4.2 million owners of its obsolete instant cameras as part of
a proposed $150 million settlement of a class action lawsuit
against the company.
   Under the settlement proposal, U.S. owners of the cameras would
receive between $50 and $70 in cash and coupons.
   Kodak stopped selling instant cameras and instant film after a
federal court in 1985 said the company had violated patents held by
Polaroid Corp.
   Millions of people own one of the 39 camera models made useless
by the ruling, which barred the manufacture of compatible film.
   ``From the start, our primary objective has been to make an
attractive exchange program available to our Kodak customers,''
said Wilbur J. Prezzano, group vice president of Kodak's
Photographic Products division.
   ``We have worked hard to help reach this settlement and we are
pleased with the results,'' Prezzano said.
   Under the proposed agreement, filed with Cook County Circuit
Judge Thomas Rakowski, instant camera owners would receive $50,
$55, $60 or $70 in cash and Kodak coupons, depending on the model
of their instant camera.
   Cash and coupons will be disbursed when Rakowski gives his final
approval to the settlement, which is expected Sept. 19.
   The proposed settlement is limited to U.S. owners.
   When Kodak's instant film was no longer available, a group of
Chicago attorneys, led by Burton I. Weinstein, filed a class-action
lawsuit on behalf of camera owners in 1986.
   Kodak, based in Rochester, N.Y., said the settlement could cover
as many 16 million people since the company made that many instant
cameras for domestic sale between 1976 and 1985.
   But Weinstein said he would be surprised if many other owners
emerge in addition to the 4.2 million who are parties to the
lawsuit.
   ``We think we have garnered the entire universe,'' he said
outside Rakowski's courtroom.
   Still, Kodak will publicize the settlement in 100 newspapers May
22. Anyone who owns an instant camera and is not yet a party to the
lawsuit can clip the claim form and send it in along with the
camera's nameplate by Aug. 1.
   ``We think the settlement is fair, just and adequate,''
Weinstein said.
   The lawsuit had challenged Kodak's original proposed settlement
for camera owners of a Kodak Disc Camera, a $50 coupon or one share
of Kodak stock.
   Instant photography was invented by Dr. Edwin H. Land, founder
of Polaroid, and was first marketed in 1948.
   The invention enabled users to view a photographic print within
minutes of taking a picture. Conventional photography requires
development and printing of exposed film in a darkroom.
   Polaroid retained a monopoly in the instant photography field
until 1976, when Kodak entered the market with a competing system.
A week after that entry, Polaroid sued Kodak for patent
infringement.
   A federal judge in Boston sided with Polaroid and the U.S.
Supreme Court let stand lower court rulings when it refused to hear
Kodak's appeal in October 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
