<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EaglePremier     05-16 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eagle Premier,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slow Sales Prompt Production Cuts as Eagle Struggles to Grow Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. is cutting production of the
Eagle Premier, the flagship car of its new Jeep-Eagle division,
because of slower-than-expected sales during a difficult
image-building period.
   For two weeks in June and again for a previously scheduled
two-week vacation period in late July, Chrysler will close the
brand-new former American Motors Corp. assembly plant in Bramalea,
Ontario, which builds Premier.
   Bramalea's assembly line will produce 50 fewer cars a day when
the plant reopens after the shutdown during the weeks of June 13
and June 20, Chrysler spokesman Baron Bates said Monday. Bramalea
now builds about 360 cars a day.
   Through April 30, Bramalea had built more than 24,000 cars this
year and dealers had sold less than 10,000. Sales had been
increasing steadily throughout 1988 and Bates said Chrysler
expected them to reach 5,000 cars a month by June.
   At the end of both March and April, unsold inventories averaged
133 days' supply, twice the industry norm of about 60 to 65 days'
supply.
   Bates said Chrysler is pleased with Premier's progress because
the car is attracting younger, more affluent buyers than other
Chrysler products and has not taken sales away from Chrysler, Dodge
or Plymouth.
   Analysts agreed that Premier is a good car whose launch has been
difficult because the Eagle name and lineup is not familiar to
buyers and the market has been crowded with buyer incentives.
   It has been further hampered by the dealer network that sells
it, they said.
   ``The kind of traffic that you get into an old American Motors
dealership wasn't really the type that's going to go out and buy a
mid-size car,'' said Ted Sullivan, analyst with Wharton
Econometrics in Philadelphia.
   Sullivan said AMC dealers have attracted upscale buyers for
Jeep, but added that Jeep buyers are not buying Premiers.
   ``Part of the problem is the way it has to be marketed _ through
AMC dealers who haven't had a car to sell for a long time,'' said
David Healy, analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``If you're in the market for an Audi-type mid-size car, your
AMC dealer is not the place you think of first to go look for
one,'' he said. ``Chrysler's trying to change that.''
   Chrysler bought AMC in August, beginning with French
government-owned Renault's 46.1 percent interest in the ailing
automaker. Under an agreement with Renault, which designed the
Premier and helped AMC build the Bramalea plant, Chrysler buys
major components including engines and transmissions from Renault.
   Because of the weakness of the dollar against western European
currencies, that arrangement is cutting severely Chrysler's profits
on Premier as the imported parts become more expensive, analysts
said.
   But the car _ and the entire Jeep-Eagle network _ still is
faring far better under Chrysler than it would have under AMC, they
said.
   ``If they kept the AMC nameplate it would have been extremely
difficult to make a success of the car because AMC had a negative
image. Now they are starting over with no image,'' said Chris
Cedergren, analyst with J. D. Power and Associates in Agoura Hills,
Calif.
   ``It's better to have no image than a negative image,'' he said.
   This summer, Chrysler will add a four-door, upscale new car
called the Eagle Summit and based on the Japanese Mitsubishi Mirage
to the lineup, followed in 1989 by a sports coupe built at a
Chrysler-Mitsubishi plant in Bloomington-Normal, Ill.
   ``The Summit will help draw buyers to the show room. The more
buyers you draw ... the more Premiers you'll sell,'' Cedergren said.
</TEXT>
