<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AirplaneOrder-Boeing     05-16 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airplane Order-Boeing,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Boeing Unhurt By Recent Air Incidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airplane Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $3.69 billion jet order received by Boeing Co.
demonstrates the airplane manufacturer's reputation has been unhurt
_ and may even have been helped _ by recent air safety incidents,
industry analysts said Monday.
   An Aloha Airlines incident, in which part of a Boeing 737's
fuselage came off during a flight over Hawaii, was called ``a
positive, not a negative for Boeing'' by Judith L. Comeau an
aerospace industry analyst with Goldman Sachs & Co. in New York.
   ``That incident underscored the need to place new orders,'' Ms.
Comeau said.
   ``The integrity of that 737 was impressive. It's unfortunate
that one person died but remember, all the others landed safely,''
Ms. Comeau said.
   Other analysts agreed that while passenger concerns may have
been raised by the Aloha Airlines incident, people within the
airline industry continue to place great faith in Boeing's jets.
   That faith was evident Monday when Boeing, which has about 60
percent of the world's commercial airplane market, captured 77
percent of the biggest commercial airplane order in history.
   Interational Lease Finance ordered 130 planes, 100 from Boeing
and 30 from Airbus Industrie, a consortium of European-based
airlines. The order was for $5.04 billion, with planes to be
delivered over the next six years.
   Boeing's workhorse 737 series snagged the biggest chunk of the
order _ 72 of the 100 Boeing planes ordered _ and a mix of
wide-body and jumbo jets made up the rest of the order.
   Boeing spokeswoman Elizabeth Reese called the order a vote of
confidence in light of the Aloha Airlines incident.
   ``We really need it after everything that happened,'' Ms. Reese
said of the order.
   William Whitlow Jr., a Seattle-based securites analyst for Dain
Bosworth Inc., said Boeing might see more orders because of the
Aloha Airlines incident and other fuselage cracks reported in the
wheel well of an American Airlines jet.
   ``It didn't hurt Boeing. In fact these things have strengthened
their position in that people will start to look at airplanes and
admit that there's an end to their usefulness,'' Whitlow said.
   ``Age is going to become a factor, and that means demand will
increase because people are going to have to start retiring
airplanes earlier than they might have,'' he said.
   The Boeing order consists of 72 planes of models 737-300,
737-400 and 737-500; eight 757-200s; nine 767-300ERs; four
747-400s; and a previously unannounced order of six planes in the
737 series and one 757-200.
   The Airbus order consists of 18 model A320-200s; four
A300-600Rs; six A310-300s, two A340-300s and options for 40 more
planes.
   Boeing valued its share of the contract at $4.6 billion,
counting toward that total the price of 24 additional planes on
which the company has options to buy.
   The largest civilian airplane order to date was in 1986, when
British Airways ordered 16 Boeing 747s for $2.3 billion. That deal
includes options for 12 more of the jumbo jets that would bring the
value to $4.1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
