<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 1850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MarketReport-Reax     05-16 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Report-Reax,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Has No Comment on Market Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Market Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handful of major Wall Street investment houses
had no comment late Monday on the Reagan administration working
group's recommendations to prevent gyrations in the stock market.
   The report recommended the adopting of a ``circuit breaker''
mechanism that would shut down trading in the stock and futures
markets if the Dow Jones industrial average falls 250 points from
its previous close.
   On a separate issue, the working group, headed by Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, said existing margin requirements
appear to be adequate.
   On Wall Street, spokesmen for Merrill Lynch & Co., First Boston
Corp., Bear Stearns & Co. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. had no
comment on the recommendation. They said they needed more time to
study the report.
   But New York Stock Exchange spokesman Richard Torrenzano said
there did not seem to be ``any surprise in the announcement ...
Basically, what they had said is what they've been discussing
before.''
   Torrenzano said he was not sure the report would affect
operations at the exchange because ``nothing has been put into
place yet.''
   The working group was appointed in March as a follow-up to a
White House-appointed commission chaired by Wall Street investment
banker Nicholas F. Brady. The group issued its report amid
criticism that the administration has not gone far enough to
prevent a recurrence of the Oct. 19 market crash, when the Dow
average plunged 508 points in a single session.
   Currently there is no mechanism in place that can halt trading.
</TEXT>
