<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LTVBankruptcy     05-16 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LTV Bankruptcy,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Grants LTV 90-Day Filing Extension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge in New York granted LTV
Corp. a 90-day extension Monday to file a reorganization plan for
the company and its 65 subsidiaries.
   With the extension, LTV until Aug. 18 has the exclusive right to
present a reorganization plan to the U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the
Southern District of New York.
   The court in February had extended the deadline to May 20 from
Feb. 20 at the steel and aerospace giant's request.
   LTV filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors in
1986, saying the company was running out of cash because of
unprecedented problems in the steel industry, the company's large
debt burden and its heavy pension obligations.
   Last week, the company submitted a proposed reorganization plan
to its creditor groups for their consideration. Creditors are
negotiating to reach a consensus plan, company officials said.
   When the company achieves a plan agreeable to creditors, a
disclosure statement will be filed with the bankruptcy court for a
hearing. The hearing will be followed by a vote on the plan by all
creditors and shareholders, after which the bankruptcy court will
conduct a hearing to confirm the plan.
   LTV is the parent company of the nation's second largest
steelmaker and operates a diversified manufacturing company
involved in steel, aerospace-defense and energy products.
</TEXT>
